1. Nf3 ({Welcome along or back to the rich world of the Reti! In this second part of Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Reti, Simon and I will complete our repertoire for White with} 1. Nf3 {. The first part of the LTR was devoted to} d5 2. c4 {and here, against 1...Nf6 and other tries, we'll once again be looking to usually go 2.c4 , sometimes followed by e2-e3 and an advance of the b-pawn, whether to b3 or even b4, preparing a fianchetto of the queen's bishop on b2. Other times, 2.c4 will be followed up by 3.Nc3, and then either e2-e3 and d2-d4 or even e2-e4 and d2-d4. We will examine Black's less common first-move possibilities, but first we must deal with the big alternative to 1...d5 , namely 1...Nf6 .}) 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 ({At this stage Black has some important moves available:} 2... g6 {in King's Indian fashion,}) (2... c5 {keeping things symmetrical, and a small step but popular move in}) (2... e6 {, which is likely to appeal to Nimzo-Indian and Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) players.}) 3. e3 b6 ({We counter in kind with one of our own favourite little pawn pushes, bringing the light-squared bishop into the game. Here play will often go} 3... d5 4. Nc3 {, and we're back in those QGD style lines, which we covered in Chapters 11 to 14 [/variation/23789948] in the first part of this Reti repertoire. Here, in the second part, we'll examine what else Black can play here, and to wet the appetite, let's see Simon in action on the white side.}) {With White yet to play Nc3, ...Bb4 ideas would make little sense, so Black opts for a Queen's Indian style set-up.} 4. b3 ({It's also possible to begin with} 4. Nc3 {, but why not copy Black and prepare to put our own queen's bishop on a fine, open diagonal?}) 4... Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 {Black heads for Symmetrical waters, although this is by no means forced, as we will see.} (5... Be7 6. Nc3 {Completing the development of the queenside minor pieces, freeing the rook on a1 to move. Now} c5 {would, of course, transpose to 5...c5, with Black's main alternative to return to QGD waters after all: 6...d5 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Ne2! A clever little manoeuvre to open up the fianchettoed bishop, as we noted in the first part [/variation/23790044/#/6/w] of the course. It was seen in Dardha-Tsaruk, World Rapid Championship, Almaty 2022, leaving White with a choice between probing on the kingside after Ng3 or introducing a fairly useful second fianchetto in g2-g3 and Bg2.}) 6. Nc3 {Consistent development with the repertoire as White waits for Black to finally develop the bishop from f8.} Be7 7. g4 $5 ({Boom! White spies the chance to cause early problems for Black over his king and also the g7-square. Simon has very much enjoyed making this powerful advance, although in the first theory section of this course, we'll also examine the more restrained} 7. Be2 {(see here [/variation/35967288/#/7/w]), lest you prefer to keep things tight at the back and play more in positional mode.}) 7... O-O (7... Nxg4 $6 8. Rg1 {As White always has h2-h3 if required. White is going to regain his pawn on g7, after which the active rook will supply an early initiative and advantage.}) 8. g5 {Forcing the pace.} Ne4 9. Nxe4 {Sensibly exchanging pieces on our terms, thereby avoiding Black causing any early difficulties by taking on g5 or exchanging on c3 ahead of breaking with ...d5.} Bxe4 10. d3 ({Immediately asking the question of the bishop so is our main recommendation. We'll return to this position in chapter 1b [/variation/35967303/#/10/w]. Instead,} 10. Rg1 {was preferred in Williams-Vaibhav [/variation/35967898], Douglas 2018, which isn't as good, but do please also check out this striking and instructive game to see how the 2597-rated Indian GM was slowly squeezed to death on the kingside - it's annotated later in the course. Enjoy your Reti adventures! It's time now to flesh out the lines we'll be proposing here [/course/222325/36] in the Quickstarter, supplying a brief repertoire there to get you up and running with the Modern Reti: Part Two!}) *

