1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} e6 3. e3 ({A modest little move, but one which denies Black the Nimzo-Indian-like play they were likely hoping for with} 3. Nc3 Bb4 {. White will now fianchetto the queen's bishop and here play often goes 3...d5 4.Nc3 with a transposition back to our anti-QGD line as covered in Part One [/variation/23789994/#/4/w] of the LTR.}) 3... b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 {Mission accomplished on the queenside. Now White will complete minor piece development with Nc3 then Be2, unless something more aggressive catches the eye.} g6 $5 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be2 {Routine and sensible development is best against Black's double fianchetto approach. Next White will castle then look to expand in the centre ourselves.} O-O 8. O-O c5 ({Housing the king and now White will meet} 8... d5 {with} 9. cxd5 {, thereby either obtaining decent control after} exd5 10. d4 {or some pressure down the c-file if 9...Nxd5 10.Rc1 .}) 9. d4 {A key break, as we'll see further at the start of Chapter 1 [/variation/35967252/#/9/w]. White introduces ideas of dxc5 and, if allowed, may go Qc2, Rad1 and then rather cramp Black with d4-d5.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 $1 ({A much stronger recapture than} 10. exd4 d5 {. White now has ideas of not just Bf3, but also a rapid assault on the dark squares with Ndb5 and possibly Ba3.}) *

