1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} e6 3. e3 ({A modest little move, but one which denies Black the Nimzo-Indian-like play they were likely hoping for with} 3. Nc3 Bb4 {. White will now fianchetto the queen's bishop and here play often goes 3...d5 4.Nc3 with a transposition back to our anti-QGD line as covered in Part One [/variation/23789994/#/4/w] of the LTR.}) 3... b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 {Mission accomplished on the queenside. Now White will complete minor piece development with Nc3 then Be2, unless something more aggressive catches the eye.} Be7 6. Nc3 O-O ({Here Black doesn't have to go} 6... d5 {or}) (6... c5 {, but may keep those options open for a move, as we'll appreciate fully in Chapter 1a [/variation/35967257/#/6/w].}) 7. Be2 {White too can retain central flexibility, not least with the d-pawn. We may now castle kingside unless Black himself quickly becomes quite ambitious.} d5 8. cxd5 {Exchanging without delay, just as we often did in related positions after 1.Nf3 d5 2.c4 e6 3.e3 Nf6 4.Nc3 .} exd5 {A more classical recapture.} 9. O-O {Getting the king to safety ahead of competing for the centre with d2-d4.} c5 10. d4 {A necessary as well as good advance, ruling out ...d4 while placing the black centre under some pressure.} Nbd7 11. Rc1 Z0 ({A good spot for the rook. Clearly White would be delighted to see} 11... cxd4 $6 12. Nxd4 {with a rather passive IQP position for Black, and in any case it may be possible to increase the pressure with a timely Ne5 or dxc5.}) *

