1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} e6 3. e3 ({A modest little move, but one which denies Black the Nimzo-Indian-like play they were likely hoping for with} 3. Nc3 Bb4 {. White will now fianchetto the queen's bishop and here play often goes 3...d5 4.Nc3 with a transposition back to our anti-QGD line as covered in Part One [/variation/23789994/#/4/w] of the LTR.}) 3... b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 {Mission accomplished on the queenside. Now White will complete minor piece development with Nc3 then Be2, unless something more aggressive catches the eye.} c5 {A Symmetrical English-like response after all.} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. g4 $5 ({Classical development from Black. Here we'll examine both the sensible} 7. Be2 {and something more aggressive for White.}) 7... O-O ({A favourite advance of Simon's. White wants to make good use of both the bishop on b2 and undefended g7 point to seize an early initiative with either g4-g5 or} 7... Nxg4 8. Rg1 {. Note too that even 7...h6 8.Rg1 followed by h2-h4 should cause Black some early problems.}) 8. g5 Ne4 9. Nxe4 {Dragging Black's own fianchettoed bishop into mid-board rather than allow a slightly awkward exchange on c3.} Bxe4 10. d3 {Driving the bishop backwards followed by h2-h4 is our principle recommendation in Chapter 1b [/variation/35967303/#/10/w].} (10. Rg1 $6 {isn't such a precise move order, but did lead to a very instructive win for White in Williams-Vaibhav [/variation/35967898], Isle of Man Open, Douglas 2018, which we must also examine.}) *

