1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} b6 3. e3 {Consistent with our approach against 2...e6 to which play may well transpose.} Bb7 4. b3 {Once again a queenside fianchetto is a good plan and here Black actually doesn't have to go in for an ...e6 set-up.} g6 $5 5. Bb2 Bg7 6. Be2 {Calm does it here. White holds back on Nc3 until after castling in a bid to reduce Black's options, not least surrounding the ...d5 break.} O-O 7. O-O c5 8. Nc3 {With development almost complete, we are now all set to expand in the centre ourselves with d2-d4.} d5 9. Nxd5 {Forcing the pace. The position may now become unbalanced, but not in an unfavourable way for White.} Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Nxe3 $5 ({Now if} 10... Kxg7 {White will recapture on d5 then hit back in the centre with d2-d4, as we'll explore in Chapter 1c [/variation/35967281/#/10/b].}) 11. fxe3 Kxg7 12. d4 {With ideas of both d4-d5 and even a kingside attack, such as after Qe1-h4, White cannot be unhappy with the outcome of the opening.} *

