1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} d5 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges ahead of going e2-e3.} Nxd5 5. e3 ({A handy little advance. Unlike} 5. e4 {,}) (5. e3 {means that} Nb4 {is nothing to worry about in view of} 6. d4 {.}) 5... g6 $6 {Here too Black won't manage to trick us into a Grunfeld.} 6. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 ({Black must now either allow the slightly awkward} 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 {or slightly misplace the light-squared bishop.}) 7. Qb3 Nb6 8. Ne4 {Attacking c5 and also facilitating Qc3 leaves White doing well, as we'll see in a little more detail at the start of Chapter 2a [/variation/35967327/#/8/w].} *

