1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} d5 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges ahead of going e2-e3.} Nxd5 5. e3 ({A handy little advance. Unlike} 5. e4 {,}) (5. e3 {means that} Nb4 {is nothing to worry about in view of} 6. d4 {.}) 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 g6 ({White already enjoys an extra central pawn, one we can immediately deploy in the event of} 6... Nc6 7. d4 {and 6...e6 7.d4 , although 6...Qc7 should be met by 7.Bb2 rather than 7.d4 g6 .}) 7. h4 $1 ({Now} 7. d4 {would give Black the Grunfeld he presumably desires after all, but never forget about Harry the h-pawn in such positions!}) 7... Bg7 ({Racing the h-pawn up to h5 unless Black prefers to suffer after} 7... h5 8. Bc4 {and Ng5.}) 8. h5 Nc6 9. Rb1 {Reminding Black that White also has a definite asset on the queenside in the shape of the half-open b-file. Now d2-d4 and Bd3 may continue development, with a timely Ba3 very much an idea too, as we'll appreciate further in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/36088584/#/9/w].} *

