1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} d5 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges ahead of going e2-e3.} Nxd5 5. e3 ({A handy little advance. Unlike} 5. e4 {,}) (5. e3 {means that} Nb4 {is nothing to worry about in view of} 6. d4 {.}) 5... e6 6. Nxd5 exd5 ({A perhaps slightly unexpected exchange of knights, but} 6... Qxd5 7. b3 {would give White easy development and we're also preparing a positional pawn sacrifice.}) 7. b4 $5 {A radical but good way to facilitate a fianchetto, as White refuses to allow Black to dominate with their pawn centre.} cxb4 8. Bb2 {White's compensation should already be clear: pressure down the long diagonal towards g7, pressure on the kingside which might be amplified, whether by Bd3 or Nd4 or Ne5 followed by activating the queen. Rc1 too is high on the agenda, causing Black definite difficulties in terms of completing their development, as we'll enjoy exploring in much greater detail in both Chapter 2a2 [/variation/35967364/#/8/w] and with the illustrative game Parligras-Gaehwiler [/variation/35967899/#/8/w], European Individual Championship, Skopje 2019.} *

