1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} d5 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges ahead of going e2-e3.} Nxd5 5. e3 ({A handy little advance. Unlike} 5. e4 {,}) (5. e3 {means that} Nb4 {is nothing to worry about in view of} 6. d4 {.}) 5... Nc6 6. Bb5 {A useful pin, already threatening Ne5 and leaving Black's knights in a slight pickle.} Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd7 8. O-O {Black has kept their structure intact, but must still be quite accurate to equalise with White able to choose from approaches with d2-d4, Ba3 and Bxc6 followed by Ne5.} e6 9. d4 {It's high time to begin central expansion.} Be7 10. Rb1 {As good a square as any for the rook as Black is forced to think about b7.} O-O 11. Bd3 {Its work done on b5, the bishop skips back into the heart of the white camp. Black is very solid, but White definitely has some chances on the kingside and may even be able to follow up Qe2 with h2-h4, as we'll see in Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967399/#/11/w].} *

