1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} g6 4. e4 ({A change of approach, but a better choice here than allowing Black a fairly comfortable set-up with} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 $1 {. Instead, White prepares to advance in the centre.}) 4... Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 d6 ({Play can clearly now transpose after} 6... Bg7 7. Be3 {to the 4...Bg7 mainlines, but Black may also go in for the Gurgenidze variation.}) 7. Be2 ({An alert move, keeping Black out of g4, something which} 7. Be3 $6 Ng4 {would fail to do.}) 7... Nxd4 $5 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 {Natural development and now Black is likely to threaten ...Ng4.} O-O 10. Qd3 $5 {We prefer to retreat here rather than to d2. The queen will jump back to c2 in the event of ...Nd7-c5, thereby keeping e4 secure, and meanwhile O-O followed by f2-f4 or even b2-b4 is on the way.} *

