1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} g6 4. e4 ({A change of approach, but a better choice here than allowing Black a fairly comfortable set-up with} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 $1 {. Instead, White prepares to advance in the centre.}) 4... Bg7 5. d4 {A vital break getting ready to establish the Maroczy Bind.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 O-O ({A fairly essential move to maintain the structure and secure White's central position against the threat of ...Nxe4. Black now has two main approaches. The slightly discredited or at least unfashionable one is} 7... Ng4 $5 {when} 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 {returns the queen to base camp with tempo and gives White good chances for an edge, as we'll see in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967414/#/9/w].}) 8. Be2 {Keeping Black out of g4 for good and preparing to castle.} d6 9. O-O Bd7 10. h3 $5 {A very useful little move. White prepares to move the queen to c2, partly depending on what Black plays, followed by Rad1, with f2-f4 another idea in the position.} Nxd4 {A standard freeing mechanism for Black in this main line of the Accelerated Dragon.} 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. Qc2 {Keeping e4 secure. Everything is now set for Rad1 followed by e4-e5 or even c4-c5. White has scored quite well with this approach, as we'll see further in both Chapter 2b [/variation/35967449/#/12/w] and Pranesh-Livaic [/variation/35967900/#/11/w], Rilton Cup, Stockholm 2022/23.} *

