1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} Nc6 {Maintaining the symmetry is a very important option, but so are Black's two principle alternatives.} 4. e3 {White gets ready to break with d2-d4 and we'll come on to this sub-variation of the Symmetrical in Chapter 2c [/variation/35967462/#/4/w].} g6 {Only now that we're committed to an e3 set-up does Black fianchetto.} 5. d4 {The logical break and now Black surely doesn't want to be hit by an early d4-d5.} cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {This actually takes play into a line of the Caro-Kann, the Panov-Botvinnik! Indeed, 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 g6 would lead to the same position.} 7. h3 $5 ({A crafty little move, cutting out ...Bg4 and avoiding the theory of the big main lines after} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {. White doesn't mind an IQP position if Black wants to exchange on c4, but is now ready to carry out a key Panov advance in the shape of c4-c5.}) 7... Bg7 8. c5 $1 {Establishing something of a central grip, one that Bb5 followed by O-O will but reinforce.} O-O 9. Bb5 {Continuing the fight for control of e5.} Ne4 $5 {A natural attempt by Black to liberate his position, if also a leap White can ignore.} 10. O-O $1 {Now, if needed, White will always be able to increase the central pressure with Re1.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 {White's doubled pawns are actually quite useful here, helping to keep Black cramped. With Re1 then Bg5 on the way, the onus remains on Black to try and find a way to free their position, and White is surely for choice as we'll see further in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967476/#/11/w].} *

