1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} Nc6 {Maintaining the symmetry is a very important option, but so are Black's two principle alternatives.} 4. e3 {White gets ready to break with d2-d4 and we'll come on to this sub-variation of the Symmetrical in Chapter 2c [/variation/35967462/#/4/w].} e5 $5 5. d4 {Breaking in the centre before Black can get in ...e4.} e4 {The modern interpretation of this sub-variation.} 6. d5 {White responds in kind, just like we do with ...f5 played instead of ...Nf6.} exf3 7. dxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ ({As} 8. Qxf3 $6 Bg4 9. Qg3 Bd6 {wouldn't be wise, White should remove the queens and interfere slightly with Black's development.}) 8... Kxd8 9. gxf3 g6 10. b3 {Even with Black having sensibly gone ...g6, White's best policy remains a queenside fianchetto.} Bg7 11. Bb2 Z0 ({Black is pretty solid here, but White threatens to win a pawn with} 11... Z0 12. Ne4 {and should have a nibble, with Ne4 likely on the way in any case, supported if need be by Bg2.}) *

