1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} Nc6 {Maintaining the symmetry is a very important option, but so are Black's two principle alternatives.} 4. e3 {White gets ready to break with d2-d4 and we'll come on to this sub-variation of the Symmetrical in Chapter 2c [/variation/35967462/#/4/w].} e6 ({Maintaining the symmetry. Black is also again allowed to be more adventurous and} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {would take play back into a position we've already seen in the realm of chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967379/#/6/w].}) 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 ({White now has ideas of d4-d5 and will even meet} 6... Bb4 {with} 7. d5 {.}) 7. c5 $1 {We're once again in a line of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, one no longer seen much at grandmaster level due to this powerful, cramping advance. White shuts down Black's play and will follow up with Bb5 and O-O with a definite grip and edge.} *

