1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} c5 {Black heads for the theoretically important waters of the Symmetrical English. There are, however, some major and pretty common alternatives.} 3. Nc3 {Natural development. White will usually follow up with e2-e3 then d2-d4, although we'll push the pawn instead to e4 if Black now goes in for a fianchetto on the kingside.} Nc6 {Maintaining the symmetry is a very important option, but so are Black's two principle alternatives.} 4. e3 {White gets ready to break with d2-d4 and we'll come on to this sub-variation of the Symmetrical in Chapter 2c [/variation/35967462/#/4/w].} e6 ({Maintaining the symmetry. Black is also again allowed to be more adventurous and} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {would take play back into a position we've already seen in the realm of chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967379/#/6/w].}) 5. d4 d5 {Taking play into Semi-Tarrasch waters.} 6. cxd5 {there Bb5 A pinning device we've already make good use of in a related position as White prepares to generate some pressure with Ne5. cxd4 exd4!? The more dynamic recapture as White takes on an isolated pawn in return for central and potentially kingside pressure. Be7 O-O Now Ne5 Bd7 would be very solid for Black, but White can hardly object to instead completing kingside development. O-O Re1 A fine square for the rook. Black is quite solid, but still has some problems to solve. White does, for instance, welcome an exchange on c3 which should strengthen our centre and may generate some pressure after a timely Bxc6 or even Bd3, looking to launch a kingside attack, as we'll see White sometimes able to do in Line 2C3 [/variation/35967543/#/10/w].} *

