1. Nf3 c5 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) {Black offers a Sicilian...} 2. c4 ({...But we decline the chance for} 2. e4 {and instead make our favourite second move, the same as we do against 1...d5. We're now officially in the realm of the Symmetrical English and} Nf6 3. Nc3 {would take play into the world of Chapter Two [/variation/35967305/#/3/w] ( 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.Nc3 ).}) 2... Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 ({Knights before bishops as they say. White is now all set to dominate the centre with e2-e3 and d2-d4, and} 3... Nf6 {would return theory to the realm of Chapter 2c [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] ( 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 ).}) 4. e3 f5 $6 ({White is set to break with d2-d4, and now} 4... Nf6 5. d4 {is the critical line - see 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e5 5.d4 , as covered in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w].}) 5. d4 e4 6. d5 $1 {Seizing space and counterattacking against the black knight. As Black doesn't have a great square for it, exchanges are likely to follow.} exf3 7. dxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. gxf3 {Without the pawn on f5, Black would have chances to be OK, but there's no doubt that they've both weakened their kingside this way and obstructed the bishop on c8.} Nf6 10. b3 {The a1-h8 diagonal will be a fine home for the dark-squared bishop. White wants to go Bb2, O-O-O and will then look to target the black kingside, not least g7, such as with an advance of the h-pawn and/or a Ne2-f4 manoeuvre. We'll examine this in more detail in Chapter 3 [/variation/35967586/#/10/w].} *

