1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 d5 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) {A Grunfeld-like response.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White should exchange, in the process dragging the black knight away from the kingside.} Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {A powerful advance and a topical line which has scared away a number of leading Grunfeld protagonists from wishing to defend their favourite opening in this Reti guise. White exploits the early lead in development to apply some kingside pressure with h4-h5.} Nxc3 6. bxc3 h6 $5 ({Recapturing in classical fashion towards the centre while renewing the possibility of h4-h5. Black can play to prevent that, but} 6... h5 7. Ng5 {would take immediate advantage of the weakened black kingside.}) 7. h5 g5 8. d4 {Finally claiming a toehold in the centre now that Black's kingside has been weakened. White will follow up with e2-e3, securing d4, after which Rb1 will be one useful idea, taking control of the b1-h7 diagonal another.} *

