1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 d5 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) {A Grunfeld-like response.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White should exchange, in the process dragging the black knight away from the kingside.} Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {A powerful advance and a topical line which has scared away a number of leading Grunfeld protagonists from wishing to defend their favourite opening in this Reti guise. White exploits the early lead in development to apply some kingside pressure with h4-h5.} h5 6. Qb3 {Not only attacking the knight, but beginning to put f7 under pressure.} Nb6 7. Ng5 {With a definite threat!} e6 8. a4 $5 {And now the other rook's pawn joins in as White refuses to let Black settle. White aims to follow up with a4-a5 and then get on with development beginning with e2-e3.} *

