1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 d5 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) {A Grunfeld-like response.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White should exchange, in the process dragging the black knight away from the kingside.} Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {A powerful advance and a topical line which has scared away a number of leading Grunfeld protagonists from wishing to defend their favourite opening in this Reti guise. White exploits the early lead in development to apply some kingside pressure with h4-h5.} c5 6. h5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 $1 {Not our standard recapture, but a good one here with Black having weakened themselves in the centre, as well as on the kingside.} Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Bg7 9. e4 Z0 ({White already enjoys a pleasant edge with the king bound for c2, the dark-squared bishop for e3 or f4 and h5-h6 very much a possibility too, not least when, as here,} 9... Z0 10. h6 Bf6 $2 11. e5 {would win a piece.}) *

