1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 d5 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) {A Grunfeld-like response.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White should exchange, in the process dragging the black knight away from the kingside.} Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {A powerful advance and a topical line which has scared away a number of leading Grunfeld protagonists from wishing to defend their favourite opening in this Reti guise. White exploits the early lead in development to apply some kingside pressure with h4-h5.} Bg7 6. h5 Nc6 ({It may now be possible to disrupt Black's smooth development with h5-h6 and White is very much able to still expand in the centre, be it with d2-d4 or e2-e4. Note too that} 6... O-O $6 {is pretty risky for Black in view of} 7. hxg6 hxg6 8. Qa4 $1 {, angling to land the queen on h4.}) 7. d4 {The pawn is fairly safe here now that ...c5 is ruled out. White fights for control of e5 while threatening to advance with e2-e4.} Bf5 8. Rh4 $5 {This highly creative move renews the threat of e2-e4.} Bf6 9. g4 $1 Bxh4 10. gxf5 {A dangerous exchange sacrifice. White threatens e2-e4, as well as Nxh4, and it's not hard to grasp that Black's position has already rather collapsed on the light squares.} *

