1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 4. e4 ({Clamping down on the d5-square denies Black any Grunfeld options, unlike} 4. d4 d5 {.}) 4... e5 $5 {This is another dynamic choice sometimes used by Grunfeld adherents who do not want to be move ordered into a King's Indian.} 5. Nxe5 {The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating, so White annexes the pawn ahead of ideally going d2-d4 and dropping the knight back to f3.} O-O 6. Nf3 $1 {A prophylactic retreat. We want to ensure that we'll be able to shore up e4 with d2-d3.} Re8 7. d3 d5 {Black must break so or they'll just find themselves a clear pawn in arrears.} 8. cxd5 {White should exchange ahead of covering against threats on c3 with Bd2.} Nxd5 9. Bd2 Bg4 10. Be2 {Breaking the pin and meaning the knight on d5 is now en prise. White will actually meet ...Bxf3 with gxf3, keeping the bishop on e2 to take some of the wind out of the sails of ...Nb4 ideas, after which Be3 and h2-h4 will see us beginning to head forwards. And, yes, White is still a pawn to the good, as we'll appreciate further in Chapter 4b [/variation/36143748/#/10/w].} *

