1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 4. e4 ({Clamping down on the d5-square denies Black any Grunfeld options, unlike} 4. d4 d5 {.}) 4... d6 ({Taking play into King's Indian waters (} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {with a transposition does likewise).}) 5. d4 {Only now that a Grunfeld is off the table, do we advance the d-pawn and so construct a perfect centre.} O-O 6. Bd3 $5 ({By far the main move for White here is, of course,} 6. Be2 {. Only really during the Covid era did this alternative bishop development begin to be explored at a high level, Dubov defeating Carlsen with it before Magnus himself deployed the line against Nakamura. White prepares to castle and gets ready to react to ...c5 or ...e5 with the space-gaining d4-d5, while also tempting Black into trying to target d4.}) 6... Nc6 7. d5 {Sensibly kicking the knight before Black can bring any more pressure to bear in the centre.} Nb4 8. Bb1 $5 {A perhaps slightly unexpected retreat, but one which helps to keep e4 secure. White can drive the knight back from b4 with a2-a3 and is also set to take control of the position with h2-h3 and O-O.} a5 {Ruling out any quick a2-a3 and b2-b4 advance from White.} 9. h3 e6 10. O-O {With e4 secure White can now meet an exchange on d5 with cxd5. Be3 and a2-a3 are also on their way, which may well add up to an edge as we'll see further at the start of Chapter 5 [/variation/35967654/#/10/w].} *

