1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 4. e4 ({Clamping down on the d5-square denies Black any Grunfeld options, unlike} 4. d4 d5 {.}) 4... d6 ({Taking play into King's Indian waters (} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {with a transposition does likewise).}) 5. d4 {Only now that a Grunfeld is off the table, do we advance the d-pawn and so construct a perfect centre.} O-O 6. Bd3 $5 ({By far the main move for White here is, of course,} 6. Be2 {. Only really during the Covid era did this alternative bishop development begin to be explored at a high level, Dubov defeating Carlsen with it before Magnus himself deployed the line against Nakamura. White prepares to castle and gets ready to react to ...c5 or ...e5 with the space-gaining d4-d5, while also tempting Black into trying to target d4.}) 6... c5 7. d5 {Naturally White closes lines and may now enjoy a fairly pleasant space advantage thanks to the bridgehead on d5.} e6 8. h3 {A useful little move, beginning to restrict Black's pieces, not least the bishop on c8.} exd5 9. exd5 $1 ({And a further important move to remember.} 9. cxd5 {would take play into the Modern Benoni, whereas in this somewhat less unbalanced structure Black will find it harder to create counterplay. Already White is set to assume control of the position with O-O, Re1 and Bf4 or Bg5.}) 9... Re8+ 10. Be3 Rxe3+ $5 ({We should also be fairly happy if Black prefers to be the side to sacrifice. The best way to deal with the check and White should now be happy to sacrifice a pawn for a significant lead in development with} 10... Bh6 11. O-O $1 {.}) 11. fxe3 Qe7 12. O-O $1 {Ignoring the threat on e3 as White doesn't mind going Rf2 and would welcome the e-file quickly opening with Black's queenside still asleep.} Nbd7 13. Qe1 {The queen may now emerge in a bit on h4 and White is all set to complete full deployment of the pieces with Rd1, after which Rd2-f2 is definitely a plan, one which appears to indicate that Black doesn't have quite enough for the exchange, as we'll appreciate further in Chapter 5a [/variation/35967674/#/13/w].} *

