1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 4. e4 ({Clamping down on the d5-square denies Black any Grunfeld options, unlike} 4. d4 d5 {.}) 4... d6 ({Taking play into King's Indian waters (} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {with a transposition does likewise).}) 5. d4 {Only now that a Grunfeld is off the table, do we advance the d-pawn and so construct a perfect centre.} O-O 6. Bd3 $5 ({By far the main move for White here is, of course,} 6. Be2 {. Only really during the Covid era did this alternative bishop development begin to be explored at a high level, Dubov defeating Carlsen with it before Magnus himself deployed the line against Nakamura. White prepares to castle and gets ready to react to ...c5 or ...e5 with the space-gaining d4-d5, while also tempting Black into trying to target d4.}) 6... e5 {The most King's Indian-like break at Black's disposal, echoing the big main line that is 6.Be2 e5.} 7. d5 {Keeping lines closed in thematic fashion and now Black often combines ...a5 with bringing a knight to c5, with there being a few different ways of achieving that.} Nbd7 8. O-O {Calm development as White gets ready to expand with a2-a3 and b2-b4.} Nc5 9. Bc2 {Preserving an important piece while getting ready to quickly overrun Black, if allowed, with b2-b4.} a5 10. a3 Bd7 ({Now Rb1 (or Be3) then b2-b4 may follow, and Black shouldn't tarry unless they want to get swept away on the queenside. We will though see what happens to} 10... b6 {in the positional tour de force that is Smyslov-Karadzhaev [/variation/35967902/#/10/b], USSR Team Championship, Moscow 1959.}) 11. Re1 $5 Z0 ({This useful semi-waiting move gets ready for Be3 (} 11... a4 12. Be3 {will now threaten Bxc5 and Nxe5) while keeping White's options open depending on how Black now seeks counterplay, as we'll explore further in Chapter 5b [/variation/35967694/#/11/w].}) *

