1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 ({Here we'll be looking to go e2-e4, not e2-e3, and} 3... c5 4. e4 {followed by d2-d4 would again take play into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 4. e4 ({Clamping down on the d5-square denies Black any Grunfeld options, unlike} 4. d4 d5 {.}) 4... d6 ({Taking play into King's Indian waters (} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {with a transposition does likewise).}) 5. d4 {Only now that a Grunfeld is off the table, do we advance the d-pawn and so construct a perfect centre.} O-O 6. Bd3 $5 ({By far the main move for White here is, of course,} 6. Be2 {. Only really during the Covid era did this alternative bishop development begin to be explored at a high level, Dubov defeating Carlsen with it before Magnus himself deployed the line against Nakamura. White prepares to castle and gets ready to react to ...c5 or ...e5 with the space-gaining d4-d5, while also tempting Black into trying to target d4.}) 6... Bg4 $5 7. Be2 $1 {This gives up a whole tempo, but retains full control over d4 and Black's problem is that they are a move ahead of the line 6.Be2 Bg4, which isn't considered particularly good for Black. Indeed, even this version gives White good chances of emerging with the advantage, partly as he is again ready to counter any ...c5 or ...e5 central strikes with d4-d5.} Nfd7 8. Be3 {Securing d4 to take the sting out of any exchange on f3.} e5 9. d5 {Thematically exchanging knights. Now White may rid Black of some of their dynamism and make a positionally favourable exchange of light-squared bishops after Nd2 or even Ng5.} a5 10. Ng5 $1 Z0 ({White's most ambitious and strongest move, as well as our recommendation in Chapter 5c [/variation/35967710/#/10/w], getting ready to follow up} 10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 {with a quick g2-g4. Even 10.Nd2 Bxe2 11.Qxe2 is a pleasant edge for White, as we'll quickly realise when we tackle the instructive encounter, Dubov-Carlsen [/variation/35967903/#/11/w], Steinitz Memorial (blitz) 2020.}) *

