1. Nf3 Nf6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) ({A very common, flexible and important alternative to} 1... d5 {.}) 2. c4 {Our ideal second move, one just as good against 1...Nf6 as 1...d5. Now Nc3 and/or e2-e3 will follow.} d6 3. d4 Nbd7 ({Preventing ...e5. Now play will often return to King's Indian waters after} 3... g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 {. White should also be fairly happy to see 3...Bf5 4.Nc3 g6 when 5.Qb3 begins to exploit the downside to the early bishop development.}) 4. Nc3 {Thematically preparing e2-e4 against Black's Old Indian approach.} e5 5. e4 {Not for the first time, we'd be quite happy with a Maroczy Bind and early control in the event of an exchange on d4.} Be7 6. Bd3 $5 {An approach consistent with our line against the King's Indian. White gets ready to castle and may follow up with Re1, retaining the central tension and looking for a favourable moment to push d4-d5, as we'll appreciate further in Chapter 6a [/variation/35967742/#/6/w].} *

