1. Nf3 d6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) 2. d4 $1 ({Another important move order to remember. Just like after 1...g6 we don't go 2.c4, but here} 2. d4 {is the move and now play will often go} g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. e4 {when either a Modern or King's Indian is the result. Black also has 2...Nf6 when we'll see 3.c4 via a 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 d6 3.d4 move order.}) 2... f5 $6 {Black attempts to slide into a Dutch after all.} 3. Nc3 $1 {A strong response and the downside to this move order for Black. Already that key break for White against the Dutch, e2-e4, is threatened.} Nf6 4. Bg5 {Threatening to mash up Black's structure while also continuing the theme of speedy development.} Nbd7 5. Qd3 {Black is able to defend f5, but not also prevent White from breaking with e2-e4, which should result in a pretty pleasant early advantage due to Black's potential weaknesses down the e-file and slightly vulnerable kingside in general.} *

