1. Nf3 d6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) 2. d4 $1 ({Another important move order to remember. Just like after 1...g6 we don't go 2.c4, but here} 2. d4 {is the move and now play will often go} g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. e4 {when either a Modern or King's Indian is the result. Black also has 2...Nf6 when we'll see 3.c4 via a 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 d6 3.d4 move order.}) 2... Bg4 {The Wade Defence.} 3. c4 {A thematic advance which may be followed by Nc3, all the while as White crucially doesn't mind an exchange on f3.} Bxf3 4. exf3 {The right way to recapture, facilitating quick development with Bd3, after which O-O and even Re1 may follow.} c6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. d5 $1 {Another useful gain of space as White begins to cramp Black. After Bd3 and O-O, White's extra space, bishop-pair and freer development will more than offset the doubled f-pawns, as we'll see further in Chapter 6a [/variation/35967727/#/6/w].} *

