1. Nf3 g6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) 2. e4 $1 ({In general in this repertoire our usual move order is} 2. c4 {, but actually only by going}) (2. e4 {here can we avoid being move ordered (}) (2. c4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c5 {is the problem). Now if 2...c5 3.c4 followed by d2-d4 and we get back into the Symmetrical English/ Accelerated Dragon world of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 3. d4 ({Further precision as well as classical development, denying Black the chance for a Grunfeld which} 3. c4 Nf6 4. Nc3 d5 {would yield.}) 3... d6 4. c4 e5 ({Only now does the c-pawn reach its favourite square and here play will usually go} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {with a transposition to the King's Indian and Chapter 5 [/variation/35967650/#/5/w].}) 5. Nc3 exd4 ({Maintaining the tension and waiting for} 5... Nc6 {before going in for} 6. dxe5 {and exchanges, when the knight on c6 will prove slightly misplaced (were a pawn there instead White wouldn't be able to go Nd5).}) 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 Nge7 ({White has established another of our favourite pawn structures, the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the black position and now} 7... Nf6 {(threatening ...Ng4)} 8. Be2 {would continue to deny Black easy counterplay.}) 8. h4 $5 {Sounding the charge so is quite justified when White has a firm grip on the centre and there isn't a black knight on f6. White will follow up with h4-h5 if allowed and may continue development with Qd2 and O-O-O or just Be2.} *

