1. Nf3 g6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) 2. e4 $1 ({In general in this repertoire our usual move order is} 2. c4 {, but actually only by going}) (2. e4 {here can we avoid being move ordered (}) (2. c4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c5 {is the problem). Now if 2...c5 3.c4 followed by d2-d4 and we get back into the Symmetrical English/ Accelerated Dragon world of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 3. d4 ({Further precision as well as classical development, denying Black the chance for a Grunfeld which} 3. c4 Nf6 4. Nc3 d5 {would yield.}) 3... d6 4. c4 Bg4 ({Only now does the c-pawn reach its favourite square and here play will usually go} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {with a transposition to the King's Indian and Chapter 5 [/variation/35967650/#/5/w].}) 5. Be2 {Sensibly breaking the pin and keeping d4 secure.} Nc6 6. Nbd2 $1 Nf6 ({Not the most common move, but one we quite like. White can now meet} 6... Bxf3 {with} 7. Nxf3 {and 6...Nxd4?? 7.Nxd4 would, of course, cost Black a piece.}) 7. d5 {Seizing some useful space.} Nb8 8. Qc2 {White's space advantage should secure a small but pleasant edge. As we'll see further in Chapter 6b [/variation/35967797/#/8/w], h2-h3 will deal with the bishop on g4, after which White even has time to untangle and improve the queenside pieces, beginning with Nb1-c3.} *

