1. Nf3 f5 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) {The Dutch Defence.} 2. c4 Nf6 ({Calmly continuing our favourite policy.} 2... Z0 3. e3 {will likely follow as we wait to see how Black intends to untangle their kingside pieces.}) 3. e3 e6 4. b3 {One of our favourite Reti deployments as White gets ready to fianchetto the queen's bishop.} d5 5. cxd5 {Exchanging so quickly isn't especially common in the Stonewall Dutch (a set-up with ...f5 and ...d5) in general, but makes good sense here as White plays for control, as well as a double fianchetto.} exd5 6. Bb2 c6 7. g3 {There were limited prospects for the light-squared bishop on the f1-a6 diagonal, so we switch it to g2, thereby ensuring that the king will be especially well protected once it's castled.} Bd6 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O {Mission complete. White will now continue with d2-d3, Nbd2 and most likely Qc2. Black must then be wary of being hit by the classic anti-Dutch break, e3-e4, and White may also look to expand on the queenside, all the while enjoying good control of some key central squares. We'll see more on this position and related ones in Chapter 7a [/variation/35967807/#/9/w].} *

