1. Nf3 f5 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) {The Dutch Defence.} 2. c4 Nf6 ({Calmly continuing our favourite policy.} 2... Z0 3. e3 {will likely follow as we wait to see how Black intends to untangle their kingside pieces.}) 3. e3 e6 4. b3 {One of our favourite Reti deployments as White gets ready to fianchetto the queen's bishop.} Be7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 d6 ({Blocking the bishop, but also a good square for the knight, just like it was in the anti-Queen's Gambit lines we considered back in Part One. Here too Black may go in for a Stonewall approach, albeit with the bishop slightly less actively placed on e7 rather than d6, and again White should meet} 6... d5 {with} 7. cxd5 {followed by a quick g2-g3 and Bg2.}) 7. d4 Qe8 ({Preventing ...e5 and transposing to a slightly unusual version of a Classical Dutch. White will follow up with Bd3 and/or Qc2, and should keep an eye open for potential aggressive ideas, as well as just O-O and breaking with e2-e4, be it with} 7... Nc6 8. d5 {or even potential ideas of castling queenside.}) 8. Qc2 {Already the potential pawn lever in e3-e4 becomes a weapon for once White has got on a bit more with development.} Qg6 9. h4 $1 {Seizing an early initiative. With O-O-O and Bd3 on the way (and a2-a3 in the event of ...Nc6), Black may well find themselves being hit by a powerful h4-h5 or e3-e4 advance, as we'll see further in Chapter 7b [/variation/35967814/#/9/w].} *

