1. Nf3 f5 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) {The Dutch Defence.} 2. c4 Nf6 ({Calmly continuing our favourite policy.} 2... Z0 3. e3 {will likely follow as we wait to see how Black intends to untangle their kingside pieces.}) 3. e3 g6 {A Leningrad Dutch approach.} 4. d4 {This time we do go in for an early d2-d4 and transposition into the standard lines of the Dutch, albeit not the main lines of the Leningrad characterised by an early g2-g3.} Bg7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Be2 {For now White controls e5 and is set to both swiftly castle and expand with b2-b4.} d6 7. b4 $5 e5 ({Seizing space and White doesn't mind claiming some more if} 7... a5 8. b5 {. White is now all set to castle and may then find both Bb2 and Qb3 useful moves, as well as continuing the queenside advance with a2-a4 and b4-b5.}) 8. dxe5 {Opening the centre before Black can annoy us with ...e4.} dxe5 9. Qb3 {A fine spot for the queen, introducing ideas of c4-c5+ and also threatening Nxe5 now that the knight on c3 is defended.} ({Please just don't fall for} 9. Nxe5 $4 Ne4 {.}) 9... e4 10. Nd4 {With Bb2 or Ba3, as well as O-O and Rd1 on the way, White is definitely exerting some early pressure as we'll see further in Chapter 7d [/variation/35967852/#/10/w].} *

