1. Nf3 b6 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) 2. c4 Bb7 3. e3 {There's no need to allow the English Defence player the chance to double the f-pawns.} e6 4. b3 f5 $5 ({Our ideal queenside development and now play will transpose into the anti-Nimzo and Queen's Indian-type lines (1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.e3) after} 4... Nf6 5. Bb2 {.}) 5. Bb2 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Straightforward queenside development once again from White.} Be7 7. g3 $1 {A slight twist on our standard development scheme, but a good one here as White goes in for a second fianchetto to challenge the bishop on b7 for control of the long light-square diagonal.} O-O 8. Bg2 Qe8 9. O-O {With ideas of both d2-d4-d5 and a timely Ne2-f4 good plans, White has every chance of emerging with a small early advantage, as we'll see further in Chapter 7c [/variation/35967822/#/9/w].} *

