1. Nf3 Nc6 $5 ({Our favourite Reti first move, and now we'll tackle everything apart from} 1... d5 {which was, of course, the subject of the Modern Reti: Part One [/variation/23789295].}) 2. d4 {)} ({We regain control of e5 and thereby avoid} 2. c4 e5 {with a reversed Sicilian. Once again, c2-c4 will follow assuming Black takes steps to prevent or at least minimise the damage d4-d5 could cause.}) 2... d5 3. c4 {We're now in the Chigorin Defence where the plan will be to exert early pressure against d5.} Bg4 4. Nc3 {White is now ready to go cxd5 and will meet any exchange on f3 with exf3, after which the light-squared bishop may quickly find a good spot on b5.} e6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Qb3 $5 {The main downside to most cases of ...Bg4 is that b7 can become weak, as is certainly the case here. White presses against both b7 and d5, all while dangling d4 before Black.} Bxf3 7. exf3 Nxd4 $2 ({Qxb7 is now a threat, and} 7... Qe7+ {can be met by} 8. Be3 {, but better that for Black than falling into our little trap.}) 8. Qa4+ $1 ({A far stronger choice than} 8. Qxb7 {as White prepares to hit Black with an unexpected bishop deployment.}) 8... Nc6 9. Ba6 $1 Z0 ({Black's light squares are shot and they are actually quite fortunate to be able to grovel their way to only a clearly worse position with} 9... Qe7+ 10. Kf1 Qb4 {, as we'll see further in Chapter 8b [/variation/35967890/#/9/w].}) *

