1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 {This is likely to be the choice of a Nimzo and Queen's Indian player, deploying the same first two moves as they like to do against 1.d4 and 2.c4.} 3. e3 b6 ({A modest little move, but also a good choice from a practical perspective, since it may confuse opponents and will often lead to} 3... d5 4. Nc3 {, with a transposition into the Reti QGD lines ( 1.Nf3 d5 2.c4 e6 3.e3 Nf6 4.Nc3 ) covered in chapters 13 and 14 [/variation/23789994/#/4/w] of the first part of this course. With 3.e3 White keeps plenty of options open and may well still look to fianchetto the queen's bishop. Richard must even admit that back in 2006 when he wrote Beating Unusual Chess Openings, that while he considered 3.b3, 3.e3 went under the radar.}) ({Black decides to continue in Queen's Indian fashion, fianchettoing his own queen's bishop. As we've already noted, an even more popular choice in practice has been} 3... d5 4. Nc3 {with the aforementioned transposition back to the first part of this course. Instead, 3...Bb4?! would make no sense here, and after 4.a3 Bc5 White might well elect to develop with tempo and a very pleasant edge after 5.b4 Be7 6.Bb2 .}) ({That leaves} 3... c5 4. Nc3 {when} b6 5. b3 Bb7 6. Bb2 {transposes to Chapter 1b [/variation/35967285/#/6/w], while 4...d5 would be another transposition and here we advocated 5.cxd5 in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of this Reti repertoire. We should also mention 3...Be7 , which looks rather passive, but after 4.b3 O-O 5.Bb2 Black can either head via 5...d5 6.Nc3 into Chapter 14 [/variation/23790046/#/6/w] of The Modern Reti: Part One, or into Chapter 1a [/variation/35967257/#/6/b] here with 5...b6 6.Nc3 Bb7 .}) 4. b3 {White decides that imitation is the sincerest form of flattery and that it's high time to make our favourite queenside fianchetto.} Bb7 5. Bb2 Z0 ({With our bishop exerting pressure down the a1-h8 diagonal, White may now even look to try and seize an early initiative with a quick g2-g4 once Black has moved the bishop from f8. Development is also likely to be continued with Nc3, and here} 5... d5 {(Lawrence Trent's choice in his '1...b6 Against Everything' course)} 6. Nc3 {would again take play into Chapter 13 [/variation/23789995/#/6/w] in the first part of this course. That leaves: 1a: 5...Be7 (any attempts to play without ...c5) 1b: 5...c5 (any setups that involve ...c5) 1c: 2...b6 (lines without ...e6). That all just leaves one sideline for us to consider, 5...g6!? , which has been extremely rare in practice, but has twice been deployed by that highly respected theoretician Peter Wells.}) *

