1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 {This is likely to be the choice of a Nimzo and Queen's Indian player, deploying the same first two moves as they like to do against 1.d4 and 2.c4.} 3. e3 b6 ({A modest little move, but also a good choice from a practical perspective, since it may confuse opponents and will often lead to} 3... d5 4. Nc3 {, with a transposition into the Reti QGD lines ( 1.Nf3 d5 2.c4 e6 3.e3 Nf6 4.Nc3 ) covered in chapters 13 and 14 [/variation/23789994/#/4/w] of the first part of this course. With 3.e3 White keeps plenty of options open and may well still look to fianchetto the queen's bishop. Richard must even admit that back in 2006 when he wrote Beating Unusual Chess Openings, that while he considered 3.b3, 3.e3 went under the radar.}) ({Black decides to continue in Queen's Indian fashion, fianchettoing his own queen's bishop. As we've already noted, an even more popular choice in practice has been} 3... d5 4. Nc3 {with the aforementioned transposition back to the first part of this course. Instead, 3...Bb4?! would make no sense here, and after 4.a3 Bc5 White might well elect to develop with tempo and a very pleasant edge after 5.b4 Be7 6.Bb2 .}) ({That leaves} 3... c5 4. Nc3 {when} b6 5. b3 Bb7 6. Bb2 {transposes to Chapter 1b [/variation/35967285/#/6/w], while 4...d5 would be another transposition and here we advocated 5.cxd5 in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of this Reti repertoire. We should also mention 3...Be7 , which looks rather passive, but after 4.b3 O-O 5.Bb2 Black can either head via 5...d5 6.Nc3 into Chapter 14 [/variation/23790046/#/6/w] of The Modern Reti: Part One, or into Chapter 1a [/variation/35967257/#/6/b] here with 5...b6 6.Nc3 Bb7 .}) 4. b3 {White decides that imitation is the sincerest form of flattery and that it's high time to make our favourite queenside fianchetto.} Bb7 5. Bb2 g6 $5 ({With our bishop exerting pressure down the a1-h8 diagonal, White may now even look to try and seize an early initiative with a quick g2-g4 once Black has moved the bishop from f8. Development is also likely to be continued with Nc3, and here} 5... d5 {(Lawrence Trent's choice in his '1...b6 Against Everything' course)} 6. Nc3 {would again take play into Chapter 13 in the first part of this course. That leaves: 1a: 5...Be7 1b: 5...c5 1c: And in this first theoretical section, we'll also head back to move two to cover: 2...b6 . Note that chapter 1a will see Black trying to play without ...c5, chapter 1b focusses on those set-ups with ...c5 and in 1c we'll see Black trying to make do without an early ...e6. That all just leaves one sideline for us to consider, 5...g6!? , which has been extremely rare in practice, but has twice been deployed by that highly respected theoretician Peter Wells.}) 6. Nc3 {Consistent play, completing the minor piece development on the queenside and intending Be2 followed by O-O.} Bg7 7. Be2 ({Straightforward development, although if you don't mind Queen's Indian-type positions, there's also nothing wrong with the} 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3 {of Spraggett-Wells, Edmonton 2000.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O {Development is largely complete and in true Reti fashion, White has remained very flexible in the centre where we may advance with d2-d4 or prefer to first manoeuvre, such as with Qc2. We've also now reached a slightly more common position, one which can come about via a number of different move orders.} d5 9. cxd5 {Just as we often did in the first part of the course, it makes sense to exchange on d5 here, thereby giving Black a small dilemma over how best to recapture.} exd5 10. d4 {It's sensible to advance straight away here and so make Black think twice about ...c5, which White might elect to take and then increase the pressure against the hanging pawns on c5 and d5, not least with Rc1 and Na4.} Nbd7 ({White would also meet} 10... c5 {with} 11. Rc1 {, looking to quickly pressurise c5.}) 11. Rc1 {Placing the rook on a good file and now if Black plays slowly, White may complete mobilisation with Rc2, Qc1 and Rfd1, which continues to be directed against ...c5 ideas. Another more active approach would be to leap forwards with Ne5, likely followed by f2-f4 and Bf3.} c5 $5 12. dxc5 {Exchanging without delay, to ask Black a fairly big question and also open up the long dark-squared diagonal.} bxc5 ({Sergei Tiviakov once preferred} 12... Nxc5 {, taking on an IQP, when after} 13. Nb5 {and Nbd4 White should have a small but definite and pleasant edge.}) 13. Na4 $1 {Immediately pressing on the weakness. Now Rc2 may follow and then Qc1 or even Qa1 (Richard Reti's favourite square for the queen, of course) and Rfc1.} Qe7 $6 14. Bxf6 $1 ({Black was solid enough here after} 14. Ba3 Rac8 {in Stephan-Kiolbasa, Internet (blitz) 2021, but White should have been paying attention to other forcing methods to increase the pressure against c5.}) 14... Bxf6 15. Bb5 {With the simple threat of Bxd7 as Black finds that c5 is falling after all and for clearly insufficient compensation.} *

