1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 {This is likely to be the choice of a Nimzo and Queen's Indian player, deploying the same first two moves as they like to do against 1.d4 and 2.c4.} 3. e3 b6 ({A modest little move, but also a good choice from a practical perspective, since it may confuse opponents and will often lead to} 3... d5 4. Nc3 {, with a transposition into the Reti QGD lines ( 1.Nf3 d5 2.c4 e6 3.e3 Nf6 4.Nc3 ) covered in chapters 13 and 14 [/variation/23789994/#/4/w] of the first part of this course. With 3.e3 White keeps plenty of options open and may well still look to fianchetto the queen's bishop. Richard must even admit that back in 2006 when he wrote Beating Unusual Chess Openings, that while he considered 3.b3, 3.e3 went under the radar.}) ({Black decides to continue in Queen's Indian fashion, fianchettoing his own queen's bishop. As we've already noted, an even more popular choice in practice has been} 3... d5 4. Nc3 {with the aforementioned transposition back to the first part of this course. Instead, 3...Bb4?! would make no sense here, and after 4.a3 Bc5 White might well elect to develop with tempo and a very pleasant edge after 5.b4 Be7 6.Bb2 .}) ({That leaves} 3... c5 4. Nc3 {when} b6 5. b3 Bb7 6. Bb2 {transposes to Chapter 1b [/variation/35967285/#/6/w], while 4...d5 would be another transposition and here we advocated 5.cxd5 in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of this Reti repertoire. We should also mention 3...Be7 , which looks rather passive, but after 4.b3 O-O 5.Bb2 Black can either head via 5...d5 6.Nc3 into Chapter 14 [/variation/23790046/#/6/w] of The Modern Reti: Part One, or into Chapter 1a [/variation/35967257/#/6/b] here with 5...b6 6.Nc3 Bb7 .}) 4. b3 {White decides that imitation is the sincerest form of flattery and that it's high time to make our favourite queenside fianchetto.} Bb7 5. Bb2 g6 $5 ({With our bishop exerting pressure down the a1-h8 diagonal, White may now even look to try and seize an early initiative with a quick g2-g4 once Black has moved the bishop from f8. Development is also likely to be continued with Nc3, and here} 5... d5 {(Lawrence Trent's choice in his '1...b6 Against Everything' course)} 6. Nc3 {would again take play into Chapter 13 in the first part of this course. That leaves: 1a: 5...Be7 1b: 5...c5 1c: And in this first theoretical section, we'll also head back to move two to cover: 2...b6 . Note that chapter 1a will see Black trying to play without ...c5, chapter 1b focusses on those set-ups with ...c5 and in 1c we'll see Black trying to make do without an early ...e6. That all just leaves one sideline for us to consider, 5...g6!? , which has been extremely rare in practice, but has twice been deployed by that highly respected theoretician Peter Wells.}) 6. Nc3 {Consistent play, completing the minor piece development on the queenside and intending Be2 followed by O-O.} Bg7 7. Be2 ({Straightforward development, although if you don't mind Queen's Indian-type positions, there's also nothing wrong with the} 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3 {of Spraggett-Wells, Edmonton 2000.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O {Development is largely complete and in true Reti fashion, White has remained very flexible in the centre where we may advance with d2-d4 or prefer to first manoeuvre, such as with Qc2. We've also now reached a slightly more common position, one which can come about via a number of different move orders.} d5 9. cxd5 {Just as we often did in the first part of the course, it makes sense to exchange on d5 here, thereby giving Black a small dilemma over how best to recapture.} Nxd5 $5 10. Rc1 {We prepare to recapture with a piece on c3 - twice if needed - and are now all set to advance with d2-d4 if allowed.} c5 11. d4 {Played anyhow as we angle to create a target on c5.} Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Nd7 13. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 ({Seizing a small initiative as White creates the ideas of} 13... Bxc3 14. c6 Bxc6 15. Rxc3 {to recapture with tempo while activating the rook, as well as of getting in b3-b4 with tempo.}) 14. b4 $5 ({This position was, of course, very solid for Black in Adly-Sargissian, Dubai 2005, but White didn't have to go} 14. Bb4 {here.}) 14... Ne4 ({The aforementioned tempo gain, as we also hope that Black might rush to simplify and concede handy control of the d-file after} 14... Qxd1 $6 15. Rfxd1 {.}) 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qxd8 {It's also possible to retain the queens, but this way we do get a rook to the seventh.} Rfxd8 17. Rc7 ({White is all set to increase the pressure with Ne5 and Black must be quite accurate to equalise here. After} 17. Rc7 {one plausible trap could occur:} Bd5 18. Ne5 Rf8 $2 {18...Nd6 19.Ba6! This is also quite unpleasant for Black, as White takes control of c8 and prepares to roll forwards with f2-f3 and e3-e4. 19...Bxa2 20.e4! Black's bishop is in trouble, White will at least get to favourably regain his pawn after Ra1 and maybe Nc6 and, yes, the e-pawn is taboo: 20...Nxe4 21.Bb7 White is winning the exchange while maintaining very strong pressure along the seventh rank.} 19. f3 $1 {All of a sudden Black's minor pieces are embarrassed mid-board.} Nf6 20. e4 Ne8 21. Rd7 $1 {Staying on the seventh rank.} Nf6 22. Re7 {and Black's bishop will be snared on d5 or after} Bxa2 23. Ra1 Bb3 24. Ra3 {.}) *

