 a quick g2-g4 once Black has moved the bishop from f8. Development is also likely to be continued with Nc3, and here} 5... d5 {(Lawrence Trent's choice in his '1...b6 Against Everything' course)} 6. Nc3 {would again take play into Chapter 13 in the first part of this course. That leaves: 1a: 5...Be7 1b: 5...c5 1c: And in this first theoretical section, we'll also head back to move two to cover: 2...b6 . Note that chapter 1a will see Black trying to play without ...c5, chapter 1b focusses on those set-ups with ...c5 and in 1c we'll see Black trying to make do without an early ...e6. That all just leaves one sideline for us to consider, 5...g6!? , which has been extremely rare in practice, but has twice been deployed by that highly respected theoretician Peter Wells.}) 6. Nc3 {Consistent play, completing the minor piece development on the queenside and intending Be2 followed by O-O.} Bg7 7. Be2 ({Straightforward development, although if you don't mind Queen's Indian-type positions, there's also nothing wrong with the} 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3 {of Spraggett-Wells, Edmonton 2000.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O {Development is largely complete and in true Reti fashion, White has remained very flexible in the centre where we may advance with d2-d4 or prefer to first manoeuvre, such as with Qc2. We've also now reached a slightly more common position, one which can come about via a number of different move orders.} c5 ({Black decides to compete for the centre. Black can also start with} 8... Qe7 {, which will likely transpose after} 9. d4 c5 {.}) 9. d4 $1 {A critical advance. White may now look to obtain some pressure down the d-file after Qc2 and Rad1, perhaps even after first exchanging on c5 to open lines.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 $1 ({A key recapture, facilitating Bf3 while keeping the a1-h8 diagonal open, in contrast to which} 10. exd4 d5 {would be quite pleasant for Black. White is now ready to go 11.Rc1, although Bf3 can also be a good follow-up, as we’ll now see.}) 10... Nc6 11. Ndb5 $5 ({Catching up in development, but not equalising. White now made a good case for} 11. Bf3 {in Kalajzic-Averjanov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, but we suspect that White could have done even better.}) 11... Ne4 ({The simple idea is Nd6 and} 11... d5 12. Ba3 {would also conquer that square. As such, Black should probably try to simplify.}) 12. Qc1 $1 ({Forcing the pace whilst keeping the queen safe from the likes of} 12. Qc2 Nb4 {.}) 12... Nxc3 13. Bxc3 {With Black being vulnerable on the dark squares, White is quite happy to exchange those bishops.} Bxc3 14. Nxc3 $5 ({One of two tempting recaptures, since a decent case can also be made for} 14. Qxc3 d5 15. Rad1 {followed by saddling Black with an IQP. Instead, we switch the knight away from d6, but the simple plan now is Qb2 and Ne4, while 14...Qf6?! 15.Qd2 and Ne4 would conquer d6 after all.}) 14... d6 15. Rd1 {Simply threatening Ne4.} Qe7 16. Qb2 {The threat is again Ne4 and while Black should be able to cover d6, White enjoys a pretty pleasant edge. The knight may also head into b5 at an opportune moment, the rooks may be doubled on the d-file and f2-f4 in conjunction with Bf3 will also improve White's position.} *

