 a quick g2-g4 once Black has moved the bishop from f8. Development is also likely to be continued with Nc3, and here} 5... d5 {(Lawrence Trent's choice in his '1...b6 Against Everything' course)} 6. Nc3 {would again take play into Chapter 13 in the first part of this course. That leaves: 1a: 5...Be7 1b: 5...c5 1c: And in this first theoretical section, we'll also head back to move two to cover: 2...b6 . Note that chapter 1a will see Black trying to play without ...c5, chapter 1b focusses on those set-ups with ...c5 and in 1c we'll see Black trying to make do without an early ...e6. That all just leaves one sideline for us to consider, 5...g6!? , which has been extremely rare in practice, but has twice been deployed by that highly respected theoretician Peter Wells.}) 6. g4 $5 {This dynamic and slightly cheeky advance threatens to immediately win material with g4-g5.} Bg7 7. g5 ({A consistent advance, although you might wish to consider} 7. h4 $5 {too, only then intending 8.g5, and winning material in the event of} h5 $4 8. g5 {.}) 7... Nh5 8. Bxg7 Nxg7 9. h4 $5 ({Here} 9. Nc3 h6 $1 {was a little awkward for White in Li-Cardoso, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, so we would prefer to continue on the kingside.}) {Only now will White go Nc3, with Bg2 and the space-gaining d2-d4 likely to follow.} 9... h6 10. Rg1 Z0 ({Retaining the tension to the maximum and preparing to maintain the strong clamping point on g5 in the event of} 10... hxg5 11. hxg5 {. The position is pretty unclear, but White's space advantage supplies an attractive enough position, one where Nc3 and Bg2 are likely to continue development, after which Qc2 and O-O-O may follow.}) *

