1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 Be7 {Black continues to develop in solid, classical Queen's Indian fashion.} 6. Nc3 {in the first part of this course. Be2 Straightforward development and a useful move, whether White simply wants to castle next or try to make Qc2 ideas work. Re8!? O-O Against a slightly slow approach from Black, it makes good sense to house the king and then look to expand after Qc2 with d2-d4 and even e3-e4 if allowed. a6!? d4 d5 White threatens to bury the bishop on b7 with} Z0 {d5 , so here keeping the queen on d1 makes sense. cxd5 Simple chess and a frequent exchange in this repertoire. White looks to obtain a spot of pressure down the c-file after Rc1 and Qc2 and may yet expand in the centre, with a timely e3-e4 in the event of a knight recapture or by borrowing a plan from the Colle-Zukertort if Black takes back with the pawn. exd5 Ne5! White's light-squared bishop is on e2, not d3, and yet this still seems like a decent advance, looking to take advantage of Black's slightly slow play. Rc1 may follow and f2-f4 will help to secure the knight in situ on e5. Bd6 f4 c5 Of course, White would now be delighted to be gifted a free and strong kingside attack after Bxe5? fxe5 . Na4! This timely leap kept the b2-bishop very much in play while securing a pleasant edge in Larsen-Balashov, Bugojno 1978. White will increase the pressure against c5 with Rc1 and will likely improve the light-squared bishop to f3, although a decent case can be made for Bd3 and even Bh5 too.} *

