[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 Be7 {Black continues to develop in solid, classical Queen's Indian fashion.} 6. Nc3 {Our standard scheme of queenside development and a sensible choice here, whether White wants to simply complete development with Be2 and O-O or look towards more ambitious schemes involving an early g2-g4 and perhaps queenside castling.} ({We did, of course, also consider} 6. g4 $6 {, but unfortunately here} Nxg4 7. Rg1 f5 $1 8. Bxg7 Rg8 9. Bb2 Rg6 {looks like more fun for Black than White.}) 6... O-O ({Black's most common response. Instead,} 6... c5 7. g4 {and 7.Be2 will be seen in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/w], 1B, while 6...d5 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Ne2 would take play back into the realm of Chapter 14 [/variation/23790044/#/8/w] in the first part of this course.}) 7. Be2 {Straightforward development and a useful move, whether White simply wants to castle next or try to make Qc2 ideas work.} d5 ({Black heads into Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) type waters after all. His main alternative is} 7... c5 {when we'll examine} 8. O-O {in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/b].}) 8. cxd5 {Even though we can't go Ne2 here, swapping immediately makes sense to deny Black any ...dxc4 options.} exd5 {The solid, more QGD-like and classical recapture.} 9. O-O {Housing the king and White is now likely to continue with Rc1 and d2-d4.} c5 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Rc1 Re8 ({We've actually transposed to a sideline of the Queen's Indian, where Black is quite solid, but not definitely equal. White can look to increase the pressure with dxc5 or Ne5 and would most definitely welcome} 11... cxd4 $6 12. Nxd4 {with control and a very pleasant anti-IQP set-up.}) 12. Bd3 $5 ({Calmly manoeuvring (White can also go} 12. Bb5 {) to free the e2-square for a different piece.}) 12... a6 {This position was seen in Mekhitarian-Danielyan, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where White should have continued a thematic regrouping:} 13. Ne2 $1 Bd6 14. Ng3 {All of a sudden White would like to whip up a strong initiative with Nf5 followed by Ne5 or Ng5 when his knights and lurking raking bishops would be pretty well placed indeed.} g6 15. Qe2 {Aiming to tie Black down to a6. Making further progress as White in such positions is never trivial, but one plan is that of Rfe1, Ba1 and Qb2, looking to exchange on c5 and/or suddenly break with e3-e4 to exploit the pressure down the long, dark-square diagonal. Meanwhile if Black ever resets with ...Bf8, White should immediately be looking to get in Ne5, probably followed by f2-f4.} *

