1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 Be7 {Black continues to develop in solid, classical Queen's Indian fashion.} 6. Nc3 {Our standard scheme of queenside development and a sensible choice here, whether White wants to simply complete development with Be2 and O-O or look towards more ambitious schemes involving an early g2-g4 and perhaps queenside castling.} ({We did, of course, also consider} 6. g4 $6 {, but unfortunately here} Nxg4 7. Rg1 f5 $1 8. Bxg7 Rg8 9. Bb2 Rg6 {looks like more fun for Black than White.}) 6... O-O ({Black's most common response. Instead,} 6... c5 7. g4 {and 7.Be2 will be seen in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/w], 1B, while 6...d5 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Ne2 would take play back into the realm of Chapter 14 [/variation/23790044/#/8/w] in the first part of this course.}) 7. Be2 {Straightforward development and a useful move, whether White simply wants to castle next or try to make Qc2 ideas work.} d5 ({Black heads into Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) type waters after all. His main alternative is} 7... c5 {when we'll examine} 8. O-O {in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/b].}) 8. cxd5 {Even though we can't go Ne2 here, swapping immediately makes sense to deny Black any ...dxc4 options.} exd5 {The solid, more QGD-like and classical recapture.} 9. O-O {Housing the king and White is now likely to continue with Rc1 and d2-d4.} c5 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Rc1 Rc8 ({We've actually transposed to a sideline of the Queen's Indian, where Black is quite solid, but not definitely equal. White can look to increase the pressure with dxc5 or Ne5 and would most definitely welcome} 11... cxd4 $6 12. Nxd4 {with control and a very pleasant anti-IQP set-up.}) 12. Rc2 $5 ({Freeing Reti's favourite a1-square for the queen (here too} 12. Bd3 $5 {is also an option if you prefer).}) 12... a6 13. dxc5 $5 {With Black yet to slightly weaken himself on the a1-h8 diagonal, White prefers to spin the queen over to a different square, b1, in the event of a hanging pawns position now appearing.} bxc5 14. Qb1 {The queen may look a little strange here, but after Rd2 and Rfd1 her gaze towards the kingside will actually be quite a strong one.} Re8 15. Rd1 Bd6 16. Rcd2 {This unbalanced position arose in Andersson-Planinc, Banja Luka 1976, where White was actually threatening a pretty strong exchange sacrifice on d5 followed by launching a strong queenside idea, with other ways to improve the pieces Bf1 (looking to get in g2-g3 and Bg2 one day), and Qf5.} Z0 ({Let's see a few more moves of this instructive strategic encounter:} 16... d4 $2 {16...Qe7 17.Nxd5 Carrying out the aforementioned threat. 17...Nxd5 18.Rxd5 Bxd5 19.Rxd5 White already has one pawn for the exchange and threatens Bxa6 as well as just to attack - and with some power: Rg5 isn't going to be easy for Black to face and neither is Ng5, with Bc4 or Bd3 set to increase the pressure, as might Qf5.} 17. exd4 {White should accept the gift as he begins to tee up another exchange sacrifice.} Ne4 $1 {Now 18.Rc2 Nxf2! would reveal Black's big idea and just be very unclear after 19.Kxf2 cxd4 , so Andersson preferred to exchange then move the queen into the corner after all:} 18. Nxe4 $1 Bxe4 19. Qa1 Bf4 20. Rd3 {The Swedish positional maestro went on to win (surprisingly quickly in fact) after 20...c4 21.Rc3 , but what would have happened if Black had taken the exchange?} Bxd3 21. Bxd3 cxd4 22. Bxd4 {White's powerful bishop-pair and well coordinated army provides at least full compensation for the exchange and, yes, both Bxg7 and Bxa6 are threatened!}) *

