1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 Be7 {Black continues to develop in solid, classical Queen's Indian fashion.} 6. Nc3 {Our standard scheme of queenside development and a sensible choice here, whether White wants to simply complete development with Be2 and O-O or look towards more ambitious schemes involving an early g2-g4 and perhaps queenside castling.} ({We did, of course, also consider} 6. g4 $6 {, but unfortunately here} Nxg4 7. Rg1 f5 $1 8. Bxg7 Rg8 9. Bb2 Rg6 {looks like more fun for Black than White.}) 6... O-O ({Black's most common response. Instead,} 6... c5 7. g4 {and 7.Be2 will be seen in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/w], 1B, while 6...d5 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Ne2 would take play back into the realm of Chapter 14 [/variation/23790044/#/8/w] in the first part of this course.}) 7. Be2 {Straightforward development and a useful move, whether White simply wants to castle next or try to make Qc2 ideas work.} d5 ({Black heads into Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) type waters after all. His main alternative is} 7... c5 {when we'll examine} 8. O-O {in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/b].}) 8. cxd5 {Even though we can't go Ne2 here, swapping immediately makes sense to deny Black any ...dxc4 options.} Nxd5 $5 {The more dynamic of the two recaptures available to Black, who doesn't really want to part with the bishop-pair at such an early stage.} 9. O-O {White keeps everything solid at the back and will now likely follow up with Rc1 and d2-d4.} c5 10. d4 {Raising the issue of an exchange on c5 is usually the only way to cause Black any real problems in such positions.} Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Bf6 12. Rc1 Nd7 ({Black was pretty solid here, but we'd slightly prefer to take White here, since dxc5 is on the cards and} 12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 {followed by Bf3 will begin to exert a bit of pressure.}) 13. dxc5 {The simple approach in what may be a familiar looking position (we cover something very similar in the 5...g6 lines), either intending to throw in c5-c6 as a tempo-gaining zwischenzug or liquidating to a fractionally better endgame.} ({If, though, you'd prefer to retain the tension, then} 13. b4 $5 {should be considered.}) 13... Nxc5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Rfd1 {White has a small structural advantage, will look to gradually probe after Nd4 (possibly heading for b5, possibly followed by Bf3 or f2-f3), and he eventually ground out the win in Harvey-A.Moskalenko, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2017.} *

