1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 Be7 {Black continues to develop in solid, classical Queen's Indian fashion.} 6. Nc3 {Our standard scheme of queenside development and a sensible choice here, whether White wants to simply complete development with Be2 and O-O or look towards more ambitious schemes involving an early g2-g4 and perhaps queenside castling.} ({We did, of course, also consider} 6. g4 $6 {, but unfortunately here} Nxg4 7. Rg1 f5 $1 8. Bxg7 Rg8 9. Bb2 Rg6 {looks like more fun for Black than White.}) 6... O-O ({Black's most common response. Instead,} 6... c5 7. g4 {and 7.Be2 will be seen in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/w], 1B, while 6...d5 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Ne2 would take play back into the realm of Chapter 14 [/variation/23790044/#/8/w] in the first part of this course.}) 7. Be2 {Straightforward development and a useful move, whether White simply wants to castle next or try to make Qc2 ideas work.} d5 ({Black heads into Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) type waters after all. His main alternative is} 7... c5 {when we'll examine} 8. O-O {in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/b].}) 8. cxd5 {Even though we can't go Ne2 here, swapping immediately makes sense to deny Black any ...dxc4 options.} Nxd5 $5 {The more dynamic of the two recaptures available to Black, who doesn't really want to part with the bishop-pair at such an early stage.} 9. Qc2 $5 {) The aggressive choice. White facilitates long castling while looking to quickly target h7 with h2-h4 and Ng5.} ({Dmitrij Kollars's} 9. Qb1 $5 {also makes some sense, after which} a6 $6 10. h4 Nc6 $2 11. Ng5 {was already extremely dangerous for Black in Kollars-Sakorenko, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020.}) 9... Nb4 10. Qb1 {Naturally White must retain control of d3 and can now look to kick the knight back with a2-a3.} Ba6 11. Bxa6 {Dragging one of Black's knights to the rim ahead of advancing in the centre with d2-d4.} N8xa6 12. d4 c5 13. O-O {White has retained control of d3 and should have any pull that is going in a position not dissimilar to a Catalan, if, of course, without the light-squared bishops. White will meet any capture on d4 with Nxd4 and definitely wants to go Rd1, after which a2-a3 may follow and the queen would ideally like to zoom into play, if allowed, via e4 and g4.} *

