1. Ng5 $6 {with} Bxg5 $1 12. hxg5 Qxg5 {, but now that idea is back on the agenda since White would have Rg3 at the end. The way is also now clear for g2-g4, with White likely to find his king safer after Rd1 and Kf1 than after O-O-O, which would allow Black to aim for a counterattack on the queenside. This fascinating position is in need of tests and both your authors would enjoy testing it on the white side!}) {For now, we should just demonstrate why Black must be very careful about any capture on g5:} 11... Nd7 12. Ng5 $1 hxg5 ({Threatening mate, and now} 12... Bxg5 $6 13. hxg5 Qxg5 14. Nxd5 {would be game over after} Bxd5 15. Rg3 {or 14...Qxd5 15.Bf3 .}) 13. hxg5 f5 {A fairly forced advance, if one White is ready for.} 14. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 ({This powerful exchange is the point of White's play and now} 14... exd5 $2 15. Qc3 {, and if} d4 16. Qc4+ Rf7 17. g6 {would be fairly embarrassing for Black.}) 15. Qc3 Rf7 ({White continues to threaten mate and is also now all set to go long. Indeed,} 15... Nf6 {would be well met by} 16. O-O-O {as there's no rush to take on f6 here, with Rdh1 on the way, as well as such ideas as g2-g4 and g5-g6.}) 16. Bh5 {Keeping up the threats, and already the engines think that Black is pretty much down to an only move to avoid accepting a major disadvantage.} e5 $1 17. f4 $1 {White remains determined not to let Black settle, as well as to retain that useful bridgehead on g5. Everything is now set for O-O-O and Rdh1 or Kf2 and Rah1, with Qc2 a nifty little idea to also be aware of, causing Black serious issues on the light squares or back on the long diagonal, and kingside after ...e4 Qc3.} *

