{A) 18...Nd3+ In practice, many opponents would likely be tempted to head straight for an opposite-coloured bishop scenario so. 19.Bxd3 Bxd3 20.c4 There are opposite bishops present, but Black must actually be quite careful, since Rd1 could lead to problems on the d-file and White also has quite useful and quick ideas in both e3-e4 and Be5. B) 18...Bd3! 19.Bd1!? Trying to retain more pieces than 19.Rd1 Rd5 would, and now White would quite like to edge forwards with Ba3 or c3-c4 followed by Bc3 or Bd4. 19...Bg6 20.Bc2 Declining a possible repetition with 20.Be2 Bd3 and again not fearing an opposite-coloured bishop scenario. 20...Bxc2 20...Nd3+ 21.Bxd3 Rxd3 22.e4 This rook and bishop endgame should be a draw, but White will get in c3-c4 and Kc2 and can hope to make something of either the cramping pawn on g5 or better bishop, as after Be5 or a2-a4-a5 and Ra1. 21.Kxc2 Rd5 22.Rd1 , Sensibly challenging for the open file and hoping to gradually, Carlsen style, exploit the superior minor piece. There's also a fascinating alternative here in 22.b4!? Na4 23.c4 Rxg5 24.Bc1 Suddenly the position is most unbalanced and White ready for both g2-g4 and Kb3. 24...Rxg2+ 25.Kb3 b5 26.cxb5 Nb6 27.a4 Talk about quickly unbalancing the position! The engines still think that Black can hold, but with White's queenside play so fast -- 28.a5 Nd5 29.e4 and then Be3 is the main idea, Bb2-d4 another, it doesn't look like it should be so easy to defend in practice.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 Be7 {Black continues to develop in solid, classical Queen's Indian fashion.} 6. Nc3 {Our standard scheme of queenside development and a sensible choice here, whether White wants to simply complete development with Be2 and O-O or look towards more ambitious schemes involving an early g2-g4 and perhaps queenside castling.} ({We did, of course, also consider} 6. g4 $6 {, but unfortunately here} Nxg4 7. Rg1 f5 $1 8. Bxg7 Rg8 9. Bb2 Rg6 {looks like more fun for Black than White.}) 6... O-O ({Black's most common response. Instead,} 6... c5 7. g4 {and 7.Be2 will be seen in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/w], 1B, while 6...d5 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Ne2 would take play back into the realm of Chapter 14 [/variation/23790044/#/8/w] in the first part of this course.}) 7. Be2 {Straightforward development and a useful move, whether White simply wants to castle next or try to make Qc2 ideas work.} d5 ({Black heads into Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) type waters after all. His main alternative is} 7... c5 {when we'll examine} 8. O-O {in our next section [/variation/35967288/#/7/b].}) 8. cxd5 {Even though we can't go Ne2 here, swapping immediately makes sense to deny Black any ...dxc4 options.} Nxd5 $5 {The more dynamic of the two recaptures available to Black, who doesn't really want to part with the bishop-pair at such an early stage.} 9. Qc2 $5 {The aggressive choice. White facilitates long castling while looking to quickly target h7 with h2-h4 and Ng5.} ({Dmitrij Kollars's} 9. Qb1 $5 {also makes some sense, after which} a6 $6 10. h4 Nc6 $2 11. Ng5 {was already extremely dangerous for Black in Kollars-Sakorenko, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020.}) 9... Nxc3 10. dxc3 $5 {Arguably the most dynamic recapture as White reveals that he'd still quite like to get h2-h4 then Ng5 in.} Nd7 11. O-O-O {A consistently aggressive choice as White pins the knight on d7 and thereby keeps the idea of h2-h4 and Ng5 high on the agenda.} Qc8 {Sensibly unpinning, although the queen now finds herself further from the defence of the kingside.} 12. h4 $1 Nc5 $1 ({The position is once again fascinating and pretty unclear, but with White the side attacking and even able to meet} 12... h6 {with} 13. Ng5 $1 {, we'd prefer to be in his shoes.}) 13. Ng5 ({Instead,} 13. Rd4 $6 f5 $1 {saw Black shutting down lines ahead of beginning to take over in Pruijssers-L'Ami, Dutch Championship, Utrecht 2023, where White should have stuck to plan A.}) (13. Ng5 {threatens mate. Now after} f5 14. f3 {White would look to go c3-c4 then perhaps g2-g4 or Nh3-f4, depending on how Black sets up. Erwin L'Ami though may well have intended the other method of covering h7.}) 13... Bxg5 $5 14. hxg5 Be4 ({Fairly forced or at least} 14... f5 $2 15. f3 $1 {doesn't look wise with White bearing down on h7.}) 15. Qd2 {Another fairly forced move, and now White would quite like to go f2-f3 followed by e3-e4 and/or c3-c4.} Rd8 $1 16. Qxd8+ $1 ({Black angles to invade on d3 after} 16. Qe1 $2 Rxd1+ $1 17. Qxd1 Qf8 {and ...Rd8.}) {White must head for the resulting unbalanced ending.} 16... Qxd8 17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. f3 {White continues to challenge the bishop on e4 and would now like again to expand with c3-c4 and/or e3-e4. Another important idea is that of retaining the bishop-pair for now with ( 18...Bd3 19.Bd1 . The endgame is, of course, most likely a draw with best play, but White can certainly hope to obtain a nibble and press. For example:} Z0 *

