1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Nc6 $5 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) 7. Be2 ({This was once used by Karpov to draw with Korchnoi (Brussels, 1986), where White went} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {, which is a sensible approach if you have some experience of such English Opening structures, but is not, of course, the only option.}) ({White continues in sensible vein (} 7. g4 $6 Nxg4 {and}) (7. Qc2 d5 {are somewhat less appealing) and now 7...Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.d4 will be analysed via a 6...Be7 7.Be2 Nc6 8.O-O O-O 9.d4 move order - see here.}) 7... d5 $5 8. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 ({As ever, a well-timed exchange before Black can get ...d4 in and White would now enjoy a pleasant enough anti-Tarrasch-type set-up after} 8... exd5 9. d4 {.}) {This position has been extremely rare and when it has occurred, White has tended to castle, but it's also possible to ask an early question of Black.} 9. Nxd5 $5 Qxd5 $1 10. Qb1 $5 O-O-O $5 ({Here rather than c2 to avoid being hit by ...Nb4, and now} 10... Be7 $2 11. Bxg7 Rg8 12. Qxh7 {would not be good news for Black. Meanwhile White is all set to castle and then introduce some central play after Rd1.}) 11. h3 $5 ({A small prophylactic step to avoid the complexity of} 11. O-O Bd6 $5 {, although we doubt that many Queen's Indian players will feel too at home with Black's very aggressive set-up here. White is now ready to go O-O when ...Qh5 ideas should be less scary and after castling White can go Rd1 and d2-d4 (just don't recapture with the knight on d4!), or even Rc1, a2-a3 and b3-b4, angling to attack on the queenside. Meanwhile ...Bd6 is no longer to be feared:}) 11... Bd6 $6 12. Bxg7 Rhg8 13. Bc4 $1 ({Forcing the pace so is somewhat clearer than the greedy} 13. Qxh7 Be5 $1 {.}) 13... Qh5 14. g4 $1 {An only move, but a strong one, since there's only one square for the queen, which White can then exchange.} Qg6 15. Qxg6 hxg6 16. Bf6 {With tempo, and now Ke2 may simply follow to shore up the knight on f3. Black only has one scary-looking response, and it's one White should welcome, not fear.} Ne5 $6 17. Nxe5 $1 Bxe5 18. Bxe5 Bxh1 19. Bf6 Z0 ({Here the engines want to immediately return the exchange as Black and then grovel. Why? Well, quite simply the bishop on f6 is a monster and after} 19... Z0 20. f4 {followed by Ke2 that h-pawn is a major asset while White's bishops can also and easily continue to harass Black's rook on d7 or d6.}) *

