1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Nc6 $5 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) 7. Be2 ({This was once used by Karpov to draw with Korchnoi (Brussels, 1986), where White went} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {, which is a sensible approach if you have some experience of such English Opening structures, but is not, of course, the only option.}) ({White continues in sensible vein (} 7. g4 $6 Nxg4 {and}) (7. Qc2 d5 {are somewhat less appealing) and now 7...Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.d4 will be analysed via a 6...Be7 7.Be2 Nc6 8.O-O O-O 9.d4 move order - see here.}) 7... d5 $5 8. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 ({As ever, a well-timed exchange before Black can get ...d4 in and White would now enjoy a pleasant enough anti-Tarrasch-type set-up after} 8... exd5 9. d4 {.}) {This position has been extremely rare and when it has occurred, White has tended to castle, but it's also possible to ask an early question of Black.} 9. Nxd5 $5 exd5 $2 10. O-O ({Somewhat stronger than} 10. d4 {, as White makes it hard for Black to deploy his remaining bishop which is currently tied to the defence of g7. 10...f6 11.d4 would now be very pleasant for White, but much better that for Black than any the other attempt to block the long diagonal.}) 10... d4 $2 11. exd4 cxd4 $6 12. Bb5 {This is the problem: both the d4-pawn and the king are already very serious concerns for Black.} Bc5 13. b4 $1 {Not only hitting the bishop with tempo, but making Qa4 an idea.} Bxb4 14. Nxd4 Z0 ({White is already winning. Not only are we threatening to win a piece on c6, but} 14... Z0 15. Re1+ Kf8 16. Qg4 {will overload the defence which will be unable to cover both g7 and the bishop on b4.}) *

