1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 d6 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) 7. Be2 ({This can be played with an aggressive or modest follow-up in mind, although here} 7. d4 $5 {is also quite tempting, threatening to block out the b7-bishop with d4-d5 and so likely forcing Black, to avoid accepting a definite disadvantage, into losing a tempo with} cxd4 8. exd4 d5 {.}) 7... Be7 8. g4 $5 ({This echoes 6...Be7 7.g4, but for more positional souls there's absolutely nothing wrong here with} 8. O-O {when we'll consider} O-O 9. d4 {via a 6...Be7 7.Be2 O-O 8.O-O d6 9.d4 move order - see the next line [/variation/35967288/#/9/w]. With the text, White simply wants to blast ahead with 9.g5 followed by seizing an early initiative and very useful space advantage with h2-h4.}) 8... O-O ({Castling into it, but also a more critical line than} 8... Nxg4 $6 9. Rg1 Nf6 {(or 9...f5 10.h3 )} 10. Rxg7 {followed by Qc2 and O-O-O would be.}) 9. g5 Ne4 10. Nxe4 {It makes sense to drag Black's bishop into the middle of the board before hurling the h-pawn forwards.} Bxe4 11. h4 {This fun position will one day be tested over the board. Objectively things are far from clear, but with Rg1 and at some stage d2-d3 high on the agenda, we would quite like to test White's position which is brimming with aggressive potential. Not only is h4-h5 one idea, but there's also Nh2-g4, freeing the f-pawn to advance while looking to get in Nf6+ or even Nh6+, thereby making full use of the fine bishop on b2, as well as the rook on g1.} *

