1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Be7 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) {A sensible choice, if not forced and on the odd occasion, Black prefers something different.} 7. g4 $5 {) Simon's favourite advance, wasting no time trying to open the position and disturb Black's pieces with g4-g5. Of the four OTB games we could find from this position, Black has struggled to deal with the early initiative, White scoring three wins and a draw.} Nxg4 $6 8. Rg1 {White will now favourably regain the pawn on g7 and while retaining the initiative.} h5 $5 9. h3 {Forcing the knight to retreat after all.} Nh6 10. Rxg7 Bf6 11. Rg1 {There isn't a better square for the rook, but White should be quite happy here, since he has two fairly strong and not unconnected plans: taking over the centre with d4-d5 and housing the king with Qe2 and O-O-O, a policy which may even be prefaced by Bd3, especially if Black has gone ...Nf5.} *

