1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Be7 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) {A sensible choice, if not forced and on the odd occasion, Black prefers something different.} 7. g4 $5 {Simon's favourite advance, wasting no time trying to open the position and disturb Black's pieces with g4-g5. Of the four OTB games we could find from this position, Black has struggled to deal with the early initiative, White scoring three wins and a draw.} h6 8. Rg1 {Supporting the g-pawn so and thereby intending h2-h4 followed by g4-g5 is definitely the best policy here and in practice Black is yet to try a critical counterstrike.} d5 $5 9. h4 $5 ({Continuing to insist on g4-g5. There's nothing wrong with} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. d4 {, but this is a rare position where we're not overly concerned by ...d5-d4.}) 9... d4 10. exd4 {An important exchange, so that White's next move comes with tempo.} cxd4 11. Nb5 Nc6 ({Of course, 12.Nbxd4 is now a threat and} 11... d3 {fairly well met by} 12. Nbd4 {after all.}) 12. Bg2 $1 e5 ({Development appears more challenging than swiping the d-pawn and allowing Black a fair amount of counter-activity. Now Nfxd4 is threatened,} 12... Nb4 {can be dealt with simply enough by} 13. d3 {and White is also encouraging Black to advance the e-pawn.}) 13. Nxe5 $1 {Forcing favourable liquidation.} Nxe5 14. Bxb7 Nd3+ 15. Kf1 {Clearly the safer of the squares available to the king.} Nxb2 16. Qf3 $1 {The dust is settling with Black currently a piece up, but also in trouble. For a start, his knight is trapped on b2 and White also threatens both Bxa8 and g4-g5, the latter likely to quickly leave Black feeling the heat on the kingside and the light squares.} *

