1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Be7 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) {A sensible choice, if not forced and on the odd occasion, Black prefers something different.} 7. g4 $5 {Simon's favourite advance, wasting no time trying to open the position and disturb Black's pieces with g4-g5. Of the four OTB games we could find from this position, Black has struggled to deal with the early initiative, White scoring three wins and a draw.} d6 8. g5 ({Here White settled for} 8. Rg1 {in Paunovic-Peric, Kragujevac 2016, but there was no good reason not to be consistent and advance.}) 8... Nfd7 ({Now} 8... Ne4 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Bxg7 {must be quite pleasant for White, as would be}) (8... Nh5 9. Rg1 {, leaving the knight stuck on the rim.}) 9. Rg1 {White menaces not only h2-h4-h5, but problematic expansion for Black to deal with in the shape of d2-d4.} Ne5 $5 10. Nxe5 ({An understandable bid for freedom, but White should now be slightly better after} 10. Be2 {or something more aggressive.}) 10... dxe5 11. h4 {White now intends to borrow an idea from the Keres Attack in Qh5. He will then be able to castle long and also intends to force Black to weaken with ...g6, after which Qg4 and then Ne4 and h4-h5 will begin to target the resulting weaknesses.} *

