1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Be7 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) {A sensible choice, if not forced and on the odd occasion, Black prefers something different.} 7. g4 $5 {Simon's favourite advance, wasting no time trying to open the position and disturb Black's pieces with g4-g5. Of the four OTB games we could find from this position, Black has struggled to deal with the early initiative, White scoring three wins and a draw.} O-O {Bravely castling into it, but also quite a critical choice, as well as one which threatens simply to take on g4.} 8. g5 {) Naturally White proceeds full steam ahead, and would love to enjoy early attacking chances after getting in Rg1 and h2-h4.} Ne4 9. Nxe4 {Continuing to force the pace and thereby avoid any potentially annoying exchange on c3.} Bxe4 10. d3 ({Challenging the bishop without delay improves over the} 10. Rg1 Nc6 {of the annotated game Williams-Vaibhav [/variation/35967898/#/10/w], Douglas 2018, although that is still a pretty instructive encounter and one we would suggest that you take a look at.}) 10... Bb7 {Keeping c6 free for the knight, while not allowing the bishop to become a target for White's pawns as would be the case were it to retreat to the kingside.} 11. h4 $1 {White may now complete development with Bg2, Qe2 and O-O-O. Our favourite dark-squared Reti bishop is certainly well placed on b2, with another possible plan that of Nh2-g4 (or even Ne5, if allowed, then Ng4), looking to land the knight on f6 or h6.} Nc6 12. Bg2 d5 13. Qe2 {The position isn't totally clear, but White should be fairly happy. The king can go to c1 or even f1 if that looks safer, while if Black moves the queen then h4-h5 will definitely be possible and that advance may well also be possible as a pawn sacrifice. Meanwhile White can also regroup and expand with Nh2 followed by Ng4 and f2-f4.} *

