1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Be7 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) {A sensible choice, if not forced and on the odd occasion, Black prefers something different.} 7. Be2 {Straightforward development as White prepares to castle and doesn't rush with the d2-d4 break. This line isn't especially topical, but was used by such strategic greats as Andersson, Lombardy and Keene back in the day, and is still a decent, sensible route into the game.} O-O 8. O-O {Development is almost complete and only now will White break in the centre with d2-d4.} d6 ({Note that} 8... d5 9. cxd5 {will transpose back to chapter 1a, either here [/variation/35967258/#/9/b] after} exd5 {or here [/variation/35967262/#/9/b] after 9...Nxd5 .}) 9. d4 {This is especially well-timed when any ...d5 from Black in response would cost a tempo.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 $1 ({An important way to recapture, in contrast to which} 10. exd4 d5 $1 {is still OK for Black. Now White will be able to challenge Black's more active bishop with Bf3 and may also be able to target d6 one day with a timely knight leap to b5.}) 10... a6 11. Bf3 ({Consistent and now Black must take care over the c6-square, where White would love to install a knight, although it's also possible to first expand with} 11. f4 $5 {.}) 11... Ra7 $5 12. Rc1 d5 $2 ({The queen's rook isn't going to find a better square and now} 12... Nbd7 $6 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. Nc6 {would be a bit awkward for Black.}) ({Clearly} 12... b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Ndxb5 {would just win a pawn and this alternative break isn't much better. Don't forget about the importance of the c6-square!}) 13. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Trying not to concede a bishop or allow White a huge initiative after} 13... exd5 $2 14. Nf5 {.}) 14. Nxd5 ({One of two pretty strong options, the other being} 14. Bxd5 $5 Bxd5 {. Now 15...exd5 16.Nf5 would again leave Black under heavy pressure, so he would be likely to prefer recapturing with a piece.}) 14... Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Qxd5 16. Nc6 Qxd1 ({The point of White's play, forcing a favourable transition, whether after} 16... Nxc6 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. Rxc6 {or the other queen exchange.}) 17. Nxe7+ $1 {A key zwischenzug.} Rxe7 18. Rfxd1 {White threatens Ba3, has the superior and more active minor piece, and threatens to invade either with Rd6 or down the c-file in the event of a rook exchange.} *

