1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Be7 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) {A sensible choice, if not forced and on the odd occasion, Black prefers something different.} 7. Be2 {Straightforward development as White prepares to castle and doesn't rush with the d2-d4 break. This line isn't especially topical, but was used by such strategic greats as Andersson, Lombardy and Keene back in the day, and is still a decent, sensible route into the game.} O-O 8. O-O {Development is almost complete and only now will White break in the centre with d2-d4.} Nc6 ({Note that} 8... d5 9. cxd5 {will transpose back to chapter 1a, either here [/variation/35967258/#/9/b] after} exd5 {or here [/variation/35967262/#/9/b] after 9...Nxd5 .}) ({Instead,} 8... d5 $5 {is a critical choice, although not all Queen's Indian players will feel so comfortable in more QGD waters or with the emergence of some central tension. Our standard response is} 9. cxd5 {, looking only to counter with d2-d4 once Black has a pawn on d5.} exd5 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Rc1 {White has ideas of both Ne5 and dxc5 and we examined this sideline of the Queen's Indian by transposition in Chapter 1a [/variation/35967258/#/11/w]. , while 9...Nxd5!? 10.d4 prepares to pose a few early questions with an exchange on c5, as we also saw by transposition in Chapter 1a [/variation/35967262/#/10/w].}) 9. d4 cxd4 ({A thematic advance, here threatening to cause Black early problems with d4-d5 followed by e3-e4 and again White would now meet} 9... d5 {with} 10. cxd5 {when} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. dxc5 {should lead to a small pull.}) 10. Nxd4 $1 ({As ever, the more challenging recapture compared to} 10. exd4 d5 $1 {. Now after 10.Nxd4, Bf3 may follow and here Black has often elected to rule out ideas of Ndb5 ahead of placing the queen on c7.}) 10... Qb8 $5 11. Bf3 Rc8 ({White would now be quite happy to meet} 11... Nxd4 {with an exchange on b7. After} 12. Bxb7 Qxb7 {and the recapture} 13. Qxd4 {, White is also set to improve the rooks with Rc1 and possibly even Re1 while waiting to see how Black will attempt to untangle.}) 12. Rc1 Ne5 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. f4 $5 ({This was all very logical from both sides in Costa-Gheorghiu, Swiss League 1998, where White settled for} 14. Qe2 {and it was also possible to be a little more ambitious.}) 14... Nc6 ({Now} 14... Ng6 15. Qe2 {and especially}) (14... Neg4 $6 15. Qe2 {then h2-h3 and perhaps even g2-g4 would leave the black knight a little out of play.}) 15. Qf3 Z0 ({Pinning the knight while preparing either to exchange on c6 then advance with e3-e4 or even keep pieces on and Black slightly bottled up with} 15... Z0 16. Nde2 $5 {, followed by e3-e4 or even g2-g4-g5. Meanwhile any break out with ...d5 will be met by exchanges on c6 then d5, saddling Black with an IQP.}) *

