1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 ({Black might, of course, also begin with} 3... c5 {when} 4. Nc3 {is the move order to remember ( 4.b3 d5 would see White being move ordered). The point is that 4...d5 5.cxd5 then keeps us within the repertoire proposed in Chapter 13 [/variation/23789996/#/5/w] of the first part of the course. Instead, 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 transposes back to this section, while we'll see 4...Nc6 via a 2...c5 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.e3 e6 move order in Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/4/b].}) 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 c5 ({Everything is set for Nc3 and we'll now see what happens when Black elects to challenge in the centre, not with} 5... d5 6. Nc3 {and a transposition back to the QGD lines [/variation/23789995/#/6/w], but by deploying the d-pawn.}) 6. Nc3 Be7 ({White is once again ready for} 6... d5 {when} 7. cxd5 {would follow, so here Black has tended to get on with completing kingside development.}) {A sensible choice, if not forced and on the odd occasion, Black prefers something different.} 7. Be2 {Straightforward development as White prepares to castle and doesn't rush with the d2-d4 break. This line isn't especially topical, but was used by such strategic greats as Andersson, Lombardy and Keene back in the day, and is still a decent, sensible route into the game.} O-O 8. O-O {Development is almost complete and only now will White break in the centre with d2-d4.} Nc6 ({Note that} 8... d5 9. cxd5 {will transpose back to chapter 1a, either here [/variation/35967258/#/9/b] after} exd5 {or here [/variation/35967262/#/9/b] after 9...Nxd5 .}) ({Instead,} 8... d5 $5 {is a critical choice, although not all Queen's Indian players will feel so comfortable in more QGD waters or with the emergence of some central tension. Our standard response is} 9. cxd5 {, looking only to counter with d2-d4 once Black has a pawn on d5.} exd5 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Rc1 {White has ideas of both Ne5 and dxc5 and we examined this sideline of the Queen's Indian by transposition in Chapter 1a [/variation/35967258/#/11/w]. , while 9...Nxd5!? 10.d4 prepares to pose a few early questions with an exchange on c5, as we also saw by transposition in Chapter 1a [/variation/35967262/#/10/w].}) 9. d4 cxd4 ({A thematic advance, here threatening to cause Black early problems with d4-d5 followed by e3-e4 and again White would now meet} 9... d5 {with} 10. cxd5 {when} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. dxc5 {should lead to a small pull.}) 10. Nxd4 $1 ({As ever, the more challenging recapture compared to} 10. exd4 d5 $1 {. Now after 10.Nxd4, Bf3 may follow and here Black has often elected to rule out ideas of Ndb5 ahead of placing the queen on c7.}) 10... a6 11. Rc1 {Deploying the rook to its best square ahead of going Bf3 if Black now elects to maintain the tension.} Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Bc5 ({Our preferred recapture, and now} 12... d5 $6 13. Na4 {is surprisingly awkward for Black, but what about if the queen is kicked before White has had time for Na4 or just Rfd1?}) 13. Qf4 {Rarely a bad square for the white queen in the Hedgehog, keeping an eye on the hole on d6, one Black is reluctant to now place a pawn on with his dark-squared bishop having advanced. Meanwhile White is all set to increase the pressure with Na4 or simply Rfd1 and Bf3.} Bc6 14. Rfd1 Qb8 $5 ({Here the} 14... Qc8 $2 {of Grabow-Lochte, Gibraltar 2015, should have been punished by} 15. Nd5 {with a serious initiative and advantage.}) 15. Qh4 ({White begins to probe on the kingside (} 15. Qxb8 Raxb8 16. Bf3 {would be a decent, positional alternative), possibly even looking for -- 16.Bf3 Bxf3 17.gxf3 then using the g-file, or simply 16.Bd3 threatening to crash through with -- 17.Nd5 .}) *

