35967258/#/11/w]. , while 9...Nxd5!? 10.d4 prepares to pose a few early questions with an exchange on c5, as we also saw by transposition in Chapter 1a [/variation/35967262/#/10/w].}) 9. d4 cxd4 ({A thematic advance, here threatening to cause Black early problems with d4-d5 followed by e3-e4 and again White would now meet} 9... d5 {with} 10. cxd5 {when} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. dxc5 {should lead to a small pull.}) 10. Nxd4 $1 ({As ever, the more challenging recapture compared to} 10. exd4 d5 $1 {. Now after 10.Nxd4, Bf3 may follow and here Black has often elected to rule out ideas of Ndb5 ahead of placing the queen on c7.}) 10... a6 11. Rc1 {Deploying the rook to its best square ahead of going Bf3 if Black now elects to maintain the tension.} Rc8 12. Bf3 Qc7 $6 ({And here Black might also fall into a well-known Hedgehog mechanism: This pinned to leave White with a small plus in Barle-Shipov, Ljubljana 1992, Black is, of course, very solid, but after} 12... d6 {White should be able to obtain a bit of pressure with} 13. Ne4 $5 {, with the restrictive 13.Nde2!? followed by Ng3 and continuing to fight against the ...b5 and ...d5 another possibility.}) 13. Nd5 $1 {Ouch. The queen should now scurry back to d8 when White will collect the bishop-pair on e7, since accepting the offer is somewhat more of a concession.} exd5 $2 14. cxd5 {White will regain the piece on c6 and is all set to exert some awkward pressure on the dark squares after Nf5.} *

