1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 $5 {This isn't especially common at club level, but is far from a bad way for the Queen's Indian player to look to counter the Reti and has been used by the likes of Carlsen and Rapport of late.} 3. e3 ({Our standard approach. White can also go} 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. e3 {and only then fianchetto, while fans of an early imbalance may wish to consider a 3.b3 Bb7 4.Bb2!? move order. This tempts Black into exchanging on f3, while preparing to meet 4...g6 with 5.Bxf6 exf6 6.e3 when it's Black who has the doubled f-pawns and with Karpov-Browne (San Antonio, 1972) still a model game for White in such structures in general.}) 3... Bb7 4. b3 c5 ({Only now, with} 4... Bxf3 $6 5. Qxf3 {clearly not to be feared, do we fianchetto. Many Queen's Indian players will now transpose into Chapter 1a or 1b after}) (4... e6 5. Bb2 {, but on occasion fairly strong players have been known to prefer a more ambitious double fianchetto.}) 5. Bb2 d5 $5 ({Here too a Hedgehog and Queen's Indian player, especially at club level, is likely to go} 5... e6 {, but ambitious souls may again prefer something else.}) 6. cxd5 {Exchanging as White aims to open lines and secure an early initiative in what has been a pretty rare position in practice.} Qxd5 $5 7. Nc3 {With tempo and White also has designs on exploiting the b5-square. He would quite like to develop an early initiative with 8.Bb5+ then d2-d4, but may also use that square for a knight.} Qh5 $2 8. Nb5 $1 Na6 {How else to cover c7, but now White has a strong gambit continuation available.} 9. b4 $1 {With Qa4 on the way, Black is simply in all manner of trouble.} e6 10. Qa4 Nd7 11. Be2 {Now Ne5 is the big idea as Black remains firmly under the cosh (and at almost '-3' in engine speak).} *

