1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 $5 {This isn't especially common at club level, but is far from a bad way for the Queen's Indian player to look to counter the Reti and has been used by the likes of Carlsen and Rapport of late.} 3. e3 ({Our standard approach. White can also go} 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. e3 {and only then fianchetto, while fans of an early imbalance may wish to consider a 3.b3 Bb7 4.Bb2!? move order. This tempts Black into exchanging on f3, while preparing to meet 4...g6 with 5.Bxf6 exf6 6.e3 when it's Black who has the doubled f-pawns and with Karpov-Browne (San Antonio, 1972) still a model game for White in such structures in general.}) 3... Bb7 4. b3 c5 ({Only now, with} 4... Bxf3 $6 5. Qxf3 {clearly not to be feared, do we fianchetto. Many Queen's Indian players will now transpose into Chapter 1a or 1b after}) (4... e6 5. Bb2 {, but on occasion fairly strong players have been known to prefer a more ambitious double fianchetto.}) 5. Bb2 d5 $5 ({Here too a Hedgehog and Queen's Indian player, especially at club level, is likely to go} 5... e6 {, but ambitious souls may again prefer something else.}) 6. cxd5 {Exchanging as White aims to open lines and secure an early initiative in what has been a pretty rare position in practice.} Nxd5 7. d4 e6 $1 ({With the dangerous ideas of Ne5 and/or Bb5+ high on the agenda, Black clearly must take care and} 7... a6 $6 8. dxc5 bxc5 9. Be2 {followed by O-O and Nbd2 would just be a very pleasant edge for White.}) 8. Bb5+ $1 {Developing rapidly, with White already ready to castle and still also with the useful ideas of a timely Ne5 or dxc5.} Bc6 9. Bxc6+ ({Simple chess, although it's also possible to keep pieces on with} 9. Bc4 $5 {.}) 9... Nxc6 10. O-O Z0 ({With g2 now secure, White holds a small but pleasant edge and is all set to go} 10... Z0 11. dxc5 {, and if} Bxc5 12. Bxg7 {, while 10...cxd4 11.Nxd4 will also help to keep up the early pressure on Black.}) *

