1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 $5 {This isn't especially common at club level, but is far from a bad way for the Queen's Indian player to look to counter the Reti and has been used by the likes of Carlsen and Rapport of late.} 3. e3 ({Our standard approach. White can also go} 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. e3 {and only then fianchetto, while fans of an early imbalance may wish to consider a 3.b3 Bb7 4.Bb2!? move order. This tempts Black into exchanging on f3, while preparing to meet 4...g6 with 5.Bxf6 exf6 6.e3 when it's Black who has the doubled f-pawns and with Karpov-Browne (San Antonio, 1972) still a model game for White in such structures in general.}) 3... Bb7 4. b3 c5 ({Only now, with} 4... Bxf3 $6 5. Qxf3 {clearly not to be feared, do we fianchetto. Many Queen's Indian players will now transpose into Chapter 1a or 1b after}) (4... e6 5. Bb2 {, but on occasion fairly strong players have been known to prefer a more ambitious double fianchetto.}) 5. Bb2 g6 ({Here too a Hedgehog and Queen's Indian player, especially at club level, is likely to go} 5... e6 {, but ambitious souls may again prefer something else.}) 6. Bxf6 $5 ({Inflicting structural ruin ahead of clamping down on the d5-square is a good alternative to} 6. Be2 {and a transposition to our mainline here [/variation/35967273/#/6/w].}) 6... exf6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. g3 $1 {Preparing to contest the long light-square diagonal.} f5 9. Bg2 Z0 ({As} 9... Bxc3 10. dxc3 {would still leave Black with issues down the d-file, White didn't need to rush with Rc1 in Bischoff-Vogt, Altensteig 1994. Black's position isn't terrible, but for our money White has a small but pretty pleasant edge, almost in Trompowsky fashion. Here O-O and d2-d4 may follow, with another plan that of a timely Ne1, angling for an exchange of light-squared bishops.}) *

