1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 $5 {This isn't especially common at club level, but is far from a bad way for the Queen's Indian player to look to counter the Reti and has been used by the likes of Carlsen and Rapport of late.} 3. e3 ({Our standard approach. White can also go} 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. e3 {and only then fianchetto, while fans of an early imbalance may wish to consider a 3.b3 Bb7 4.Bb2!? move order. This tempts Black into exchanging on f3, while preparing to meet 4...g6 with 5.Bxf6 exf6 6.e3 when it's Black who has the doubled f-pawns and with Karpov-Browne (San Antonio, 1972) still a model game for White in such structures in general.}) 3... Bb7 4. b3 g6 $5 ({Only now, with} 4... Bxf3 $6 5. Qxf3 {clearly not to be feared, do we fianchetto. Many Queen's Indian players will now transpose into Chapter 1a or 1b after}) (4... e6 5. Bb2 {, but on occasion fairly strong players have been known to prefer a more ambitious double fianchetto.}) 5. Bb2 {Eyeing a possible exchange, albeit one Black is likely to immediately rule out.} Bg7 6. Be2 O-O ({There's no need to rush with Nc3 here as White prepares to castle and reasons that a} 6... d5 7. cxd5 {exchange will merely help him to improve his own forces. Depending on your experience of Queen's Indian and English positions, you may also wish to consider 6.d4 or 6.g3!? here.}) ({Once again, play is likely to transpose after} 6... c5 7. O-O {with} O-O 8. Nc3 {.}) 7. O-O {White completes kingside development and only now will begin to consider ideas of Nc3 and d2-d4.} d6 8. Nc3 Ne4 $5 ({Continuing development and a flexible choice, as White waits to see if Black might want to contest} 8... c5 9. d4 {after all (a line we'll examine via a 7...c5 8.Nc3 d6 9.d4 move order [/variation/35967275/#/9/w]).}) 9. Qc2 {White is happy to maintain pawn flexibility and prepares to recapture, twice if necessary, with a piece on c3.} Nxc3 10. Bxc3 e5 $5 11. d4 $1 Z0 ({This was a key break to take the fight to Black in A. Mastrovasilis-Anton Guijarro, Minsk 2017. White should be fairly happy to see both} 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 {and}) (11... e4 12. Nd2 {and meanwhile threatens not just dxe5, but d4-d5 followed by Nd2, after which Black's bishop on b7 would look a little strange in the resulting King's Indian type scenario, where White would look to advance on the queenside.}) *

