1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 $5 {This isn't especially common at club level, but is far from a bad way for the Queen's Indian player to look to counter the Reti and has been used by the likes of Carlsen and Rapport of late.} 3. e3 ({Our standard approach. White can also go} 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. e3 {and only then fianchetto, while fans of an early imbalance may wish to consider a 3.b3 Bb7 4.Bb2!? move order. This tempts Black into exchanging on f3, while preparing to meet 4...g6 with 5.Bxf6 exf6 6.e3 when it's Black who has the doubled f-pawns and with Karpov-Browne (San Antonio, 1972) still a model game for White in such structures in general.}) 3... Bb7 4. b3 g6 $5 ({Only now, with} 4... Bxf3 $6 5. Qxf3 {clearly not to be feared, do we fianchetto. Many Queen's Indian players will now transpose into Chapter 1a or 1b after}) (4... e6 5. Bb2 {, but on occasion fairly strong players have been known to prefer a more ambitious double fianchetto.}) 5. Bb2 {Eyeing a possible exchange, albeit one Black is likely to immediately rule out.} Bg7 6. Be2 O-O ({There's no need to rush with Nc3 here as White prepares to castle and reasons that a} 6... d5 7. cxd5 {exchange will merely help him to improve his own forces. Depending on your experience of Queen's Indian and English positions, you may also wish to consider 6.d4 or 6.g3!? here.}) ({Once again, play is likely to transpose after} 6... c5 7. O-O {with} O-O 8. Nc3 {.}) 7. O-O {White completes kingside development and only now will begin to consider ideas of Nc3 and d2-d4.} c5 ({Black's most popular choice, one played by a number of strong players. Instead, we saw} 7... e6 8. Nc3 {via a 5...g6 6.Nc3 Bg7 7.Be2 O-O 8.O-O move order [/variation/35967250/#/8/w], and 7...Nc6 8.d4 would just leave Black's pieces looking a little strange.}) 8. Nc3 ({Completing development ahead of challenging with d2-d4 and thereby giving Black a few extra options compared to the immediate} 8. d4 {(threatening d4-d5)} cxd4 9. Nxd4 {, which you may prefer.}) 8... d6 {Untitled players rarely venture into this line, but if they did, this is the sort of natural, less committal choice many would prefer. White should not object.} 9. d4 cxd4 ({Our favourite advance, threatening to blunt the bishop on b7 with} 9... Z0 10. d5 {, after which Qc2 and e3-e4 may follow.}) 10. Nxd4 {This position-type should be fairly well known by now and here White is all set to improve the pieces with Rc1 and Bf3.} Nbd7 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Bf3 {Due to Black's potential issues on c6 and d5 (a timely Nd5 can be awkward for Black if ...Nxd5; cxd5 then safely clamps down on the hole on c6), White enjoyed a small but pleasant edge in Spata-Dubov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023.} *

