 9. d4 {With the king safe and minor pieces deployed, it's high time to advance, threatening 10.d5.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 ({Our standard mechanism, facilitating Bf3, although if you don't mind a complex, more dynamic manoeuvring battle you may wish to consider} 10. exd4 $5 d5 11. Re1 {.}) 10... d5 $5 11. Nxc6 {Ulf Andersson fans may prefer to hoover everything on d5 and then set about trying to exploit the resulting nibble in the endgame. The text attempts to retain more pieces by exchanging the knights on White's terms, not d4, then going Rc1.} Bxc6 12. Rc1 dxc4 13. Bxc4 {Black should be able to prove full equality with care here, but in the short term White's position is slightly the easier to handle. There are ideas of Ba3, Qe2 too if the queens don't come off or f2-f3 and e3-e4 if they do. Meanwhile Black must be careful about rushing to play for further exchanges:} Ne4 14. Nxe4 $1 Bxb2 $2 ({Now Black should settle for only being a touch worse after} 14... Bxe4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qg4 {, not fall for a tactic:}) 15. Bxf7+ $1 {LPDO! (John Nunn's mnemonic - Loose Pieces Drop Off.) The bishop on c6 is falling to leave White a clear pawn to the good.} *

