 9. d4 {With the king safe and minor pieces deployed, it's high time to advance, threatening 10.d5.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 ({Our standard mechanism, facilitating Bf3, although if you don't mind a complex, more dynamic manoeuvring battle you may wish to consider} 10. exd4 $5 d5 11. Re1 {.}) 10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 {White is now ready to swing the queen to h4 ahead of going Rfd1, so Black might be likely to seek further exchanges.} Ne4 12. Qd3 {The only real square, of course.} Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 {Perhaps this isn't too terrible for Black, despite the small space disadvantage, but in Sadhwani-Pap, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021, White went on to grind out the win.} Rc8 15. Rfd1 {White may now double the rooks after Rd4 and can either edge forwards on the queenside or consider ideas of h4-h5. All the while, Black cannot easily free his position:} d5 $2 16. e4 $1 e6 ({Simply threatening to win material with} 16... Z0 17. exd5 {, and if} Bxd5 $2 18. Qe3 {.}) 17. exd5 exd5 18. Bf3 {Due to the two pins, Black is unable to avoid losing a pawn, since White is all set to unpin with Qd4 then bag d5.} *

