$5 {Black's most ambitious choice, beating White to the central break.} 9. Nxd5 {Once again, we may now get to channel our inner Ulf Andersson and settle down to grind, while in any case White should be determined to show Black that early exchanges do not mean an easy draw.} Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. cxd5 Qxd5 ({Now} 11... Bxd5 12. d4 {would menace dxc5 and hope to win a piece after} cxd4 $4 13. Qxd4+ {and Rfd1, so Black may well prefer the alternative recapture.}) 12. Qc2 $5 ({Heading for b2, as White angles to keep pieces on and the position not without some dynamism. If though you prefer to channel your inner Ulf, then by all means prefer} 12. d4 cxd4 13. Qxd4+ Qxd4 14. Nxd4 {and look to grind away with the slightly more active pieces.}) 12... Nc6 13. Qb2+ Kg8 14. a3 $1 {Usefully keeping Black's knight out of b4, while even looking to break with b3-b4. We've reached a reversed Sicilian position, where Black should be OK, but White is also quite comfortable and should look towards the b3-b4 and d2-d4 pawn breaks.} Rfd8 15. Rfd1 Rac8 16. b4 $1 c4 $5 ({A key advance and} 16... cxb4 $6 17. axb4 {would now leave White with a handy central majority and some pressure down the a-file.}) 17. Rac1 ({This ambitious advance turned out well after} 17. d4 $6 b5 {in A. Moskalenko-G.Shahade, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, but White should have been somewhat less accommodating.}) {White attacks the pawn and keeps the d2-d3 break in reserve.} 17... Ba6 $5 18. Bf1 $5 Z0 ({A nifty little retreat, securing the bishop and so threatening} 18... Z0 19. e4 {, and if} Qxe4 $2 20. b5 {. The position isn't totally clear, but like the engines we slightly prefer White, who also has the d2-d3 and a3-a4 advances on the agenda.}) *

