$5 {Black's most ambitious choice, beating White to the central break.} 9. Nxd5 {Once again, we may now get to channel our inner Ulf Andersson and settle down to grind, while in any case White should be determined to show Black that early exchanges do not mean an easy draw.} Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Nxe3 $5 {This is likely to be the choice of a higher-rated opponent looking to unbalance the position or a player who doesn't fancy too many exchanges and a potentially lengthy defensive task.} 11. fxe3 $1 {White should take the chance to make the more dynamic recapture, since now d2-d4 will follow.} Kxg7 12. d4 {White would now like to gain a handy central pawn preponderance with d4-d5 followed by e3-e4.} e6 $5 {This seemed quite sensible in Goganov-Xiong, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, where White switched the queen to the queenside, not that it had to go there.} 13. Qe1 $5 {Heading instead for the kingside while freeing d1 for the queen's rook.} Nd7 14. Rd1 Qe7 15. Qg3 {Black should be OK here, but we would still be happy enough as White, with the slightly greater activity and safer king position. To increase the pressure, White may go Ne5, perhaps prefaced by h2-h4.} *

