1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 {Symmetry! With this copycat advance, Black reveals that he is determined to fight not on Reti ground, but in those lines classified as the Symmetrical English. As so often, there is a large amount of crossover between the Reti and English, and this solid response is to be respected, but not feared.} 3. Nc3 ({A change from our usual} 3. e3 {policy (when} g6 {is likely awkward to meet, and if} 4. d4 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 {with a decent enough type of Panov-Botvinnik for Black), if also our usual early destination for the queen's knight.}) ({According to ChessBase's latest vast database, Black's most common options after} 3. Nc3 {, in descending order of popularity, are:} Nc6 {, 3...e6 , 3...d5 , 3...g6 and 3...b6 . As White we will still largely be looking to go e2-e3, although on the odd occasion that pawn will instead land up on e4. Here we will focus our attention on: 2a: 3...d5 2b: 3...g6 2c: 3...Nc6 But what about 3...e6 and 3...b6 we hear you cry? Let's take a look in this introductory chapter. 3...e6 4.e3 and now: A) 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 Our favourite line against the Tarrasch, with Bb5 on the way, as we analysed in Chapter 12 in the first part [/variation/23789957/#/5/w] of this LTR. B) 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 and we're back in Chapter 1b [/variation/35967285/#/6/w] of this course. C) 4...Nc6 5.d4 and this time we've transposed to chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w] of this course.}) 3... Z0 *

