1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 {Symmetry! With this copycat advance, Black reveals that he is determined to fight not on Reti ground, but in those lines classified as the Symmetrical English. As so often, there is a large amount of crossover between the Reti and English, and this solid response is to be respected, but not feared.} 3. Nc3 ({A change from our usual} 3. e3 {policy (when} g6 {is likely awkward to meet, and if} 4. d4 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 {with a decent enough type of Panov-Botvinnik for Black), if also our usual early destination for the queen's knight.}) ({According to ChessBase's latest vast database, Black's most common options after} 3. Nc3 {, in descending order of popularity, are:} Nc6 {, 3...e6 , 3...d5 , 3...g6 and 3...b6 . As White we will still largely be looking to go e2-e3, although on the odd occasion that pawn will instead land up on e4. Here we will focus our attention on: 2a: 3...d5 2b: 3...g6 2c: 3...Nc6 But what about 3...e6 and 3...b6 we hear you cry? Let's take a look in this introductory chapter. 3...e6 4.e3 and now: A) 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 Our favourite line against the Tarrasch, with Bb5 on the way, as we analysed in Chapter 12 in the first part [/variation/23789957/#/5/w] of this LTR. B) 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 and we're back in Chapter 1b [/variation/35967285/#/6/w] of this course. C) 4...Nc6 5.d4 and this time we've transposed to chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w] of this course.}) 3... b6 4. e3 ({Our usual approach, although if you don't mind tackling the Hedgehog in aggressive fashion,} 4. e4 $5 {is also quite a good option.}) 4... Bb7 5. b3 d5 $5 ({Preparing to fianchetto after all and now play will usually transpose to the waters of Chapters 1b or 1c, depending on what Black does with the bishop on f8 (} 5... e6 {or}) (5... g6 {).}) 6. cxd5 {Naturally we exchange before Black can get in any annoying ...d4 advance.} Nxd5 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 ({A further exchange to discombobulate. White will follow up with Bb2 and Bc4 or Bb5+, with definite prospects to obtain an early initiative and advantage in a position which has been extremely rare in practice. Now} 7... Bxd5 8. Bb2 {makes it tricky for Black to untangle the kingside and} f6 $6 9. d4 {surely must be pretty good for White, so perhaps the queen must come out.}) 8. Bb2 {Again, eyeing the g7-pawn while also taking control of the e5-square. White will most likely follow up with Bc4, O-O and then break with d2-d4, looking to seize that aforementioned early initiative.} e6 9. Bc4 Qh5 10. Be2 $1 ({Refusing to let the queen settle while introducing Ne5 as a semi-threat (} 10. Rg1 $5 {is also quite tempting here and engine-approved, intending to simply if radically seize space with g2-g4).}) 10... Nc6 11. Ne5 ({Consistent and somewhat more pleasant than} 11. O-O Bd6 {would be.}) 11... Qg5 12. f4 $1 Qh4+ ({The position resembles a Nimzo-Larsen, so White can and should expand in the manner of that cowboy-approved opening while dangling some bait before Black. Now, of course,} 12... Qxg2 $4 13. Bf3 {would lead to Black losing a piece and the game on c6.}) 13. g3 Qd8 14. Bb5 {Pinning and securing the initiative. Qf3 or even Qh5 will follow and White must be at least slightly for choice.} *

