1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 {Symmetry! With this copycat advance, Black reveals that he is determined to fight not on Reti ground, but in those lines classified as the Symmetrical English. As so often, there is a large amount of crossover between the Reti and English, and this solid response is to be respected, but not feared.} 3. Nc3 ({A change from our usual} 3. e3 {policy (when} g6 {is likely awkward to meet, and if} 4. d4 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 {with a decent enough type of Panov-Botvinnik for Black), if also our usual early destination for the queen's knight.}) ({According to ChessBase's latest vast database, Black's most common options after} 3. Nc3 {, in descending order of popularity, are:} Nc6 {, 3...e6 , 3...d5 , 3...g6 and 3...b6 . As White we will still largely be looking to go e2-e3, although on the odd occasion that pawn will instead land up on e4. Here we will focus our attention on: 2a: 3...d5 2b: 3...g6 2c: 3...Nc6 But what about 3...e6 and 3...b6 we hear you cry? Let's take a look in this introductory chapter. 3...e6 4.e3 and now: A) 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 Our favourite line against the Tarrasch, with Bb5 on the way, as we analysed in Chapter 12 in the first part [/variation/23789957/#/5/w] of this LTR. B) 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 and we're back in Chapter 1b [/variation/35967285/#/6/w] of this course. C) 4...Nc6 5.d4 and this time we've transposed to chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w] of this course.}) 3... d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, in part because our favourite approach will now pose some early problems for Black.} 4. e3 g6 ({White simply helps himself to the space on offer and now} 4... Nc6 5. d4 {would already leave Black lacking a good way to deal with the issue that is} Z0 6. d5 {.}) 5. d4 Bg7 $5 ({White threatens to exchange on c5, but may also be happy to enter favourable Benoni style waters, such as with} 5... Nbd7 6. d5 {when Black may well struggle to free his position with ...e6.}) 6. dxc5 ({By no means forced and you might well prefer to retain the tension with} 6. Be2 {, perhaps followed by O-O and a queenside fianchetto, but keeping Black's king in the centre must be the critical test of his ambitious approach.}) 6... dxc5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bd2 {Preparing to castle long and White should also be keeping an eye open for the right time to cause trouble with a Ng5 raid.} Nc6 9. O-O-O b6 10. Ng5 $5 {The position isn't completely clear, but White has a certain threat on f7 and also ideas of trying to seize an early initiative with Nd5 when ...Nxd5; cxd5 is unlikely to spell great news for Black.} Rf8 $6 {We've followed the 2600+ clash Indjic-Predojevic, Internet (blitz) 2020, where White could have seized the upper hand:} 11. Nd5 $1 Z0 ({The big threat is Bc3, with} 11... h6 $2 12. Bc3 $1 {definitely very good for White and Black in any case simply in some trouble whether he exchanges on d5 or gives up the h7-pawn by retreating his knight to e8.}) *

