1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 {Symmetry! With this copycat advance, Black reveals that he is determined to fight not on Reti ground, but in those lines classified as the Symmetrical English. As so often, there is a large amount of crossover between the Reti and English, and this solid response is to be respected, but not feared.} 3. Nc3 ({A change from our usual} 3. e3 {policy (when} g6 {is likely awkward to meet, and if} 4. d4 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 {with a decent enough type of Panov-Botvinnik for Black), if also our usual early destination for the queen's knight.}) ({According to ChessBase's latest vast database, Black's most common options after} 3. Nc3 {, in descending order of popularity, are:} Nc6 {, 3...e6 , 3...d5 , 3...g6 and 3...b6 . As White we will still largely be looking to go e2-e3, although on the odd occasion that pawn will instead land up on e4. Here we will focus our attention on: 2a: 3...d5 2b: 3...g6 2c: 3...Nc6 But what about 3...e6 and 3...b6 we hear you cry? Let's take a look in this introductory chapter. 3...e6 4.e3 and now: A) 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 Our favourite line against the Tarrasch, with Bb5 on the way, as we analysed in Chapter 12 in the first part [/variation/23789957/#/5/w] of this LTR. B) 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 and we're back in Chapter 1b [/variation/35967285/#/6/w] of this course. C) 4...Nc6 5.d4 and this time we've transposed to chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w] of this course.}) 3... d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, in part because our favourite approach will now pose some early problems for Black.} 4. e3 g6 ({White simply helps himself to the space on offer and now} 4... Nc6 5. d4 {would already leave Black lacking a good way to deal with the issue that is} Z0 6. d5 {.}) 5. d4 cxd4 ({White threatens to exchange on c5, but may also be happy to enter favourable Benoni style waters, such as with} 5... Nbd7 6. d5 {when Black may well struggle to free his position with ...e6.}) 6. exd4 {The right recapture here, taking a small space advantage while preparing to complete development in classical fashion with Be2 and O-O.} Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Bg4 $5 ({This position can come about via a number of different move orders and has long been known to be slightly better for White, who has a number of useful ideas: seizing space with d4-d5 (especially in the event of} 8... Nc6 $6 9. d5 {), probing on the queenside with Qb3, and straightforward development through Bf4 and Re1.}) 9. h3 Bxf3 ({Wasting no time challenging the bishop and now 10.d5 may well be a strong advance if the bishop retreats, with} 9... Bf5 10. d5 Nbd7 $6 11. Nd4 {already superb for White.}) 10. Bxf3 Nc6 11. Be3 {Simply maintaining control of d4. White has a pleasant edge with the extra space and bishop-pair and should now look to calmly improve his position, as with Rc1, b2-b3 and Qd2, thereby continuing to deny Black effective counterplay} e5 $5 12. Bxc6 {Simple chess, as White exchanges on c6 and e5, thereby swapping the bishop-pair to retain control and obtain both a structural advantage and the initiative.} bxc6 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Qa4 {A fine square for the queen, eyeing Black's weakened queenside. White will follow up with Rfd1 and may then begin to advance the queenside majority with b2-b4, possibly followed by Bc5 or doubling rooks on the d-file, looking to stretch Black down the d-file and on a7.} *

