pace advantage while preparing to complete development in classical fashion with Be2 and O-O.} Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 ({CLICKABLE This position can come about via a number of different move orders and has long been known to be slightly better for White, who has a number of useful ideas: seizing space with d4-d5 (especially in the event of} 8... Nc6 $6 9. d5 {), probing on the queenside with Qb3, and straightforward development through Bf4 and Re1.}) 9. h3 $5 {Yet another useful move and approach at White's disposal, keeping Black out of g4 while facilitating Be3; with Black lining up ...e5, the bishop might not be so happy on f4.} Nbd7 10. Be3 {White is now all set to go Qd2 and Rfe1, and will also ignore 10...e5: 11.Re1 maintains control, and if 11...e4 12.Nd2 when White can combine pressure against e4 with queenside expansion.} b6 $6 11. d5 $1 Bb7 12. Nd4 {A superb post for the knight, pressing on Black's position. With not just Rc1, but effective expansion through b2-b4 and even f2-f4 on the way, White was already clearly for choice in Abasov-Kandil, Mersin 2017.} *

