1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 {Symmetry! With this copycat advance, Black reveals that he is determined to fight not on Reti ground, but in those lines classified as the Symmetrical English. As so often, there is a large amount of crossover between the Reti and English, and this solid response is to be respected, but not feared.} 3. Nc3 ({A change from our usual} 3. e3 {policy (when} g6 {is likely awkward to meet, and if} 4. d4 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 {with a decent enough type of Panov-Botvinnik for Black), if also our usual early destination for the queen's knight.}) ({According to ChessBase's latest vast database, Black's most common options after} 3. Nc3 {, in descending order of popularity, are:} Nc6 {, 3...e6 , 3...d5 , 3...g6 and 3...b6 . As White we will still largely be looking to go e2-e3, although on the odd occasion that pawn will instead land up on e4. Here we will focus our attention on: 2a: 3...d5 2b: 3...g6 2c: 3...Nc6 But what about 3...e6 and 3...b6 we hear you cry? Let's take a look in this introductory chapter. 3...e6 4.e3 and now: A) 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 Our favourite line against the Tarrasch, with Bb5 on the way, as we analysed in Chapter 12 in the first part [/variation/23789957/#/5/w] of this LTR. B) 4...b6 5.b3 Bb7 6.Bb2 and we're back in Chapter 1b [/variation/35967285/#/6/w] of this course. C) 4...Nc6 5.d4 and this time we've transposed to chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w] of this course.}) 3... d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, in part because our favourite approach will now pose some early problems for Black.} 4. e3 g6 ({White simply helps himself to the space on offer and now} 4... Nc6 5. d4 {would already leave Black lacking a good way to deal with the issue that is} Z0 6. d5 {.}) 5. d4 cxd4 ({White threatens to exchange on c5, but may also be happy to enter favourable Benoni style waters, such as with} 5... Nbd7 6. d5 {when Black may well struggle to free his position with ...e6.}) 6. exd4 {The right recapture here, taking a small space advantage while preparing to complete development in classical fashion with Be2 and O-O.} Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d5 $5 ({This position can come about via a number of different move orders and has long been known to be slightly better for White, who has a number of useful ideas: seizing space with d4-d5 (especially in the event of} 8... Nc6 $6 9. d5 {), probing on the queenside with Qb3, and straightforward development through Bf4 and Re1.}) ({Black is now a tempo down on a hybrid line of the Panov-Botvinnik and Grunfeld known to be fine for him, and even here ruling out d4-d5 so must be critical.} 8... Re8 9. h3 $5 {is yet another useful move and approach at White's disposal, keeping Black out of g4 while facilitating Be3; with Black lining up ...e5, the bishop might not be so happy on f4.} Nbd7 10. Be3 {White is now all set to go Qd2 and Rfe1, and will also ignore 10...e5 - 11.Re1 maintains control, and if 11...e4 12.Nd2 when White can combine pressure against e4 with queenside expansion.} b6 $6 11. d5 $1 Bb7 12. Nd4 {A superb post for the knight, pressing on Black's position. With not just Rc1, but effective expansion through b2-b4 and even f2-f4 on the way, White was already clearly for choice in Abasov-Kandil, Mersin 2017.}) 9. c5 $5 ({If you don't mind an IQP scenario then by all means maintain the tension with} 9. Be3 {or}) (9. Re1 {, but the space-gaining advance must be a critical test of Black's tempo-down approach. If allowed, White would now like to expand while supporting the bridgehead on c5 with Be3 and b2-b4 in some order.}) 9... b6 10. Bf4 ({White facilitates Rc1 as well as b2-b4 (the immediate} 10. b4 {is fairly well met by} Ne4 {), while clamping down on the e5-square.}) 10... Ne4 $5 11. cxb6 {Simple chess as White swaps the bridgehead to maintain a lead in development and now both Rc1 and Re1 may follow.} Nxc3 12. bxc3 axb6 13. Bb5 $1 {Fighting against Black's queenside development. White can secure the bishop with a2-a4 and may then be able to take control and an edge after Qb3 and Rfe1.} *

