pace advantage while preparing to complete development in classical fashion with Be2 and O-O.} Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d5 $5 ({This position can come about via a number of different move orders and has long been known to be slightly better for White, who has a number of useful ideas: seizing space with d4-d5 (especially in the event of} 8... Nc6 $6 9. d5 {), probing on the queenside with Qb3, and straightforward development through Bf4 and Re1.}) ({Black is now a tempo down on a hybrid line of the Panov-Botvinnik and Grunfeld known to be fine for him, and even here ruling out d4-d5 so must be critical.} 8... Re8 9. h3 $5 {is yet another useful move and approach at White's disposal, keeping Black out of g4 while facilitating Be3; with Black lining up ...e5, the bishop might not be so happy on f4.} Nbd7 10. Be3 {White is now all set to go Qd2 and Rfe1, and will also ignore 10...e5 - 11.Re1 maintains control, and if 11...e4 12.Nd2 when White can combine pressure against e4 with queenside expansion.} b6 $6 11. d5 $1 Bb7 12. Nd4 {A superb post for the knight, pressing on Black's position. With not just Rc1, but effective expansion through b2-b4 and even f2-f4 on the way, White was already clearly for choice in Abasov-Kandil, Mersin 2017.}) 9. c5 $5 ({If you don't mind an IQP scenario then by all means maintain the tension with} 9. Be3 {or}) (9. Re1 {, but the space-gaining advance must be a critical test of Black's tempo-down approach. If allowed, White would now like to expand while supporting the bridgehead on c5 with Be3 and b2-b4 in some order.}) 9... Nc6 10. Bf4 {) Fighting for the e5-square once again and White may now find all of Rc1, Re1 and h2-h3 to be useful moves.} Ne4 11. h3 {Denying Black use of the g4-square ahead of involving the rooks.} Nxd4 $5 12. Nxd4 e5 13. Be3 {Naturally White wants to maintain the bishop, as well as control of d4.} exd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Nxc3 16. bxc3 (16. Qxc3 $5 d4 17. Qd2 {is also possible, but we're not too unhappy with the pawn recapture, thereby maintaining full control of d5. Black may be able to draw, but the onus is on him to equalise, especially with the easy moves Rb1 followed by Bf3 and Rfd1 on the way for White.}) *

