1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 {Black's most ambitious response, striking out in the centre.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges and does not allow Black to push on.} Nxd5 5. e3 Bg4 $2 ({Our favourite square for the king's pawn, supporting the d2-d4 break and also allowing the light-squared bishop to take up an active role on c4 or b5. White might even now be ready to go} 5... Z0 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. b3 {, and at this stage Black has three main moves: 2a1: 5...Nxc3 2a2: 5...e6 2a3: 5...Nc6 The alternatives are rather rare, with the attempt to fianchetto on the kingside the most notable of them.}) 6. Bc4 Nxc3 ({The pressure down the a2-g8 diagonal is already rather uncomfortable for Black, pressure which} 6... Be6 7. Qb3 {would only increase.}) 7. Ne5 $1 ({Even stronger as well as more aesthetic than} 7. Qb3 {, as White leaves the queen en prise to two pieces to threaten mate.}) 7... Be6 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. bxc3 {Qa4+ or Qg4 may follow and Black's position is already something of a wreck.} *

