1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 {Black's most ambitious response, striking out in the centre.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges and does not allow Black to push on.} Nxd5 5. e3 Nb4 ({Our favourite square for the king's pawn, supporting the d2-d4 break and also allowing the light-squared bishop to take up an active role on c4 or b5. White might even now be ready to go} 5... Z0 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. b3 {, and at this stage Black has three main moves: 2a1: 5...Nxc3 2a2: 5...e6 2a3: 5...Nc6 The alternatives are rather rare, with the attempt to fianchetto on the kingside the most notable of them.}) 6. d4 cxd4 ({Simple chess, advancing while not allowing Black into d3. White even threatens to annex more space with d4-d5 and would meet} 6... Bf5 $2 {with} 7. e4 {.}) 7. exd4 {Again threatening d4-d5, as well as a2-a3 and rapid development with Bb5+. White certainly shouldn't mind the IQP here due to his easy and superior development.} Bf5 8. Bb5+ {Developing with tempo while dealing with the threatened fork by preparing to evacuate the king to g1.} N8c6 9. O-O ({Consistent, although} 9. d5 $5 a6 10. Ba4 {is also quite tempting and clearly better for White.}) 9... e6 $6 10. d5 $1 {Vigorously seizing the initiative and introducing the powerful concept of Nd4.} exd5 $5 11. Nd4 Bd7 12. Re1+ $1 {White can even afford to check so ahead of prodding the knight on b4.} Be7 13. a3 Nxd4 ({Already the engines think that Black has nothing better than to give up a piece. Clearly} 13... Na6 14. Nxd5 {would be extremely strong, so an opponent might try to win rather than lose material.}) 14. Qxd4 $1 {With two massive threats, White's initiative should be a decisive one.} Nc2 15. Qxg7 {This actually wins the rook since it won't be able to escape.} Rf8 16. Bh6 $1 Nxe1 17. Rxe1 {Black might be a rook ahead, but should resign since there's just no good way to deal with the threat of Qxf8#.} *

