1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 {Black's most ambitious response, striking out in the centre.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges and does not allow Black to push on.} Nxd5 5. e3 Nc7 ({Our favourite square for the king's pawn, supporting the d2-d4 break and also allowing the light-squared bishop to take up an active role on c4 or b5. White might even now be ready to go} 5... Z0 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. b3 {, and at this stage Black has three main moves: 2a1: 5...Nxc3 2a2: 5...e6 2a3: 5...Nc6 The alternatives are rather rare, with the attempt to fianchetto on the kingside the most notable of them.}) {A slightly strange square for the knight, if also a much better choice for Black than sending it down the board.} 6. d4 {Once again, White shouldn't fear an active IQP position, with Bc4 high on the agenda, as well as the space-gaining d4-d5.} e6 7. Bd3 {With the a2-g8 diagonal no longer fully open, the bishop switches to a different good diagonal, as White simply prepares to castle while creating the option of dxc5 Bxc5; a2-a3 followed by b2-b4 and Bb2.} Nd7 {Countering the aforementioned plan by preparing to recapture on c5 with the knight, but Black is some way behind in development.} 8. O-O Be7 9. Qc2 $1 cxd4 ({White prevents castling and even prepares to take} 9... Z0 10. Bxh7 {, as} g6 {can be met by} 11. Bxg6 {when White will emerge with four pawns for the piece.}) 10. exd4 ({This is how White would have recaptured had Black exchanged sooner, although here} 10. Nxd4 $5 {followed by Rd1 is also a pretty tempting option,}) 10... h6 11. Bf4 {White enjoyed an excellent version of an IQP position and some advantage in Larsen-Erlingsson, Lone Pine 1978. The rooks are set to come to d1 and e1, Ne5 may follow and also Qd2, lining up a sacrifice on h6 should Black castle.} *

