1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 {Black's most ambitious response, striking out in the centre.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges and does not allow Black to push on.} Nxd5 5. e3 a6 ({Our favourite square for the king's pawn, supporting the d2-d4 break and also allowing the light-squared bishop to take up an active role on c4 or b5. White might even now be ready to go} 5... Z0 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. b3 {, and at this stage Black has three main moves: 2a1: 5...Nxc3 2a2: 5...e6 2a3: 5...Nc6 The alternatives are rather rare, with the attempt to fianchetto on the kingside the most notable of them.}) {Keeping White out of b5 and ...a6 won't be too out of place if an IQP scenario now arises.} 6. Nxd5 $5 {with b2-b3 the plan. Qxd5 b3! The bishops are bound for fine posts on c4 and b2. Nc6 Bc4 Qh5 Bb2 White enjoys a harmonious set-up and pleasant edge. There's always Be2 if needed, but White would really like to castle then seize the initiative as the position opens up after d2-d4. Bg4 h3! Refusing to let the enemy bishop settle while simply intending Be2 then O-O. Bxf3 Qxf3 Qxf3 gxf3 With the two bishops and useful expansion through f3-f4 and h3-h4-h5 on the way, White must be slightly for choice. The king will tuck in on e2 and g7 may well become a target.} *

