1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 {Black's most ambitious response, striking out in the centre.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges and does not allow Black to push on.} Nxd5 5. e3 g6 $5 ({Our favourite square for the king's pawn, supporting the d2-d4 break and also allowing the light-squared bishop to take up an active role on c4 or b5. White might even now be ready to go} 5... Z0 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. b3 {, and at this stage Black has three main moves: 2a1: 5...Nxc3 2a2: 5...e6 2a3: 5...Nc6 The alternatives are rather rare, with the attempt to fianchetto on the kingside the most notable of them.}) 6. Qa4+ $1 {)} ({Discombobulating, as White only wants to put the queen on b3 once Black has moved the bishop from c8. Dmitri Andreikin once played something similar with} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Qb3 {and there's nothing wrong with the immediate 6.Qb3 , but we do quite like the check - as do the engines. After 6.Qa4+ , now 6...Qd7?? 7.Qxd7+ and -- 8.Nxd5 would already be game over.}) 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 $1 {This powerful pin is the other reason why the check on a4 just looks like a good one. White simply threatens to take twice on c6.} Ndb4 $5 8. d4 a6 ({Ever a critical response to an early ...Ndb4, here simply threatening} 8... Z0 9. a3 {.}) 9. Bxc6+ Nxc6 ({The easiest way of dealing with the threat and now} 9... bxc6 $6 10. O-O {would leave Black with a rather ragged position.}) 10. d5 b5 {Clearly forced, but now White has a small tactic to net a pawn.} 11. Nxb5 $1 Bd7 12. Nd6+ $1 {Even stronger than retreating to c3 as White spots a neat way to simplify.} exd6 13. dxc6 Be6 14. Bd2 {The check may not lead anywhere, but White should still be happy after the calm text move. Bc3 and O-O will follow, after which White will be quick to introduce some pressure down the d-file with Rfd1.} *

