1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 {Black's most ambitious response, striking out in the centre.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges and does not allow Black to push on.} Nxd5 5. e3 g6 $5 ({Our favourite square for the king's pawn, supporting the d2-d4 break and also allowing the light-squared bishop to take up an active role on c4 or b5. White might even now be ready to go} 5... Z0 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. b3 {, and at this stage Black has three main moves: 2a1: 5...Nxc3 2a2: 5...e6 2a3: 5...Nc6 The alternatives are rather rare, with the attempt to fianchetto on the kingside the most notable of them.}) 6. Qa4+ $1 ({Discombobulating, as White only wants to put the queen on b3 once Black has moved the bishop from c8. Dmitri Andreikin once played something similar with} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Qb3 {and there's nothing wrong with the immediate 6.Qb3 , but we do quite like the check - as do the engines. After 6.Qa4+ , now 6...Qd7?? 7.Qxd7+ and -- 8.Nxd5 would already be game over.}) 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 $1 {This powerful pin is the other reason why the check on a4 just looks like a good one. White simply threatens to take twice on c6.} Nxc3 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. bxc3 ({Simply regaining the piece and naturally not} 9. Qxc6+ $4 Bd7 {.}) 9... Bd7 $6 10. Ba3 {Black's position is again a wreck, with White clearly better and all set to castle as well as pick off a pawn on c5, Lindberg-R.Cox, correspondence 2015.} *

