1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 {Black's most ambitious response, striking out in the centre.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges and does not allow Black to push on.} Nxd5 5. e3 g6 $5 ({Our favourite square for the king's pawn, supporting the d2-d4 break and also allowing the light-squared bishop to take up an active role on c4 or b5. White might even now be ready to go} 5... Z0 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. b3 {, and at this stage Black has three main moves: 2a1: 5...Nxc3 2a2: 5...e6 2a3: 5...Nc6 The alternatives are rather rare, with the attempt to fianchetto on the kingside the most notable of them.}) 6. Qa4+ $1 ({Discombobulating, as White only wants to put the queen on b3 once Black has moved the bishop from c8. Dmitri Andreikin once played something similar with} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Qb3 {and there's nothing wrong with the immediate 6.Qb3 , but we do quite like the check - as do the engines. After 6.Qa4+ , now 6...Qd7?? 7.Qxd7+ and -- 8.Nxd5 would already be game over.}) 6... Bd7 7. Qb3 $5 {)} ({Simply attacking the knight as well as hitting b7. White has more often preferred} 7. Qc4 {when} Bc6 $5 8. Qxc5 e5 9. Qc4 Bg7 {should offer Black some, but not quite enough compensation for the pawn.}) ({After} 7. Qb3 {,} Bc6 8. Ne5 {is a bit awkward for Black, as would be 7...Nxc3 8.Qxc3 .}) 7... Bc6 $5 8. Ne5 $1 Bg7 $2 ({White not only prepares to exchange on c6, but eyes the f7 point and so threatens 9.e4. Now} 8... e6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Be2 {would be quite miserable for Black, but is also the best that the engines can see.}) 9. e4 $1 {Not forgetting about the threat.} Bxe5 10. exd5 Bd7 11. Qxb7 {There goes a pawn and now even a slightly sneaky tactic will bring Black nowhere near to equality.} Qb6 12. Qxa8 $1 O-O 13. a4 $1 Nc6 $5 ({A vital follow-up and the reason why White was happy to grab the rook in the corner. The key point is} 13... Na6 14. a5 $1 {when either the white queen will escape or White will emerge with too much for her after} Qc7 15. Qxf8+ Kxf8 16. Bxa6 {.}) 14. dxc6 $5 Rxa8 ({This tricky continuation hopes to escape with} 14... Bxc6 $2 15. a5 Qc7 16. Nd5 $1 {, threatening the queen, as well as Qxc6 and Nxe7+, and probably allows Black less counterplay than 14.Qxf8+ Kxf8 15.dxc6 Qxc6 would do.}) 15. cxd7 Qe6 16. Be2 {Naturally White blocks the e-file and should be doing pretty well with rook, bishop and knight for the queen. One useful idea appears to be Nd1-e3 to further plug the e-file ahead of castling and then beginning to activate with moves like Bc4 and Ra3.} *

