1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 {Black's most ambitious response, striking out in the centre.} 4. cxd5 {Naturally White exchanges and does not allow Black to push on.} Nxd5 5. e3 g6 $5 ({Our favourite square for the king's pawn, supporting the d2-d4 break and also allowing the light-squared bishop to take up an active role on c4 or b5. White might even now be ready to go} 5... Z0 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. b3 {, and at this stage Black has three main moves: 2a1: 5...Nxc3 2a2: 5...e6 2a3: 5...Nc6 The alternatives are rather rare, with the attempt to fianchetto on the kingside the most notable of them.}) 6. Qa4+ $1 ({Discombobulating, as White only wants to put the queen on b3 once Black has moved the bishop from c8. Dmitri Andreikin once played something similar with} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Qb3 {and there's nothing wrong with the immediate 6.Qb3 , but we do quite like the check - as do the engines. After 6.Qa4+ , now 6...Qd7?? 7.Qxd7+ and -- 8.Nxd5 would already be game over.}) 6... Bd7 7. Qb3 $5 ({Simply attacking the knight as well as hitting b7. White has more often preferred} 7. Qc4 {when} Bc6 $5 8. Qxc5 e5 9. Qc4 Bg7 {should offer Black some, but not quite enough compensation for the pawn.}) ({After} 7. Qb3 {,} Bc6 8. Ne5 {is a bit awkward for Black, as would be 7...Nxc3 8.Qxc3 .}) 7... Nb6 8. Ne4 $1 ({White now hurried with} 8. Ne5 $6 Be6 {in Kono-Cawston, Bad Homburg 2017, and we can do much better.}) 8... e6 $2 ({White introduces the idea of Qc3 and also wants to favourably pick up a pawn with Nxc5 followed by d2-d4. The engines can see nothing better for Black than accepting a clear disadvantage with} 8... Bg7 9. Nxc5 {, since it's just not really possible to defend c5.}) 9. Qc3 {Thanks to the potential check on f6, White is already winning material.} *

