1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... Nc6 7. d4 {It's high time to make use of the extra central pawn which the exchanges on d5 and c3 have given us. White now threatens d4-d5 and Black doesn't have an especially good sort of Semi-Tarrasch.} e6 8. Bd3 {)} ({Clearly the best square for the bishop here, lining up against h7, although you actually have a choice here as we'll see} 8. Bb5 {by transposition in chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967536/#/8/w].}) 8... Be7 {White is now set to castle, after which one simple and decent plan is that of Bb2 followed by e3-e4. Meanwhile White would again be delighted to see 8...cxd4 9.exd4 and a path open up for the dark-squared bishop.} 9. O-O {It makes sense to safely house the king ahead of deciding where to deploy the queen and when to push e3-e4.} O-O 10. Bb2 ({A simple approach, preparing e3-e4, although with this move order} 10. Qc2 $5 {is also quite tempting to tickle the black kingside.}) 10... b6 11. e4 Bb7 $6 ({Play is now likely to transpose to a position [/variation/35967330/#/13/w] we saw via 9...b6 10.e4 after} 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Bb7 13. Rc1 {, or at least Black would be well advised to exchange so.}) 12. d5 $1 {Had Black exchanged on d4, this advance would have been well met by ...Nb4, whereas now it's a strong and secure gain of space, since Black can't take twice on d5 due to Bxh7+.} exd5 13. exd5 Na5 14. c4 {The d5-pawn is a powerful bridgehead, helping to blunt Black's queenside pieces. Qc2 and Rfe1 will follow and White must be clearly for choice.} *

