1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... Nc6 7. d4 {It's high time to make use of the extra central pawn which the exchanges on d5 and c3 have given us. White now threatens d4-d5 and Black doesn't have an especially good sort of Semi-Tarrasch.} e6 8. Bd3 ({Clearly the best square for the bishop here, lining up against h7, although you actually have a choice here as we'll see} 8. Bb5 {by transposition in chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967536/#/8/w].}) 8... Be7 {White is now set to castle, after which one simple and decent plan is that of Bb2 followed by e3-e4. Meanwhile White would again be delighted to see 8...cxd4 9.exd4 and a path open up for the dark-squared bishop.} 9. O-O {It makes sense to safely house the king ahead of deciding where to deploy the queen and when to push e3-e4.} b6 $5 {Black tries to avoid or at least delay castling into a potential kingside attack.} 10. e4 $1 {Possible as the d-pawn is, of course, taboo.} cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O ({White is now all set to go Bb2 followed by Re1 and perhaps Rc1, ideally building towards a timely and powerful d4-d5 push or a classic queen-and-bishop battery with Bb1 and Qd3. And, yes,} 11... Nxd4 $4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 $2 13. Bb5+ {would leave Black red-faced.}) 12. Bb2 {A fine spot for the bishop and by now, of course, the d-pawn was actually attacked.} Bb7 13. Rc1 ({Facilitating a timely Bb1. White should also have a fairly pleasant edge - again, Black would be slightly struggling for counterplay - after} 13. Qe2 Rc8 14. a3 {, as played by Ivanchuk.}) 13... Bf6 14. Bb1 Rc8 ({Keeping d4 secure while actually introducing a direct threat:} 14... Z0 15. e5 Be7 16. Rxc6 $1 Bxc6 17. Qc2 {, threatening mate as well as the loose bishop on c6.}) 15. Qd3 Z0 ({White should be slightly for choice. Clearly e4-e5 is a threat, h2-h4 also high on the agenda and} 15... Nb4 {can simply be met by} 16. Qd2 {, continuing to keep everything under control.}) *

