1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... e6 7. d4 Qc7 $5 ({Expansion without delay and now} 7... Nc6 8. Bd3 {would, of course, take play back into the realm of the 6...Nc6 7.d4 lines [/variation/35967328/#/7/w]. Meanwhile White is all set to go Bd3 and O-O after all.}) 8. Rb1 $5 ({A sneaky move, as now} 8. Bd3 $2 cxd4 {would be quite awkward for White, not least after} 9. cxd4 $2 Qc3+ {.}) {A slightly sneaky reply! The half-open file is never going to be a bad place to put the rook and now everything is ready for Bd3 after all.} 8... Be7 9. Bd3 {White is now all set to go O-O then e3-e4, which doesn't need support as Black has reduced the pressure against d4. White may even wish to tickle the kingside with Qc2, then go Qe2 and e3-e4, hoping to gradually exploit any weakness created by ...g6 or ...h6. Black is fairly solid, but White's strong centre should promise an edge. Note too that an invasion on c3 is no longer to be feared:} cxd4 10. cxd4 Qc3+ $6 11. Kf1 $5 ({One of two good approaches, the other being} 11. Qd2 Qxd2+ 12. Bxd2 {followed by Ke2 and Rhc1 with control, a handy lead in development and queenside pressure. The text sees White prefer to expand with Bb2 and e3-e4, while h2-h4 followed by Rh3-g3 is also a useful plan to bear in mind.}) 11... O-O 12. h4 $1 {This powerful advance also allows White to consider Ng5 ideas, although the Greek Gift isn't on due to Black's actively placed queen.} Nd7 13. Rh3 $1 {White's king is quite safe on f1 and he is doing pretty well. The simple idea is Rg3 followed by e3-e4, creating potential attacks across the third rank against the black queen while also enabling the dark-squared bishop to land straight on h6.} *

