1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... e6 7. d4 cxd4 ({Expansion without delay and now} 7... Nc6 8. Bd3 {would, of course, take play back into the realm of the 6...Nc6 7.d4 lines [/variation/35967328/#/7/w]. Meanwhile White is all set to go Bd3 and O-O after all.}) 8. cxd4 ({A simple approach, maintaining the central majority and easy plan of Bd3 and O-O, although if you're a fairly aggressive player you may prefer} 8. exd4 $5 Qc7 9. Bb2 {followed by Bd3.}) 8... Bb4+ {Black tries to disrupt and develop as quickly as possible.} 9. Bd2 {The most straightforward way to block, keeping the plan of Bd3 and O-O very much on the cards.} Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6 ({This position would be somewhat more common and an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch had White a pawn on e4. With it on e3, d4 is more secure and White can instead looking to use the e4-square for the bishop instead (} 11... b6 $4 12. Be4 {would be immediately embarrassing for Black). While White has scored quite well in the limited testing from here, Black is, of course, pretty solidly placed.}) 12. O-O Na5 $5 ({Housing the king and preparing to meet} 12... b6 $2 {with} 13. Qc2 {and a double-attack on c6 and h7. Meanwhile White is all set to exert some pressure, either after Rac1, Bb1 and Qd3 or against the black queenside with Rfc1, Rab1 and Be4.}) 13. Be4 Rb8 ({Directed against Black's hope of fianchettoing his bishop after all. He can force that through with} 13... f5 14. Bd3 b6 {, but then} 15. Qe2 {followed by Ba6 will immediately challenge the bishop and leave Black having created weaknesses.}) 14. Rfc1 {Simple chess secures a large edge. White keeps Ne5 ideas in reserve, prepares to double rooks on the c-file and will meet any ...b6 and ...Bb7 with an exchange of bishops followed by Ne5, leaving Black vulnerable on c6 as well as c7.} *

