1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... e6 7. d4 cxd4 ({Expansion without delay and now} 7... Nc6 8. Bd3 {would, of course, take play back into the realm of the 6...Nc6 7.d4 lines [/variation/35967328/#/7/w]. Meanwhile White is all set to go Bd3 and O-O after all.}) 8. cxd4 ({A simple approach, maintaining the central majority and easy plan of Bd3 and O-O, although if you're a fairly aggressive player you may prefer} 8. exd4 $5 Qc7 9. Bb2 {followed by Bd3.}) 8... Bb4+ {Black tries to disrupt and develop as quickly as possible.} 9. Bd2 {The most straightforward way to block, keeping the plan of Bd3 and O-O very much on the cards.} Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nd7 ({This position would be somewhat more common and an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch had White a pawn on e4. With it on e3, d4 is more secure and White can instead looking to use the e4-square for the bishop instead (} 11... b6 $4 12. Be4 {would be immediately embarrassing for Black). While White has scored quite well in the limited testing from here, Black is, of course, pretty solidly placed.}) 12. O-O Nf6 ({Completing development and preparing to meet} 12... b6 {with the slightly disruptive} 13. Be4 {. White is also all set to obtain some pressure on the queenside, as with Rfc1, Qb4 and a2-a4.}) 13. Rfc1 {A fine spot for the rook as White begins to play on the queenside.} b6 14. Ne5 $1 {And this is an important advance, looking to land the knight on c6 and so create problems at a timely juncture.} Bb7 15. a4 $1 Z0 ({Black is quite solid, but also slightly worse. Any ...Nd7 may well be met by Nc6, a4-a5 is set to arrive and so create a target on the queenside and} 15... Qd5 {can simply be met by} 16. f3 {.}) *

