1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... Qc7 $5 7. Bb2 $5 ({Another slightly sneaky move, once used by Anish Giri and more recently by Peter Svidler at the World Rapid. Black waits for} 7. d4 {before going} g6 {.}) 7... Nd7 ({White too can very much be sneaky and now} 7... g6 $6 8. c4 f6 9. Be2 {would leave Black's position looking a bit strange. Note too that Black can't prevent c3-c4, since 7...c4? 8.Qa4+ would just cost him a pawn.}) 8. Qb3 $1 ({Introducing the possibility of} 8. Z0 c4 {(if} 9. Qa4 b5 $1 {) while also intending to meet 8.c4 with 8...e5 , which may not be too bad for Black.}) {White remembers that f7 as well as b7 can become an issue for Black in this structure.} 8... e5 $2 9. Ng5 $1 {The attack on f7 can always be reinforced by Bc4 and is simply extremely unpleasant for Black who quite simply lacks a satisfactory defence.} Nb6 10. Bb5+ {Black might have prevented Bc4, but the bishop finds an even better square and now f7 will fall next move.} *

