1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... Qc7 $5 7. Bb2 $5 ({Another slightly sneaky move, once used by Anish Giri and more recently by Peter Svidler at the World Rapid. Black waits for} 7. d4 {before going} g6 {.}) 7... Nd7 ({White too can very much be sneaky and now} 7... g6 $6 8. c4 f6 9. Be2 {would leave Black's position looking a bit strange. Note too that Black can't prevent c3-c4, since 7...c4? 8.Qa4+ would just cost him a pawn.}) 8. Qb3 $1 ({Introducing the possibility of} 8. Z0 c4 {(if} 9. Qa4 b5 $1 {) while also intending to meet 8.c4 with 8...e5 , which may not be too bad for Black.}) {White remembers that f7 as well as b7 can become an issue for Black in this structure.} 8... e6 9. c4 {) Opening up the gaze of the bishop on b2 and White may now consider ideas of Bd3 and Qc2, as well as of seizing space with a2-a4 and getting castled, depending on how Black reacts.} b6 10. a4 $1 {A powerful advance, looking to quickly place Black under some pressure on the queenside.} Bb7 11. a5 Z0 ({White's instructive play left him with a pleasant edge in Navara-Nepomniachtchi, Jerusalem 2015. Of course,} 11... bxa5 $6 12. Bc3 {would break up Black's queenside structure and he also has to solve the problem of untangling the kingside. In contrast White is all set to go Bd3 and Qc2, with raking pressure against the black kingside as well as ideas of a timely Be4.}) *

