1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 h5 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) 8. Bc4 {This is the problem with Black's approach. Ng5 possibly even followed by Qf3 is going to ask some awkward questions.} e6 {Blunting the diagonal without delay.} 9. d4 {With Black's development not exactly something to write home about, White is happy to finally get on with central expansion.} Bg7 10. Ng5 $5 ({White made a good case for} 10. e4 O-O {(10...Qa5 would be met by 11.Bd2)} 11. O-O {in Lerner-Romanovich, St Petersburg 1997, with a good version of a main-line Grünfeld as Black is a bit low on counterplay, but exploiting the hole on g5 is also a very tempting option. White menaces Qf3, may even meet 10...O-O with 11.g4 (there's also simply 11.O-O if you really don't want to enjoy a strong attack), and Black won't find it all at easy to shift the knight from g5.}) 10... Nd7 $1 {This is probably Black's best option, bringing the knight over to help bolster the kingside defences.} 11. O-O {White's king is quite safe here and everything now set for Ba3 and/or e3-e4.} O-O 12. Ba3 b6 13. e4 {Finally moving the e-pawn for a second time and leaving White with a promising version of a Grünfeld. Black is slightly tied down and a bit low on counterplay. White may even be able to clamp down further with e4-e5 followed by Qe2 and centralising the rooks, thereby leaving Black a little passive and potentially vulnerable to an eventual d4-d5 push or even kingside attack.} *

