1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 h5 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) 8. Bc4 {This is the problem with Black's approach. Ng5 possibly even followed by Qf3 is going to ask some awkward questions.} Bg7 9. Qc2 $5 {)} Qd6 ({Preventing Black from castling (if} 9... O-O $2 10. Qxg6 {) might be even stronger than the also tempting 9.Ng5!? of Frey Beckman-Gruenberg, Reykjavik 1982. White is still ready to go Ng5 and also has ideas of Ba3 and d2-d4 to increase the pressure.}) 10. Ba3 {Pinning the c5-pawn ahead of getting in d2-d4 and safely housing the king on g1.} b6 11. d4 Bb7 12. Ng5 $1 {There's no need to allow an exchange on f3 when it's possible to create a direct threat against f7.} O-O 13. O-O {Once again we find White's knight something of a Trojan on g5. The set-up is also a pretty harmonious one and further expansion with Rad1 (threatening dxc5) and f2-f4 may follow.} *

