1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 h6 $5 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) 8. d4 ({White is content to head into Grünfeld-type waters after all, arguing that the insertion of h2-h4 and ...h6 is in his favour, since Black's kingside has been slightly weakened and there's always h4-h5 to effectively force ...g5. Indeed,} 8. h5 $5 g5 9. d4 {might also be considered, as suggested by David Cummings in his ChessPublishing column. After the text, White is likely to deploy the light-squared bishop to d3 and may well find Rb1 a useful move, posing Black a few issues over the b7-square.}) 8... Bg7 9. Rb1 $5 Qc7 ({Ensuring that} 9... Bg4 $6 10. Rxb7 {will now win a pawn for insufficient compensation.}) 10. Bd3 O-O ({This is in need of an over-the-board test, but makes sense and now} 10... Bg4 {would be fairly well met by} 11. Qa4+ {, and if} Nd7 12. Be4 {or 11...Bd7 12.Qb3 .}) 11. O-O b6 ({Calmly following suit on the kingside as White keeps his options open. Pushing e3-e4 may be a good approach (not least in the event of} 11... Nd7 12. e4 {when e4-e5 may follow), the bishop can also use e4 and there are ideas too of both Ba3 and Qc2, angling to get in h4-h5 after all.}) 12. h5 $1 g5 ({Only now does White weaken the black kingside and, of course,} 12... gxh5 $6 13. Nh2 {would see White regaining the pawn with interest.}) 13. Ne5 $1 {A strong sacrifice as White heads forwards, intending f2-f4 while continuing to target Black on the light squares.} Bxe5 14. dxe5 Qxe5 $6 15. Qf3 {The point of White's play and, frankly, Black is now a little fortunate that he has a move to stay afloat.} Na6 $1 16. Qc6 $1 ({Instead,} 16. Qxa8 Bf5 {is actually just quite unclear, but White retains the upper hand by targeting h6 so. Now 16...Qg7? 17.Qxa8 would just be a free rook in view of 17...Bf5 18.Qd5 , 16...Kg7? 17.Bb2 and c3-c4 is also quite unwise for Black and 16...Bf5 well enough met by 17.e4 .}) 16... c4 $5 17. Bxc4 Bf5 18. Rb5 $1 {Forcing the pace as Black will come up short even in this top engine line after 16.Qc6.} Nc5 19. Qxh6 {To save g5, Black is going to have to trade queens, after which while he is fairly well coordinated, he will just be a clear pawn down.} *

