1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 Bg7 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) {Black's main move, sensibly getting on with development.} 8. h5 {Naturally White presses ahead before getting in d2-d4 or perhaps even first pressing on the light squares with Qb3.} O-O 9. Qa4 $1 {White's most direct approach, simply threatening to exchange on g6 then land the queen on h4.} e5 $1 10. Ba3 Bd7 ({White attempts to decoy Black's queen to the wrong side of the board or to step into} 10... Qe7 $6 11. d4 {. Note that 10...b6? 11.Qe4 would also now be misguided, and that 10...Nd7 11.hxg6 hxg6 12.Qg4 begins to look quite scary for Black.}) 11. Qc2 b6 ({A switch of approach, but this way c5 is still attacked, Bc4 on the way and} 11... Bf5 $6 {would run into} 12. e4 {then} Z0 13. Bxc5 {.}) 12. Bc4 {Maintaining the initiative as White threatens to take twice on g6 and would also be fairly happy to get in Bd5 and e3-e4.} Qf6 $1 13. d4 Z0 ({Black has defended well, but White is likely still slightly for choice in this complex position. There's a threat to take on e5,} 13... exd4 14. cxd4 {followed by Rd1 only really helps White and White may either exchange on g6 or establish a potentially useful, AlphaZero style pawn with h5-h6.}) *

