1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 Bg7 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) {Black's main move, sensibly getting on with development.} 8. h5 {Naturally White presses ahead before getting in d2-d4 or perhaps even first pressing on the light squares with Qb3.} Qd5 $6 9. Bb2 {Simply threatening c3-c4 may be even stronger here than 9.Qb3.} c4 $6 {Black got away with this extremely ambitious approach in Lehtonen-Alenius, Finland 1980, but probably shouldn't have done.} 10. Qe2 $1 b5 ({Simply targeting the pawn. White will now meet} 10... Be6 {with} 11. Nd4 {and also find a2-a4, h5-h6 and e3-e4 to be potentially very useful advances.}) 11. h6 Bf8 ({Forcing the bishop backwards as} 11... Bf6 $2 12. e4 {would cost Black a piece.}) 12. a4 {Beginning to undermine the queenside pawn chain.} a6 13. d3 $1 cxd3 ({Yet another pawn manages to make a powerful impact, and now} 13... Be6 {would again be well met by} 14. Nd4 {.}) 14. Qd2 $5 ({This is even stronger than the hardly shabby} 14. Qxd3 {. White threatens 14...-- 15.c4 and would also quite like to go Bxd3, thereby keeping queens on and Black somewhat behind in development, as well as rather vulnerable on both flanks.}) *

