1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 Bg7 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) {Black's main move, sensibly getting on with development.} 8. h5 {Naturally White presses ahead before getting in d2-d4 or perhaps even first pressing on the light squares with Qb3.} Nc6 {Black's most common choice by some margin as he aims to avoid castling into a potential attack.} 9. Rb1 $5 ({Pressing on b7 makes sense (} 9. Qb3 {and the simple}) (9. Be2 {, as used by Aronian, are also decent options), and now 9...Bf5? 10.Rxb7 O-O 11.hxg6 Bxg6 12.Nh4 was already clearly better for White in Goganov-Zakhartsov, Anapa 2021.}) 9... O-O $5 10. hxg6 ({Naturally White wants to try and drum up an early attack against Black's brave choice (} 10. h6 Bf6 11. d4 {would be a sensible, positional alternative).}) 10... hxg6 11. Ng5 $5 ({Here} 11. Qa4 e5 $1 {thwarted White's hopes of Qh4 in So-Vachier Lagrave, Airthings Masters (rapid) 2020, but that isn't the only way to launch an attack.}) 11... e5 $1 ({Blocking the h4-d8 diagonal and so intending Qa4-h4 after all, while also giving the queen a route into the game via f3 and the} 11... Qd5 12. f4 {would now usefully support the knight.}) 12. Nh7 $5 ({Fearlessly heading forwards, although} 12. Ne4 {followed by Nxc5 or Qf3 can hardly be a bad option either.}) 12... Re8 13. e4 $1 {Fighting against Black's central expansion while very much played with an eye still on the kingside. The position is pretty unclear, but we'd be happy to take the white side, with Qf3 definitely an idea, after which d4!? and Bg5 might even be a possibility.} *

