1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 Bg7 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) {Black's main move, sensibly getting on with development.} 8. h5 {Naturally White presses ahead before getting in d2-d4 or perhaps even first pressing on the light squares with Qb3.} Nc6 {Black's most common choice by some margin as he aims to avoid castling into a potential attack.} 9. Rb1 $5 ({Pressing on b7 makes sense (} 9. Qb3 {and the simple}) (9. Be2 {, as used by Aronian, are also decent options), and now 9...Bf5? 10.Rxb7 O-O 11.hxg6 Bxg6 12.Nh4 was already clearly better for White in Goganov-Zakhartsov, Anapa 2021.}) 9... b6 10. Bb5 $1 {Discombobulating before pushing the d-pawn which would now like to make it all the way to d5 if allowed.} Qc7 11. Ng5 $5 ({There's also nothing too much wrong with} 11. d4 Bf5 12. Bd3 {, but it's nice to introduce Qf3 as a threat.}) 11... Bf5 12. Qf3 $1 O-O-O $1 ({Played anyhow and with} 12... Rc8 $2 {running into} 13. e4 {, Black must be creative to find the only move which really stays on the board.}) 13. Rb2 Ne5 $1 14. Qa8+ $1 {Black has found the only way to deal with both threats, but White should now be fairly happy to simplify so.} Qb8 15. Qxb8+ Kxb8 16. h6 $5 {Continuing to ignore the hole on d3 as White keeps up the pace.} Bf6 17. d4 $1 Bxg5 ({We can now appreciate why there was no need to panic about the potential check on d3. White would, of course, be very happy to see} 17... Nd3+ $6 18. Bxd3 Bxd3 $2 19. Nxf7 {, and 17...cxd4 18.exd4 is also unlikely to help Black.}) 18. dxe5 e6 19. Ke2 {Finally White covers the d3-square. The position isn't completely clear, but we quite like White who threatens to trouble Black's other bishop with f2-f3 and e3-e4 and is also all set to expand with a4-a5. Finally, don't forget that cramping pawn on h6 might well make its presence felt in any, say, rook ending.} *

