1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 Bg7 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) {Black's main move, sensibly getting on with development.} 8. h5 {Naturally White presses ahead before getting in d2-d4 or perhaps even first pressing on the light squares with Qb3.} Nc6 {Black's most common choice by some margin as he aims to avoid castling into a potential attack.} 9. Rb1 $5 ({Pressing on b7 makes sense (} 9. Qb3 {and the simple}) (9. Be2 {, as used by Aronian, are also decent options), and now 9...Bf5? 10.Rxb7 O-O 11.hxg6 Bxg6 12.Nh4 was already clearly better for White in Goganov-Zakhartsov, Anapa 2021.}) 9... Qc7 {Black has tended to cover b7 so, including in some high-level encounters.} 10. d4 ({Only now does White advance in the centre and in part because} 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 {doesn't lead anywhere for him. Now, though, Ng5 is definitely an idea, pressing on f7 and h7, and also intending h5-h6 ...Bf6 Ne4. Also, as so often in these lines, some or all of Bd3, Ba3 and Qb3 may also prove useful.}) 10... Bg4 11. Qb3 {There's no need to fear an exchange on f3 when Black is already a little weak on the light squares, a factor accentuated by White applying some pressure to both b7 and f7.} b6 12. d5 $1 ({White now went for it with} 12. Ng5 $5 {in Jakovenko-Vachier Lagrave, Khanty-Mansiysk (rapid) 2019, but had a simple and strong alternative:}) 12... Ne5 ({Kicking the knight, and now} 12... Na5 13. Qa4+ Bd7 14. Qc2 {would keep everything secure.}) 13. Nxe5 (13. h6 $5 {is also fairly promising, but this way White relies on the powerful ideas of Bb5+ and f2-f4.}) 13... Bxe5 14. f4 Bd6 {An unusual square for the bishop, but Black needed to prevent e3-e4-e5.} 15. Bb5+ $1 {White must be slightly for choice, since he's seized some useful space and hxg6 will follow when Black cannot take back with the h-pawn. Meanwhile the white queen should find a useful role be it on a4, c2 or even d1 with O-O followed by e3-e4-e5 an ideal goal.} *

