1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 Bg7 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) {Black's main move, sensibly getting on with development.} 8. h5 {Naturally White presses ahead before getting in d2-d4 or perhaps even first pressing on the light squares with Qb3.} Nc6 {Black's most common choice by some margin as he aims to avoid castling into a potential attack.} 9. Rb1 $5 ({Pressing on b7 makes sense (} 9. Qb3 {and the simple}) (9. Be2 {, as used by Aronian, are also decent options), and now 9...Bf5? 10.Rxb7 O-O 11.hxg6 Bxg6 12.Nh4 was already clearly better for White in Goganov-Zakhartsov, Anapa 2021.}) 9... Qc7 {Black has tended to cover b7 so, including in some high-level encounters.} 10. d4 ({Only now does White advance in the centre and in part because} 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 {doesn't lead anywhere for him. Now, though, Ng5 is definitely an idea, pressing on f7 and h7, and also intending h5-h6 ...Bf6 Ne4. Also, as so often in these lines, some or all of Bd3, Ba3 and Qb3 may also prove useful.}) 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 {Keeping the central majority intact. White still has the useful options of Qb3, Bd3 and Ng5 and we should now see what happens if Black does bravely elect to castle.} O-O 12. hxg6 ({The most direct, although the engines also quite like both} 12. h6 {and the calm}) (12. Bd2 $5 {followed by Rc1.}) 12... hxg6 ({An essential recapture (Black would quickly come a cropper after} 12... fxg6 $2 13. Qb3+ e6 14. Bd3 {and Ng5), and now the position was pretty unclear after 13.Qc2 Be6 in Popov-Vorobiov, Tomsk 2006.}) 13. Bd2 $5 Be6 ({Meanwhile aggressive ideas of Ng5 or even a rook lift are not yet off the table by any means: A useful developing move to eliminate any checks on the e1-a5 diagonal. White may now follow up with Rc1 or just go Qb3, such as with} 13... Bg4 14. Qb3 {to unpin.}) 14. Rb5 $1 Z0 ({White has seized the initiative. Not only is} 14... Z0 15. d5 {a definite threat, but Qb1 followed by Ng5 is on the way, when any ...Bf5 would be extremely risky in view of Rxf5 ...gxf5 Qxf5.}) *

