1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 {This forcing approach is often the choice of a Grünfeld player, but, worry not, we don't have to transpose into their favourite opening.} 6. bxc3 ({The more dynamic and more popular recapture, although if you're happy to grind away in a queenless middlegame,} 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is by no means a bad choice, as used by Andersson, Miles and even Carlsen. With the text move, White holds back on d2-d4, waiting to see what Black is up to and now 6...Bg4?! would be well met by 7.Qb3 , pressing against b7 and f7.}) 6... g6 {Going for the aforementioned Grünfeld-type approach is standard here, if not absolutely forced.} 7. h4 $1 Bg7 ({White has tried all manner of moves here, but this advance, deploying Harry, is, of course, a Simon favourite in general and makes good sense here, while also being engine-approved. White is very secure in the centre, so quite justified in placing Black under some pressure on the kingside. As well see, why Black can block with} 7... h5 {that only serves to leave his position looking a little fragile after} 8. Bc4 {.}) {Black's main move, sensibly getting on with development.} 8. h5 {Naturally White presses ahead before getting in d2-d4 or perhaps even first pressing on the light squares with Qb3.} Nc6 {Black's most common choice by some margin as he aims to avoid castling into a potential attack.} 9. Rb1 $5 ({Pressing on b7 makes sense (} 9. Qb3 {and the simple}) (9. Be2 {, as used by Aronian, are also decent options), and now 9...Bf5? 10.Rxb7 O-O 11.hxg6 Bxg6 12.Nh4 was already clearly better for White in Goganov-Zakhartsov, Anapa 2021.}) 9... Qc7 {Black has tended to cover b7 so, including in some high-level encounters.} 10. d4 ({Only now does White advance in the centre and in part because} 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 {doesn't lead anywhere for him. Now, though, Ng5 is definitely an idea, pressing on f7 and h7, and also intending h5-h6 ...Bf6 Ne4. Also, as so often in these lines, some or all of Bd3, Ba3 and Qb3 may also prove useful.}) 10... Bd7 11. Bd3 Rd8 ({Calmly continuing development while preparing to strike boldly, quickly and effectively in the event of} 11... O-O 12. Ng5 {.}) 12. Ng5 $1 ({Here} 12. Qc2 {was hardly a bad move in Svidler-Nepomniachtchi, Nizhny Novgorod 2013, which White went on to win, but as Danny Gormally pointed out in his annotations at the time, White might also have been consistently direct.}) 12... O-O $2 ({White threatens both} 12... Z0 13. Qf3 {and 13.h6 Bf6 14.Ne4 . Meanwhile 12...h6 13.Ne4 would just weaken Black's structure, 12...Qa5 still walks into 13.h6 and 12...cxd4 can simply be met by 13.exd4 . All in all, there's a good reason why the engines have White at least at '+1'.}) {A classic case of from the frying pan into the fire...} 13. Nxh7 $1 {Crashing through in decisive fashion. Already there's no satisfactory defence to the threats of Nxf8 and hxg6.} Kxh7 $2 14. hxg6+ Kg8 15. Qh5 Z0 ({Mate follows. For a quick exercise can you work out the only mate in four after} 15... fxg6 $2 {(Clue: it involves a classic rook sacrifice).}) *

