1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... Qxd5 {An ambitious, less classical recapture.} 7. b3 (7. b4 $6 cxb4 {would make little sense here, so White instead prefers a simple method of fianchettoing the queen's bishop while also creating the option of Bc4.}) 7... Bd6 $6 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Bc4 ({Here White settled for} 9. Be2 {back in Franklin-Safvat, Tel Aviv Olympiad 1964, but it was possible to be somewhat more critical, either with the engines'}) (9. h4 $5 {or simply kicking the queen.}) {Now if the queen retreats, White may be quick to target the under-defended black kingside with Qc2 and Ng5.} 9... Qf5 {Attempting to cut out Qc2 and Ng5 ideas, but...} 10. g4 $1 Qe4 ({The pawn is, of course, taboo due to} 10... Qxg4 11. Rg1 {, and the potential game-ending breakthrough on g7, while 10...Qg6?! 11.h4 would also be pretty unwise for Black.}) 11. Rg1 {Stepping off the long diagonal enables White to press forwards with Ng5 and h2-h4, with a strong initiative.} *

