1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... Qxd5 {An ambitious, less classical recapture.} 7. b3 (7. b4 $6 cxb4 {would make little sense here, so White instead prefers a simple method of fianchettoing the queen's bishop while also creating the option of Bc4.}) 7... Be7 ({Black usually reacts so. Instead, we saw} 7... b6 8. Bb2 Bb7 {via a 3...b6 4.e3 Bb7 5.b3 d5 6.cxd5 move order [/variation/35967310/#/8/b] at the start of Chapter Two.}) 8. Bb2 ({Simply targeting g7. White can also begin with} 8. Bc4 {, but that gives Black the extra option of} Qd8 9. Bb2 Bf6 {.}) 8... Bf6 $6 9. Bxf6 {Naturally White should avail himself of the structural gains on offer.} gxf6 10. Bc4 {Developing with tempo ahead of housing the king then breaking with d2-d4.} Qd6 11. O-O Bd7 12. d4 {This left White with a useful early initiative in Neubert-Wiesen, correspondence 1993, where dxc5 followed by Rc1 and possibly Nd4 (to free a path for the white queen over to the kingside) or Qc2 was on the way.} *

