1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... Qxd5 {An ambitious, less classical recapture.} 7. b3 (7. b4 $6 cxb4 {would make little sense here, so White instead prefers a simple method of fianchettoing the queen's bishop while also creating the option of Bc4.}) 7... Be7 ({Black usually reacts so. Instead, we saw} 7... b6 8. Bb2 Bb7 {via a 3...b6 4.e3 Bb7 5.b3 d5 6.cxd5 move order [/variation/35967310/#/8/b] at the start of Chapter Two.}) 8. Bb2 ({Simply targeting g7. White can also begin with} 8. Bc4 {, but that gives Black the extra option of} Qd8 9. Bb2 Bf6 {.}) 8... Nc6 $6 9. Bxg7 {Don't be bluffed! The pawn can be safely taken.} Rg8 10. Bc3 $1 {The most secure square for the bishop, as well as one which helps to deter ...Nb4 ideas.} e5 11. Bc4 Qd6 12. Bb5 $5 ({Here} 12. Qc2 {wasn't a bad move in Grachev-Ponkratov, Croatian Team Championship 2019, and there was likely even better.}) 12... Bd7 ({Pinning the knight on c6. Now both} 12... Rxg2 $6 13. Nxe5 {followed by Qf3 and 12...e4?! 13.Ne5 Rxg2 14.Qh5 would leave Black under heavy pressure.}) 13. Qc2 {Only now does White attack the pawn on h7.} Rxg2 14. Bxc6 $1 {This fearless exchange is the star point of White's play.} Bxc6 15. Nxe5 {Black lacks a strong discovery, White can always exchange on c6 and h7 is still hanging.} Rg6 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 17. O-O-O {Black doesn't have enough for the pawn. White can always move the king to b2 or b1 if needed and meanwhile h4-h5 will kick the black rook, with Rhg1 another potentially useful move.} *

