1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... Qxd5 {An ambitious, less classical recapture.} 7. b3 (7. b4 $6 cxb4 {would make little sense here, so White instead prefers a simple method of fianchettoing the queen's bishop while also creating the option of Bc4.}) 7... Be7 ({Black usually reacts so. Instead, we saw} 7... b6 8. Bb2 Bb7 {via a 3...b6 4.e3 Bb7 5.b3 d5 6.cxd5 move order [/variation/35967310/#/8/b] at the start of Chapter Two.}) 8. Bb2 ({Simply targeting g7. White can also begin with} 8. Bc4 {, but that gives Black the extra option of} Qd8 9. Bb2 Bf6 {.}) 8... O-O 9. h4 $5 {)} Nc6 ({Hurling Harry into the fray! White has tested the alternatives and most often gone for Bc4, but there's no need to rush with that and White would again be fairly happy to now see} 9... Bf6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bc4 {. Meanwhile there are now ideas of Qc2, as well as Ng5, a leap made possible thanks to White's last.}) 10. Bc4 {Kicking the queen seems best before deciding where to place her counterpart and whether to make any further attacking moves on the kingside.} Qd8 11. Qc2 $1 ({Sacrificing a pawn with} 11. Ng5 $5 {is tempting, but not strictly necessary when White can prepare the idea with}) (11. Qc2 {. Now} Nb4 12. Qb1 {doesn't especially help Black, since White would still then threaten Ng5, as well as a2-a3.}) 11... h6 12. g4 {Exploiting the hook on h6 to aim to open lines with g4-g5. Once again, ( 12...Nb4 can simply be met by 13.Qb1 followed by a2-a3, and if White is ever concerned about the h1-a8 diagonal there's always Rh3 or even Ke2. However, Black can't exactly gradually place the light-squared bishop on b7:} b6 $2 13. g5 {Threatening Qc3, as well as gxh6 and, of course, White would also be delighted to see the h-file open.} h5 14. Qc3 f6 15. Rg1 Z0 ({The attack is an extremely strong one, with White even ready to go} 15... Z0 16. Qc2 {followed by} Z0 17. Qg6 {or 17.gxf6 Bxf6 18.Ng5 .}) *

