1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... Qxd5 {An ambitious, less classical recapture.} 7. b3 (7. b4 $6 cxb4 {would make little sense here, so White instead prefers a simple method of fianchettoing the queen's bishop while also creating the option of Bc4.}) 7... Be7 ({Black usually reacts so. Instead, we saw} 7... b6 8. Bb2 Bb7 {via a 3...b6 4.e3 Bb7 5.b3 d5 6.cxd5 move order [/variation/35967310/#/8/b] at the start of Chapter Two.}) 8. Bb2 ({Simply targeting g7. White can also begin with} 8. Bc4 {, but that gives Black the extra option of} Qd8 9. Bb2 Bf6 {.}) 8... O-O 9. h4 $5 Nc6 ({Hurling Harry into the fray! White has tested the alternatives and most often gone for Bc4, but there's no need to rush with that and White would again be fairly happy to now see} 9... Bf6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bc4 {. Meanwhile there are now ideas of Qc2, as well as Ng5, a leap made possible thanks to White's last.}) 10. Bc4 {Kicking the queen seems best before deciding where to place her counterpart and whether to make any further attacking moves on the kingside.} Qf5 $2 11. g4 $1 Qe4 ({This dangerous idea once again and, of course,} 11... Qxg4 $4 12. Rg1 {would now clean Black up.}) 12. d3 {The queen is forced back to continue a precarious existence on the kingside.} Qg6 13. h5 Qh6 14. Kd2 $5 ({This is at least as strong as the} 14. Rh3 {of Navara-Heimann, European Online Club Cup 2021, The king is quite safe on d2 and Black doesn't have anything better than ditching a clear pawn with 14...e5 15.Nxe5 due to the huge threat of 14...-- 15.g5 Bxg5 16.Nxg5 Qxg5 17.Rg1 .}) 14... f6 $6 ({Note too that other attempts to prevent g4-g5 don't exactly help Black's king and queen, like} 14... Bg5 $6 15. Nxg5 Qxg5 16. f4 {or:}) 15. Qe2 {Not only connecting the rooks, but especially covering the f2-pawn as White menaces a very strong sacrifice in g4-g5 followed by Nh2.} Bd7 16. g5 $1 fxg5 17. Nh2 {It's fast becoming a massacre and, yes, the black queen is trapped on h6, with only one possible escape try.} g4 18. Nxg4 Qg5 19. f4 $1 {Naturally White continues to hound the queen.} Qf5 20. Rag1 Z0 ({The attack is overwhelming, with Nh6+ the first threat and White always able to reinforce with Qg2 if needed (like after} 20... Kf7 {).}) *

