1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... Qf6 $5 8. Rb1 {Dealing with the threat while renewing the ideas of Bb2 and bxc5.} Qg6 9. Bb2 c4 $5 10. Bc3 ({A calm choice and for once we prefer such an approach to the highly creative} 10. h4 $5 h5 11. Ne5 {which was just very unclear in Liang-Yoo, Saint Louis 2022. Instead, White secures b4, will meet 10...b5 with 11.a4 and is all set to expand with Ne5 (or if 10...Bf5? 11.Nh4 ), then d2-d3 to chip away at the bridgehead on c4.}) *

