1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... c4 $5 {Salem Salah's creative idea, fighting against the bishop on f1.} 8. Bb2 {) Naturally White is happy to again ignore the pressure against b4 and in return eyes the g7-square. Left undisturbed, White may now go a2-a3, then Qc2 and d2-d3 or even prefer a second fianchetto with g2-g3. Of course, Qc2 is useful too for cutting out ... Bf5 ideas.} f6 $6 9. a3 Nc6 10. d3 $1 ({A simple improvement over the} 10. b5 $6 Na5 {of Bok-Ivanchuk, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021. White threatens to take on c4 and would be pretty happy with two well-placed bishops after 10...cxd3?! 11.Bxd3 .}) 10... b5 11. dxc4 bxc4 $6 ({Capturing in any case, and now} 11... dxc4 12. Nd4 $1 {would open up a pretty useful path towards h5 for the white queen.}) 12. Qc2 ({Stronger than} 12. Nd4 {here as White cuts out ...Bf5 ideas while simply intending Rd1 and/or e3-e4 (the immediate}) (12. e4 $5 {is also quite tempting). There's also simply Be2 and O-O as Black already looks rather overextended in the centre.}) *

