1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... c4 $5 {Salem Salah's creative idea, fighting against the bishop on f1.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is happy to again ignore the pressure against b4 and in return eyes the g7-square. Left undisturbed, White may now go a2-a3, then Qc2 and d2-d3 or even prefer a second fianchetto with g2-g3. Of course, Qc2 is useful too for cutting out ... Bf5 ideas.} Bf5 9. Nd4 $1 {Refusing to let the bishop settle and now the b-pawn will be taboo due to the check on a4 with White's knight controlling c6.} Bg6 10. Be2 ({We were also tempted by} 10. h4 $5 {, but this simple approach intends f2-f4 and O-O followed by d2-d3 with tempo once Black's bishop is on e4.}) *

