1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... c4 $5 {Salem Salah's creative idea, fighting against the bishop on f1.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is happy to again ignore the pressure against b4 and in return eyes the g7-square. Left undisturbed, White may now go a2-a3, then Qc2 and d2-d3 or even prefer a second fianchetto with g2-g3. Of course, Qc2 is useful too for cutting out ... Bf5 ideas.} Bxb4 9. Bxg7 {White pretty much must swipe the pawn if he wants to test Black's entire concept.} Rg8 10. Bb2 Nc6 ({The simplest retreat, keeping the bishop safe while intending Qc2 or if} 10... Bf5 11. Nd4 {(Nepomniachtchi's 10.Be5!? Nc6 11.Bg3 also leads to some very rich positions).}) 11. Qc2 {With a certain threat on the kingside.} Rg6 $1 12. Be2 ({The immediate} 12. h4 $5 {has also been tested, but White should be quite happy to see 12...Rxg2? 13.Qxh7 when the passed h-pawn would be a very useful asset.}) 12... Be7 $5 13. h4 ({Continuing to go after the h7-pawn (} 13. Kf1 $5 {also deserves attention followed by h2-h4 or} Bf6 14. Rd1 {).}) 13... Bf6 14. Rb1 a6 $5 ({A useful square for the rook as White renews the idea of} 14... Z0 15. h5 {when} Rh6 $2 16. g4 $1 {could be a strong follow-up, and if} Bxg4 17. Rg1 {.}) 15. h5 $1 Rxg2 $1 ({Now if} 15... Rg7 $6 16. Kf1 $1 {when White should be at least slightly for choice and would enjoy ideas of not only d2-d3, but also Rh4!?.}) 16. Qxh7 Bxb2 17. Kf1 $1 ({A very important intermezzo played to avoid being cleaned up by} 17. Rxb2 $2 Qf6 18. Qc2 Ne5 {and 17...Rg7 can now be met by 18.Qh8+ .}) 17... Rg4 18. Rxb2 Qf6 19. Qc2 {This extremely unclear position arose in Harf-Kuhn, correspondence 2019, which was later drawn and as well as the passed h-pawn White can play for control and to stabilise the position to an extent with Qc3 and/or Nd4.} *

