{Let's see how play might continue: 16...a5!? Perhaps not the most natural of moves, but also the only way that the engines can see for Black to avoid becoming clearly worse. 17.Bxg4 Simple does it. Ambitious souls may also wish to look into 17.f3!? Bd7 18.g4!? , striving for a passed h-pawn after all and being prepared to walk the king leftwards if needed. 17...Rxg4 18.Kf1 Covering g2 while sidestepping the threat on d4 and now White is all set to go Qf5, whether before or after f2-f3. 18...O-O-O 19.g3 Sensibly keeping h4 secure. Here 19.Qf5+ is fine, but after 19...Qe6 White should exchange queens as 20.Qxh5? Qe4 would be unwise. Instead, 19.g3 maintains an extremely rich position, one which looks slightly easier for White to play and in which he may well untangle with a timely Kg2 and also has ideas of both d2-d3 and Bc3, as well as still Qf5+.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... c4 $5 {Salem Salah's creative idea, fighting against the bishop on f1.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is happy to again ignore the pressure against b4 and in return eyes the g7-square. Left undisturbed, White may now go a2-a3, then Qc2 and d2-d3 or even prefer a second fianchetto with g2-g3. Of course, Qc2 is useful too for cutting out ... Bf5 ideas.} Bxb4 9. Bxg7 {White pretty much must swipe the pawn if he wants to test Black's entire concept.} Rg8 10. Bb2 Nc6 ({The simplest retreat, keeping the bishop safe while intending Qc2 or if} 10... Bf5 11. Nd4 {(Nepomniachtchi's 10.Be5!? Nc6 11.Bg3 also leads to some very rich positions).}) 11. Qc2 {With a certain threat on the kingside.} Rg6 $1 12. Be2 ({The immediate} 12. h4 $5 {has also been tested, but White should be quite happy to see 12...Rxg2? 13.Qxh7 when the passed h-pawn would be a very useful asset.}) 12... Qe7 13. h4 $1 ({A suggested improvement by the Filipino Grandmaster Julio Sadorra over the} 13. g3 $6 Bh3 {of Anton Guijarro-Salem, Martuni 2015. White again plays to destabilise the rook on g6 with h4-h5. Now 13...Rxg2? 14.Qxh7 would again leave White with a very useful passed pawn, while Sadorra also notes the line 13...Bg4? 14.h5 Rh6 15.Bg7 .}) 13... h5 14. Nd4 $1 {A useful move, unfurling an attack on h5 while lining up an exchange of knights as White aims to retain reasonable control over the position. The knight also hints at leaping into f5, after which it might well managed to take up a good role on g3.} Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bg4 16. Rb1 $5 ({In his annotations, Sadorra thought that White was slightly better after} 16. Bxg4 Rxg4 17. Kf1 {, which is a very sensible line, as is the text move. White need not fear 16...Bxe2 17.Kxe2 when the king would remain fairly safe. Meanwhile Qa4+ is a big threat and the white queen may also be able to find a good role on either f5, after an exchange of light-squared bishops, or b2.}) 16... Z0 *

