1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nd7 9. Rc1 {A fine spot for the rook made possible by White's last and now Qa4 would further inconvenience Black's development, after which Bb5 or even Be5 might be possible to further increase the pressure.} Nb6 10. Ne5 ({Heading forwards with the simple ideas of Bb5+ and Qh5, although we should note that the engines are also quite drawn to the idea of annexing space with} 10. h4 $5 {, which would be very modern, as well as consistent with having such a fine bishop on b2.}) 10... Bd6 11. Bb5+ Kf8 ({Not an easy check for Black to deal with, as we might quickly appreciate from} 11... Bd7 $2 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Qg4 {.}) 12. Qh5 {Threatening mate and while Black's king is far from happy, White's will be very safe on g1, after which it might well be time to expand with f2-f4. Already we can safely say that White enjoys excellent play for the pawn.} Be6 $2 13. f4 $1 {White simply castled in Navara-Skvortsov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, but the immediate advance would have been even stronger, preparing to drive the defender away from e6 and perhaps even get the pawn all the way to f6.} *

