1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nd7 9. Rc1 {A fine spot for the rook made possible by White's last and now Qa4 would further inconvenience Black's development, after which Bb5 or even Be5 might be possible to further increase the pressure.} Nf6 $6 10. Bb5+ Bd7 ({Allowing Black the chance to save his structure, but} 10... Nd7 $2 11. Ne5 {would unsurprisingly not make for good news for him.}) 11. Bxf6 gxf6 ({Destroying Black's kingside for good as} 11... Qxf6 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 13. Qa4+ Kd8 14. Qa5+ {is scarcely now an option for him.}) 12. Bxd7+ $1 ({Here White went} 12. Nd4 {in Kuzubov-Schreiner, Heraklion 2017, going on to win a fine game, but it seems that an immediate exchange of bishops is more precise.}) 12... Qxd7 13. Nd4 {Just look at Black's structure! It's pretty grim and he can no longer deflect the white knight to b5. Meanwhile Qf3 is on the way and the king may take up station on g1 or even e2.} *

