1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} f6 9. Nd4 {White has been kept out of e5, but that's no reason to give up on the ideas of Bb5+ and Qh5+. Here too with Black fairly weak on the light squares, Bd3 will likely also ask some fairly pointed questions.} a6 $6 {White now went 10.Qc2 in Truyens-Prokopets, correspondence 2019, and could probably have done even better:} 10. Bd3 $1 {Now Qh5+ is a definite threat and Rc1 also on the way. Black is, of course, already somewhat behind in development and should probably elect to allow the check, move the king and suffer.} g6 $6 11. Qc2 {Only now! White enjoys superb compensation and a large initiative: Rc1 will come with tempo and h4-h5 is about to smash into the flimsy black kingside.} *

