1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nc6 {The main line and likely best try.} 9. Rc1 {Involving the rook at the earliest opportunity and putting ideas of Bb5, ideally followed by Ne5 or Nd4, high on the agenda.} a6 10. Bd3 $5 ({A small change of approach now that b5 has been taken away from the bishop. White has much more often gone} 10. Nd4 {here when the main debate has been around} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bf5 12. Be2 {, after which White may look to expand on the kingside with g2-g4. Instead, 10.Bd3 retains pieces, gives White a second attractively-placed bishop and continues to ask Black what he's going to do about g7.}) 10... f6 $6 11. Qc2 {Simply threatening to take on h7 then check on g6, against which the attempted cure is far worse than the disease for Black.} g6 $2 12. h4 $1 Bg4 $2 ({All of a sudden} 12... Z0 13. h5 {is a significant threat. Black is simply in serious trouble, in part because he can't cover h5 with his light-squared bishop.}) 13. Bxg6+ $1 {Taking full advantage of the loose piece on g4 to already obtain a pretty much decisive advantage.} *

