1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nc6 {The main line and likely best try.} 9. Rc1 {Involving the rook at the earliest opportunity and putting ideas of Bb5, ideally followed by Ne5 or Nd4, high on the agenda.} a6 10. Bd3 $5 ({A small change of approach now that b5 has been taken away from the bishop. White has much more often gone} 10. Nd4 {here when the main debate has been around} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bf5 12. Be2 {, after which White may look to expand on the kingside with g2-g4. Instead, 10.Bd3 retains pieces, gives White a second attractively-placed bishop and continues to ask Black what he's going to do about g7.}) 10... Bg4 11. h3 {) Prodding the bishop without delay as White definitely wouldn't mind receiving the bishop-pair after an exchange on f3.} Bh5 12. Qc2 {Unpinning while intending to obtain some pressure after Nd4 or Ne5. White also makes sure that the bishop on d3 is covered, which will prove useful in the event of any ...Bg6 ideas.} Rc8 13. Qb1 Bxf3 ({Calmly stepping off the open file to keep everything under control on the queenside. White is now ready to go Nd4 or even Bxh7 and would meet} 13... Bg6 {with} 14. O-O {followed by Rfe1, looking to break with e3-e4.}) 14. gxf3 {Now the king will be quite happy on e2 and Rg1 will be quick to increase the pressure against g7.} d4 $5 15. Rc4 {Striving to keep the dark-squared bishop involved in the game, with White all set to go Bxd4, after which his pressure on the light squares, not least against h7, should leave him slightly for choice.} *

