1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nc6 {The main line and likely best try.} 9. Rc1 {Involving the rook at the earliest opportunity and putting ideas of Bb5, ideally followed by Ne5 or Nd4, high on the agenda.} a6 10. Bd3 $5 ({A small change of approach now that b5 has been taken away from the bishop. White has much more often gone} 10. Nd4 {here when the main debate has been around} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bf5 12. Be2 {, after which White may look to expand on the kingside with g2-g4. Instead, 10.Bd3 retains pieces, gives White a second attractively-placed bishop and continues to ask Black what he's going to do about g7.}) 10... Bd6 11. h4 $5 ({Here} 11. Bxg7 $6 Rg8 {isn't so wise, since} 12. Be5 {is, of course, then impossible.}) ({As such, with} 11. h4 {White exploits the fact that} Bg4 $2 12. Bxg7 Rg8 13. Bb2 {would be on (the bishop on g4 obstructs the g-file) to seize some useful space. The h-pawn would, of course, like to get all the way to h6 and also currently facilitates ideas involving Ng5.}) 11... f6 12. h5 $5 ({Clamping down ahead of going Qc2 (the immediate} 12. Qc2 h5 13. Bg6+ {very much comes into consideration too), and now the engines recommend that Black should be brave and castle.}) 12... O-O $5 13. Nh4 Ne5 ({Continuing to focus on the light squares (only a very brave opponent would now want to see} 13... f5 14. h6 {), as White retains full and fairly attractive compensation. One idea is to take control of e5 with f2-f4, another a strong exchange sacrifice in the shape of 13...-- 14.Rxc6! bxc6 15.Qc2 , thereby hitting both c6 and h7. The queen may, of course, go to c2 in any case and White shouldn't mind if Black tries to activate the knight while he still can.}) 14. Bb1 {Now f2-f4 and Bd4 may follow and/or expansion with Nf5, after which h5-h6 ideas would continue to hang over the black king's head.} *

