1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nc6 {The main line and likely best try.} 9. Rc1 {Involving the rook at the earliest opportunity and putting ideas of Bb5, ideally followed by Ne5 or Nd4, high on the agenda.} a6 10. Bd3 $5 ({A small change of approach now that b5 has been taken away from the bishop. White has much more often gone} 10. Nd4 {here when the main debate has been around} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bf5 12. Be2 {, after which White may look to expand on the kingside with g2-g4. Instead, 10.Bd3 retains pieces, gives White a second attractively-placed bishop and continues to ask Black what he's going to do about g7.}) 10... Be7 $5 {A critical response, since White pretty much now must accept the pawn before ...Bf6 lands.} 11. Bxg7 $1 {An important pawn to snaffle when the bishop can make it out via e5.} Rg8 12. Be5 $1 Nxe5 ({Heading for g3. A key point is, of course, that} 12... Rxg2 $2 13. Bg3 {would entomb the black rook.}) 13. Nxe5 {White threatens not only Bxh7, but Qh5 to take full advantage of Black's broken-up kingside.} Qd6 14. Qh5 {Keeping up the pressure even against Black's improved defence.} Qf6 15. f4 {Shoring up the powerful knight to deal with the threat on g5.} Rxg2 16. Qf3 $5 ({Spurning the h7-pawn, as after taking this pawn the position is simply extremely unclear after} 16. Qxh7 Be6 17. h4 {. Instead, White forks the rook and big pawn on d5, while provoking a certain check.}) 16... Qh4+ 17. Kd1 Bg4 $5 ({The king heads towards safety on the queenside and} 17... Rxh2 $6 18. Kc2 {would definitely leave White with a promising initiative. As such, Black should probably play for simplification, be it via a queen exchange on f2 (which leaves h7 hanging and White able to claim the g-file), or with the aid of a small tactical and forcing idea:}) 18. Nxg4 Qxg4 19. Qxg4 Rxg4 20. Bxh7 Z0 ({The dust settles to leave White with the more active bishop and a potentially useful passed h-pawn. There are also ideas of Rc7 and, of course,} 20... Kd7 $4 21. Bf5+ {would not be wise for Black. He should be able to hold with care and precision, but White's more harmonious position is definitely the easier to handle at this stage.}) *

