1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nc6 {The main line and likely best try.} 9. Rc1 {Involving the rook at the earliest opportunity and putting ideas of Bb5, ideally followed by Ne5 or Nd4, high on the agenda.} Qd6 $5 10. Bb5 ({Pinning after all, in contrast to which White was slightly frustrated by} 10. Nd4 a6 {in Andersen-Agdestein, Helsingor 2018. The text move prepares not only to castle, but again to leap forwards with Ne5 if allowed.}) 10... a6 11. Ba4 {Maintaining an important bishop and the threat of Ne5.} f6 12. O-O {Quickly housing the king as now White has ideas of not just Nd4, but e3-e4 in conjunction with Re1 to quickly pose problems for the black king.} Be7 13. Bd4 {Here too, White appears to have decent, lasting compensation. White would now quite like to go Bc5 followed by Nd4, keeping Black under some pressure, while any ...Bg4 raid can be met by h2-h3 and perhaps even g2-g4 if needed.} *

