1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nc6 {The main line and likely best try.} 9. Rc1 {Involving the rook at the earliest opportunity and putting ideas of Bb5, ideally followed by Ne5 or Nd4, high on the agenda.} Qd6 $5 10. Bb5 ({Pinning after all, in contrast to which White was slightly frustrated by} 10. Nd4 a6 {in Andersen-Agdestein, Helsingor 2018. The text move prepares not only to castle, but again to leap forwards with Ne5 if allowed.}) 10... Bd7 11. O-O {Simply does it and now Re1 followed by e3-e4 is very much on the agenda.} Be7 $6 12. Bxg7 $1 {White should be brave and annex the pawn.} Rg8 13. Bd4 {A good retreat square, as White clearly doesn't object to exchanges on d4 and d7, and may now again have ideas of Bc5.} Bh3 14. g3 $1 (14. Ne1 {followed by Qf3 is also possible, but this is a strong exchange sacrifice.}) 14... Bxf1 15. Qxf1 Z0 ({White enjoys the far more harmonious position and superb compensation. Ne5 is imminent, the queen will take up a great role on h3 or d3 (or even a6 in the event of} 15... O-O-O $2 16. Bxc6 {), and just where is the black king going to find sanctuary?}) *

