1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 e6 {A solid and very respectable, if also slightly hesitant move, just the sort of one which might be played after a bit of thought by an opponent caught out by the Reti at club level.} 6. Nxd5 $5 ({This forcing response may surprise non-titled or at least un-up-to-date opponents. White more usually goes} 6. d4 {when} cxd4 7. exd4 {brings about an IQP position which also arises from the QGA and the Caro, Panov-Botvinnik. It's a decent choice if you're happy to play with an IQP, but the exchange on d5 also packs a certain punch as White prepares to bring the dark-squared bishop out to b2 and sometimes even in quite a radical manner.}) 6... exd5 7. b4 $5 ({A vigorous gambit, looking to break up Black's centre, as well as get in Bb2. If you prefer there's also nothing wrong with} 7. b3 {or, as we mentioned in passing in the first part of the course,}) (7. Bb5+ {followed by d2-d4 and O-O, likely leading to a fairly standard IQP (for Black) scenario.}) 7... cxb4 {Acceptance of the gambit must be critical, but is far from forced.} 8. Bb2 {Naturally White is quick to place the g7 point under some pressure and practice has shown that Black can easily get into trouble by attempting to block the long diagonal.} Nc6 {The main line and likely best try.} 9. Rc1 {Involving the rook at the earliest opportunity and putting ideas of Bb5, ideally followed by Ne5 or Nd4, high on the agenda.} f6 10. Nd4 {)} ({Increasing the pressure against c6 and clearing a path for the queen to h5. This looks like a better try than} 10. Bb5 Bd7 {, although Krikor Mekhitarian's 10.Bd3!? deserves attention when 10...Bd6 11.Qc2 g6?! 12.h4! was already excellent for White in Mekhitarian-Jakubowski, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023.}) 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Be6 12. Bd3 ({Supporting Qh5+, as well as simply preparing to castle. White has also tested} 12. Bb5+ {here, but it's not clear how much he then gains from} Kf7 13. Bd3 {, so we're quite happy to leave the king on e8 for now.}) 12... Bd6 13. Qh5+ {Once again, White should be happy enough to disturb the black king so.} Bf7 14. Qg4 {White attacks g7 and also has ideas of not just O-O and f2-f4, but Bc5 to exchange off Black's better bishop. We'll return to this rich position in the illustrative game Parligras-Gaehwiler [/variation/35967899], Skopje 2019.} *

