1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Ndb4 $6 7. d4 $1 Bf5 $2 ({White plays by analogy with 5...Nb4 6.d4 and should again be fairly happy to see Black's ambitious knight leap. Now} 7... cxd4 8. exd4 Bf5 9. O-O {would transpose to our coverage [/variation/35967319/#/9/w] of that line. In any case, White is all set to go a2-a3 and/or d4-d5 (not least in the case of 7...a6 8.Bxc6+ Nxc6 9.d5 ), as well as to castle.}) 8. d5 $1 {A powerful advance as White even provokes the check, having lined up a certain queen sacrifice.} Nc2+ 9. Qxc2 $1 Bxc2 10. dxc6 Z0 ({White threatens both cxb7+ and c6-c7+, while} 10... bxc6 11. Bxc6+ {would also regain the queen. Quite simply, Black has nothing better than 10...a6 11.c7+ and coming out a clear piece down.}) *

