1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Ndb4 $6 7. d4 $1 e6 ({White plays by analogy with 5...Nb4 6.d4 and should again be fairly happy to see Black's ambitious knight leap. Now} 7... cxd4 8. exd4 Bf5 9. O-O {would transpose to our coverage [/variation/35967319/#/9/w] of that line. In any case, White is all set to go a2-a3 and/or d4-d5 (not least in the case of 7...a6 8.Bxc6+ Nxc6 9.d5 ), as well as to castle.}) 8. a3 {Driving the knight back before Black can ask any questions himself with ...a6.} Nd5 9. O-O Nxc3 ({Calmly housing the king ahead of looking to expand with e3-e4, while} 9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 Bd7 11. Qd3 {would leave White with pressure down the d-file and a pleasant edge.}) 10. bxc3 Be7 11. e4 O-O ({Threatening} 11... Z0 12. d5 {as White enjoys a promising version of a Semi-Tarrasch thanks to Black's loss of tempi with his knight.}) 12. Re1 {White's strong centre supplies a pleasant advantage. Bf4 may follow or even Ba4-c2 and Qd3, looking to build up a strong attack on the kingside.} *

