1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... e6 {A slightly ugly, but also pretty solid move for Black.} 7. Ne5 ({White plays to inflict doubled c-pawns on Black and without having to give up bishop for knight in the process. The main alternative is} 7. O-O Be7 8. d4 cxd4 9. exd4 {, transposing to an unbalanced IQP scenario and line of the Panov-Botvinnik.}) 7... Qc7 8. Nxc6 bxc6 ({Carrying out the structural threat while preparing to meet} 8... a6 {with} 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Qa4 {, when after} Bd7 {only} 11. Nd4 $1 cxd4 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd4 {leaves White a clear pawn up.}) 9. Be2 {Tucking the bishop back inside the pawn chain, while intending to fianchetto the queen's bishop which may even be prefaced by a preliminary Qc2 or Na4 to avoid any knight exchange on c3.} Be7 10. O-O {White sensibly housed the king so before looking to develop the queenside in Taimanov-Mukhitdinov, Voroshilovgrad 1955.} O-O 11. b3 $5 ({Taimanov preferred} 11. Na4 {when} Bd6 {might have been slightly annoying, but White can fianchetto so without any preparation here. Bb2 and Rc1 are on their way, beginning to highlight Black's weaknesses down the c-file.}) 11... Nxc3 12. dxc3 {White is now set to obtain a pleasant set-up after Bb2, c3-c4 and Qc2, with potential play against the black kingside and/or c6.} a5 $5 13. a4 {A big move as it leaves b3 slightly weak, but it does fix the weaknesses on a5 and c5. White is now set to go Qc2, Bb2 and c3-c4, after which Bd3 might follow or Rad1 and f2-f4.} *

