1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... e6 {A slightly ugly, but also pretty solid move for Black.} 7. Ne5 ({White plays to inflict doubled c-pawns on Black and without having to give up bishop for knight in the process. The main alternative is} 7. O-O Be7 8. d4 cxd4 9. exd4 {, transposing to an unbalanced IQP scenario and line of the Panov-Botvinnik.}) 7... Bd7 8. Nxc6 {Inflicting the doubled pawns, although Black doesn't now also have to be saddled with a bad light-squared bishop.} Bxc6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. b3 $5 {Fianchettoing without delay as White is actually fairly happy to provoke an exchange on c3. If Black now completes development along straightforward lines, White will now go Bb2 followed by O-O and Na4.} Nb4 11. O-O Be7 ({Naturally White has no desire to see ...Nd3 arrive with check, and can now consider meeting} 11... Nd3 {with} 12. Qg4 $5 {, as well as simply 12.Na4 and Bb2.}) 12. Bb2 Nd3 13. Na4 {Covering the bishop while unfurling an attack on g7. Despite the hole on d3, White should be slightly for choice, with Qc2 on the way and one other pretty useful plan that of Bc3 and Nb2, aiming to exchange Black's best minor piece.} *

