1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... e6 {A slightly ugly, but also pretty solid move for Black.} 7. Ne5 ({White plays to inflict doubled c-pawns on Black and without having to give up bishop for knight in the process. The main alternative is} 7. O-O Be7 8. d4 cxd4 9. exd4 {, transposing to an unbalanced IQP scenario and line of the Panov-Botvinnik.}) 7... Bd7 8. Nxc6 {Inflicting the doubled pawns, although Black doesn't now also have to be saddled with a bad light-squared bishop.} Bxc6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. b3 $5 {Fianchettoing without delay as White is actually fairly happy to provoke an exchange on c3. If Black now completes development along straightforward lines, White will now go Bb2 followed by O-O and Na4.} Nxc3 11. dxc3 {) White would now like to exchange on d8, expand with c3-c4 and then complete development with Bb2 and Ke2, perhaps followed by kingside expansion. White is also able to castle and after c3-c4 may begin to target Black's weaknesses, not least with Qf3.} Qa5 $5 12. Bd2 {Breaking the pin and preparing to drive the queen back with c3-c4, after which the bishop can always relocate to c3.} c4 $5 {This must be critical, offering a pawn to remain active and hoping to obtain targets on the queenside.} 13. Qf3 {White calmly ignores the pawn and instead creates a major threat.} Qb6 14. O-O ({Completing development looks clearer than} 14. bxc4 Rd8 {. White is now ready to seize the initiative with Rfb1, after which bxc4 may become a strong concept.}) 14... cxb3 15. axb3 Be7 16. c4 {Black is very solid here, but at least his queenside pawns are split while the b-pawn remains taboo due to the pressure against c6. White can always follow up with Rfb1 if required and has two useful plans: Ba5 to disturb the black queen followed by Ra2-d2, and Bc3 looking to obtain some pressure against g7.} *

