1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... e6 {A slightly ugly, but also pretty solid move for Black.} 7. Ne5 ({White plays to inflict doubled c-pawns on Black and without having to give up bishop for knight in the process. The main alternative is} 7. O-O Be7 8. d4 cxd4 9. exd4 {, transposing to an unbalanced IQP scenario and line of the Panov-Botvinnik.}) 7... Bd7 8. Nxc6 {Inflicting the doubled pawns, although Black doesn't now also have to be saddled with a bad light-squared bishop.} Bxc6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. b3 $5 {Fianchettoing without delay as White is actually fairly happy to provoke an exchange on c3. If Black now completes development along straightforward lines, White will now go Bb2 followed by O-O and Na4.} Nxc3 11. dxc3 {White would now like to exchange on d8, expand with c3-c4 and then complete development with Bb2 and Ke2, perhaps followed by kingside expansion. White is also able to castle and after c3-c4 may begin to target Black's weaknesses, not least with Qf3.} Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 13. Kc2 {A very safe spot for the king and White may now follow up with c3-c4 or even e3-e4, aiming to keep the c4-square open for the king in the event that all the rooks could be traded.} Be7 14. e4 $1 h5 15. Be3 {This left White with a pleasant edge in Kramnik-Anand, Monaco (blindfold) 2011, no less where Rad1 was on the way, after which White might look to double with Rd3 and Rhd1. As well as gradually targeting the vulnerable c5-pawn, White may look to cramp Black with a timely e4-e5, after which the endgame could become quite uncomfortable to defend.} *

