1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nc7 $6 7. Bxc6+ {White is quite happy to be provoked and the black knight not especially happy on c7.} bxc6 8. Qa4 {This is why White was happy to be provoked as c6 can quickly be targeted (likewise, 6...a6?! would be well met by 7.Bxc6+ bxc6 8.Qa4 ).} Bb7 9. O-O {Calmly housing the king and allowing White to consider plans of Rd1, d2-d3 and e3-e4, as well as simply b2-b3 and Ba3, all the while as Black suffers with not just the doubled pawns, but some rather miserable minor pieces too.} e6 10. b3 Be7 $6 ({White elects to head straight for targeting the vulnerable front c-pawn and now even} 10... Na6 $5 11. Rd1 Nb4 12. d4 $1 {seems to leave White clearly for choice.}) 11. Ba3 O-O 12. Ne4 {With Rfc1 and Qc4 always able to follow, White was already winning a clear pawn in Ghosh-Zakhartsov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023.} *

