1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Bg4 $6 7. Qa4 {The double-attack already leaves Black in some trouble.} Ndb4 8. Bxc6+ ({Now} 8. Ne5 Bd7 {wasn't too bad for Black in Sadzikowski-Gawor, Krakow 2018, but White can improve with either 8.a3!? Nd3+ 9.Ke2 or a simple approach:}) {Inflicting doubled pawns after all unless Black prefers to lose a piece.} 8... bxc6 9. Ne5 {Continuing to hit the bishop with tempo while also supplying some cover to d3. White should be pretty happy here with O-O then a2-a3 on the way.} *

