1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Qc7 ({The safest square if Black wants to move the queen, since} 7... Qb6 8. Rb1 a6 9. Qa4 $1 {would be slightly awkward, as would be 7...Qd6 8.d4 .}) 8. d4 {Expanding without delay as White aims to obtain a quick lead in development and initiative. While allowing d4-d5 then going ... a6 may not be too terrible for Black, he is now forced to consider the ideas of that and Ne5, as well as White simply improving his position with O-O and e3-e4 or even Ba3.} cxd4 9. exd4 $1 a6 $5 ({The right way to recapture as White wants to seize the initiative and now} 9... Z0 10. d5 {is a definite threat, since} a6 11. Qa4 Rb8 {would run into} 12. Bf4 {. White is also all set to castle then seize some useful space with c3-c4.}) 10. Ba4 {A good case can also be made for dropping the bishop back to d3, but this way White maintains the pin and so may well be able, if allowed, to go d4-d5 after castling.} e6 ({Meanwhile, after} 10... b5 11. Bc2 {the bishop can always head to e4 if needed, while White would also be looking to target the extended black queenside with a2-a4.}) 11. O-O Be7 {We've followed the game Zakhartsov-Seyb, Riga 2018, where White might have made a slightly surprised but also fairly strong retreat:} 12. Bc2 $5 O-O ({White can now consider meeting} 12... b5 {with} 13. d5 {and is also ready to support that potential breakthrough with Re1 and/or c3-c4, while Ng5 is another useful idea since Black may find himself a little vulnerable on h7.}) 13. Qd3 g6 ({With tempo. Now} 13... f5 14. Re1 {wouldn't be positionally great for Black.}) 14. Bh6 {Again, developing a tempo.} Re8 15. Rfe1 {White enjoys a useful initiative and advantage. Bb3 may help to put the d4-d5 break back on the agenda, there's always Rad1, Ng5-e4 might well help to highlight Black's weaknesses and White can very much attack too with h2-h4-h5, quite possibly even immediately.} *

