1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Qc7 ({The safest square if Black wants to move the queen, since} 7... Qb6 8. Rb1 a6 9. Qa4 $1 {would be slightly awkward, as would be 7...Qd6 8.d4 .}) 8. d4 {Expanding without delay as White aims to obtain a quick lead in development and initiative. While allowing d4-d5 then going ... a6 may not be too terrible for Black, he is now forced to consider the ideas of that and Ne5, as well as White simply improving his position with O-O and e3-e4 or even Ba3.} e6 9. O-O Bd6 ({Calmly housing the king. You may now be happy to expand with e3-e4 and enjoy the resulting centre and possible small advantage, although it's also possible to continue by exerting piece pressure, with Ne5, Ba3 or} 9... a6 $6 10. Bxc6+ $1 Qxc6 11. Ne5 {followed by swinging the white queen into play.}) 10. Ba3 b6 ({White is happy to maintain the pawn on d4 and may now meet} 10... cxd4 {with} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. cxd4 {and then perhaps Ng5-e4 to clamp down to a certain extent.}) 11. dxc5 $1 bxc5 ({White slightly weakens Black on c5 ahead of aiming to send his knight forwards with} 11... Bxc5 $6 12. Bxc5 bxc5 13. Ng5 {, a manoeuvre possible even if Black retains the bishops.}) 12. Ng5 $1 Bb7 $6 ({A strong advance, refusing to fear} 12... Bxh2+ $2 13. Kh1 {when White threatens Qh5 and c5 remains vulnerable while White maintains a strong initiative after} Bd6 14. Ne4 {, for example} Be7 15. Qa4 $1 {. White is also ready to meet 12...O-O with 13.Qh5 h6 14.Ne4 which should supply at least a pull, if better that for Black than trying to be too ambitious with his bishops.}) 13. Ne4 $1 Bxh2+ $6 ({Hitting the bishop as well as c5, while White might now even meet} 13... O-O-O {with} 14. Qa4 $5 {and an attack, as well as just 14.Qh5 .}) 14. Kh1 O-O ({The king is quite safe here and meanwhile both Bxc5 and f2-f4 are sizeable threats, while} 14... Rd8 15. Qh5 {wouldn't especially help Black.}) 15. f4 {This was already very good for White in Rusev-Nabaty, Baku 2016, since he was ready to take on c5 and with the black bishop rather stranded behind enemy lines.} *

