1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Qc7 ({The safest square if Black wants to move the queen, since} 7... Qb6 8. Rb1 a6 9. Qa4 $1 {would be slightly awkward, as would be 7...Qd6 8.d4 .}) 8. d4 {Expanding without delay as White aims to obtain a quick lead in development and initiative. While allowing d4-d5 then going ... a6 may not be too terrible for Black, he is now forced to consider the ideas of that and Ne5, as well as White simply improving his position with O-O and e3-e4 or even Ba3.} e6 9. O-O Be7 ({Calmly housing the king. You may now be happy to expand with e3-e4 and enjoy the resulting centre and possible small advantage, although it's also possible to continue by exerting piece pressure, with Ne5, Ba3 or} 9... a6 $6 10. Bxc6+ $1 Qxc6 11. Ne5 {followed by swinging the white queen into play.}) 10. Ne5 $5 ({A decent alternative to the obvious} 10. e4 {as White threatens to increase the pressure with Qa4, as well as obtain a useful initiative after} a6 $6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Ba3 {.}) 10... O-O 11. Bxc6 $1 {Playing for a small structural advantage and against Black's light-squared bishop.} bxc6 12. Qa4 {Pressing against c6, ruling out ...Ba6 possibilities and also hoping to obtain some pressure while clamping down on the c-file with Nd3, and if ...cxd4; cxd4.} Bd6 $5 13. Ba3 $5 ({White now opted for} 13. f4 {in Abasov-Seel, German Bundesliga 2019, which was sensible. It's also possible to provoke an opposite-coloured bishop scenario:}) 13... Bxe5 ({White is now all set to go Nf3 when ...cxd4; cxd4 will supply a definite clamp. Even} 13... Z0 14. Nc4 $5 {may be a threat, since both Black's bishop and c5 would be in trouble after} Bxh2+ 15. Kh1 {.}) 14. dxe5 {White now threatens to take on c5 and also wouldn't mind getting to go Rfd1-d6.} Qxe5 15. Qxc6 {Attacking both c5 and the rook, thereby leaving Black with only a choice of how to give up a pawn.} Qd5 $5 16. Qxd5 exd5 17. Bxc5 {Black may be able to eventually hold, but can be tortured for quite some time, since White's pressure against a7 will mean that he can take control of the b-file with Rfb1 (the rook on a1 keeps the a-pawn covered) followed by Rb4 or even possibly Rb5 or Rb7 on the way.} *

