1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Bd7 8. O-O {Housing the king as there's no need to rush with d2-d4 here, with White also happy to provoke ... a6.} a6 9. Bxc6 $5 ({Playing for a small pull. White has also done quite well with} 9. Be2 {followed by} e5 10. d4 {or 9...e6 10.Rb1 .}) 9... Bxc6 10. Ne5 {Threatening structural ruin, as well as expansion through c3-c4 and Bb2.} Rc8 $6 {This was tried in Steinhauser-Milgram, correspondence 1995, where White should just have continued the plan:} 11. c4 e6 12. Bb2 {Black has definite issues on g7 and White may simply increase the pressure with Rb1 and Qg4 or even Qh5. Meanwhile the light-squared bishop can't really run away:} Be4 $6 13. d3 Bg6 14. Qa4+ {Black has secured his kingside, but at a cost: he must either ditch a pawn or move the king when Rab1 will follow with a clear advantage for White.} *

