1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Bd7 8. O-O {Housing the king as there's no need to rush with d2-d4 here, with White also happy to provoke ... a6.} a6 9. Bxc6 $5 ({Playing for a small pull. White has also done quite well with} 9. Be2 {followed by} e5 10. d4 {or 9...e6 10.Rb1 .}) 9... Bxc6 10. Ne5 {Threatening structural ruin, as well as expansion through c3-c4 and Bb2.} Qd5 11. Nxc6 {A rather necessary exchange, if also one White was happy to make in any case.} Qxc6 12. c4 {Taking control of d5 and b5 while clearing the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop.} e6 13. Bb2 {Eyeing g7. White may not be able to take the pawn immediately, but a preliminary Qh5 may threaten to do so (the queen may also head to g4 or simply sit on c2 or e2). This position looks slightly more pleasant for White with the extra central pawn and some simple improving moves available in Rab1, Bc3, a2-a4-a5 and f2-f4.} *

