1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Bd7 8. O-O {Housing the king as there's no need to rush with d2-d4 here, with White also happy to provoke ... a6.} g6 {An ambitious, Grünfeld-like choice and now White is able to seize the initiative.} 9. Ba3 $1 b6 ({Simply threatening the pawn on c5. Black's position would now look a little strange after} 9... e6 10. Rb1 {or 9...Qa5 10.Qb3 , as Caruana once got to play.}) 10. d4 {Only expanding in the centre now that doing so comes with tempo.} Bg7 $5 11. dxc5 O-O ({The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating, as they say, and now} 11... Bxc3 $4 12. Rc1 {would cost Black material down the c-file.}) 12. Qa4 $1 {This created a threat on the c-file and also left White set to go Nd4, which meant that Black didn't have enough for the pawn in Landa-Saduakassova, Nakhchivan 2013.} *

