1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Bd7 8. O-O {Housing the king as there's no need to rush with d2-d4 here, with White also happy to provoke ... a6.} e6 {Black's most common and solid defence.} 9. d4 Bd6 ({There's nothing better here than this useful central advance. Now if} 9... a6 {the bishop can simply regroup with} 10. Bd3 {. Meanwhile White may expand with e3-e4 or perhaps prefer to probe, beginning with Rb1.}) 10. Ba3 $5 ({Here, too,} 10. Rb1 {is an option, but the bishop development pins and creates the option of dxc5. It also enables White to consider the idea of Nd2-e4 and now 10...Qa5 11.Qa4 would keep up the pressure, as would 10...Qe7 11.Bd3 , maintaining a fair degree of control and angling for Qb1.}) 10... Qc7 $5 11. dxc5 ({White now gambited the h-pawn with} 11. Nd2 {in Piasetski-Sethuraman, Hanoi 2018, where it was also possible just to take on c5.}) 11... Be7 12. Rb1 {Castling queenside will now be rather risky for Black and White may now aim to increase the pressure with Qb3, Rfd1 and Nd4, with both Nd2-e4 and Qc2 followed by Bd3 other plans to very much consider depending on how Black responds.} *

