1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Bd7 8. O-O {Housing the king as there's no need to rush with d2-d4 here, with White also happy to provoke ... a6.} e6 {Black's most common and solid defence.} 9. d4 Be7 ({There's nothing better here than this useful central advance. Now if} 9... a6 {the bishop can simply regroup with} 10. Bd3 {. Meanwhile White may expand with e3-e4 or perhaps prefer to probe, beginning with Rb1.}) 10. Rb1 $5 (10. e4 {has been more popular and can scarcely be a bad move, of course, but here we're happy to maintain control and begin to probe, with b7 and h7 targets after any subsequent Bd3.}) 10... cxd4 $6 11. exd4 $1 {) Our favourite, dynamic recapture. The bishop will now leap back to d3 and Black may find himself coming under pressure on b7, as well as h7.} O-O 12. Bd3 b6 13. Re1 {White enjoys a pleasant attacking scenario and definite edge. Bf4 may follow, although White may also be tempted to gambit a pawn with h2-h4. That creates ideas of both Ng5 and h4-h5-h6, as well as intending ... Bxh4; Nxh4 Qxh4; Rb5 followed by Bg5 or Rh5.} *

