1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 ({Natural development from Black and a fairly popular move at all levels. Now} 6. d4 e6 {would take play into an important line of the Semi-Tarrasch.}) {White continues to develop rapidly and this is a very useful pin, already intending to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Qa4 if allowed.} 6... Nxc3 {Black's most popular choice in practice, altering the structure.} 7. bxc3 {The dynamic recapture, keeping ideas of Ne5 and Bxc6+ high on the agenda, while also intending to seize an early initiative with O-O then d2-d4. White has scored very well from here in practice, with Black usually now attempting to avoid being saddled with doubled c-pawns.} Bd7 8. O-O {Housing the king as there's no need to rush with d2-d4 here, with White also happy to provoke ... a6.} e6 {Black's most common and solid defence.} 9. d4 Be7 ({There's nothing better here than this useful central advance. Now if} 9... a6 {the bishop can simply regroup with} 10. Bd3 {. Meanwhile White may expand with e3-e4 or perhaps prefer to probe, beginning with Rb1.}) 10. Rb1 $5 (10. e4 {has been more popular and can scarcely be a bad move, of course, but here we're happy to maintain control and begin to probe, with b7 and h7 targets after any subsequent Bd3.}) 10... O-O 11. Bd3 {Unfurling an attack on b7, while hoping that White will be able to get something going on the kingside at some point.} Qc7 {Covering b7. This is also how Jeffery Xiong has met both 11.Qe2 and 11.Re1 in this line.} 12. Qe2 {Calmly does it as White prepares to maintain control and slowly edge forwards with Bd2 followed by e3-e4, with a quick h2-h4 another possible aggressive advance.} Rfd8 13. h4 $5 ({A very modern, engine-approved advance. Instead, White was happy to proceed gradually with} 13. Bd2 Be8 {(preventing e3-e4 due to the pressure against d4)} 14. Rfc1 {in Nei-Barsauskas, Vilnius 1959, which was hardly a bad plan, but Black was clearly pretty solidly placed.}) ({Instead,} 13. h4 {continues to aim to provoke} cxd4 $6 14. exd4 {while preparing to ram the pawn all the way up to h6 if allowed.}) 13... Rac8 14. h5 {Black must either now allow White to cause long-term problems on the kingside with h5-h6 or prevent that advance entirely.} h6 15. e4 $1 cxd4 $2 ({A powerful follow-up, simply intending e4-e5 and Qe4. Like the engines we slightly prefer White here, as with} 15... e5 16. d5 {, and do note too that we don't have to allow Black's knight into b4.}) 16. e5 $1 ({Much stronger than} 16. cxd4 $6 Nb4 {as now the threat of Qe4 is simply a very strong one and Black in some trouble, since 16...f5 fails to close lines in view of 17.exf6 Bxf6 18.Qe4 .}) *

