ut of the way of ...Ng4.} 10. Qd2 {has been overwhelmingly a more popular square for the queen over the years. However, White is in no rush to exchange the dark-squared bishops, and if Black now goes ...Nd7-c5, the queen may simply retreat to c2, thereby keeping e4 secure, just as we'll see White doing in our mainline.}) 10... Bd7 11. O-O {Naturally White wants to get the king safe and connect the rooks before expanding anywhere.} Bc6 12. b4 $5 {By analogy with what might be considered the main line ( 10...Nd7 11.O-O Nc5 12.Qc2 ), 12.Rad1 is also a good move, but this is a tempting advance before going Rad1 and maybe even f2-f4. Now 12...a5?! 13.b5! Bd7 14.Na4 would be a bit uncomfortable for Black, who in any case, is slightly low on counterplay.} Nd7 13. Rad1 $1 ({The right square for this rook, rather than create some targets for Black with} 13. b5 $6 Ne5 {. Note too that the e-pawn isn't hanging here, as 13...Bxc3? 14.Qxc3 Bxe4 15.Bh6 would win the exchange.}) 13... b6 14. Bd4 $1 ({Only now does White offer a timely exchange of dark-squared bishop, with Black a little passive, and because the alternative} 14. f4 $6 {allows} Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Bxe4 {with Bh6 no longer possible.}) 14... a5 15. a3 ({Now White is happy to support b4 and so maintain control of c5, although the fearless engines prefer to go} 15. b5 $5 Bb7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. f4 {followed by throwing the kitchen sink at the black kingside.}) 15... Bxd4 16. Qxd4 axb4 17. axb4 Ra3 18. f4 $1 {This supplied a pleasant pull for White in both Hellers-Petursson, Brocco 1990, and Bjerre-Chatalbashev, Danish Championship, Svendborg 2023. Just like in the 10...Nd7 main line [/variation/35967409/#/10/b], Bg4 is very much a possibility to potentially exchange off a decent defender and to support e4-e5 ideas, while here White might well also consider being quite direct with Rd3-h3 or even first h2-h4-h5.} *

