ut of the way of ...Ng4.} 10. Qd2 {has been overwhelmingly a more popular square for the queen over the years. However, White is in no rush to exchange the dark-squared bishops, and if Black now goes ...Nd7-c5, the queen may simply retreat to c2, thereby keeping e4 secure, just as we'll see White doing in our mainline.}) 10... Be6 11. Bd4 $5 {White spies that Black's plan is likely to be ...Nd7 and prepares to meet that with an exchange of dark-squared bishops. Black doesn't have to go ...Nd7, but how else can he free his position? After all, ...Rc8 can always be met easily enough by b2-b3.} Nd7 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. O-O Qb6 ({An alternative role for the queen shouldn't trouble White: Naturally White exchanges the bishops before housing the king and looking to expand with f2-f4. Now} 13... Ne5 {can be met by} 14. Qd4 {or even 14.Qe3 , while 13...Qa5 14.b3 transposes to our coverage [/variation/36008143/#/14/b] with 11...Qa5 12.O-O.}) 14. b3 {Keeping those cramping queenside pawns secure. White may now simply go Kh1 and f2-f4, with a timely Nd5 another idea to bear in mind.} f5 $6 15. exf5 $1 {Giving up part of the bind as White prepares to target Black down the e-file and on the kingside.} Bxf5 16. Qd2 Nf6 17. Bf3 $1 {With Rfe1 and Rad1 on their way, possibly followed by Re3, Black remained low on counterplay and with the more vulnerable structure in Hovhannisyan-Grigoryan, Yerevan 2016.} *

