1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Nc6 5. d4 ({Now} 5. e5 $6 Ng4 {would leave White looking overextended, so we should prefer the other central advance.}) {Clearly, Black doesn't want to allow d4-d5, so will surely now exchange.} 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White has erected the famous Maroczy Bind with the pawns on c4 and e4 clamping down firmly on the d5-square, thereby making it tricky for Black to fully free his position. White is now all set to complete development with Be3, Be2 and O-O, and Black must decide how to respond.} d6 ({Note that} 6... Bg7 {(threatening 7...Nxe4)} 7. Be3 {transposes to our mainline [/variation/35967414/#/7/w], 4...Bg7 5.d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7.Be3, while 6...Nxd4 7.Qxd4 (threatening 8.e5) 7...d6 8.Be2 is the same as 6...d6 7.Be2 Nxd4 8.Qxd4 to which we'll now come on to.}) 7. Be2 ({An important move, taking control of the g4-square (} 7. Be3 $6 Ng4 {wouldn't be wise), and now 7...Bg7 (threatening 8...Nxe4) 8.Be3 would again return play to our mainline [/variation/35967440/#/8/w] with 4...Bg7.}) 7... Nxd4 $5 {The Gurgenidze variation, exchanging knights before White has been able to bring the dark-squared bishop to e3.} 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 {A very natural square for the bishop and now White will drop the queen back to d3 when necessary, while also being ready to castle short and connect the rooks.} O-O 10. Qd3 $5 ({A modern try, stepping out of the way of ...Ng4.} 10. Qd2 {has been overwhelmingly a more popular square for the queen over the years. However, White is in no rush to exchange the dark-squared bishops, and if Black now goes ...Nd7-c5, the queen may simply retreat to c2, thereby keeping e4 secure, just as we'll see White doing in our mainline.}) 10... Be6 11. Bd4 $5 {White spies that Black's plan is likely to be ...Nd7 and prepares to meet that with an exchange of dark-squared bishops. Black doesn't have to go ...Nd7, but how else can he free his position? After all, ...Rc8 can always be met easily enough by b2-b3.} Qa5 12. O-O Rfc8 ({Sensibly getting out of the pin ahead of overprotecting c4 with b2-b3 and mobilising the f-pawn. Now we'll see} 12... Nd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. b3 {in the illustrative game Pranesh-Livaic [/variation/35967900], Stockholm 2023.}) 13. b3 Nd7 14. Bxg7 ({This exchange was, of course, the point of White's play, although the engines point out that} 14. Kh1 $5 {might also be considered.}) 14... Kxg7 15. f4 Nf6 ({Thematic expansion and already} 15... Z0 16. f5 {is a threat, since} Ne5 {can be easily met by} 17. Qg3 Bd7 18. Nd5 {when White would rather dominate the board. Observe too that 15...f6 would now be rather ugly when 16.Rab1!? a6 17.a4 would be a known method to keep Black's counterplay under control.}) 16. Kh1 ({Tucking the king out of the way of any checks. Jansa's old} 16. Rae1 {must also be a good move.}) 16... a6 {This was seen in Hracek-Hausrath, German Bundesliga 2022, where White didn't need to rush with f4-f5 and might first have kept Black's counterplay under control.} 17. a4 $1 {White would now like, if allowed, to support the central and kingside advances (f4-f5 and e4-e5) with Qg3 and Rad1, may also find a timely Bf3 a useful move.} Z0 ({We also need not fear weakening the b4-square:} 17... Qb4 18. f5 Bd7 19. fxg6 {Ripping open lines and threatening to annex f7 next if allowed, while 19...fxg6? would lose to the thematic blow 20.e5! dxe5 21.Rxf6 , and if 21...Kxf6 22.Nd5+ or 21...exf6 22.Qxd7+ .} hxg6 20. Rxf6 {Exploiting the unfortunate position of the black queen to make a strong exchange sacrifice.} exf6 21. Nd5 Qa5 22. Qd4 {With Rf1 on the way and complete control of the position, White enjoys more than enough play for the exchange.}) *

