1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Nc6 5. d4 ({Now} 5. e5 $6 Ng4 {would leave White looking overextended, so we should prefer the other central advance.}) {Clearly, Black doesn't want to allow d4-d5, so will surely now exchange.} 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White has erected the famous Maroczy Bind with the pawns on c4 and e4 clamping down firmly on the d5-square, thereby making it tricky for Black to fully free his position. White is now all set to complete development with Be3, Be2 and O-O, and Black must decide how to respond.} d6 ({Note that} 6... Bg7 {(threatening 7...Nxe4)} 7. Be3 {transposes to our mainline [/variation/35967414/#/7/w], 4...Bg7 5.d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7.Be3, while 6...Nxd4 7.Qxd4 (threatening 8.e5) 7...d6 8.Be2 is the same as 6...d6 7.Be2 Nxd4 8.Qxd4 to which we'll now come on to.}) 7. Be2 ({An important move, taking control of the g4-square (} 7. Be3 $6 Ng4 {wouldn't be wise), and now 7...Bg7 (threatening 8...Nxe4) 8.Be3 would again return play to our mainline [/variation/35967440/#/8/w] with 4...Bg7.}) 7... Nxd4 $5 {The Gurgenidze variation, exchanging knights before White has been able to bring the dark-squared bishop to e3.} 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 {A very natural square for the bishop and now White will drop the queen back to d3 when necessary, while also being ready to castle short and connect the rooks.} O-O 10. Qd3 $5 ({A modern try, stepping out of the way of ...Ng4.} 10. Qd2 {has been overwhelmingly a more popular square for the queen over the years. However, White is in no rush to exchange the dark-squared bishops, and if Black now goes ...Nd7-c5, the queen may simply retreat to c2, thereby keeping e4 secure, just as we'll see White doing in our mainline.}) 10... Ng4 11. Bxg4 {Naturally, White wants to preserve the dark-squared bishop and shouldn't mind conceding the bishop-pair so.} Bxg4 12. O-O {Housing the king ahead of preparing to deny Black the bishop-pair with Bd4, all the while their other bishop rather floats in mid-air doing little on g4.} Be6 13. Bd4 $1 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Qa5 15. b3 {While Black is quite solid, White has a small but pleasant edge. We may gradually arrange f2-f4 and always have a2-a4 to deny Black easy equality with ...b5. The queen's rook may sit happily enough on b1 as well as d1, or even come via e1 to e3 if you really want to be aggressive and attack with f2-f4-f5.} *

