1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Nc6 5. d4 ({Now} 5. e5 $6 Ng4 {would leave White looking overextended, so we should prefer the other central advance.}) {Clearly, Black doesn't want to allow d4-d5, so will surely now exchange.} 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White has erected the famous Maroczy Bind with the pawns on c4 and e4 clamping down firmly on the d5-square, thereby making it tricky for Black to fully free his position. White is now all set to complete development with Be3, Be2 and O-O, and Black must decide how to respond.} d6 ({Note that} 6... Bg7 {(threatening 7...Nxe4)} 7. Be3 {transposes to our mainline [/variation/35967414/#/7/w], 4...Bg7 5.d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7.Be3, while 6...Nxd4 7.Qxd4 (threatening 8.e5) 7...d6 8.Be2 is the same as 6...d6 7.Be2 Nxd4 8.Qxd4 to which we'll now come on to.}) 7. Be2 ({An important move, taking control of the g4-square (} 7. Be3 $6 Ng4 {wouldn't be wise), and now 7...Bg7 (threatening 8...Nxe4) 8.Be3 would again return play to our mainline [/variation/35967440/#/8/w] with 4...Bg7.}) 7... Nxd4 $5 {The Gurgenidze variation, exchanging knights before White has been able to bring the dark-squared bishop to e3.} 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 {A very natural square for the bishop and now White will drop the queen back to d3 when necessary, while also being ready to castle short and connect the rooks.} O-O 10. Qd3 $5 ({A modern try, stepping out of the way of ...Ng4.} 10. Qd2 {has been overwhelmingly a more popular square for the queen over the years. However, White is in no rush to exchange the dark-squared bishops, and if Black now goes ...Nd7-c5, the queen may simply retreat to c2, thereby keeping e4 secure, just as we'll see White doing in our mainline.}) 10... a5 {This also suggests that Black may want to go ...Nd7-c5, as well as ...a4, so again our favourite bishop manoeuvre is a good choice.} 11. Bd4 {)} ({Preparing to challenge the bishops, although} 11. O-O {, and if} a4 12. Bd4 {must also be a decent move order.}) 11... a4 $5 12. O-O Bd7 ({There's now little preventing us from expanding with f2-f4, as in the case of} 12... Be6 13. f4 {when} Rc8 14. b3 {would be nothing to fear.}) 13. b4 $1 ({This seems more promising than} 13. Rad1 {here. White simply seizes a useful fair degree of control over the queenside.}) 13... axb3 14. axb3 Bc6 15. b4 {White enjoyed a pleasant edge in Asadli-Fidalgo, Lisbon 2020, where a timely Nd5 was one plan. There was also nothing stopping White from going Rad1, followed by Qe3 and/or f2-f4, with ...Ra3 always being able to be easily sidestepped with Qc2.} *

