ut of the way of ...Ng4.} 10. Qd2 {has been overwhelmingly a more popular square for the queen over the years. However, White is in no rush to exchange the dark-squared bishops, and if Black now goes ...Nd7-c5, the queen may simply retreat to c2, thereby keeping e4 secure, just as we'll see White doing in our mainline.}) 10... a5 {This also suggests that Black may want to go ...Nd7-c5, as well as ...a4, so again our favourite bishop manoeuvre is a good choice.} 11. Bd4 ({Preparing to challenge the bishops, although} 11. O-O {, and if} a4 12. Bd4 {must also be a decent move order.}) 11... a4 $5 12. O-O Qa5 ({There's now little preventing us from expanding with f2-f4, as in the case of} 12... Be6 13. f4 {when} Rc8 14. b3 {would be nothing to fear.}) 13. f4 $1 Bg4 $5 ({Simply getting on with it. Now White may even be able to initiate some strong central play with Rad1 and e4-e5, as well as f4-f5. Now} 13... e5 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Be3 {must surely be at least a pleasant edge for White due to the weakened d5-square, if also perhaps a better try for Black than what we’ll examine next.}) 14. Rad1 $5 ({The queen's rook's favourite square in such lines and ever good preparation for e4-e5 when the d-file may well open (if though you prefer to maintain full control, do by all means consider} 14. Rab1 $5 {as an anti-...a3 device).}) 14... Bxe2 15. Qxe2 a3 {Destabilising the white queenside, but we should be fairly happy to have provoked this considering White's central coordination.} 16. e5 $1 ({Blowing open lines and seizing the initiative, while sidestepping} 16. b3 e5 $1 {. To be fair, it's all getting pretty murky now, though.}) 16... dxe5 17. fxe5 Nd7 18. b4 $1 Z0 ({This key follow-up ensured that Nd5 would come with tempo and so ensured that White had the initiative in Perez Ponsa-Fiorito, Villa Martelli 2021. Note too that} 18... Qd8 $4 19. e6 $1 {would now win material for White down the d-file. It may be worth seeing a few more moves: 18...Qxb4 19.Nd5 Qa5 Clearly forced, and now White settled for 20.Bc3 in the game, but certainly didn't have to: 20.Nxe7+ Kh8 21.Nd5 Retrieving the pawn and leaving White slightly for choice in a fairly wild position. White would like to take control with Kh1 and Bc3, and is not losing the e5-pawn: 21...Rae8 22.Bc3! Qc5+ 23.Kh1 Black can take on e5, but shouldn't have enough for the exchange after Bb4, since White's rooks will then be very active.}) *

