1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Nc6 5. d4 ({Now} 5. e5 $6 Ng4 {would leave White looking overextended, so we should prefer the other central advance.}) {Clearly, Black doesn't want to allow d4-d5, so will surely now exchange.} 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White has erected the famous Maroczy Bind with the pawns on c4 and e4 clamping down firmly on the d5-square, thereby making it tricky for Black to fully free his position. White is now all set to complete development with Be3, Be2 and O-O, and Black must decide how to respond.} d6 ({Note that} 6... Bg7 {(threatening 7...Nxe4)} 7. Be3 {transposes to our mainline [/variation/35967414/#/7/w], 4...Bg7 5.d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7.Be3, while 6...Nxd4 7.Qxd4 (threatening 8.e5) 7...d6 8.Be2 is the same as 6...d6 7.Be2 Nxd4 8.Qxd4 to which we'll now come on to.}) 7. Be2 ({An important move, taking control of the g4-square (} 7. Be3 $6 Ng4 {wouldn't be wise), and now 7...Bg7 (threatening 8...Nxe4) 8.Be3 would again return play to our mainline [/variation/35967440/#/8/w] with 4...Bg7.}) 7... Nxd4 $5 {The Gurgenidze variation, exchanging knights before White has been able to bring the dark-squared bishop to e3.} 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 {A very natural square for the bishop and now White will drop the queen back to d3 when necessary, while also being ready to castle short and connect the rooks.} O-O 10. Qd3 $5 ({A modern try, stepping out of the way of ...Ng4.} 10. Qd2 {has been overwhelmingly a more popular square for the queen over the years. However, White is in no rush to exchange the dark-squared bishops, and if Black now goes ...Nd7-c5, the queen may simply retreat to c2, thereby keeping e4 secure, just as we'll see White doing in our mainline.}) 10... Nd7 {Black wastes no time in sending his knight to arguably its favourite square in such structures, c5, unfurling the fianchettoed bishop in the process. Such a policy is, however, by no means forced.} 11. O-O $1 ({Calmly housing the king. We're less keen on} 11. Bd4 {here due to both} Bxd4 12. Qxd4 Qb6 {and 11...Nc5 12.Qe3 Bxd4 13.Qxd4 e5!? . Why allow Black easy counterplay when we don't need to?}) ({After} 11. O-O {, the move} a5 {can now just be met by} 12. Rad1 {as White limbers up for f2-f4.}) 11... Nc5 12. Qc2 {The best square for the queen, provoking Black into an attempt at grabbing the e-pawn. Meanwhile, Rad1 followed by f2-f4, or even b2-b4 is on the way.} b6 13. b4 $5 ({You can also go} 13. f3 {here, but unsurprisingly, we prefer this critical and consistent pawn sacrifice. If the knight retreats (e.g. 13...Nd7 ), White will tidy with 14.Rad1 followed by -- 15.a3 and/or 15.Bd4 , so acceptance is likely critical.}) 13... Bxc3 14. Qxc3 Nxe4 15. Qb2 {With a definite threat in Bh6, as well as potential pressure down the central files and even on the queenside.} Re8 {Sidestepping the threat of Bh6.} 16. a4 $5 {Introducing the idea of a4-a5. White may also press with such moves as Rfd1, Qd4 and Bf3, and enjoys lasting compensation right across the board.} *

