ut of the way of ...Ng4.} 10. Qd2 {has been overwhelmingly a more popular square for the queen over the years. However, White is in no rush to exchange the dark-squared bishops, and if Black now goes ...Nd7-c5, the queen may simply retreat to c2, thereby keeping e4 secure, just as we'll see White doing in our mainline.}) 10... Nd7 {Black wastes no time in sending his knight to arguably its favourite square in such structures, c5, unfurling the fianchettoed bishop in the process. Such a policy is, however, by no means forced.} 11. O-O $1 ({Calmly housing the king. We're less keen on} 11. Bd4 {here due to both} Bxd4 12. Qxd4 Qb6 {and 11...Nc5 12.Qe3 Bxd4 13.Qxd4 e5!? . Why allow Black easy counterplay when we don't need to?}) ({After} 11. O-O {, the move} a5 {can now just be met by} 12. Rad1 {as White limbers up for f2-f4.}) 11... Nc5 12. Qc2 {The best square for the queen, provoking Black into an attempt at grabbing the e-pawn. Meanwhile, Rad1 followed by f2-f4, or even b2-b4 is on the way.} Bxc3 $5 13. Qxc3 $1 ({The right way to recapture. White should be happy to gambit a pawn for the initiative and dark squares rather than allow Black easy play with} 13. bxc3 b6 {.}) 13... Nxe4 14. Qd4 Nf6 ({With tempo. Now if} 14... Nc5 $6 15. Rad1 {White is all set to go Bh6 (the immediate 15.Bh6 runs into 15...e5 ) and Black may also run into trouble after a quick b2-b4.}) 15. Rfe1 $5 ({Thus far in the limited over-the-board and correspondence testing, White has only tried} 15. Bf3 {and}) (15. Rfd1 {, proving full compensation, but not more than that. The text is a fairly clever engine suggestion, simply intending a policy of centralisation and gradual expansion through Rad1, Bf3 and Bg5.}) 15... e5 $5 16. Qh4 Nh5 $5 ({Now Black surely doesn't want to allow Bg5, and} 16... Nd7 17. Bg5 f6 18. Bh6 {followed by Rad1, looks like good compensation for White.}) 17. Qe4 {Dancing away, with a certain structural threat as well as ideas of simply playing Rad1.} Nf6 18. Qf3 Z0 ({One point of 15.Rfe1 becomes clear as now} 18... Bg4 $6 {can just be met by} 19. Qxb7 {. Meanwhile, Rad1 is on the way, and Black is clearly under pressure right across the board.}) *

