1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} d6 7. Be2 {Taking control of g4 and so facilitating Be3.} O-O 8. Be3 Nbd7 $5 ({Now play will usually go} 8... Nc6 9. O-O {with a transposition to our mainline [/variation/35967446/#/9/w], 6...Nc6 7.Be3 O-O 8.Be2 d6 9.O-O. Black doesn't have to develop that way, but otherwise may well drift into an overly passive set-up.}) 9. O-O Nc5 10. f3 Bd7 ({Securing e4 and giving the queen a good post on d2. White may now expand with b2-b4 and also aim to keep pieces on if Black tries to exchange, as with} 10... Ne6 11. Nc2 $1 {when the knight on e6 is misplaced, and White will be in full control after Qd2 and Rad1.}) 11. Qd2 Re8 ({Consistent, as well as thematic and now} 11... a5 12. b3 $1 {would prepare to meet} a4 $6 {with} 13. b4 {when} Ne6 14. Ndb5 {would underline that all Black has achieved is to somewhat weaken his queenside.}) 12. Rad1 ({White couldn't resist} 12. b4 $5 {in Kasparov-Dragon, Corfu (simul) 1996, but it's also possible not to rush.}) 12... a6 13. b3 Z0 ({This is rarely a bad move, fully securing c4. White is in full control here, since} 13... b5 $2 14. cxb5 {will just win a clear pawn and may meet 13...Qa5 with 14.Nc2 or 14.Rb1 . In any case, 14.Nc2 should be a decent move, threatening e4-e5 and allowing White to consider advancing on the queenside with b3-b4 and/or landing a timely Nd5.}) *

