ther passive scenario, one where after Qd2 White may be able to drum up a fairly fast attack with f2-f4, so Black is likely to prefer something more creative here.}) {Strong-pointing the knight on d4 at the cost of creating weaknesses on the d-file.} 10. Bd3 {Calm development, preparing to house the king, and we don't really want to give up a fairly big piece in the dark-squared bishop to exchange on d4.} O-O 11. O-O d6 {Black's standard set-up. This position can, of course, also arise via a 10...d6 11.O-O O-O move order.} ({Just like after} 11... d6 {, after}) (11... b6 {the advance} 12. a4 $5 {is also a good one, clamping down on the b5-square while allowing White to tickle the black queenside with a timely a4-a5 advance.} Bb7 13. Nd5 $5 {White has tended to prefer 13.Nb5 in the limited practice with this position, and you may prefer to be consistent and go 13.b3 (do then please meet 13...f5 with 14.exf5 ), but we quite like the knight leap as now 13...Bxd5 14.cxd5 would leave Black a bit vulnerable on the light squares. White also introduces the idea of Bxd4 exd4; f2-f4, annexing some useful space while leaving neither black bishop overly happy. Being slightly low on counterplay, Black might well attempt to break out:} f5 14. Bxd4 $5 {A more critical choice than 14.f3. Many an opponent might now recapture, but 14...exd4? 15.exf5 gxf5 16.Qh5 leaves Black's position creaking.} Bxd5 $1 15. cxd5 {One of two good moves, the other being 15.Be3!?.} fxe4 16. Bxe4 exd4 17. Qd3 {The pawn on d4 isn't going anywhere, and White has a small but pleasant edge. He can calmly improve the kingside with g2-g3, Kg2 and h2-h4, looking to attack on the light squares. White probably wants to retain a pair of rooks to support any such advance, but may also consider teaming up kingside expansion with Rac1, a4-a5 or even in some positions d5-d6 to activate the unopposed light-squared bishop.}) 12. a4 $5 ({White's most popular choice has been the natural} 12. Qd2 {, but we quite like this space-gaining advance. White threatens to annex further space with a4-a5 and also obtains the idea of Nb5 when ...Nxb5?!; axb5 would leave Black vulnerable down the a- and d-files.}) 12... a6 13. a5 {) Consistently annexing space and now Nd5 may follow to augment the clamp.} Be6 14. Qa4 $5 {A decent square for the queen, who can always switch to b4 if it helps, and now all is set for Nd5.} Rc8 15. Nd5 Bxd5 ({Observe how White hasn't rushed to exchange on d4, first improving his position. At some point, the knight may have to go, but White has several useful moves to make first, including Qb4 and Rac1. Of course, the first player is also hoping that Black will lash out with} 15... f5 $2 {when} 16. Bxd4 $1 exd4 17. exf5 {would once again leave Black with major weaknesses.}) 16. cxd5 $1 Rc5 ({The right way to recapture, preparing to bring a rook to the c-file, while once again hoping for} 16... f5 $2 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. exf5 gxf5 19. f4 {with a large positional advantage.}) 17. Rfc1 Z0 ({This left White with a very pleasant edge indeed in Shabalov-Baburin, Mermaid Beach 1998. White has control and is all set to force Black on to the defensive on the queenside with} 17... Z0 18. Rxc5 dxc5 19. Rc1 {followed by Qc4, after which the b2-b4 and f2-f4 pawn breaks might well prove useful.}) *

