1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} Nc6 {The main line of what is now, of course, an important hybrid variation of the English and Accelerated Dragon Sicilian.} 7. Be3 ({An important move, and not} 7. Be2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {which would just be embarrassing. However, now after 7.Be3, White is ready to go Be2 and Black finds himself at a crossroads.}) 7... Ng4 $5 {This ambitious attempt angles for immediate counterplay.} 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 ({This knight simply has to go, and the queen can easily now drop back to d1, although after} 8... Bxd4 $6 9. Bxd4 Nxd4 {White should prefer} 10. O-O-O $1 {with an active and attractive set-up, while f2-f4 is on the way.}) 9. Qd1 $1 e5 $5 ({An important retreat, keeping the queen safe while forcing the pace. Now} 9... Nc6 $6 10. Rc1 {followed by Be2 and O-O just leaves Black in a rather passive scenario, one where after Qd2 White may be able to drum up a fairly fast attack with f2-f4, so Black is likely to prefer something more creative here.}) {Strong-pointing the knight on d4 at the cost of creating weaknesses on the d-file.} 10. Bd3 {Calm development, preparing to house the king, and we don't really want to give up a fairly big piece in the dark-squared bishop to exchange on d4.} O-O 11. O-O d6 {Black's standard set-up. This position can, of course, also arise via a 10...d6 11.O-O O-O move order.} ({Just like after} 11... d6 {, after}) (11... b6 {the advance} 12. a4 $5 {is also a good one, clamping down on the b5-square while allowing White to tickle the black queenside with a timely a4-a5 advance.} Bb7 13. Nd5 $5 {White has tended to prefer 13.Nb5 in the limited practice with this position, and you may prefer to be consistent and go 13.b3 (do then please meet 13...f5 with 14.exf5 ), but we quite like the knight leap as now 13...Bxd5 14.cxd5 would leave Black a bit vulnerable on the light squares. White also introduces the idea of Bxd4 exd4; f2-f4, annexing some useful space while leaving neither black bishop overly happy. Being slightly low on counterplay, Black might well attempt to break out:} f5 14. Bxd4 $5 {A more critical choice than 14.f3. Many an opponent might now recapture, but 14...exd4? 15.exf5 gxf5 16.Qh5 leaves Black's position creaking.} Bxd5 $1 15. cxd5 {One of two good moves, the other being 15.Be3!?.} fxe4 16. Bxe4 exd4 17. Qd3 {The pawn on d4 isn't going anywhere, and White has a small but pleasant edge. He can calmly improve the kingside with g2-g3, Kg2 and h2-h4, looking to attack on the light squares. White probably wants to retain a pair of rooks to support any such advance, but may also consider teaming up kingside expansion with Rac1, a4-a5 or even in some positions d5-d6 to activate the unopposed light-squared bishop.}) 12. a4 $5 ({White's most popular choice has been the natural} 12. Qd2 {, but we quite like this space-gaining advance. White threatens to annex further space with a4-a5 and also obtains the idea of Nb5 when ...Nxb5?!; axb5 would leave Black vulnerable down the a- and d-files.}) 12... a5 $5 {An old suggestion of Peter Heine Nielsen and Carsten Hansen.} 13. Nb5 ({The immediate} 13. b3 {is also a good move, but with}) (13. Nb5 {, White hopes that Black will go} Nxb5 $6 {when} 14. cxb5 $5 {followed by Rc1 and Bc4 would leave Black vulnerable on the queenside and down the d-file.}) 13... Bd7 14. b3 $5 ({We prefer this modest prophylactic advance to} 14. Bxd4 Bxb5 15. Be3 {, which still supplied an edge in Van Wely-Edouard, French Team Championship 2017. By covering a4, White threatens Nxd6 ( 14.Nxd6?! Bxa4 isn't too clear), can also consider ideas of Nc7-d5 if the black queen moves, and is especially ready to increase the pressure down the d-file with Ra2-d2.}) *

