ther passive scenario, one where after Qd2 White may be able to drum up a fairly fast attack with f2-f4, so Black is likely to prefer something more creative here.}) {Strong-pointing the knight on d4 at the cost of creating weaknesses on the d-file.} 10. Bd3 {Calm development, preparing to house the king, and we don't really want to give up a fairly big piece in the dark-squared bishop to exchange on d4.} O-O 11. O-O d6 {Black's standard set-up. This position can, of course, also arise via a 10...d6 11.O-O O-O move order.} ({Just like after} 11... d6 {, after}) (11... b6 {the advance} 12. a4 $5 {is also a good one, clamping down on the b5-square while allowing White to tickle the black queenside with a timely a4-a5 advance.} Bb7 13. Nd5 $5 {White has tended to prefer 13.Nb5 in the limited practice with this position, and you may prefer to be consistent and go 13.b3 (do then please meet 13...f5 with 14.exf5 ), but we quite like the knight leap as now 13...Bxd5 14.cxd5 would leave Black a bit vulnerable on the light squares. White also introduces the idea of Bxd4 exd4; f2-f4, annexing some useful space while leaving neither black bishop overly happy. Being slightly low on counterplay, Black might well attempt to break out:} f5 14. Bxd4 $5 {A more critical choice than 14.f3. Many an opponent might now recapture, but 14...exd4? 15.exf5 gxf5 16.Qh5 leaves Black's position creaking.} Bxd5 $1 15. cxd5 {One of two good moves, the other being 15.Be3!?.} fxe4 16. Bxe4 exd4 17. Qd3 {The pawn on d4 isn't going anywhere, and White has a small but pleasant edge. He can calmly improve the kingside with g2-g3, Kg2 and h2-h4, looking to attack on the light squares. White probably wants to retain a pair of rooks to support any such advance, but may also consider teaming up kingside expansion with Rac1, a4-a5 or even in some positions d5-d6 to activate the unopposed light-squared bishop.}) 12. a4 $5 ({White's most popular choice has been the natural} 12. Qd2 {, but we quite like this space-gaining advance. White threatens to annex further space with a4-a5 and also obtains the idea of Nb5 when ...Nxb5?!; axb5 would leave Black vulnerable down the a- and d-files.}) 12... Be6 {Black's most popular choice, if by no means forced.} 13. b3 $5 ({A new Stockfish-approved idea. White has tended to go} 13. Nb5 {here, but then} a6 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Bd2 {isn't completely clear. Instead, White keeps Nb5 ideas in reserve, as well as those of a4-a5, while also introducing the plan of Ra2-d2, after which Ne2 or Nb5 might well begin to leave Black looking a bit vulnerable down the d-file.}) 13... Rc8 14. Ra2 {Now Ne2 before or after Rd2 is the plan, and White looks to enjoy a stable edge. Note, too, that once again breaking out doesn't exactly solve Black's problems.} f5 $6 15. exf5 $1 Nxf5 ({A strong exchange yet again. Now} 15... Bxf5 16. Bxf5 {would leave Black either walking into a bad bishop against good knight scenario after an exchange on d4 or a pawn in arrears after} Nxf5 17. Bxa7 $1 {, and neither are the other recaptures completely ideal.}) 16. Bxf5 $1 ({Forcing the pace and refusing to fear Black's Sveshnikov centre (} 16. Bd2 {followed by Be4 would retain a clear plus), with Rd2 on the way.}) 16... gxf5 17. Rd2 Rc6 18. f4 $1 Z0 ({A key advance to fix the pawn on f5. White is in control and at least clearly better here, with Nb5 or Nd5 on the way and even Black's kingside potentially vulnerable too, not least in the event of} 18... exf4 $6 19. Bd4 {.}) *

