er passive scenario, one where after Qd2 White may be able to drum up a fairly fast attack with f2-f4, so Black is likely to prefer something more creative here.}) ({Bent Larsen used to score fairly well with such an approach, often followed by ...Qa5, ...b6, ...Bb7 and then taking over the dark squares with such moves as ...g5 and ...Be5. Nowadays it is seen somewhat less often.} 9... Nc6 $6 10. Rc1 {takes the option of ...Bxc3+; bxc3 off the table ahead of completing kingside development.} d6 11. Be2 Be6 $5 12. O-O {Next up, Qd2 will complete development, and just how is Black going to develop any counterplay? It's certainly not an easy task.} O-O 13. Qd2 Qa5 14. f4 $5 {The most aggressive option, taking control of e5 and intending to gradually arrange the f4-f5 advance, if allowed.} f5 $5 {A big decision, but without it Black might well have found herself slowly being suffocated. 14...a6 15.b3! Ever a useful way of shoring up the queenside, as well as a move here that rather provokes Black's next: 15...b5? 16.f5! Bd7 17.f6! Black's position is imploding in the centre and on the dark squares. 17...Bxf6? 18.Rxf6! Boom! 18...exf6 19.Qxd6 Thanks to the threats of Qxd7 and Nd5, not to mention Qxf6 and Bh6, White will emerge material ahead.} 15. exf5 $1 {This is usually the best way of dealing with an ...f5 advance, removing any pressure from the e4-pawn ahead of improving the light-squared bishop to f3.} Bxf5 16. Bf3 Kh8 17. Kh1 $5 {This made the king safe and left White in control in Schlosser-Mamedjarova, Pardubice 2008. Note especially the continued light-square clamp. Now g2-g4 is one possibility, Bg1 and Rfe1 another, perhaps played in conjunction with a gradual queenside advance.}) 10. Rc1 {Dissuading an exchange on c3. Now we will largely advocate a set-up with Bd3 and O-O, holding back on Qd2 at least for a couple of moves.} b6 11. Bd3 {Once again, we delay Qd2, while preparing O-O and to retreat the bishop to b1 in the event of any ...Nc5.} Bb7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bb1 $5 ({Prophylaxis ahead of f2-f4, as} 13. f4 Nc5 {would be slightly annoying when Black may be able to exchange on c3 and grab e4 in the event of} 14. Bb1 {.}) 13... Rc8 14. b3 {) Wisely covering c4 ahead of advancing on the kingside.} Nc5 $5 (14... d6 15. f4 $1 {With Black again not up to too much, White can very much expand so and might now again meet 15...f5!? with 16.exf5 gxf5 17.Qh5 .} Nc5 16. f5 $1 {Here 16...Bxc3? 17.Rxc3 Nxe4 18.Bxe4 Bxe4 19.Bh6 quickly won material and the game in Nisipeanu-Todoran, Curtea de Arges 2002, and, yes, this trap in general has claimed a surprising number of victims.} Nd7 $1 17. Qg4 $5 {Direct. 17.Bg5 would be a calmer and decent alternative if you ever reached this position.} Ne5 18. Qg3 $5 {A step backwards, not to the h-file, as White has an instructive positional idea in mind:} Bc6 19. Nd5 $1 Bxd5 20. exd5 {White was in full control here in Matamoros Franco-Sgnaolin, Seville 2015, where, as well as the Kh1 and Bd4 of the game, it was even possible to hurl Harry down the board with h2-h4-h5.}) 15. b4 $1 {Once again dangling a poisoned e-pawn before Black as White would again have Bh6 and Qd4 at the end.} Ne6 16. Qd3 {Ensuring c4 is protected while connecting the rooks ahead of potentially leaping forward with Nd5.} d6 17. a3 $5 ({Prophylaxis, as White essentially asks Black: 'Just where is your play?'. This seems clearer than} 17. f4 f5 {. Now there are ideas of a timely Ba2, as well as Nd5 or even Nb5-d4.}) 17... f5 $6 18. exf5 $1 {Exchanging to expose Black's weaknesses and defuse the positional threat of ...f4.} gxf5 19. f3 $1 {Another effective prophylactic move, stymieing the bishop on b7. White may now consider a timely g2-g4, but is much more likely to increase the pressure with Rfe1, leaving Black looking a little vulnerable down the e-file and on the light squares.} *

