1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} Nc6 {The main line of what is now, of course, an important hybrid variation of the English and Accelerated Dragon Sicilian.} 7. Be3 ({An important move, and not} 7. Be2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {which would just be embarrassing. However, now after 7.Be3, White is ready to go Be2 and Black finds himself at a crossroads.}) 7... Ng4 $5 {This ambitious attempt angles for immediate counterplay.} 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 ({This knight simply has to go, and the queen can easily now drop back to d1, although after} 8... Bxd4 $6 9. Bxd4 Nxd4 {White should prefer} 10. O-O-O $1 {with an active and attractive set-up, while f2-f4 is on the way.}) 9. Qd1 $1 Ne6 ({An important retreat, keeping the queen safe while forcing the pace. Now} 9... Nc6 $6 10. Rc1 {followed by Be2 and O-O just leaves Black in a rather passive scenario, one where after Qd2 White may be able to drum up a fairly fast attack with f2-f4, so Black is likely to prefer something more creative here.}) ({Bent Larsen used to score fairly well with such an approach, often followed by ...Qa5, ...b6, ...Bb7 and then taking over the dark squares with such moves as ...g5 and ...Be5. Nowadays it is seen somewhat less often.} 9... Nc6 $6 10. Rc1 {takes the option of ...Bxc3+; bxc3 off the table ahead of completing kingside development.} d6 11. Be2 Be6 $5 12. O-O {Next up, Qd2 will complete development, and just how is Black going to develop any counterplay? It's certainly not an easy task.} O-O 13. Qd2 Qa5 14. f4 $5 {The most aggressive option, taking control of e5 and intending to gradually arrange the f4-f5 advance, if allowed.} f5 $5 {A big decision, but without it Black might well have found herself slowly being suffocated. 14...a6 15.b3! Ever a useful way of shoring up the queenside, as well as a move here that rather provokes Black's next: 15...b5? 16.f5! Bd7 17.f6! Black's position is imploding in the centre and on the dark squares. 17...Bxf6? 18.Rxf6! Boom! 18...exf6 19.Qxd6 Thanks to the threats of Qxd7 and Nd5, not to mention Qxf6 and Bh6, White will emerge material ahead.} 15. exf5 $1 {This is usually the best way of dealing with an ...f5 advance, removing any pressure from the e4-pawn ahead of improving the light-squared bishop to f3.} Bxf5 16. Bf3 Kh8 17. Kh1 $5 {This made the king safe and left White in control in Schlosser-Mamedjarova, Pardubice 2008. Note especially the continued light-square clamp. Now g2-g4 is one possibility, Bg1 and Rfe1 another, perhaps played in conjunction with a gradual queenside advance.}) 10. Rc1 {Dissuading an exchange on c3. Now we will largely advocate a set-up with Bd3 and O-O, holding back on Qd2 at least for a couple of moves.} Qa5 $5 {Black's most ambitious choice a la Larsen.} 11. Bd3 {A consistent and good choice, preparing to castle, then maybe again go f2-f4, while dangling a certain exchange and the a-pawn before Black.} Bxc3+ $2 12. Rxc3 Qxa2 13. Qc1 {Calmly covering b2 while usefully enough stepping on to a dark square. Now Ra3 is a threat.} Qa5 14. c5 $1 ({This anti-...b6 and ...d6 advance is even stronger than the hardly shabby} 14. O-O {here. White is now all set to castle, then steamroll Black with f2-f4, and may also have ideas of b2-b4, and if ...Qxb4; Qa1 with strong threats down the long diagonal, and of Rb1.}) 14... O-O 15. O-O Qc7 16. f4 {With f4-f5 and then Bd4 on the way, it had fast become something of a massacre in Sadorra-Halay, Kuala Lumpur 2006.} *

