1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} Nc6 {The main line of what is now, of course, an important hybrid variation of the English and Accelerated Dragon Sicilian.} 7. Be3 ({An important move, and not} 7. Be2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {which would just be embarrassing. However, now after 7.Be3, White is ready to go Be2 and Black finds himself at a crossroads.}) 7... Ng4 $5 {This ambitious attempt angles for immediate counterplay.} 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 ({This knight simply has to go, and the queen can easily now drop back to d1, although after} 8... Bxd4 $6 9. Bxd4 Nxd4 {White should prefer} 10. O-O-O $1 {with an active and attractive set-up, while f2-f4 is on the way.}) 9. Qd1 $1 Ne6 ({An important retreat, keeping the queen safe while forcing the pace. Now} 9... Nc6 $6 10. Rc1 {followed by Be2 and O-O just leaves Black in a rather passive scenario, one where after Qd2 White may be able to drum up a fairly fast attack with f2-f4, so Black is likely to prefer something more creative here.}) ({Bent Larsen used to score fairly well with such an approach, often followed by ...Qa5, ...b6, ...Bb7 and then taking over the dark squares with such moves as ...g5 and ...Be5. Nowadays it is seen somewhat less often.} 9... Nc6 $6 10. Rc1 {takes the option of ...Bxc3+; bxc3 off the table ahead of completing kingside development.} d6 11. Be2 Be6 $5 12. O-O {Next up, Qd2 will complete development, and just how is Black going to develop any counterplay? It's certainly not an easy task.} O-O 13. Qd2 Qa5 14. f4 $5 {The most aggressive option, taking control of e5 and intending to gradually arrange the f4-f5 advance, if allowed.} f5 $5 {A big decision, but without it Black might well have found herself slowly being suffocated. 14...a6 15.b3! Ever a useful way of shoring up the queenside, as well as a move here that rather provokes Black's next: 15...b5? 16.f5! Bd7 17.f6! Black's position is imploding in the centre and on the dark squares. 17...Bxf6? 18.Rxf6! Boom! 18...exf6 19.Qxd6 Thanks to the threats of Qxd7 and Nd5, not to mention Qxf6 and Bh6, White will emerge material ahead.} 15. exf5 $1 {This is usually the best way of dealing with an ...f5 advance, removing any pressure from the e4-pawn ahead of improving the light-squared bishop to f3.} Bxf5 16. Bf3 Kh8 17. Kh1 $5 {This made the king safe and left White in control in Schlosser-Mamedjarova, Pardubice 2008. Note especially the continued light-square clamp. Now g2-g4 is one possibility, Bg1 and Rfe1 another, perhaps played in conjunction with a gradual queenside advance.}) 10. Rc1 {Dissuading an exchange on c3. Now we will largely advocate a set-up with Bd3 and O-O, holding back on Qd2 at least for a couple of moves.} Qa5 $5 {Black's most ambitious choice a la Larsen.} 11. Bd3 {A consistent and good choice, preparing to castle, then maybe again go f2-f4, while dangling a certain exchange and the a-pawn before Black.} b6 {Black's most popular and consistent choice, aiming for maximum piece activity.} (11... Qe5 $2 12. O-O {Threatening f2-f4 and so rather provoking Black's thematic next move.} g5 13. c5 $1 {With Bc4 and Nd5 on the way, White was all set to take over and scarcely inconvenienced by Black's current grip on f4 in Eingorn-Gyorkos, Austrian League 1995, where the c-pawn was again taboo due to the potential fork on c7.}) 12. O-O {Development is pretty much complete. f2-f4 is imminent.} g5 $2 {This dissuades f2-f4, but rather walks into...} 13. Nd5 $1 {White is now set to harass the black queen with b2-b4 or Bd2 and may also find a2-a4 a useful advance.} Bxb2 14. Bd2 $5 Qxa2 ({Now} 14... Qa3 15. Bb4 {wouldn't spell good news for Black, and neither would 14...Qa6 15.Bb4!? (the simple 15.Rc2 is also fairly strong), threatening e7 as well as c4-c5, but taking a second pawn might be even worse.}) 15. Qc2 $1 Nd4 16. Qb1 $1 Qxb1 ({In view of} 16... Qb3 $2 17. Bc2 Qa3 18. Bb4 {Black's queen can't run away.}) 17. Rxb1 {White will either win the bishop or safely collect the rook in the corner while remaining in control of the board.} *

