er passive scenario, one where after Qd2 White may be able to drum up a fairly fast attack with f2-f4, so Black is likely to prefer something more creative here.}) ({Bent Larsen used to score fairly well with such an approach, often followed by ...Qa5, ...b6, ...Bb7 and then taking over the dark squares with such moves as ...g5 and ...Be5. Nowadays it is seen somewhat less often.} 9... Nc6 $6 10. Rc1 {takes the option of ...Bxc3+; bxc3 off the table ahead of completing kingside development.} d6 11. Be2 Be6 $5 12. O-O {Next up, Qd2 will complete development, and just how is Black going to develop any counterplay? It's certainly not an easy task.} O-O 13. Qd2 Qa5 14. f4 $5 {The most aggressive option, taking control of e5 and intending to gradually arrange the f4-f5 advance, if allowed.} f5 $5 {A big decision, but without it Black might well have found herself slowly being suffocated. 14...a6 15.b3! Ever a useful way of shoring up the queenside, as well as a move here that rather provokes Black's next: 15...b5? 16.f5! Bd7 17.f6! Black's position is imploding in the centre and on the dark squares. 17...Bxf6? 18.Rxf6! Boom! 18...exf6 19.Qxd6 Thanks to the threats of Qxd7 and Nd5, not to mention Qxf6 and Bh6, White will emerge material ahead.} 15. exf5 $1 {This is usually the best way of dealing with an ...f5 advance, removing any pressure from the e4-pawn ahead of improving the light-squared bishop to f3.} Bxf5 16. Bf3 Kh8 17. Kh1 $5 {This made the king safe and left White in control in Schlosser-Mamedjarova, Pardubice 2008. Note especially the continued light-square clamp. Now g2-g4 is one possibility, Bg1 and Rfe1 another, perhaps played in conjunction with a gradual queenside advance.}) 10. Rc1 {Dissuading an exchange on c3. Now we will largely advocate a set-up with Bd3 and O-O, holding back on Qd2 at least for a couple of moves.} Qa5 $5 {Black's most ambitious choice a la Larsen.} 11. Bd3 {A consistent and good choice, preparing to castle, then maybe again go f2-f4