1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} Nc6 {The main line of what is now, of course, an important hybrid variation of the English and Accelerated Dragon Sicilian.} 7. Be3 ({An important move, and not} 7. Be2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {which would just be embarrassing. However, now after 7.Be3, White is ready to go Be2 and Black finds himself at a crossroads.}) 7... O-O {The mainline. Black is content with a solid position, aiming to gradually unravel.} 8. Be2 {) Calm development, keeping Black fully out of g4 while preparing to castle.} b6 {This was quite popular in the 1970s and 80s, but is nowadays a much more rare guest to the tournament hall. Black has some tricks, but White should be able to maintain control and emerge with a pleasant edge.} 9. O-O {Not forced, but it's hard to believe this natural move can't be a good one.} Bb7 10. f3 $1 ({An important move to shore up e4. Instead,} 10. Qd2 $6 {would walk right into one of Black's main points:} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 e5 $1 {, and if} 12. Bxe5 Nxe4 {. With e4 now secure, White can improve the major pieces, such as with Qd2 and Rac1 or Rad1.}) 10... Qb8 $6 11. Qd2 {White should not be deterred by Black's slightly strange-looking last move. We are not about to get hit by ...d5; that is not unless we're careless.} Rd8 12. Ndb5 $5 ({This perhaps unexpected advance represents a theoretical obstacle for Black, although it should be said that} 12. Rad1 {also leaves White with a large edge, and if} e6 13. f4 {.}) (12. Ndb5 {prepares to increase the pressure with Nd5, and clearly} e6 $6 13. Nd6 {wouldn't spell good news for Black. Neither does 12...a6 13.Na3 when b6 is quite tender.}) 12... d6 13. Nd5 {With a certain threat, as well as good preparation for such ideas as Bg5 and Bh6.} Rd7 14. Rad1 ({This rook, as White wants to keep the other one on f1 to support a future f3-f4 push.} 14. Bg5 {has been more popular, but we prefer to keep that option in reserve, instead angling for an exchange on f6, followed by 16.f4.}) 14... Qf8 15. Nxf6+ {By no means forced, but a simple and decent plan.} Bxf6 16. f4 Z0 ({This left White clearly better in Ginzburg-Soppe, Villa Gesell 1998, with control of the key d5- and e5-squares. Already} 16... Z0 17. e5 {is a threat, and White may also regroup with Nc3, likely followed by Nd5 and maybe f4-f5, especially in the event of ...e6.}) *

