1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} Nc6 {The main line of what is now, of course, an important hybrid variation of the English and Accelerated Dragon Sicilian.} 7. Be3 ({An important move, and not} 7. Be2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {which would just be embarrassing. However, now after 7.Be3, White is ready to go Be2 and Black finds himself at a crossroads.}) 7... O-O {The mainline. Black is content with a solid position, aiming to gradually unravel.} 8. Be2 {Calm development, keeping Black fully out of g4 while preparing to castle.} b6 {This was quite popular in the 1970s and 80s, but is nowadays a much more rare guest to the tournament hall. Black has some tricks, but White should be able to maintain control and emerge with a pleasant edge.} 9. O-O {Not forced, but it's hard to believe this natural move can't be a good one.} Bb7 10. f3 $1 ({An important move to shore up e4. Instead,} 10. Qd2 $6 {would walk right into one of Black's main points:} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 e5 $1 {, and if} 12. Bxe5 Nxe4 {. With e4 now secure, White can improve the major pieces, such as with Qd2 and Rac1 or Rad1.}) 10... Nh5 $5 11. Ndb5 $1 ({Black hopes for} 11. f4 $2 Nxf4 $1 {and is also ready to liquidate with 11.Qd2 Nf4 .}) {Once again, a strong leap, taking ...Nf4 ideas fully off the table. White is now all set to secure full control with Qd2 and Rad1.} 11... a6 12. Na3 {As well as Qd2 and Rad1, White is ready to expand with tempo through f3-f4, and Black must also watch out that b6 doesn't just collapse after a timely Nd5. This was all seen in Timman-Yusupov, 10th matchgame, Linares 1992, where it was later suggested Black should have tried to counter on the dark squares.} e5 $5 13. Nc2 {Sensibly keeping Black out of d4 while threatening Nd5.} Nf4 14. Nd5 $1 {Forcing the pace.} Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 Nd4 16. Qd2 Z0 ({Simple chess retains a pleasant edge. Black may now exchange on d5 (} 16... Bxd5 17. cxd5 {) and c2, but even then will suffer due to their less active bishop and especially slightly vulnerable queenside.}) *

