d one.} Bb7 10. f3 $1 ({An important move to shore up e4. Instead,} 10. Qd2 $6 {would walk right into one of Black's main points:} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 e5 $1 {, and if} 12. Bxe5 Nxe4 {. With e4 now secure, White can improve the major pieces, such as with Qd2 and Rac1 or Rad1.}) 10... d6 11. Qd2 {Simple chess and good chess at that. White clears a path for Rad1 (or Rfd1 and Rac1 if you prefer), and may now look to keep Black quite tied up with a timely Ndb5 or Nc2 manoeuvre.} Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e6 13. Rad1 {This rules out ...d5 for now and leaves White with a pleasant edge. Rfe1, then Bf1, will tidy up the white position, and White may increase the pressure on the dark squares with Be3 (which may leave d6 en prise), followed by Bf4, Bg5 or Bh6, or even Bf2, and then Bg3 or Bh4.} *

