d one.} Bb7 10. f3 $1 ({An important move to shore up e4. Instead,} 10. Qd2 $6 {would walk right into one of Black's main points:} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 e5 $1 {, and if} 12. Bxe5 Nxe4 {. With e4 now secure, White can improve the major pieces, such as with Qd2 and Rac1 or Rad1.}) 10... e6 $5 {Attempting to force through ...d5.} 11. Ndb5 $1 {)} ({Heading for d6, which Qd2 and Rad1 would support even more. One problem for Black with this variation is that even} 11. Qd2 d5 {doesn't seem to fully equalise after} 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. e5 {.}) 11... d5 $5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. exd5 {The pawn has to go. Now White shouldn't be looking to reinforce d5, but rather use the extra pawn as actively as possible by pushing it up to d6.} Nb4 14. d6 Nfd5 15. Bf2 $1 a6 ({White hasn't always played this retreat, but it's simply a strong one. Now} 15... Nf4 16. a3 Qg5 {can simply be met by} 17. Bg3 {. Black is just in some trouble, with a2-a3 threatened and his own queenside nudge far from a panacea.}) 16. Nc7 $1 {An important follow-up thanks to the subsequent intermezzo.} Nxc7 17. Bxb6 $1 {White is two pawns up and all set to regain the piece. The pawn on c7 will be so powerful that White will be able to avert any issues on the kingside with f2-f4 and even an exchange sacrifice if needed.} Z0 ({In other words:} 17... Be5 18. dxc7 Qh4 19. f4 $1 Bxf4 20. Rxf4 $1 {Forced by this stage.} Qxf4 21. a3 {But now White can regain the initiative, and just look at that pawn on c7!} Qf6 22. Bf2 Nc6 23. Bf3 {Contesting the long diagonal and leaving White able to consider increasing the pressure with Qb3, as well as Nd5.} Rac8 {Here 24.Bg3? Ne7! wasn't totally clear in Ivkov-Martin Gonzalez, Torremolinos 1981. White had a much stronger way to secure the key pawn:} 24. Nd5 {With tempo, and clearly the b-pawn is taboo thanks to the loose bishop on b7. White will follow up with} Z0 25. Rc1 {and then look for a strong dark-square hit, such as Bc5 or after Bh4.}) *

