1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} Nc6 {The main line of what is now, of course, an important hybrid variation of the English and Accelerated Dragon Sicilian.} 7. Be3 ({An important move, and not} 7. Be2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {which would just be embarrassing. However, now after 7.Be3, White is ready to go Be2 and Black finds himself at a crossroads.}) 7... O-O {The mainline. Black is content with a solid position, aiming to gradually unravel.} 8. Be2 {Calm development, keeping Black fully out of g4 while preparing to castle.} e6 $6 {This would be good preparation for ...d5, but for a certain thematic leap:} 9. Ndb5 $1 Ne8 ({Now} 9... d5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. exd5 {will just cost Black a pawn - not only is Nd6 imminent, but Bc5 too.}) 10. O-O {Simple chess to keep everything secure before invading d6, which might even be prefaced by Qd2 and Rad1, as any ...a6 would only weaken Black further on the dark squares.} (10. Bc5 $6 d6 $1 {actually isn't so clear in view of} 11. Nxd6 $6 Qg5 {, but White might exploit Black's temporary disarray with 10.h4!? .}) 10... d6 11. c5 $1 Z0 ({A powerful advance to leave White clearly for choice. White will simply keep taking and improving his pieces if the d-pawn now advances to d5, and clearly} 11... dxc5 $2 12. Bxc5 {would instead net the exchange.}) *

