1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} Nc6 {The main line of what is now, of course, an important hybrid variation of the English and Accelerated Dragon Sicilian.} 7. Be3 ({An important move, and not} 7. Be2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {which would just be embarrassing. However, now after 7.Be3, White is ready to go Be2 and Black finds himself at a crossroads.}) 7... O-O {The mainline. Black is content with a solid position, aiming to gradually unravel.} 8. Be2 {Calm development, keeping Black fully out of g4 while preparing to castle.} d6 {Black's main move, sensibly continuing development.} 9. O-O {Straightforward development. The Maroczy Bind is clearly showing its worth, with Black struggling slightly to free their position, since neither ...d5 or ...b5 is about to be on the cards. If an opponent unfamiliar with the subtleties now manoeuvres a little aimlessly as Black, White may consider a simple plan of h2-h3, Qd2 and Rad1, perhaps even followed by pushing the f-pawn to f4. Another useful option can be a timely Nc2, denying Black a liberating exchange on d4 and thereby keeping them quite cramped.} Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 ({This is very likely to transpose to our mainline [/variation/35967449/#/11/w] after} 10... Bd7 11. h3 {, although on the odd occasion, Black does prefer a more ambitious square for their light-squared bishop.}) 11. f4 $5 ({Here too} 11. h3 {is a good move, but the engines really like the more ambitious text move, and with good reason. White ensures that f4-f5 will come with tempo and would ideally like to attack on the kingside while maintaining full control. As such, b2-b3 and a2-a4 are likely to be useful advances to help restrict Black on the queenside, while Kh1 will avoid any potentially annoying later checks on the g1-a7 diagonal.}) 11... Qa5 (11... Qc8 12. b3 Bg4 13. e5 $1 {A small change of approach (13.Kh1 would still be a good move too), as White seizes some useful space and finds another way of making fine use of the early f2-f4.} Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Nd7 15. Rad1 {This retained the cramping bridgehead on e5 (if} dxe5 16. fxe5 {), leaving Nd5 on the way and White simply doing very well in Golod-Mensch, Biel 2010.}) 12. Kh1 $5 {Tucking the king away is rarely a bad precaution in such positions. Now White may even be able to consider direct play with Qe1-h4, since ...Nxe4 tactics won't work.} Rac8 13. b3 {Naturally White secures c4, and, of course, this position might very well come about too via an 11...Rc8 12.b3 Qa5 13.Kh1 move order. White may now consider meeting 13...a6 with 14.a4 ( 14...Bd7? 15.e5! would then be quite a powerful advance), while Qe1 and Rad1 may be a good way to initially deploy the major pieces or just Qd3, after which f4-f5 and Qe3 might well leave White in full control.} Rfe8 14. Qd3 {Supporting f4-f5, as well as bringing the queen closer to a fine square for her, e3, beginning to press on the dark squares.} Nd7 $4 15. f5 $1 Z0 ({Thanks to the insertion of Kh1,} 15... Nc5 {could now be met by} 16. Bxc5 {, leaving Black red-faced and losing a piece in Tukmakov-Ornstein, Yerevan 1976.}) *

