1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 g6 ({Another solid choice by Black and a move you should certainly be ready for, even if it does lag behind} 3... Nc6 {,}) (3... e6 {and}) (3... d5 {in the popularity stakes. For those not too au fait with the theory at the sub-2000 level, the move may look solid, and you do see a kingside fianchetto teamed up with ...c5 in a number of lines.}) 4. e4 $1 ({A change from our normal approach, but here} 4. e3 Bg7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {is known to be a fairly decent version of a Panov-Botvinnik for Black. Instead, we expand to the maximum on the e-file, threatening e4-e5 while also getting ready to break with d2-d4.}) 4... Bg7 ({Provoking White forwards.} 4... d6 {has actually been Black's most popular move here, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {play will transpose to our mainline coverage after} Bg7 7. Be2 {or with 6...Nc6 7.Be2 to our 4...Nc6 coverage [/variation/35967401/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 {Again, a thematic advance, one which prepares various pawn options in the centre (dxc5, d4-d5 and maybe even e4-e5) that Black is unlikely to want to allow.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White erects the Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square while making Black think too for now about the e4-e5 advance.} Nc6 {The main line of what is now, of course, an important hybrid variation of the English and Accelerated Dragon Sicilian.} 7. Be3 ({An important move, and not} 7. Be2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {which would just be embarrassing. However, now after 7.Be3, White is ready to go Be2 and Black finds himself at a crossroads.}) 7... O-O {The mainline. Black is content with a solid position, aiming to gradually unravel.} 8. Be2 {Calm development, keeping Black fully out of g4 while preparing to castle.} d6 {Black's main move, sensibly continuing development.} 9. O-O {Straightforward development. The Maroczy Bind is clearly showing its worth, with Black struggling slightly to free their position, since neither ...d5 or ...b5 is about to be on the cards. If an opponent unfamiliar with the subtleties now manoeuvres a little aimlessly as Black, White may consider a simple plan of h2-h3, Qd2 and Rad1, perhaps even followed by pushing the f-pawn to f4. Another useful option can be a timely Nc2, denying Black a liberating exchange on d4 and thereby keeping them quite cramped.} Bd7 10. h3 $5 {)} ({This modest little advance, taking full control of the g4-square, trails} 10. Qd2 {,}) (10. Rc1 {and}) (10. f3 {by some margin in the popularity stakes, but has become fairly topical in recent years and used regularly by such noted theoreticians as Ivan Cheparinov and Nils Grandelius. White may simply continue with Rc1 and Qd2, but also gives the queen another option, c2.}) 10... Rc8 11. Nf3 $5 {A slightly odd-looking move, but White wants to keep pieces on, thereby denying Black a freeing exchange on d4. White now plans a queenside advance with Rc1, a2-a3 and b2-b4, while the knight may usefully drop back to d2 or even head to g5 in the event of any ...Be6.} a6 12. Rc1 Qa5 $6 ({All is now set for queenside expansion. Black can prevent it, but} 12... a5 {can even be met by} 13. a3 $5 {or just 13.b3 , continuing to deny Black counterplay. After Qd2 and Rfd1, Black would have to watch out for a powerful e4-e5 or c4-c5 advance.}) 13. Nd2 $5 ({White now settled for} 13. Bd2 {in Mekhitarian-Drori, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, which was hardly terrible, but might have used that square for another piece.}) {Suddenly, two powerful advances are placed high on the agenda: f2-f4 and c4-c5, and if ...dxc5; Nb3 and Nxc5.} 13... Qd8 14. a3 ({Retreating tail between legs, but this prepares to meet} 14. c5 $6 {with} dxc5 15. Bxc5 Be6 {which would be fine for Black. However, White can instead go 14.f4!? or advance on the queenside.}) {White's set-up will now be quite a pleasant one after b2-b4 and Nb3.} 14... a5 15. Qc2 $1 {There's no rush! Indeed, it's important to never rush in Maroczy positions, which are all about retaining full control. Here, Black is low on counterplay, and White may expand with f2-f4 or even Qb1 and b2-b4, with a very pleasant edge in either case.} *

