btleties now manoeuvres a little aimlessly as Black, White may consider a simple plan of h2-h3, Qd2 and Rad1, perhaps even followed by pushing the f-pawn to f4. Another useful option can be a timely Nc2, denying Black a liberating exchange on d4 and thereby keeping them quite cramped.} Bd7 10. h3 $5 ({This modest little advance, taking full control of the g4-square, trails} 10. Qd2 {,}) (10. Rc1 {and}) (10. f3 {by some margin in the popularity stakes, but has become fairly topical in recent years and used regularly by such noted theoreticians as Ivan Cheparinov and Nils Grandelius. White may simply continue with Rc1 and Qd2, but also gives the queen another option, c2.}) 10... Nxd4 {Black usually makes this thematic freeing exchange, although it isn't forced.} 11. Bxd4 ({Naturally the right way to recapture. Not} 11. Qxd4 $2 Ng4 {.}) 11... Bc6 12. Qc2 $1 a6 ({An important follow-up to 10.h3. White secures e4, thereby retaining full control. Now} 12... e5 $6 13. Be3 {would just create weaknesses for Black on the d-file. Meanwhile, White is all set to expand with b2-b4 or just Rad1, which will place not only f2-f4, but the c4-c5 break firmly on the table.}) 13. b4 $1 {Once again, a useful early gain of space on the queenside, a side of the board where White may very much play here, not least after Rfd1 with a2-a4.} Rc8 {This angled for ...b5 and some much-needed counterplay in Rodshtein-Vogt, European Club Cup, Ulcinj 2019.} 14. Rfd1 ({We prefer this to} 14. Qd3 {when} b5 $5 {may not be so clear, whereas now 14...b5 15.c5 would very much keep up the pressure on Black.}) 14... Qc7 15. a4 $1 {Seizing even more space as White threatens to clamp the black queenside with a4-a5, as well as just go Qb2 and b4-b5.} a5 16. b5 $1 Bd7 17. Qb2 {Black has kept the queenside closed for now, but this is not at all a comfortable position for him. White simply wants to go Rac1 when Nd5 will become a major issue, and there are also then very much ideas of b5-b6, followed by breaking through with c4-c5.} *

