btleties now manoeuvres a little aimlessly as Black, White may consider a simple plan of h2-h3, Qd2 and Rad1, perhaps even followed by pushing the f-pawn to f4. Another useful option can be a timely Nc2, denying Black a liberating exchange on d4 and thereby keeping them quite cramped.} Bd7 10. h3 $5 ({This modest little advance, taking full control of the g4-square, trails} 10. Qd2 {,}) (10. Rc1 {and}) (10. f3 {by some margin in the popularity stakes, but has become fairly topical in recent years and used regularly by such noted theoreticians as Ivan Cheparinov and Nils Grandelius. White may simply continue with Rc1 and Qd2, but also gives the queen another option, c2.}) 10... Nxd4 {Black usually makes this thematic freeing exchange, although it isn't forced.} 11. Bxd4 ({Naturally the right way to recapture. Not} 11. Qxd4 $2 Ng4 {.}) 11... Bc6 12. Qc2 $1 a5 ({An important follow-up to 10.h3. White secures e4, thereby retaining full control. Now} 12... e5 $6 13. Be3 {would just create weaknesses for Black on the d-file. Meanwhile, White is all set to expand with b2-b4 or just Rad1, which will place not only f2-f4, but the c4-c5 break firmly on the table.}) {Black has usually elected to fight thematically for space so, intending to reroute his knight around to c5.} 13. Rad1 $1 a4 $5 ({White has no desire to play slowly and so reseizes control of c5 for now, since} 13... Z0 14. c5 {is a sizeable positional threat.}) 14. c5 $1 ({White might also consider} 14. f4 $5 {, but this advance has to be the critical follow-up to 13.Rad1.}) 14... Qa5 {The point of Black's play, but now he must take on an isolated queen's pawn.} 15. cxd6 exd6 16. f4 $5 ({White has also been known to maintain a fair degree of control with} 16. Rfe1 {and 17.Bf1, but there's no good reason to reject our favourite kingside advance. If allowed, White will now take full control of the position with Bf3 and a2-a3, so Black should probably react.}) 16... Nh5 $6 17. Bxh5 $1 {White instead simply exchanged on g7 in Grigoryan-Lin, Casabermeja 2021, but he should have preferred to play for a double piece exchange.} Bxd4+ 18. Rxd4 Qxh5 19. Kh2 $5 {Calmly stepping out of the way of any ...Qc5 issues. With Qd2 next up, Black is simply in some trouble on d6, as well as still struggling for meaningful counterplay.} *

