btleties now manoeuvres a little aimlessly as Black, White may consider a simple plan of h2-h3, Qd2 and Rad1, perhaps even followed by pushing the f-pawn to f4. Another useful option can be a timely Nc2, denying Black a liberating exchange on d4 and thereby keeping them quite cramped.} Bd7 10. h3 $5 ({This modest little advance, taking full control of the g4-square, trails} 10. Qd2 {,}) (10. Rc1 {and}) (10. f3 {by some margin in the popularity stakes, but has become fairly topical in recent years and used regularly by such noted theoreticians as Ivan Cheparinov and Nils Grandelius. White may simply continue with Rc1 and Qd2, but also gives the queen another option, c2.}) 10... Nxd4 {Black usually makes this thematic freeing exchange, although it isn't forced.} 11. Bxd4 ({Naturally the right way to recapture. Not} 11. Qxd4 $2 Ng4 {.}) 11... Bc6 12. Qc2 $1 a5 ({An important follow-up to 10.h3. White secures e4, thereby retaining full control. Now} 12... e5 $6 13. Be3 {would just create weaknesses for Black on the d-file. Meanwhile, White is all set to expand with b2-b4 or just Rad1, which will place not only f2-f4, but the c4-c5 break firmly on the table.}) {Black has usually elected to fight thematically for space so, intending to reroute his knight around to c5.} 13. Rad1 $1 Nd7 ({White has no desire to play slowly and so reseizes control of c5 for now, since} 13... Z0 14. c5 {is a sizeable positional threat.}) {The battle for c5 continues to rage.} 14. Bxg7 {White should exchange; there's little benefit in having the rook dragged up to d4.} Kxg7 15. Bg4 $1 Nc5 ({A strong manoeuvre, putting the c4-c5 and e4-e5 pawn breaks firmly back on the agenda. White also threatens to exchange on d7, there by taking further control of the position, not least with} 15... Z0 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. a4 {(to rule out ...b5 for good), followed by expanding on the kingside.}) 16. e5 $1 {With Black having gone one way with the knight, White goes for the remaining pawn break, thereby preparing to weaken both Black's structure and king safety with an exchange on d6.} f5 (16... h5 17. Be2 Ne6 18. Rfe1 {Simple chess, centralising a second rook to a fine square while freeing f1 for the bishop to drop back and thereby help avoid any accidents on g2.} a4 19. Bf1 Ra5 20. exd6 exd6 21. Nb5 $1 {A powerful advance, hitting d6 while freeing c3 for the queen, thereby pretty much forcing a favourable piece exchange.} Bxb5 22. Qc3+ Kh7 23. cxb5 {White was doing extremely well here in Adhiban-Bilguun, Xingtai 2019, where he didn't even want to hurry with Rxd6. Instead, Bc4 and/or Qg3 will increase the pressure against Black's slightly uncoordinated and Swiss cheese-like position.}) 17. Be2 Ne6 $6 ({Calmly dropping back. Now even} 17... f4 $5 18. Nd5 {would retain control. Meanwhile, exd6 and Qd2 are imminent.}) 18. Rfe1 {This left Black clearly worse, being set to come under heavy pressure down the central files and also the long diagonal after Nd5 and Qc3 in Andreikin-Jones, Reykjavik 2016.} *

