1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 {Black continues to copy. This solid choice can unsurprisingly become a tough nut to crack.} 4. e3 Z0 ({Our favourite set-up, looking to push d2-d4 now that any exchange on d4 can be met by exd4. At this point} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {would, of course, take play back into the realm of Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967379/#/6/w]. That leaves three major alternatives: 2c1: 4...g6 2c2: 4...e5 2c3: 4...e6 .}) *

