1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} Bg7 $6 6. d5 Na5 7. e4 {The knight on a5 is not entirely happy. White should be content with his pleasant space advantage as he continues development with h2-h3, Bd3 and O-O.} d6 8. h3 {Preventing Black from offloading his potentially problematic light-squared bishop via an exchange on f3.} O-O 9. Bd3 {White is a tempo down on a line of the Benoni, but Black's knight is much worse-placed on a5 than it would be at home on b8. Left to his own devices, White will now castle, then go Bf4 and play for the e4-e5 break. The other important thing to remember is to meet any ...a6 advance, intending to break free with ...b5 even at the cost of a pawn, with a2-a4 to keep Black cramped.} e6 10. O-O exd5 11. exd5 $1 {Denying Black any imbalance while continuing to play against a certain offside piece.} a6 12. a4 {White enjoys a pleasant edge. Qc2 and Bg5 may follow, with even Ra3 a possibility, such as if Black angles for ...Nb3 with ...Qb6.} *

