1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} d5 $6 6. dxc5 e6 ({This simply bags a pawn while threatening to harvest a second. Now} 6... dxc4 $6 7. Qxd8+ Nxd8 8. Nb5 $1 {followed by Nc7+ or Bxc4 would not spell good news for Black, so he likely has to try to shore up d5.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 ({Simple chess, forcing the pace and a favourable exchange, although after} 7... Nxd5 {White might consider} 8. Ne4 $5 {, focussing on Black's weakened dark squares.}) 8. Bb5 ({Our favourite anti-Tarrasch approach from Part One of the repertoire, although here} 8. b4 $5 {and}) (8. a3 {are also quite tempting, it must be said.}) (8. Bb5 {threatens} Z0 9. b4 {, as well as to increase the pressure with Ne5 or Nd4.}) 8... Bxc5 9. O-O {Simple chess, housing the king ahead of looking to fianchetto.} O-O 10. b3 {With Bb2 and Rc1 on the way, possibly followed by a classic Ne2/d4-f4 regrouping, White enjoys a promising version of a Tarrasch, not least because it's very hard to believe that Black wanted to weaken his kingside with ...g6.} *

