1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5.} d5 $1 {Black absolutely must challenge in the centre so. We're now in a line of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 g6 , although these days the position tends to mainly arise from a 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 move order.} 7. h3 $5 ({This move may well catch out some opponents, as these days} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 {is invariably played when Black can choose between} e6 {and 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 Nd5 10.Bxd5 e6 . You may be content to manoeuvre and play for an edge in those positions, but we'd prefer to test just how well a Symmetrical English player also knows the Panov structures.}) ({The main point of} 7. h3 {is to avoid the possibility of}) (7. c5 Bg4 $1 {, and only on the next move does White want to go 8.c5, while the pressure against d5 enables 7...Ne4?! to be met by 8.Nxd5 .}) 7... dxc4 $6 8. d5 $1 ({While there's nothing wrong with} 8. Bxc4 {, the move}) (8. d5 $1 {must be the critical test of Black's ambitious last, advancing with tempo and leaving White with an extremely pleasant edge in the event of} Nb8 $6 9. Bxc4 {followed by O-O and Re1.}) 8... Na5 9. b4 $1 {The knight on the rim isn't going to be given any peace.} Bg7 $5 {Giving up a piece so is a fairly critical try.} 10. Bf4 $1 O-O ({The knight on a5 isn't going anywhere good, so White introduces the idea of Be5, while also preventing} 10... Nxd5 $2 {due to} 11. Nxd5 {and}) (10... Ne4 {due to} 11. Nxe4 Bxa1 12. Qxa1 {respectively.}) 11. Be5 {Only now, with the long diagonal neutralised, does White want to take on a5 and then look to quickly complete development with Be2 and O-O.} b5 12. bxa5 Qxa5 ({Now} 12... b4 $6 {can even be met by} 13. Nb5 $5 {, so Black should likely take the pawn.}) 13. Be2 Ne4 $5 ({The following forcing line also leaves White clearly better: White absolutely must continue with development so. Now all is set for 14.O-O, with another important point that} 13... b4 {can be fairly well met by} 14. Qa4 $1 {. That would leave White clearly better.}) 14. Bxg7 Nxc3 ({Now} 14... Kxg7 $6 15. Qd4+ {followed by Rc1 would tidy everything up, leaving White doing pretty well.}) 15. Bxc3 Qxc3+ 16. Kf1 $1 ({We prefer this to} 16. Nd2 {, as White would now like to go 17.Qd4 and begin to take control. Black has two pawns, but surely not enough for a piece.}) *

