1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5.} d5 $1 {Black absolutely must challenge in the centre so. We're now in a line of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 g6 , although these days the position tends to mainly arise from a 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 move order.} 7. h3 $5 ({This move may well catch out some opponents, as these days} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 {is invariably played when Black can choose between} e6 {and 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 Nd5 10.Bxd5 e6 . You may be content to manoeuvre and play for an edge in those positions, but we'd prefer to test just how well a Symmetrical English player also knows the Panov structures.}) ({The main point of} 7. h3 {is to avoid the possibility of}) (7. c5 Bg4 $1 {, and only on the next move does White want to go 8.c5, while the pressure against d5 enables 7...Ne4?! to be met by 8.Nxd5 .}) 7... dxc4 $6 8. d5 $1 ({While there's nothing wrong with} 8. Bxc4 {, the move}) (8. d5 $1 {must be the critical test of Black's ambitious last, advancing with tempo and leaving White with an extremely pleasant edge in the event of} Nb8 $6 9. Bxc4 {followed by O-O and Re1.}) 8... Na5 9. b4 $1 {The knight on the rim isn't going to be given any peace.} cxb3 10. axb3 Bg7 $2 ({Renewing the piece-winning possibility of} 10... Z0 11. b4 {.}) 11. b4 $1 {White refuses to be bluffed as the tactics favour him.} Nxd5 {The point of Black's play.} 12. Nxd5 Bxa1 13. Qa4+ $1 {An important check to collect the dark-squared bishop, and with tempo.} Nc6 14. Qxa1 Z0 ({The two pieces far more than outweigh the rook and two pawns in such an open middlegame position, one where} 14... O-O $2 {will run into} 15. Bh6 {. As such, White will be able to continue with Bc4 and O-O.}) *

