1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5.} d5 $1 {Black absolutely must challenge in the centre so. We're now in a line of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 g6 , although these days the position tends to mainly arise from a 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 move order.} 7. h3 $5 ({This move may well catch out some opponents, as these days} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 {is invariably played when Black can choose between} e6 {and 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 Nd5 10.Bxd5 e6 . You may be content to manoeuvre and play for an edge in those positions, but we'd prefer to test just how well a Symmetrical English player also knows the Panov structures.}) ({The main point of} 7. h3 {is to avoid the possibility of}) (7. c5 Bg4 $1 {, and only on the next move does White want to go 8.c5, while the pressure against d5 enables 7...Ne4?! to be met by 8.Nxd5 .}) 7... dxc4 $6 8. d5 $1 ({While there's nothing wrong with} 8. Bxc4 {, the move}) (8. d5 $1 {must be the critical test of Black's ambitious last, advancing with tempo and leaving White with an extremely pleasant edge in the event of} Nb8 $6 9. Bxc4 {followed by O-O and Re1.}) 8... Na5 9. b4 $1 {The knight on the rim isn't going to be given any peace.} cxb3 10. axb3 b6 ({Renewing the piece-winning possibility of} 10... Z0 11. b4 {.}) 11. b4 $1 {Forcing the knight back to a slightly suboptimal location.} Nb7 12. Bb5+ {Developing a tempo as White wants to get castled then invade the hole on c6 after Nd4.} Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Nxd7 ({By no means the only good move, but a simple and strong choice. Now if} 13... Qxd7 {White might well even consider} 14. Ne5 {followed by Qa4+.}) 14. O-O Bg7 15. Nd4 {White has far more than enough for his pawn with Nc6 on the way, leaving Black's queen feeling the heat, as well as e7. The pressure may quickly be augmented by Re1 and Bg5 or even Nb5.} *

