{Stockfish's idea. White secures d4 and intends to ask a question of d5 after a2-a3 and Ba2.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5.} d5 $1 {Black absolutely must challenge in the centre so. We're now in a line of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 g6 , although these days the position tends to mainly arise from a 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 move order.} 7. h3 $5 ({This move may well catch out some opponents, as these days} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 {is invariably played when Black can choose between} e6 {and 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 Nd5 10.Bxd5 e6 . You may be content to manoeuvre and play for an edge in those positions, but we'd prefer to test just how well a Symmetrical English player also knows the Panov structures.}) ({The main point of} 7. h3 {is to avoid the possibility of}) (7. c5 Bg4 $1 {, and only on the next move does White want to go 8.c5, while the pressure against d5 enables 7...Ne4?! to be met by 8.Nxd5 .}) 7... a6 $5 {This move has been very rare in this position, but does transpose to Christof Sielecki's excellent Keep it Simple For Black course.} 8. c5 {Here, too, White should clamp down and seize some useful space.} Ne4 9. Bd3 {Challenging Black's most active piece.} Bf5 10. O-O Bg7 11. Re1 O-O $1 ({Having moved the king to safety, White continues to challenge for control of e4. Now} 11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 {would lead to a pleasant structure for White, with d4 secure and the b-file open. Note that 11...Nxd4?? 12.Nxd4 Bxd4 13.Qa4+ would be rather embarrassing for Black, but they can do better.}) 12. Bb1 $5 ({Now} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Rxe4 Qd5 {seems fine for Black, so White should either play the sensible 12.Be3 or be a little creative.}) *

