1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5.} d5 $1 {Black absolutely must challenge in the centre so. We're now in a line of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 g6 , although these days the position tends to mainly arise from a 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 move order.} 7. h3 $5 ({This move may well catch out some opponents, as these days} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 {is invariably played when Black can choose between} e6 {and 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 Nd5 10.Bxd5 e6 . You may be content to manoeuvre and play for an edge in those positions, but we'd prefer to test just how well a Symmetrical English player also knows the Panov structures.}) ({The main point of} 7. h3 {is to avoid the possibility of}) (7. c5 Bg4 $1 {, and only on the next move does White want to go 8.c5, while the pressure against d5 enables 7...Ne4?! to be met by 8.Nxd5 .}) 7... Bg7 8. c5 $1 {) This clamping advance is, of course, in general one of the main ideas behind the Panov-Botvinnik Attack. White clamps down on the black set-up and would now like to dominate the e5-square, if allowed, with Bb5, O-O, Bf4 and Re1.} Ne4 $5 {Angling for early counterplay.} 9. Bb5 Nxc3 ({A thematic pin, and now} 9... O-O 10. O-O {would, of course, be the same as 8...O-O 9.Bb5 Ne4 10.O-O - see here [/variation/35967476/#/10/w].}) 10. bxc3 Bd7 ({Now play is extremely likely to transpose once again after} 10... O-O 11. O-O {to our mainline [/variation/35967476/#/11/w].}) 11. O-O b6 $5 12. Re1 bxc5 $6 ({Threatening Bg5. Now Black should really just go} 12... O-O {and transpose after all.}) 13. Bxc6 ({Both the immediate} 13. Ba3 {and}) (13. Bg5 $5 {are also quite tempting and strong.}) 13... Bxc6 14. Ba3 {Clearly, Black can't take on d4 without suffering a disaster on e7, and so White will get to install his bishop on a fine outpost on c5, with a very pleasant edge thanks to the pressure down the e-file.} *

