1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5.} d5 $1 {Black absolutely must challenge in the centre so. We're now in a line of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 g6 , although these days the position tends to mainly arise from a 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 move order.} 7. h3 $5 ({This move may well catch out some opponents, as these days} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 {is invariably played when Black can choose between} e6 {and 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 Nd5 10.Bxd5 e6 . You may be content to manoeuvre and play for an edge in those positions, but we'd prefer to test just how well a Symmetrical English player also knows the Panov structures.}) ({The main point of} 7. h3 {is to avoid the possibility of}) (7. c5 Bg4 $1 {, and only on the next move does White want to go 8.c5, while the pressure against d5 enables 7...Ne4?! to be met by 8.Nxd5 .}) 7... Bg7 8. c5 $1 {This clamping advance is, of course, in general one of the main ideas behind the Panov-Botvinnik Attack. White clamps down on the black set-up and would now like to dominate the e5-square, if allowed, with Bb5, O-O, Bf4 and Re1.} O-O 9. Bb5 {White continues to fight against the ...e5 break and for the e5-square.} Bf5 10. O-O {Unsurprisingly, there's nothing better than housing the king so, not least because the king's rook would quite like to land up on e1.} Ne4 {Again, we see this liberating advance, one Black really needs to try and make work if he's not to suffer from a rather restricted position.} 11. Bf4 ({Consistently fighting for control of e5. In practice} 11. Qa4 {has also been tested, while we suspect that the engines may have a point when they wonder about}) (11. Ne2 $5 {.}) 11... Rc8 12. Re1 {White continues to welcome an exchange on c3 and a clearing of the e-file, while if Black does nothing now, White will gradually advance with Rc1, a2-a3 and b2-b4.} h6 13. Rc1 g5 $5 14. Bh2 Z0 ({That 7.h3 move continues to come in handy. The bishop is safe here, and meanwhile White was all set to roll ahead with} 14... Z0 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. b4 {as he enjoyed a pleasant, typical Panov edge in Dory-Pieterse, Wijk aan Zee 1987.}) *

