 when they wonder about}) (11. Ne2 $5 {.}) 11... Qa5 12. Qe2 $5 {Calmly overprotecting the bishop on b5 as White offers a pawn for the initiative.} Nxc3 13. bxc3 {) White is now set to trade on c6, then either pick off e7 or tidy things up with Qe3.} Qxc3 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Rac1 {Offering Black a choice of four squares for the queen ahead of pocketing e7. The position isn't completely clear, but with c6 vulnerable and Be5 or Bd6 often a useful idea, we would be quite happy as White.} Qa3 ({Note too that Black won't thrive if he now removes d4 (} 15... Qb4 16. Qxe7 Bxd4 $4 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 18. Be5 {would spell immediate dark-square ruin) or a2.}) 16. Qxe7 {Now Black must either exchange a-pawns or allow White to begin to take control with Rfe1 and Bd6.} Qxa2 17. Ra1 Qb2 18. Rxa7 Rxa7 ({Regaining the pawn while threatening to take full control with} 18... Z0 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Be5 {. Meanwhile, 18...Rae8 19.Qc7 wouldn't make for happy viewing for either the c6-pawn or rook on f8 (Bd6 or even Bh6 may well occur).}) 19. Qxa7 Bxd4 {This must be critical now that White can't just exchange on d4 then go Be5.} 20. Bd6 $1 Re8 21. Qa4 {The double-attack means that White will regain the pawn on c6, after which d5 will fall, leaving Black fighting for a draw.} *

