1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 g6 {Only with White committed to an e2-e3 set-up and so unable to play the Maroczy Bind lines from 2b does Black sneakily fianchetto. At grandmaster level, this has been a pretty trendy choice over the past 10 or so years.} 5. d4 {Naturally, we advance and so threaten to secure a pleasant edge with d4-d5, followed by e3-e4.} cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5.} d5 $1 {Black absolutely must challenge in the centre so. We're now in a line of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 g6 , although these days the position tends to mainly arise from a 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 move order.} 7. h3 $5 ({This move may well catch out some opponents, as these days} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 {is invariably played when Black can choose between} e6 {and 8...Nxc3 9.Bc4 Nd5 10.Bxd5 e6 . You may be content to manoeuvre and play for an edge in those positions, but we'd prefer to test just how well a Symmetrical English player also knows the Panov structures.}) ({The main point of} 7. h3 {is to avoid the possibility of}) (7. c5 Bg4 $1 {, and only on the next move does White want to go 8.c5, while the pressure against d5 enables 7...Ne4?! to be met by 8.Nxd5 .}) 7... Bg7 8. c5 $1 {This clamping advance is, of course, in general one of the main ideas behind the Panov-Botvinnik Attack. White clamps down on the black set-up and would now like to dominate the e5-square, if allowed, with Bb5, O-O, Bf4 and Re1.} O-O 9. Bb5 {White continues to fight against the ...e5 break and for the e5-square.} Ne4 10. O-O Nxc3 ({White shouldn't fear the doubled c-pawns, since the extra support of d4 and the half-open b-file can prove useful. Note too that} 10... e5 $6 11. Bxc6 {would now leave Black in trouble, and if} Nxc3 12. bxc3 bxc6 13. dxe5 {or 11...bxc6 12.Nxe5 Bxe5 13.Nxe4! with an extra pawn in either case.}) 11. bxc3 Bd7 ({Black's position remains slightly restricted. Both Re1 and Bg5 are on their way to keep Black tied up, and} 11... Qa5 {can simply be met by} 12. Qb3 {.}) 12. Re1 Re8 ({Now} 12... Z0 13. Bg5 {may well come with tempo against e7 , and 13...f6 14.Bh4 is normally a good deal for White, since Black won't find it all easy to force through ...e5 without creating even more weaknesses. Likewise, White should welcome 12...f6?! 13.Bf4 followed by Bd6.}) 13. Bxc6 $5 {Simple chess, playing for control of e5.} Bxc6 14. Ne5 {This left White with a small but pleasant edge in Dubovik-Kochan, correspondence 2021. Any exchange on e5 will leave White with the better bishop and safer king. Meanwhile, there are ideas of both Qf3 and Nxc6 bxc6, after which a combination of Bf4, Qa4 and Rab1 could be quick to put Black under pressure.} *

