1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} bxc6 8. Qxf3 ({A simple recapture and a decent choice, although White has also done fairly well with} 8. e4 $5 {, his grip on d5 and smoother development supplying good compensation after} fxg2 9. Bxg2 {. The text move threatens to expand with e3-e4 without losing a pawn, and Black must decide how to react.}) 8... d5 $5 9. cxd5 {White should exchange, threatening to bag another pawn as well as to advance with e3-e4.} Bg4 $6 {This was played by the leading advocate of the ...e5 variation in Hou Yifan-Vachier Lagrave, Moscow 2017, but White can do better than put the queen on f4 here.} 10. Qg3 $1 Bd6 ({Exerting potentially awkward pressure against g7 while also intending to break quickly with e3-e4, not least in the event of} 10... cxd5 $6 11. e4 $1 {followed by N(x)d5 or Bb5+.}) 11. f4 {Keeping the queen on its fine square while intending to roll ahead with e3-e4.} cxd5 12. Nxd5 $1 (12. e4 d4 13. Bb5+ Kf8 {isn't so clear, but this tactic nabs a pawn.}) 12... Nxd5 13. Qxg4 O-O 14. Qd1 {Dropping the queen back with tempo, her duty done on the kingside. White will follow up with Be2 and O-O, and Black will do well to find enough counterplay for the missing pawn and bishop-pair.} *

