1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} bxc6 8. Qxf3 ({A simple recapture and a decent choice, although White has also done fairly well with} 8. e4 $5 {, his grip on d5 and smoother development supplying good compensation after} fxg2 9. Bxg2 {. The text move threatens to expand with e3-e4 without losing a pawn and Black must decide how to react.}) 8... d5 $5 9. cxd5 {White should exchange, threatening to bag another pawn as well as to advance with e3-e4.} cxd5 10. e4 $1 {Ever a thematic break against hanging pawns, as well as one that here threatens both e4-e5 and Bg5.} dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4+ {The hanging rook and potentially awkward check on b5 mean that Black has only one good way to block the check.} Qe7 $1 13. Qe3 $1 {White wants any queen exchange to improve the development, and must have an edge. Not only is c5 potentially vulnerable, but White will be quick to complete development with Bc4 and O-O, and also has ideas of a timely Bb5+ or b2-b3 followed by a queen exchange and Ba3 or Bb2.} *

