1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} bxc6 8. Qxf3 ({A simple recapture and a decent choice, although White has also done fairly well with} 8. e4 $5 {, his grip on d5 and smoother development supplying good compensation after} fxg2 9. Bxg2 {. The text move threatens to expand with e3-e4 without losing a pawn and Black must decide how to react.}) 8... Bd6 9. g4 $5 ({An aggressive advance, one which threatens g4-g5 and so fights hard for the initiative. Instead,} 9. e4 O-O 10. Bd3 Be5 {should be solid enough for Black.}) 9... O-O 10. Bd2 $5 ({Here} 10. Bd3 {has been tested, included in Jones-Grandelius, Malmo 2019, which was drawn, but we would prefer an idea suggested by Flank Openings expert IM David Cummings on Chess Publishing.}) 10... g6 ({White facilitates both Rd1 and O-O-O, and would now meet} 10... Be5 {with} 11. g5 Ne8 12. h4 {with a pleasant initiative.}) 11. g5 Nh5 12. Qg2 {This way, to defend g5 and facilitate Be2xh5.} Be5 13. Rd1 {Cummings stopped his analysis here. The position could certainly do with some testing. We'd be happy enough as White, having restrained ...d5 and with Be2 on the way. As well as h2-h4-h5 if the black knight retreats, White also very much has ideas of f2-f4 and O-O, with Ne4 another potentially very useful move.} *

