1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} fxg2 {Black's most forcing continuation.} 8. cxd7+ {Clearly fairly essential. Now MVL has favoured keeping queens on as Black.} Qxd7 9. Bxg2 $1 ({It's important to try and tie Black to the defence of b7, not speed up his development with} 9. Qxd7+ Bxd7 {.}) 9... Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 ({Actually, this is not forced.} 10. Kxd1 $5 Bg4+ 11. Kc2 {also seemed fairly promising in Dzagnidze-A.Muzychuk, Kazan 2019. The text move intends b2-b3 and Bb2, as well as a quick return of the knight to c3.}) 10... Bd6 11. b3 Be5 12. Bb2 Bxb2 13. Nxb2 {White enjoyed a pull and a pleasant edge in Nikolac-Kragelj, Pula 1998, with the knight able to go to d3 or even a4, after which O-O-O in conjunction with Nc3 and Nb5 or Nd5 could be a promising plan, with Rg1 another potentially useful possibility.} *

