1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} fxg2 {Black's most forcing continuation.} 8. cxd7+ {Clearly fairly essential. Now MVL has favoured keeping queens on as Black.} Bxd7 $5 9. Bxg2 {Hitting b7.} g6 10. O-O ({Simple chess, housing the king ahead of rolling the central pawn majority. We prefer this to the more common} 10. b3 Bg7 11. Qd6 {, when Vachier-Lagrave has demonstrated that Black should be solid enough after} Qb6 $1 {.}) 10... Bg7 11. e4 ({Here White went} 11. Qd6 {in Sevian-Vachier Lagrave, PRO League (rapid) 2019, when} Ng4 $1 {would have been OK for Black.}) {Threatening to seize the initiative with e4-e5.} 11... O-O 12. e5 Ng4 13. f4 $1 Be6 ({An important advance, securing the bridgehead on e5 while refusing to fear} 13... Qh4 $6 14. h3 Nxe5 15. fxe5 Bxh3 {when Black shouldn't have enough for the piece after} 16. Bf4 $1 {.}) 14. Qxd8 {Removing the queens so gets rid of one black piece supporting a potential break in ...f6.} Raxd8 15. Nd5 Z0 ({Black is quite solid here, but White may have an edge thanks to the cramping central bridgehead. The plan is Bd2-c3, perhaps followed by b2-b3 and Rad1, while} 15... f6 $2 {would now be well met by} 16. h3 Nh6 17. exf6 {.}) *

