1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} dxc6 {The most solid continuation, offering an exchange of queens.} 8. Qxd8+ ({White must exchange so and force the king to move, not allow Black to seize the initiative with} 8. Qxf3 $2 Bg4 9. Qg3 Bd6 {.}) 8... Kxd8 9. gxf3 {White's structure is the more healthy one (our central pawns can advance with somewhat more purpose than Black's rather stymied queenside majority), and we would like to obtain some pressure down the long dark-square diagonal, ideally with b2-b3 and Bb2 in conjunction with Rg1.} Bd6 10. b3 {White simply wants to go Bb2 and O-O-O, after which, of course, any ...Be5 could at least be met by f3-f4.} Kc7 (10... Ke7 11. Bb2 Rd8 12. O-O-O {The first part of the plan is complete. Now White would like to obtain targets and some play on the kingside.} Be6 13. Bd3 {Preparing to cramp Black with f3-f4 and then, if allowed, f4-f5. Another potentially strong advance for White is h2-h4, and if ...h5 then Ne2-g3 may cause trouble for Black.} g6 {White went on to grind out the win after} 14. Ne2 {in Jacobson-Stearman, Las Vegas 2023, but it was also possible to keep open the possibilities of a timely Ne4 or Na4 for a while: 14.f4!? Now 15.f3 would leave White with pretty useful central control, so Black is likely to react here, and either minor piece heading to g4 can be met well enough by Rd2. 14...Ng4 15.Rd2 Threatening Ne4. 15...Bc7 15...f5 16.h4 also looks a little suspect for Black. 16.Kc2 Good prophylaxis, overprotecting the bishop on d3 to facilitate White's next. 16...Ba5 17.Re2 With Ne4 and e3-e4 threatened, as well as just f2-f3, White looks to hold a small but pleasant edge and may be able to ask an awkward and timely question over c5.}) 11. Bb2 Re8 12. O-O-O ({Housing the king without delay ahead of going Bd3, although the immediate} 12. h4 $5 {must also come into the equation.}) 12... Bf5 13. Ne2 $1 {An important manoeuvre, designed to disrupt. White prepares Ng3 while unfurling that fine bishop on b2.} Be5 14. Ba3 $5 ({White was happy enough with} 14. Ng3 {after all here in R.Svane-Samunenkov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021, but might also have kept pieces on.}) {Attacking c5 while intending expansion with Ng3 and f3-f4.} 14... b6 15. Ng3 Bg6 16. f4 Z0 ({It would take a brave opponent to go} 16... Ba1 {here, but the engines think Black must remain only slightly worse after} 17. Rg1 {or even 17.f5 , since otherwise White will be quick to increase the pressure with Bb2 and Rg1.}) *

