1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} dxc6 {The most solid continuation, offering an exchange of queens.} 8. Qxd8+ ({White must exchange so and force the king to move, not allow Black to seize the initiative with} 8. Qxf3 $2 Bg4 9. Qg3 Bd6 {.}) 8... Kxd8 9. gxf3 {White's structure is the more healthy one (our central pawns can advance with somewhat more purpose than Black's rather stymied queenside majority), and we would like to obtain some pressure down the long dark-square diagonal, ideally with b2-b3 and Bb2 in conjunction with Rg1.} Kc7 10. b3 $1 {Yet again, a good plan, intending Bb2 and O-O-O.} g6 $6 11. Bb2 Rg8 ({All of a sudden Black must be careful.} 11... Bg7 $2 12. Ne4 {would win a pawn.}) 12. Na4 $1 Nd7 13. h4 $1 Z0 ({With h4-h5 imminent and} 13... h5 14. f4 {followed by arranging f4-f5 also a bit unpleasant, Black was already under some pressure in Riemer-Marten, correspondence 2017.}) *

