1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} dxc6 {The most solid continuation, offering an exchange of queens.} 8. Qxd8+ ({White must exchange so and force the king to move, not allow Black to seize the initiative with} 8. Qxf3 $2 Bg4 9. Qg3 Bd6 {.}) 8... Kxd8 9. gxf3 {White's structure is the more healthy one (our central pawns can advance with somewhat more purpose than Black's rather stymied queenside majority), and we would like to obtain some pressure down the long dark-square diagonal, ideally with b2-b3 and Bb2 in conjunction with Rg1.} Kc7 10. b3 $1 {Yet again, a good plan, intending Bb2 and O-O-O.} Be7 11. Bb2 Rd8 ({White is now ready to go long, with h2-h4-h5 another useful idea, and here we might well again meet} 11... Bf5 {with} 12. Ne2 {, intending Ng3 with gain of tempo.}) {Preventing White from castling.} 12. h4 $1 {A useful gain of space. White has ideas of not only h4-h5 but of making a fairly helpful bishop exchange with Bh3 ahead of placing the king on e2.} g6 {Black fights to avoid becoming too cramped on the kingside.} 13. Ne4 $1 ({Forcing the pace. This is an important alternative over} 13. Bh3 Bxh3 14. Rxh3 Kd7 {, which had been OK for Black in the earlier Aronian-Vachier Lagrave, London 2015.}) 13... Nxe4 14. fxe4 h5 $1 ({White would now like to squeeze with h4-h5, with Be5+ Bd6; Bf6 another idea. The f2-pawn is also quite mobile, and White should not object to} 14... Bg4 15. Be2 $1 Bxe2 16. Kxe2 {followed by h4-h5 or f2-f4.}) 15. Be5+ $5 ({The aforementioned discombobulation. The correspondence world has though been happy with simply} 15. Be2 {.}) 15... Bd6 16. Bf6 Re8 17. f3 {Securing e4 while keeping Black out of g4. The king can advance to d2 or e2 if checked, and White holds a small but pretty pleasant edge. Just observe Black's lack of counterplay.} Z0 ({We should probably follow Aronian-Vachier Lagrave, German GRENKE Chess Classic, Karlsruhe 2017, for a few more moves:} 17... a5 $6 18. a4 {Fixing the black pawn on a5.} Be7 19. Bc3 $1 {With a pleasant space advantage, White is happy to retain pieces and will ideally now castle long, then gradually arrange to expand on the kingside.} Be6 20. O-O-O b6 21. Be2 {Keeping Black out of g4 as preparation for a future f3-f4 push while also facilitating White's next.} Red8 22. Rdg1 $5 b5 $6 23. Kc2 {Clearly, Black isn't getting anywhere on the queenside now that b3 is secure. White was ready to expand with f3-f4 or Be5+ Bd6; Bf6 followed by e4-e5, the latter plan gradually helping to run Vachier-Lagrave out of moves as Aronian won a positional game. 17...Be5 18.Bxe5+ Rxe5 19.Bd3 Even here, you'd want to take White, who may go Kf2, and only then advance the f-pawn, ideally all the way to f5. 19...a5 20.a4! It's again important to render Black's queenside majority impotent, not to allow some counterplay with ...a4. 20...Bd7 21.Kf2 Rd8 22.Rad1 Re6 23.Bc2! White doesn't allow Black to dominate the d-file and eventually won after 61 moves in R.Svane-De Abreu, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2017, his king playing a pivotal role once all the rooks had gone, dancing forwards via g3, f4 and g5.}) *

