1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} dxc6 {The most solid continuation, offering an exchange of queens.} 8. Qxd8+ ({White must exchange so and force the king to move, not allow Black to seize the initiative with} 8. Qxf3 $2 Bg4 9. Qg3 Bd6 {.}) 8... Kxd8 9. gxf3 {White's structure is the more healthy one (our central pawns can advance with somewhat more purpose than Black's rather stymied queenside majority), and we would like to obtain some pressure down the long dark-square diagonal, ideally with b2-b3 and Bb2 in conjunction with Rg1.} g6 {Many moves have been tried here, but this feels like Black's best defence, preparing to contest the key diagonal.} 10. b3 {White may as well be consistent, preparing Bb2 then O-O-O+, after which Ne4 or Ne2 may follow.} Bg7 11. Bb2 Ke7 ({Threatening to win a pawn with} 11... Z0 12. Ne4 {.}) 12. Bg2 $5 {A modest little move, if also decent enough preparation for Ne4. The bishop will also be well placed here in the event of any ...b6 from Black and f3-f4 expansion from White.} ({David Cummings's related idea of} 12. Na4 $5 b6 13. Bg2 {followed by f3-f4 also deserves attention, but in practice White has usually gone 12.O-O-O when 12...Be6 followed by ...Rhd8 has been shown to be very solid for Black.}) 12... Bf5 13. Ne4 {As an exchange on e4 would only play into White's hands, Black has only one real way to defend c5.} b6 14. Ng3 {Leaping backwards with tempo ahead of activating the bishop on g2 with f3-f4.} Be6 15. f4 Rac8 16. h4 {Black is still pretty solid, but is also under some pressure and, of course, has the inferior structure. White may now look to press ahead with Be5 and h4-h5, or even try to get in e3-e4, then ideally a timely f4-f5.} *

