1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} e4 $5 {The modern try and likely the critical line.} 6. d5 ({A forcing continuation, designed to retain a fair degree of control. The big alternative is} 6. Ne5 {, but by avoiding an exchange on d4, Black has given himself some extra options and would appear to be OK in an unclear scenario after} g6 {and even 6...h5!? .}) 6... exf3 {Without a good square for his knight, Black pretty much must exchange so.} 7. dxc6 {White threatens to win a pawn and here all three of Black's captures have seen a reasonable degree of testing.} dxc6 {The most solid continuation, offering an exchange of queens.} 8. Qxd8+ ({White must exchange so and force the king to move, not allow Black to seize the initiative with} 8. Qxf3 $2 Bg4 9. Qg3 Bd6 {.}) 8... Kxd8 9. gxf3 {White's structure is the more healthy one (our central pawns can advance with somewhat more purpose than Black's rather stymied queenside majority), and we would like to obtain some pressure down the long dark-square diagonal, ideally with b2-b3 and Bb2 in conjunction with Rg1.} g6 {Many moves have been tried here, but this feels like Black's best defence, preparing to contest the key diagonal.} 10. b3 {White may as well be consistent, preparing Bb2 then O-O-O+, after which Ne4 or Ne2 may follow.} Bg7 11. Bb2 b6 ({Threatening to win a pawn with} 11... Z0 12. Ne4 {.}) ({Arguably Black's most solid defence.} 11... Bf5 $6 12. Ne4 $1 {Played anyhow to force a favourable exchange.} Bxe4 13. fxe4 {White's central majority and bishop-pair are handy assets and already f2-f4 and e4-e5 is imminent.} Nh5 $6 14. e5 $1 Re8 15. O-O-O+ Kc7 16. Bh3 $1 Re7 17. Bg4 {With f2-f4 and an exchange on h5 on the way, White was already doing very well in Donchenko-Stijve, Bad Ragaz 2020.}) 12. a4 $5 {It's not just the kingside where White may expand. The text prepares to probe with a4-a5 and also has in mind a rather decent idea concerning the a3-square.} a5 13. O-O-O+ {Housing the king with tempo ahead of looking to obtain a bit of pressure with Ne4.} Kc7 14. Ne4 Nh5 15. Ba3 $5 {A strange looking move, but the idea is to keep pieces on and only return the bishop to b2 at a later date. Jonas Bjerre's games after 9...g6 had shown that Black should be able to hold relatively comfortably if the bishops are traded, whereas he was to be gradually ground down in Nguyen-Bjerre, Wijk aan Zee 2022. With care, Black should have been able to hold, but White's game is likely the easier to handle, with ideas of not just a quick Ng5, but Be2 and f3-f4 or Ng3, and if ...Nf6; h2-h4, as well as simply Bd3 and Kc2, as Nguyen, the Czech no.2, opted for.} *

