1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 exd4 7. Nxd4 {Naturally, White recaptures, threatening Ndb5 as well as Be2 and O-O, and, of course, this position could also come about via a 5...exd4 6.exd4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 if Black preferred.} d5 $5 8. Qa4 $1 {White keeps cxd5 ideas in reserve while simply threatening to take twice on c6.} Qe7+ $6 9. Be3 {Renewing the threat.} Qb4 10. O-O-O $1 {A powerful way to unpin while introducing the threat of Ndb5.} Qxa4 11. Nxa4 {Ndb5 was very much still an idea, as well as simply Nc3, all as White enjoyed the superior development and a pleasant early advantage in Bunzmann-Frosch, Austrian League 2008.} *

