1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 exd4 7. Nxd4 {Naturally, White recaptures, threatening Ndb5 as well as Be2 and O-O, and, of course, this position could also come about via a 5...exd4 6.exd4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 if Black preferred.} d5 $5 8. Qa4 $1 {White keeps cxd5 ideas in reserve while simply threatening to take twice on c6.} Qb6 $5 9. cxd5 {White is again happy enough to see the queens traded on a4.} Qxd4 10. dxc6 Qxa4 11. Nxa4 ({An essential recapture, since} 11. cxb7 $2 Qc6 {wouldn't be wise.}) 11... Bb4+ 12. Bd2 $1 {With queens off, White is happy enough to leave the king in the centre, and we will shortly enjoy the superior structure.} Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 O-O $5 14. Re1 $5 {Sensible chess, refusing to accelerate Black's development by grabbing a pawn. The king can now retreat to c1 if checked, and White also has ideas of Re7.} bxc6 15. Bc4 {With the superior structure and ideas of both Nc5 and Re7, White holds a small but pleasant advantage.} *

