1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 exd4 7. Nxd4 {Naturally, White recaptures, threatening Ndb5 as well as Be2 and O-O, and, of course, this position could also come about via a 5...exd4 6.exd4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 if Black preferred.} d5 $5 8. Qa4 $1 {White keeps cxd5 ideas in reserve while simply threatening to take twice on c6.} Bd7 9. cxd5 {Enabling the queen to take back on d4 and Black will now find himself a pawn in arrears unless he goes in for some tactics:} Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Bb4+ $1 {Otherwise, White would, of course, just be a piece to the good.} 11. Nxb4 Qe7+ 12. Be3 $1 ({Now} 12. Kd1 Nxd4 13. Qa3 O-O {feels like it should give Black enough for a piece, but we shouldn't forget that White is currently two pieces ahead.}) 12... Nxd4 13. Qxd7+ $5 ({Rather than allow} 13. Qa3 Qxb4+ {, White transforms the position and prepares a pin on the d-file, be it with 13...Kxd7 14.O-O-O or the following.}) 13... Qxd7 14. Rd1 $1 ({And not} 14. O-O-O $2 Qc8+ {.}) 14... Nf3+ 15. gxf3 Qa4 16. a3 {The position isn't totally clear, but with Be2 then O-O next up and the knight with good chances of dominating the board from d5, we would certainly take the three pieces over the queen, and the engines agree that White should be slightly better.} *

