1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 exd4 7. Nxd4 {Naturally, White recaptures, threatening Ndb5 as well as Be2 and O-O, and, of course, this position could also come about via a 5...exd4 6.exd4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 if Black preferred.} Bb4 8. Qe2+ $5 ({Again, this is a slightly disruptive check for Black to face, although White can also consider the simple} 8. Be2 {, followed by O-O or Ndb5 (}) (8. Ndb5 O-O 9. a3 Ba5 $1 10. b4 a6 {doesn't seem completely clear, though).}) 8... Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $5 ({A simple and consistent choice. Here} 9... Nxe7 10. Ndb5 {supplied an edge in Sanchez Gonzalez-Rodriguez de Castro, Galapagar 2009, so perhaps Black should prefer a more radical recapture.}) 10. Be3 $5 ({Sidestepping Black's idea of} 10. Ndb5 d5 $1 {while preparing to castle long and not fearing doubled c-pawns with Black potentially vulnerable on the dark squares.}) 10... Ng4 11. Nf5+ {Covering the bishop with tempo ahead of kicking the black knight.} Kf6 12. h3 $1 Nxe3 ({Now} 12... Kxf5 $2 13. hxg4+ Kxg4 $2 14. Bd3 {would only be played by those with a death wish; a sensible opponent will prefer other ways to exchange pieces.}) 13. Nxe3 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 {The position is a bit messy, but White threatens Nd5 and is all set to dominate the d-file after O-O-O. Overall, we suspect that his initiative and control should slightly outweigh the fragmented queenside pawns.} *

