1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 exd4 7. Nxd4 {Naturally, White recaptures, threatening Ndb5 as well as Be2 and O-O, and, of course, this position could also come about via a 5...exd4 6.exd4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 if Black preferred.} Bb4 8. Qe2+ $5 ({Again, this is a slightly disruptive check for Black to face, although White can also consider the simple} 8. Be2 {, followed by O-O or Ndb5 (}) (8. Ndb5 O-O 9. a3 Ba5 $1 10. b4 a6 {doesn't seem completely clear, though).}) 8... Ne7 {It looks as though White should have an easy advantage, but Black's position is dynamic.} 9. Bg5 {Threatening structural ruin on f6, as well as to castle long.} Qa5 10. Qe3 $1 {Covering g5 and c3, while intending Be2 and O-O as well as Bxf6.} Ng4 11. Qd2 {Necessary to keep everything under control, and now Be2 may come with tempo.} d5 $5 12. Bxe7 {A simple and strong exchange, forcing Black to play with his king in the centre or to give up a pawn.} Bxe7 13. Nb3 {With Nxd5 next up, followed by Be2, it would be surprising if Black had enough compensation.} *

