1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Qa5 $2 8. c5 $1 d5 ({A crushing advance to exploit the queen's absence from d8. White threatens Nc4 followed by d4-d5, and} 8... d6 9. Nc4 Qd8 10. d5 {is simply very strong.}) 9. Bb5 Bd7 ({A powerful pin, not least when} 9... Qc7 {can be met by} 10. Bf4 {.}) 10. Nxd7 {Simple and strong chess as White prepares to castle, then seize the initiative.} Nxd7 11. O-O O-O-O $2 ({Now there's even the threat of Nxd5 and} 11... Nf6 12. Bg5 {would keep up the pressure.}) 12. Bxc6 ({A classic case of from the frying pan into the fire. Now White has several tempting and strong continuations, including} 12. b4 $5 {.}) {Continuing to force the pace while weakening the black king's defences.} 12... bxc6 13. Rb1 {With b2-b4-b5 on the way, White enjoyed a very strong attack and won quickly in E.L'Ami-Bezemer, Hoogeveen 2012.} *

