1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} d6 8. Nxc6 {White doesn't mind this exchange, creating a potential weakness or hook on c6 while intending to quickly go Be2 and castle.} bxc6 9. Be2 Be7 ({Getting closer to castling, after which White would quite like to expand on the queenside and so might even meet} 9... d5 {with} 10. c5 {, followed by O-O and b2-b4.}) 10. O-O ({We prefer this to the} 10. Bg5 {of Lamard-Boumrar, Vandoeuvre les Nancy 2022. After}) (10. O-O {, White is now all set to expand on the queenside with b2-b4, or if} a5 11. a3 {followed by Rb1.}) 10... O-O 11. b4 {White's queenside space looks more relevant than Black's in the centre. White may complete development with Bf4, then aim to press ahead on the queenside with a2-a4 and b4-b5.} a5 $6 12. b5 $1 cxb5 13. cxb5 ({Also quite tempting is} 13. Nxb5 $5 {, but the passed pawn should be a useful asset. White may continue with Qb3, then look to fight for control of d5 with Bg5.}) 13... Be6 14. d5 {Forcing the pace. With Be3 and/or Qd4 on the way, White is in full control, and the passed b-pawn is already looking like a pretty handy asset indeed.} *

