1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bd6 $5 {This creative try was used by Alexander Grischuk during his 2011 Candidates match with Vladimir Kramnik.} 8. Ng4 $1 {)} ({One of two good moves, the other being} 8. c5 Bb8 9. Nc4 d5 10. cxd6 {. With the text White plays against the advanced pawn on e4, introducing ideas of Nxf6+, Bg5 and d4-d5.}) 8... Nxg4 9. Qxg4 {With tempo against e4 and g7.} O-O 10. Bh6 {It's not every day that you get to develop your bishop straight to h6, threatening mate.} Qf6 11. Be3 Bb4 $1 ({White secures d4, threatens Qxe4, and now} 11... Nxd4 $2 12. O-O-O Be5 13. Nd5 {followed by Qxe4 would supply a pretty strong initiative.}) 12. Qxe4 d5 {In conjunction with Black's last, the only real try, offering a second pawn for a lead in development.} 13. Qxd5 {The human way to pocket the pawn since White will now always have Qg5 if needed.} Rd8 $1 14. Qg5 {Returning one of the pawns to remove the queens, a policy Black should go along with, since White is threatening Qxf6, as well as a2-a3 and O-O-O.} Qxg5 15. Bxg5 Rxd4 16. Rc1 {Avoiding doubled pawns and leaving the onus on Black to demonstrate that there's enough compensation. The engines suggest that there almost is, but we would certainly be quite happy as White with Be3 and a2-a3 on the way, followed by Be2 and O-O.} *

