1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bd6 $5 {This creative try was used by Alexander Grischuk during his 2011 Candidates match with Vladimir Kramnik.} 8. Ng4 $1 ({One of two good moves, the other being} 8. c5 Bb8 9. Nc4 d5 10. cxd6 {. With the text White plays against the advanced pawn on e4, introducing ideas of Nxf6+, Bg5 and d4-d5.}) 8... Nxg4 9. Qxg4 {With tempo against e4 and g7.} O-O 10. Bh6 {It's not every day that you get to develop your bishop straight to h6, threatening mate.} Qf6 11. Be3 Bb4 $1 ({White secures d4, threatens Qxe4, and now} 11... Nxd4 $2 12. O-O-O Be5 13. Nd5 {followed by Qxe4 would supply a pretty strong initiative.}) 12. Qxe4 d5 {In conjunction with Black's last, the only real try, offering a second pawn for a lead in development.} 13. Qxd5 {The human way to pocket the pawn since White will now always have Qg5 if needed.} Bf5 $2 {Played by grandmasters on the three occasions this position has been tested over the board, but it is also a move White should be happy to see.} 14. O-O-O $1 {A strong way to break the pin. White is now set to go Qf3 and Bd3, the king should be safe enough on the queenside, and we shouldn't lose sight of the fact that Black is two pawns down.} Rfd8 15. Qf3 Nxd4 ({Threatening Nd5 as well as Bd3. Not only does White cause some problems down the f-file, but he can now meet} 15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 Qg6 {with} 17. Qg3 {.}) 16. Nd5 $1 {This would also be the refutation had Black deployed the other rook to d8.} Nxf3 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. gxf3 {Black was a pawn down and suffering in Mekhitarian-Barbosa, Florianopolis 2018, since White has ideas of not just Be2 and Rd1, but also a2-a3 and Bxa7 or Rg1+ and Bh6.} *

