1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bb4 {Black usually pins so.} 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development, preparing to castle. Do please avoid Black's trap:} 8. Bd2 $2 Nxd4 9. Nxe4 $2 Qe7 {when White loses material.}) 8... Qe7 9. Bf4 $1 Bd6 ({Securing the knight on e5 ahead of castling and, of course,} 9... d6 $2 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qa4 {wouldn't be wise for Black.}) 10. Nxc6 ({Simple chess as White plays to retain control, although creative souls may wish to consider the fascinating idea of} 10. Bg5 $5 Nxe5 11. Nd5 {when White should emerge with decent compensation for a pawn.}) 10... dxc6 11. Qd2 {Refusing to do Black's hard work for them. White would be quite happy if the queen now got to emerge via f4.} O-O {Here, White exchanged on d6 then castled in Epishin-Topalov, Elenite 1994.} 12. h3 $5 {Denying Black's bishop a liberating exchange via g4 as Topalov got to make.} Be6 13. Bxd6 ({Only exchanging now that} 13. O-O Bxf4 $1 14. Qxf4 Qb4 {would attack both b2 and c4, and in a position where b2-b3 clearly isn't available.}) 13... Qxd6 14. O-O {White has a small edge thanks to his more relevant central control. Rad1 and Qe3 will likely follow, perhaps leading to more piece tidying with Rfe1 and Bf1, after which White may look to arrange a timely d4-d5 break and/or advance on the queenside.} *

