1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bb4 {Black usually pins so.} 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development, preparing to castle. Do please avoid Black's trap:} 8. Bd2 $2 Nxd4 9. Nxe4 $2 Qe7 {when White loses material.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Re8 ({Completing kingside development. Naturally, White would now welcome} 9... Nxe5 $2 10. dxe5 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Ne8 12. Qd4 {with a large advantage. Likewise, 9...Qa5?! 10.c5! leaves Black in early trouble, while 9...Qe7 can be well met by 10.Bf4 or 10.Ng4 .}) 10. Bf4 Bf8 ({Supporting the knight on e5 while again intending} 10... d6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qa4 {.}) (10... Qb6 $2 11. c5 $1 Qd8 12. Qb3 {This effectively double attack is already overwhelming.} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qc7 15. e6 $1 {Already you'd hardly blame Black had he resigned here in Rozum-Duzhakov, St. Petersburg 2011.}) 11. h3 $5 ({A useful move and seemingly a better choice than} 11. c5 {(as tested OTB-wise)} d6 {when Black is only slightly worse. White has another useful move coming up in Re1, so Black would surely now look to untangle the queenside.}) 11... d6 12. Nxc6 ({Thanks to White's last move} 12. Ng4 $5 {, and if} Bxg4 13. hxg4 {is also quite tempting, but the text move is simple and strong.}) 12... bxc6 13. b4 $1 {White should be clearly for choice, already being somewhat advanced on the queenside. He'll meet ...d5 with c4-c5, while in any case the main plan is to continue the advance with a2-a4 then b4-b5.} *

