1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bb4 {Black usually pins so.} 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development, preparing to castle. Do please avoid Black's trap:} 8. Bd2 $2 Nxd4 9. Nxe4 $2 Qe7 {when White loses material.}) 8... d5 {Rare, if not terrible.} 9. O-O {) Unpinning while continuing development. White is now ready to increase the pressure against d5 with Bg5 and need not fear a central exchange.} dxc4 {As played in V. Moiseenko-Iljushina, Tuapse 2022, where White was happy to exchange on c6.} 10. Bg5 $5 {A strong pawn sacrifice, threatening Nxe4 and, of course, c4 is also pretty tender.} Qxd4 11. Nxc6 {It's high time to initiate a forcing sequence.} Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 {This rook, reserving the other for the c-file.} bxc6 13. Nxe4 $1 {The point of White's play, exploiting the potential mate on d8. Black can avoid that and structural ruin on f6, but is unpleasantly worse thanks to his weaknesses on the c-file.} Nd5 14. Bxc4 Be6 15. Rac1 {White is now all set to ask an awkward question of the bishop on b4 with a2-a3, since we'd like to get Nc5 in. Meanwhile, Bb3 or even Bf1 (meaning that ...Rac8 can be met by Ba6) is set to unfurl an attack on c6 and Black is definitely suffering.} *

