1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bb4 {Black usually pins so.} 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development, preparing to castle. Do please avoid Black's trap:} 8. Bd2 $2 Nxd4 9. Nxe4 $2 Qe7 {when White loses material.}) 8... Qa5 {The main line, playing against e5 and c3, if by no means a forced move.} 9. Nxc6 ({A simple approach, although a tempting alternative is the Aronian-endorsed} 9. O-O $5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Bd2 {with the initiative and good compensation for the pawn. The text forces the pace and simply intends O-O, followed by Bd2 and a2-a3, which should maintain control.}) 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 bxc6 ({Clearly there's no time for} 10... Qxc3+ $4 {on account of} 11. Bd2 {, and now 10...dxc6 can be well enough met by 11.Bd2 or 11.Qb3 followed by O-O.}) 11. Qb3 $5 {A fairly strong idea in this structure, heading for a3 as White begins to conquer the dark squares.} O-O 12. Qa3 Qf5 $1 ({Here} 12... Qxa3 $2 13. Bxa3 Re8 14. Bd6 {left White in complete control in Alvarez Pedraza-Tapie Amione, Merida 2011, so Black should probably keep the queens on and fight against Bf4 and Bg5 ideas.}) 13. O-O {The king is quite safe here. White is surely slightly for choice, with Qd6 on the way, leaving Black slightly low on counterplay as well as vulnerable on the dark squares.} *

