1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bb4 {Black usually pins so.} 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development, preparing to castle. Do please avoid Black's trap:} 8. Bd2 $2 Nxd4 9. Nxe4 $2 Qe7 {when White loses material.}) 8... Qa5 {The main line, playing against e5 and c3, if by no means a forced move.} 9. Nxc6 ({A simple approach, although a tempting alternative is the Aronian-endorsed} 9. O-O $5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Bd2 {with the initiative and good compensation for the pawn. The text forces the pace and simply intends O-O, followed by Bd2 and a2-a3, which should maintain control.}) 9... dxc6 {Black usually recaptures this way to bring his light-squared bishop into play.} 10. Bd2 {A simple approach: preparing to recapture with the bishop on c3, while intending O-O followed by a2-a3.} Bxc3 11. Bxc3 {Recapturing this way and with tempo, as White has a strong pawn sacrifice in mind for when Black attacks g2.} Qg5 12. Qd2 $1 Qxg2 ({Clearly} 12... Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 $5 {would be a pleasant edge for White with his bishop-pair and central control. Now O-O-O is on the way if the queens stay on.}) 13. O-O-O {Threatening to crash through in the centre with d4-d5, as well as just go Rhg1 and Rxg7.} Qxf2 14. Rhf1 $1 Qxh2 15. d5 $1 Z0 ({Black is three pawns ahead, but also completely lost. Why? Well, just note the strength of that fine bishop on c3, as well as the unhappily placed black king and the large threat of Qg5. Finally,} 15... O-O $2 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rh1 {would just be game over. 15...Bg4 was tried in Solleveld-Laubsch, Bethune 2011, where White went on to win after 16.Rde1 , and he had something even stronger: 16.dxc6! Threatening to take on b7 and then f6, while the queen will invade via d6 or d7 depending on how Black captures on e2. 16...Qxe2 16...O-O !? 17.Bxg4! Qxd2+ 18.Rxd2 Nxg4 19.cxb7 Rab8 20.Rd7 White's unopposed bishop and passed c-pawn will swiftly carry the day. 17.Qd6 b6 18.c7 Nd7 19.Rfe1! Qxd1+ 20.Rxd1 Bxd1 21.Kxd1 Black is still doing well enough on the material front, but just look at his coordination! Indeed, the engines have White as winning by force, since -- 22.b4 followed by -- 23.c5 bxc5 24.bxc5 and -- 25.c6 is such a threat, while there will always be a timely Bxg7.}) *

