1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bb4 {Black usually pins so.} 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development, preparing to castle. Do please avoid Black's trap:} 8. Bd2 $2 Nxd4 9. Nxe4 $2 Qe7 {when White loses material.}) 8... Qa5 {The main line, playing against e5 and c3, if by no means a forced move.} 9. Nxc6 ({A simple approach, although a tempting alternative is the Aronian-endorsed} 9. O-O $5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Bd2 {with the initiative and good compensation for the pawn. The text forces the pace and simply intends O-O, followed by Bd2 and a2-a3, which should maintain control.}) 9... dxc6 {Black usually recaptures this way to bring his light-squared bishop into play.} 10. Bd2 {A simple approach: preparing to recapture with the bishop on c3, while intending O-O followed by a2-a3.} O-O 11. O-O ({Here before a2-a3, as} 11. a3 Bxc3 $1 12. Bxc3 Qg5 {is no longer so clear in view of} 13. Qd2 $5 Qxg2 14. O-O-O e3 $1 {.}) 11... Rd8 12. a3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 $5 ({An unexpected recapture, if one we like in general, keeping the black queen away from g5. That said,} 13. Bxc3 {is also a pleasant edge here, in view of} Qg5 14. Qc1 $1 {.}) 13... c5 14. a4 $1 {Useful expansion as d4 is secure. White may now gradually improve his position with such moves as h2-h3, Qc2, Be3 and Rfb1, all the while as Black has to watch out for a timely d4-d5 or Bg5.} cxd4 $2 15. cxd4 Qf5 16. d5 $1 {With such a fine unopposed dark-squared bishop and strong centre, not to mention even such possibilities as Ra3, White was already doing pretty well in Sethuraman-Nabaty, FIDE World Cup, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019.} *

