1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bb4 {Black usually pins so.} 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development, preparing to castle. Do please avoid Black's trap:} 8. Bd2 $2 Nxd4 9. Nxe4 $2 Qe7 {when White loses material.}) 8... Qa5 {The main line, playing against e5 and c3, if by no means a forced move.} 9. Nxc6 ({A simple approach, although a tempting alternative is the Aronian-endorsed} 9. O-O $5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Bd2 {with the initiative and good compensation for the pawn. The text forces the pace and simply intends O-O, followed by Bd2 and a2-a3, which should maintain control.}) 9... dxc6 {Black usually recaptures this way to bring his light-squared bishop into play.} 10. Bd2 {A simple approach: preparing to recapture with the bishop on c3, while intending O-O followed by a2-a3.} O-O 11. O-O ({Here before a2-a3, as} 11. a3 Bxc3 $1 12. Bxc3 Qg5 {is no longer so clear in view of} 13. Qd2 $5 Qxg2 14. O-O-O e3 $1 {.}) 11... Re8 {This is usually seen, improving the rook and hoping one day soon to launch an attack on the kingside. Worry not, though; White has plenty of defensive resources and will soon enjoy the bishop-pair to boot.} (11... Be6 $6 12. a3 Bxc3 {Here we'll see this recapture, although we'd likely prefer the consistent 13.bxc3!?, perhaps followed by a2-a4 and Re1.} 13. Bxc3 Qg5 14. Qc1 $1 {An important manoeuvre to defuse Black's kingside play.} Qg6 15. Qf4 Bh3 16. Qg3 {This averted mate, to retain a small but pleasant edge in Franco Ocampos-J.Polgar, Salamanca 1989, thanks to the fine dark-squared bishop, decent central control and handy queenside majority.}) 12. a3 {Consistently forcing the pace, and, of course, if the bishop now mistakenly retreats, then Nxe4 will be on.} Bxc3 13. bxc3 $5 ({A new idea for the over-the-board world if one which has enjoyed some correspondence testing, keeping Black out of g5. The likes of Grischuk, Meier and Potkin have been happy to go} 13. Bxc3 {, but with Black's rook supporting a potential ...e3 advance,} Qg5 14. Qc1 Qg6 15. Qf4 {after} Bh3 {or 15...h5!? .}) ({After} 13. bxc3 {, two useful little advances for White are h2-h3, to keep Black out of g4 for good, and a3-a4, beginning to creep forwards on the queenside.}) 13... Bf5 14. h3 {Keeping Black out of g4, meaning that White can begin to probe with Qb3 without allowing ... Bg4 to remove the bishop-pair in return. There are also very much still ideas of a3-a4 too.} h6 15. Qb3 Qb6 16. Qa2 $5 ({A slightly unusual spot for the queen, but White wants to go Be3 then bring her to c2 or d2.} 16. Qc2 e3 $1 {would be a bit annoying, but you might also wish to look into 16.Qb4!? c5 17.Qxb6 axb6 18.Be3 .}) 16... Qc7 17. Be3 {Black did manage to hold from here in two high-level encounters, Babic-Schwenck, correspondence 2018 and Krishnan-Schwenck, correspondence 2018. Our opponents are unlikely to be 2500+ correspondence ones, though, and for our money White has a pleasant edge. The a-pawn will trundle down the board as far as it can go, helping to create targets on the b-file, and after Qd2 White will rather boss the dark squares. Black may counter with a ...Nh7-f8-g6 manoeuvre, but in turn that will allow White to carry out a breakthrough with d4-d5.} *

