{A) 15...e3?! 16.Bxe3 Bf5 17.Re1 White prepares to tidy things up with Bf1 and need not fear Black now going all in: 17...Rxe3!? 18.fxe3 White is the exchange and a pawn to the good, and should be happy to return the latter to defuse the attack, as with 18...Ne4 19.Bg4! . 18...Bxh3! 19.Bf3! Good defence, securing g2, whereas 19.gxh3? Ne4 would result in a perpetual check, with Black able to check on d6 as well as g3. 19...Bf5 20.e4! Offering a second pawn to avoid any cramp. Kg1 will follow, and after Re3 everything should be secure. 20...Bxe4 21.Kg1 Black is the exchange for a pawn down and faces a long struggle to draw. B 15...Bf5 16.Be3 Ruling out any ...e3 ideas for good ahead of advancing the a-pawn. 16...Nd7 17.a4 Qd6+ 18.Kh1 This is hardly an inconvenience and meanwhile White is inexorably making progress on the queenside, something which 18...a5 would fail to halt in view of 19.c5! followed by c3-c4. 18...Qe7 19.a5 In Ferre Perez-Maldonado Pacheco, correspondence 2008, White was all set to increase the pressure with Qb3 or Qa4, while Black was clearly worse and only escaped with a draw after 70 moves of suffering and careful defence.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 {An ambitious central advance, setting up a reversed Botvinnik central formation.} 5. d4 {Needless to say, we react in the centre, threatening dxe5 as well as d4-d5.} cxd4 {The most natural and common response.} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 {The critical knight move, introducing ideas of Ng4 and c4-c5 if Black is slow, while also simply intending to swiftly complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O.} Bb4 {Black usually pins so.} 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development, preparing to castle. Do please avoid Black's trap:} 8. Bd2 $2 Nxd4 9. Nxe4 $2 Qe7 {when White loses material.}) 8... Qa5 {The main line, playing against e5 and c3, if by no means a forced move.} 9. Nxc6 ({A simple approach, although a tempting alternative is the Aronian-endorsed} 9. O-O $5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Bd2 {with the initiative and good compensation for the pawn. The text forces the pace and simply intends O-O, followed by Bd2 and a2-a3, which should maintain control.}) 9... dxc6 {Black usually recaptures this way to bring his light-squared bishop into play.} 10. Bd2 {A simple approach: preparing to recapture with the bishop on c3, while intending O-O followed by a2-a3.} O-O 11. O-O ({Here before a2-a3, as} 11. a3 Bxc3 $1 12. Bxc3 Qg5 {is no longer so clear in view of} 13. Qd2 $5 Qxg2 14. O-O-O e3 $1 {.}) 11... Re8 {This is usually seen, improving the rook and hoping one day soon to launch an attack on the kingside. Worry not, though; White has plenty of defensive resources and will soon enjoy the bishop-pair to boot.} (11... Be6 $6 12. a3 Bxc3 {Here we'll see this recapture, although we'd likely prefer the consistent 13.bxc3!?, perhaps followed by a2-a4 and Re1.} 13. Bxc3 Qg5 14. Qc1 $1 {An important manoeuvre to defuse Black's kingside play.} Qg6 15. Qf4 Bh3 16. Qg3 {This averted mate, to retain a small but pleasant edge in Franco Ocampos-J.Polgar, Salamanca 1989, thanks to the fine dark-squared bishop, decent central control and handy queenside majority.}) 12. a3 {Consistently forcing the pace, and, of course, if the bishop now mistakenly retreats, then Nxe4 will be on.} Bxc3 13. bxc3 $5 ({A new idea for the over-the-board world if one which has enjoyed some correspondence testing, keeping Black out of g5. The likes of Grischuk, Meier and Potkin have been happy to go} 13. Bxc3 {, but with Black's rook supporting a potential ...e3 advance,} Qg5 14. Qc1 Qg6 15. Qf4 {after} Bh3 {or 15...h5!? .}) ({After} 13. bxc3 {, two useful little advances for White are h2-h3, to keep Black out of g4 for good, and a3-a4, beginning to creep forwards on the queenside.}) 13... Qf5 {Trying to drum up a kingside attack after all by swinging the queen to g6.} (13... h6 14. h3 {Again, usefully taking control of g4 before going a3-a4 and/or Qb3.} Be6 15. a4 {Sidestepping 15.Qb3 b5! .} Rad8 16. Qc2 {Tickling the e-pawn while also intending to target b7.} Re7 17. Rfe1 Red7 18. c5 $5 {A big decision, but White wants to fix the weakness on b7 while also increasing his dark-square control. Now Bf1 followed by Qb2 is the plan, after which c3-c4, Be2 and Ra3-b3 could follow, all of which left White with control and a very pleasant control, and he eventually triumphed in Ortiz-Sorcinelli, correspondence 2014.}) 14. h3 $1 {An especially useful little move here, preparing to neutralise Black's kingside by sidestepping with the king to the h-file.} Qg6 15. Kh2 ({Stepping to a dark square makes sense to us, although} 15. Kh1 {has also been tested and looks promising. White is now all set to take further control with Be3, then run the a-pawn, and just where is Black's counterplay? To see how play might pan out, here are two sample continuations:}) 15... Z0 *

