1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 . cxd4 exd4 Renewing the threat of d4-d5, an advance Black usually now elects to block. Bb4!? d5! exd5 Forcing the pace. Now} Ne7 {dxe6 fxe6} 6. Bd3 {would leave White with the more harmonious development and safer king. cxd5 White now has ideas of Be2 (or Bc4) and O-O, as well as Bg5. Ne7 Bc4 Pressuring d5 so must be critical. Now} d6 {Ned5} 7. Qe2 {Kf8 just looks most unclear. O-O Maintaining the bridgehead while intending to fight for the initiative with O-O then Bg5. Black too can battle for the initiative, but} b5 $5 {can be well enough met by Bxb5 followed by Qd3. O-O A simpler choice than d6 when Nf5 is slightly annoying. d6 Qb3 -- Securing d5 with tempo. White will now meet Bxc3 with bxc3 , and with Bg5 or Bf4 on the way should be slightly for choice.} *

