1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5, an advance Black usually now elects to block.} d5 7. c5 $1 {in Bb5} ({Ignoring the interloper on e4 (both} 7. Qc2 {and}) (7. Bd3 {Nxc3 bxc3 are also promising), as White tees up Ne5, gets ready to castle, then go Re1, and would welcome his centre being strengthened by an exchange on c3.}) 7... Qa5 $6 {O-O! A strong pawn sacrifice. Nxc3 Bxc6+ bxc6 bxc3 White has acquired a strong bind, both Ne5 and Re1 are on their way and getting greedy won't especially help Black. Qxc3?} 8. Qa4 Bd7 9. Rb1 {With all of Rb3 (to harry the offside queen), Ne5 and Rb7 on their way, Black is already in serious trouble.} *

