1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5, an advance Black usually now elects to block.} d5 7. c5 $1 {A key Panov advance and one very well known in that opening. Indeed, this position arises more often via a 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.c5! move order, although few experienced Caro players now allow the line. White clamps down and will now play for a secure grip on the e5-square with Bb5. Note too that we can even meet 7...Bd7 with 8.Bb5 when 8...Ne4 9.O-O transposes to a position we'll consider via a 7...Ne4 8.Bb5 Bd7 9.O-O move order [/variation/35967522/#/9/w].} Ne4 $5 {A freeing advance, an idea we've already seen in the related lines [/variation/35967472/#/8/b] in 2c1.} 8. Bb5 ({Ignoring the interloper on e4 (both} 8. Qc2 {and}) (8. Bd3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {are also promising), as White tees up Ne5, gets ready to castle, then go Re1, and would welcome his centre being strengthened by an exchange on c3.}) 8... Bd7 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 {Challenging Black's best placed piece, while angling to provoke Black into a fairly bad version of a Stonewall.} f5 $6 11. Bxc6 $1 {A useful exchange to take full control of e5.} Bxc6 12. Ne2 $1 {White wastes no time regrouping. The knight will be well placed on f4, after which White might go Ne5 and f3-f4 or simply begin to advance with b2-b4 and a2-a4.} g5 $6 13. Ne5 g4 ({All of a sudden} 13... Z0 14. f3 Nf6 15. Bxg5 {is a sizeable threat, and 13...f4? 14.Nxf4! wouldn't be good news for Black.}) 14. Bf4 {Black has overextended and White is in full control. Qd3 will help to maintain that control, after which White may just go Ng3 then f2-f3, evicting Black's only good piece from e4.} *

