1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5, an advance Black usually now elects to block.} d5 7. c5 $1 {A key Panov advance and one very well known in that opening. Indeed, this position arises more often via a 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.c5! move order, although few experienced Caro players now allow the line. White clamps down and will now play for a secure grip on the e5-square with Bb5. Note too that we can even meet 7...Bd7 with 8.Bb5 when 8...Ne4 9.O-O transposes to a position we'll consider via a 7...Ne4 8.Bb5 Bd7 9.O-O move order [/variation/35967522/#/9/w].} Be7 {Black's most common move, hurrying to castle.} 8. Bb5 {Consistently pinning. How will Black now deal with the idea of 9.Ne5?} Bd7 9. O-O O-O ({Continuing the policy of housing the king before undertaking anything active and we've already seen that [/variation/35967522/#/10/w]} 9... Ne4 10. Re1 {would now be a pleasant edge for White.}) 10. Re1 a6 ({Now} 10... Ne4 {would cost Black a pawn, and so they are left with a rather passive position, one from which Black has unsurprisingly not scored at all well. For our part, White is all set to clamp down further with Bf4 and to expand with a2-a3, and if ...a5 then Rb1, forcing through b2-b4.}) 11. Bxc6 $1 ({An important exchange, as} 11. Bd3 b6 12. cxb6 Qxb6 {actually isn't so clear.}) 11... Bxc6 12. Bf4 ({Clamping down on e5 looks like an even better policy than the more popular} 12. Ne5 Nd7 {. White will now meet 12...Ne4 with 13.Ne5 and 12...Nd7 with 13.b4 , and once again should also welcome a Stonewall-type approach.}) 12... Nh5 13. Be3 f5 $2 14. b4 Z0 ({White's play on the queenside is far faster than anything Black can undertake on the other flank. Ne5 will now come with tempo, likewise,} 14... f4 15. Bd2 {, leaving e6 en prise, and meanwhile a2-a4 followed by b4-b5 is imminent.}) *

