1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5, an advance Black usually now elects to block.} d5 7. c5 $1 {A key Panov advance and one very well known in that opening. Indeed, this position arises more often via a 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.c5! move order, although few experienced Caro players now allow the line. White clamps down and will now play for a secure grip on the e5-square with Bb5. Note too that we can even meet 7...Bd7 with 8.Bb5 when 8...Ne4 9.O-O transposes to a position we'll consider via a 7...Ne4 8.Bb5 Bd7 9.O-O move order [/variation/35967522/#/9/w].} Be7 {Black's most common move, hurrying to castle.} 8. Bb5 {Consistently pinning. How will Black now deal with the idea of 9.Ne5?} O-O 9. O-O {Consistently housing the king ahead of placing the rook on e1.} Qc7 10. Re1 {Thematically clamping down on e5.} Bd7 11. Bxc6 $5 ({A simple approach, settling to invade on e5, then go Bf4, and only then expand on the queenside (the immediate} 11. Rb1 {to arrange b2-b4 is also promising).}) 11... Bxc6 12. Ne5 b6 13. b4 ({We've followed Durarbayli-Idnani, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where} 13. Bf4 {might have been met by} bxc5 $1 14. Ng6 Qb7 15. Nxf8 Bxf8 {with reasonable play for the exchange. As such, White should maintain the bind.}) {Threatening b4-b5, as well as Bf4.} 13... bxc5 14. bxc5 ({Our usual recapture, although with such good central control, a decent case can also be made here for} 14. dxc5 $5 {.}) 14... Ne4 15. Ne2 $5 {Keeping pieces on and a pleasant edge. White will now go Bf4 and Ng3, likely reserving the f2-f3 push for any ...f6; Nxc6 Qxc6 moment, which wouldn't necessarily spell good news for the knight on e4.} *

