1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... cxd4 6. exd4 {Renewing the threat of d4-d5, an advance Black usually now elects to block.} d5 7. c5 $1 {A key Panov advance and one very well known in that opening. Indeed, this position arises more often via a 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.c5! move order, although few experienced Caro players now allow the line. White clamps down and will now play for a secure grip on the e5-square with Bb5. Note too that we can even meet 7...Bd7 with 8.Bb5 when 8...Ne4 9.O-O transposes to a position we'll consider via a 7...Ne4 8.Bb5 Bd7 9.O-O move order [/variation/35967522/#/9/w].} Be7 {Black's most common move, hurrying to castle.} 8. Bb5 {Consistently pinning. How will Black now deal with the idea of 9.Ne5?} O-O 9. O-O {Consistently housing the king ahead of placing the rook on e1.} Ne4 (9... Nd7 $6 10. Bf4 {Preventing Black from ever breaking free with ...e5 ( 10.Re1 is also good). 10...a6 11.Ba4!? With Black rather restricted, White can even retain the bishop ( 11.Bxc6 bxc6 12.b4 with a clear plus is the alternative). 11...b5 12.Bc2 b4?! 13.Ne2 The knight is quite happy to be driven over to the kingside, where White might well get to attack. 13...a5 14.Re1 Ba6 15.Ng3 White was in full control and doing very well in Erigaisi-Martinez Alcantara, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, with Ba4 one useful idea to disrupt Black, the direct Qd2 followed by Nh5 another.}) 10. Re1 {Thematically challenging Black's only active piece and here black players have sometimes been tempted by the Stonewall option after all.} f5 $5 11. Bxc6 {Simple does it once again as White obtains full control of e5.} bxc6 12. Bf4 $5 ({White has often rushed ahead with} 12. Ne5 {here (even Caruana has), when Black may not be doing too terribly after} Bf6 $1 {. There is, though, another thematic move available.}) {Only now does White want to go Ne5 to make f2-f3 possible, and there are also very much ideas of Rc1 followed by b2-b4.} 12... g5 $5 {A critical advance and counter.} 13. Bd6 $1 (13. Be5 g4 14. Nd2 {should also be an edge, but this is a promising positional pawn sacrifice, aiming to highlight all Black's weaknesses.}) 13... Nxd6 14. cxd6 Bxd6 15. Na4 {With Rc1 followed by Nc5 and/or Ne5 on the way, White clearly enjoys promising compensation. Never forget that pawns cannot move backwards!} *

