1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... d5 {Taking play into Semi-Tarrasch waters, although a Caro-Kann player or inexperienced opponent may prefer to exchange on d4.} 6. cxd5 {there. The other recapture is also possible though, if seen about half as often according to ChessBase's vast database. Nxd5!? Bb5!? Black is determined to stay within Semi-Tarrasch lines. Now the main line is very much Bd3 when Black has a choice between an IQP struggle after} cxd4 7. exd4 {and staying very solid with 7...Be7 . This isn't quite as dangerous as when Ne5 has been played instead of d2-d4 ( Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967382/#/7/w]), but is still a decent alternative to Bd3 and one with more bite than} Nxd5 {Qxd5 dxc5 Qxd1+ Kxd1 Bxc5 . White intends Ne5 and also simply O-O. Be7 Ne5 Forcing a small concession from Black thanks to the pressure against c6 (the calm} 8. Bd2 $5 {is also a decent choice, intending cxd4} Nxd4 {and 8...O-O 9.dxc5 , with definite chances for an edge). Qb6!? Qa4 Increasing the pressure and largely forcing Black to sacrifice if he doesn't want to get into early difficulties. O-O! Nxd5 As played in Eliskases-Portisch, Malaga 1961, where Bxc6 might just have been met by bxc6 . Forcing a small structural gain. exd5 Bxc6 Now you might be thinking that Nxc6 bxc6 Bxc6 must be good, and it's certainly a critical continuation, but Black seems to have enough for the exchange after} 9. Ba6 $5 {Bxa8 Rxa8 with the white king trapped in the centre. bxc6 O-O!? Continuing our ungreedy approach rather than becoming embroiled in} Nc6 {Bd6 . With the king safe, White is now ready to go Qxc6, and Black must also be wary of ...Ba6 running into a Nd7 exchanging tactic. In short, White is fighting hard for an edge with Nxc6 very much an idea, not least with: cxd4?! Nxc6 White is winning a pawn for not quite enough compensation.} *

