1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... d5 {Taking play into Semi-Tarrasch waters, although a Caro-Kann player or inexperienced opponent may prefer to exchange on d4.} 6. cxd5 ({Our favourite exchange from Part One of the repertoire (an important alternative in this line of the Semi-Tarrasch is, of course, the main line,} 6. a3 {), and after}) (6. cxd5 {play often goes} exd5 7. Bb5 {with a transposition to Chapter 13 [/variation/23789998/#/7/w] there. The other recapture is also possible though, if seen about half as often according to ChessBase's vast database.}) 6... Nxd5 $5 7. Bb5 $5 ({Black is determined to stay within Semi-Tarrasch lines. Now the main line is very much} 7. Bd3 {when Black has a choice between an IQP struggle after} cxd4 8. exd4 {and staying very solid with 7...Be7 .}) ({This isn't quite as dangerous as when Ne5 has been played instead of d2-d4 ( Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967382/#/7/w]), but is still a decent alternative to} 7. Bd3 {and one with more bite than}) (7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 {. White intends Ne5 and also simply O-O.}) 7... Be7 8. Ne5 ({Forcing a small concession from Black thanks to the pressure against c6 (the calm} 8. Bd2 $5 {is also a decent choice, intending} cxd4 9. Nxd4 {and 8...O-O 9.dxc5 , with definite chances for an edge).}) 8... Bd7 {Black has usually blocked solidly so.} 9. Nxd5 {This seems best, angling for a small plus.} exd5 10. Nxd7 $1 Qa5+ $1 ({Now} 10... Qxd7 11. dxc5 {would leave White with the two bishops and a small structural plus, but Black might instead check.}) 11. Bd2 Qxb5 12. Nxc5 Bxc5 ({Here} 12... Qxb2 $6 13. Na4 $1 {would leave both Rb1 and Nc3 on the way, and White with a secure structural plus, so Black should probably prefer the other capture.}) 13. a4 $5 ({Played to avoid the possibility of} 13. dxc5 Ne5 $5 {, so that White can capture with tempo if 13...Qb6 14.dxc5 , while not minding Black sending his queen down the board.}) 13... Qxb2 14. dxc5 {The engines suggest that Black is OK and they may be, but White does have the potentially superior minor piece, and O-O will make the king fully safe. After that, Rb1 may follow when such moves as Qb3, Bc3 and Rfd1 could very well see White starting to take control.} *

