{Ne5 With a threat, one that can always be augmented by Qa4 if need be. Bd7 Nxd7 Settling for a small plus with the bishop-pair. Qxd7 O-O O-O a4!? This is a decent enough prophylactic advance. White would love to be allowed to push the pawn to a5 to cramp Black or even a6. Meanwhile, the bishop will likely drop back to e2 if attacked, possibly heading for f3. That square can also be a decent spot for the queen, as is b3. If the queen is on f3, then White will probably meet ...cxd4 with exd4, looking to attack, but otherwise cxd4 may well be the preferred recapture, avoiding a backwards c-pawn while maintaining a reasonable degree of control.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... d5 {Taking play into Semi-Tarrasch waters, although a Caro-Kann player or inexperienced opponent may prefer to exchange on d4.} 6. cxd5 ({Our favourite exchange from Part One of the repertoire (an important alternative in this line of the Semi-Tarrasch is, of course, the main line,} 6. a3 {), and after}) (6. cxd5 {play often goes} exd5 7. Bb5 {with a transposition to Chapter 13 [/variation/23789998/#/7/w] there. The other recapture is also possible though, if seen about half as often according to ChessBase's vast database.}) 6... Nxd5 $5 7. Bb5 $5 ({Black is determined to stay within Semi-Tarrasch lines. Now the main line is very much} 7. Bd3 {when Black has a choice between an IQP struggle after} cxd4 8. exd4 {and staying very solid with 7...Be7 .}) ({This isn't quite as dangerous as when Ne5 has been played instead of d2-d4 ( Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967382/#/7/w]), but is still a decent alternative to} 7. Bd3 {and one with more bite than}) (7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 {. White intends Ne5 and also simply O-O.}) 7... Nxc3 {This solid choice, retaining the tension on d4 and c5, has actually been Black's most common choice in practice at this stage.} 8. bxc3 (8. d5 {cxd5} Nxd5 {e3 Nc6 Bb5 Nxc3 bxc3 Bd7} 9. O-O {e6 d4 also brings about this position}) *

