exchange. He will now follow up with O-O and Re1, and Black may regret having exchanged off one of the defenders of his kingside in the king's knight.} Bd6 $5 10. O-O O-O ({Simple does it once again. Now} 10... Qa5 {can always be met by the bishop-retaining} 11. Qd3 {.}) 11. Re1 {Clamping down on e5 while leaving White with the possibilities of Rb1 and Bd3, with Qe2 also likely to be a useful move.} Qc7 12. Bd3 $5 ({Here} 12. Qe2 Ne7 {was fairly solid for Black in Damljanovic-Ozen, Belgrade 2017, so White might drop the bishop back without delay.}) 12... Ne7 ({Black may now become concerned about the Greek Gift, although} 12... Z0 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Ng5+ Kg6 $1 15. Qg4 f5 16. Qh4 {isn't actually too clear. As such, White might prefix any sacrifice with h2-h4 or even gambit for the attack with Ng5 ( 12...e5? 13.Ng5! h6 14.Nh7 followed by Qh5 looks especially strong).}) {Bringing the knight over to help the defence, but now White can reveal another point behind the bishop retreat to d3.} 13. c4 $1 Z0 ({The hanging pawns are quite mobile here, and White slightly for choice. We are even threatening to obtain a bind on the position with} 13... Z0 14. c5 {, with other useful ideas those of h2-h4 and Ng5 again, as well as Bb2, looking to arrange a strong breakthrough with d4-d5.}) *

