{Clamping down on e5. Black is fairly solid, but we would slightly prefer to take White here, with both rook pawns set to play a part: h2-h4 will assist any attack on the king; a3-a4 will help to clamp Black on the queenside, while also helping to reduce the impact of any ...Qd5 approach.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... d5 {Taking play into Semi-Tarrasch waters, although a Caro-Kann player or inexperienced opponent may prefer to exchange on d4.} 6. cxd5 ({Our favourite exchange from Part One of the repertoire (an important alternative in this line of the Semi-Tarrasch is, of course, the main line,} 6. a3 {), and after}) (6. cxd5 {play often goes} exd5 7. Bb5 {with a transposition to Chapter 13 [/variation/23789998/#/7/w] there. The other recapture is also possible though, if seen about half as often according to ChessBase's vast database.}) 6... Nxd5 $5 7. Bb5 $5 ({Black is determined to stay within Semi-Tarrasch lines. Now the main line is very much} 7. Bd3 {when Black has a choice between an IQP struggle after} cxd4 8. exd4 {and staying very solid with 7...Be7 .}) ({This isn't quite as dangerous as when Ne5 has been played instead of d2-d4 ( Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967382/#/7/w]), but is still a decent alternative to} 7. Bd3 {and one with more bite than}) (7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 {. White intends Ne5 and also simply O-O.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 $1 ({Taking on an IQP, in part because} 8. Nxd4 Nxc3 $1 9. bxc3 Bd7 {is rock-solid for Black. Now White is ready to continue his quick development with O-O, as well as look to cause early trouble with a timely Ne5.}) 8... Bb4 {The position now resembles a fairly common line of the Caro-Kann, but with White's bishop on b5, not d3.} 9. Qd3 {Calmly keeping c3 covered while angling to provoke some early over-ambition from Black.} O-O {This calm choice is likely best.} 10. O-O {White, too, is happy to house the king, as well as to see an exchange on c3, after which it may be possible to go Ba4-c2. In any case, that retreat should be possible, setting up a famous battery. White can also even consider ideas of Ng5 Nf6; Rd1, looking to bring a knight to e4, which may help to explain why Black has usually now dropped their bishop back.} Be7 {Angling to disrupt with ...Ncb4, but that is easily enough prevented.} 11. a3 {Keeping Black out of b4 for good while intending Ba4-c2 to ask a certain question of the defence.} Nxc3 $5 12. bxc3 Bf6 13. Re1 ({Here} 13. Qe4 Qd5 $1 14. Qe2 Bd7 15. Bd3 Na5 {saw Black getting organised in Wirthensohn-Sutter, Swiss League 2006, but White has other ways to deal with the idea of ...e5.}) *

