1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... d5 {Taking play into Semi-Tarrasch waters, although a Caro-Kann player or inexperienced opponent may prefer to exchange on d4.} 6. cxd5 ({Our favourite exchange from Part One of the repertoire (an important alternative in this line of the Semi-Tarrasch is, of course, the main line,} 6. a3 {), and after}) (6. cxd5 {play often goes} exd5 7. Bb5 {with a transposition to Chapter 13 [/variation/23789998/#/7/w] there. The other recapture is also possible though, if seen about half as often according to ChessBase's vast database.}) 6... Nxd5 $5 7. Bb5 $5 ({Black is determined to stay within Semi-Tarrasch lines. Now the main line is very much} 7. Bd3 {when Black has a choice between an IQP struggle after} cxd4 8. exd4 {and staying very solid with 7...Be7 .}) ({This isn't quite as dangerous as when Ne5 has been played instead of d2-d4 ( Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967382/#/7/w]), but is still a decent alternative to} 7. Bd3 {and one with more bite than}) (7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 {. White intends Ne5 and also simply O-O.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 $1 ({Taking on an IQP, in part because} 8. Nxd4 Nxc3 $1 9. bxc3 Bd7 {is rock-solid for Black. Now White is ready to continue his quick development with O-O, as well as look to cause early trouble with a timely Ne5.}) 8... Bd6 $5 9. O-O {A consistent choice, housing the king while preparing to place a rook on the half-open e-file.} O-O 10. Re1 {The bishops on b5 and d6 are slightly unusually placed for this structure. Objectively, Black is probably OK, but White cannot be too unhappy with ideas of a timely Nxd5 exd5 exchange. We'd be more though looking to obtain some pressure with Bd3 or Ne5.} Bd7 11. Bd3 {Keeping pieces on while leaving White with the possibility of Bc2 and Qd3. Other potentially useful plans are a2-a3 and Ne4, as well as Nxd5 exd5; Ne5.} Nce7 12. Nxd5 $5 ({A thematic regrouping, maintaining piece control of d5 while boosting the kingside defence. Now} 12. Ne4 Bc6 13. Ne5 Ng6 {seemed pretty solid for Black in Abdrlauf-Tabatabaei, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021.}) {A slightly unexpected idea, but it helps White to maintain a fair degree of control while, with Ne5 on the way, ...Bc6 ideas may not be so potent.} 12... Nxd5 13. Ne5 Z0 ({This is a rare IQP position that doesn't seem to have yet had an OTB test. White clamours to go} 13... Z0 14. Qh5 {, and if} Nf6 15. Qh4 {followed by Bg5 with a strong attack. Other ideas include Be4, angling for an exchange on d5, as well as a2-a3 to take control of b4.}) *

