1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... d5 {Taking play into Semi-Tarrasch waters, although a Caro-Kann player or inexperienced opponent may prefer to exchange on d4.} 6. cxd5 ({Our favourite exchange from Part One of the repertoire (an important alternative in this line of the Semi-Tarrasch is, of course, the main line,} 6. a3 {), and after}) (6. cxd5 {play often goes} exd5 7. Bb5 {with a transposition to Chapter 13 [/variation/23789998/#/7/w] there. The other recapture is also possible though, if seen about half as often according to ChessBase's vast database.}) 6... Nxd5 $5 7. Bb5 $5 ({Black is determined to stay within Semi-Tarrasch lines. Now the main line is very much} 7. Bd3 {when Black has a choice between an IQP struggle after} cxd4 8. exd4 {and staying very solid with 7...Be7 .}) ({This isn't quite as dangerous as when Ne5 has been played instead of d2-d4 ( Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967382/#/7/w]), but is still a decent alternative to} 7. Bd3 {and one with more bite than}) (7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 {. White intends Ne5 and also simply O-O.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 $1 ({Taking on an IQP, in part because} 8. Nxd4 Nxc3 $1 9. bxc3 Bd7 {is rock-solid for Black. Now White is ready to continue his quick development with O-O, as well as look to cause early trouble with a timely Ne5.}) 8... Be7 {A solid choice and Black's most popular move.} 9. O-O ({Speedy development as White keeps pieces on and directs his king's rook towards e1 (} 9. Ne5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 {would now just be very comfortable for Black thanks to the IQP).}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 {It's hard to think of a better square for the rook than this. The position can also arise from the Caro-Kann ( 1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 Nf6 4.Nc3 cxd5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.Bb5 e6 8.O-O Be7 9.d4 O-O 10.Re1 ). Black is pretty solid, but White is not without definite chances of obtaining an edge thanks to the ideas of a timely Bxc6 or Bd3 and would again welcome an exchange on c3 to strong-point d4 and increase the dynamism in his set-up yet further.} a6 $6 11. Bxc6 $1 {White helps himself to the structural gains on offer.} bxc6 12. Ne5 {Black's queenside has clearly been weakened, and White has ideas of not just Bd2, Rc1 and Ne4, but also Qg4, spreading the play to the kingside after all.} c5 $2 13. Nc6 {Played anyhow. White threatens not just the queen, but a rather powerful capture on d5.} Nxc3 14. bxc3 Qd7 15. Nxe7+ $1 Qxe7 16. Ba3 {The pin nets White a clear pawn.} *

