e.} 9. O-O ({Speedy development as White keeps pieces on and directs his king's rook towards e1 (} 9. Ne5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 {would now just be very comfortable for Black thanks to the IQP).}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 {It's hard to think of a better square for the rook than this. The position can also arise from the Caro-Kann ( 1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 Nf6 4.Nc3 cxd5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.Bb5 e6 8.O-O Be7 9.d4 O-O 10.Re1 ). Black is pretty solid, but White is not without definite chances of obtaining an edge thanks to the ideas of a timely Bxc6 or Bd3 and would again welcome an exchange on c3 to strong-point d4 and increase the dynamism in his set-up yet further.} Nf6 {A third move with the knight and one which can hardly be a critical challenge of White's approach, but it isn't without merit and does prepare to deploy the other knight to b4 via d5.} 11. a3 $1 {) Prudently keeping Black out of b4. White may now drop the light-squared bishop back to d3 or go Qd3 in conjunction with Ba4-c2. However, positional gains are again stronger than either of those possibilities if Black is now again careless:} a6 $6 12. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 13. Na4 ({Clamping down on the c5-square (} 13. Ne5 {is also quite strong), while intending to follow up with Bd2 or Bf4 and then Rc1 and/or Qc2, all the while with a timely Ne5 in reserve.}) 13... Nd5 14. Qc2 $5 {Beginning to eye the potentially vulnerable pawn on c6.} Bb7 15. Bd2 {With Nc5, Ne5 and Rac1 on their way, Black lacked counterplay and was suffering somewhat in Benjamin-Herman, US Online League 2013.} *

