1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 ({Black continues to copy. This is the mainline, but there are two important alternatives on top of the aforementioned} 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {- 4...g6 which we've seen in 2c1, and 4...e5 in 2c2.}) 5. d4 {A consistent follow-up to 4.e3, threatening to press ahead with d4-d5.} ({You may also wish to consider} 5. b3 {when we saw} Be7 6. Bb2 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 {by transposition in the first part [/variation/23790039/#/7/b] of The Modern Reti. Here Black can also go 6...O-O which is probably best met by 7.d4 and a positional approach or, earlier, 5...d5 when the critical line is perhaps 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bb2 d4 8.Na4 .}) 5... d5 {Taking play into Semi-Tarrasch waters, although a Caro-Kann player or inexperienced opponent may prefer to exchange on d4.} 6. cxd5 ({Our favourite exchange from Part One of the repertoire (an important alternative in this line of the Semi-Tarrasch is, of course, the main line,} 6. a3 {), and after}) (6. cxd5 {play often goes} exd5 7. Bb5 {with a transposition to Chapter 13 [/variation/23789998/#/7/w] there. The other recapture is also possible though, if seen about half as often according to ChessBase's vast database.}) 6... Nxd5 $5 7. Bb5 $5 ({Black is determined to stay within Semi-Tarrasch lines. Now the main line is very much} 7. Bd3 {when Black has a choice between an IQP struggle after} cxd4 8. exd4 {and staying very solid with 7...Be7 .}) ({This isn't quite as dangerous as when Ne5 has been played instead of d2-d4 ( Chapter 2a3 [/variation/35967382/#/7/w]), but is still a decent alternative to} 7. Bd3 {and one with more bite than}) (7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 {. White intends Ne5 and also simply O-O.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 $1 ({Taking on an IQP, in part because} 8. Nxd4 Nxc3 $1 9. bxc3 Bd7 {is rock-solid for Black. Now White is ready to continue his quick development with O-O, as well as look to cause early trouble with a timely Ne5.}) 8... Be7 {A solid choice and Black's most popular move.} 9. O-O ({Speedy development as White keeps pieces on and directs his king's rook towards e1 (} 9. Ne5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 {would now just be very comfortable for Black thanks to the IQP).}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 {It's hard to think of a better square for the rook than this. The position can also arise from the Caro-Kann ( 1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 Nf6 4.Nc3 cxd5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.Bb5 e6 8.O-O Be7 9.d4 O-O 10.Re1 ). Black is pretty solid, but White is not without definite chances of obtaining an edge thanks to the ideas of a timely Bxc6 or Bd3 and would again welcome an exchange on c3 to strong-point d4 and increase the dynamism in his set-up yet further.} Bd7 {Black's most common choice, solidly continuing development.} 11. Bc4 $5 ({White's main move has been} 11. Bd3 {, as Magnus once used to defeat Jan Smeets, but we're quite happy with another bishop retreat. The light-squared bishop's job was clearly done on b5, with White not really interested in Bxc6 when it can be met by ...Bxc6. Instead, the bishop makes a small backwards move with tempo, angling to tempt Black into exchanging on c3.}) 11... Nxc3 {This has been Black's most popular choice in the limited OTB experience with the position, but again, it's an exchange which White should largely welcome.} 12. bxc3 {All is now set for two of our favourite little moves, Bd3 and Rb1, angling to attack and for a bit of pressure down the half-open b-file respectively.} Rc8 13. Bd3 {The bishop leaps out of the way of any discovered attack. Now White might play for a bind with Bf4 or even go Qe2 and Qe4.} Bf6 {Black sensibly prepares to regroup with ...Ne7-g6.} 14. Rb1 {Tickling the b-pawn. Black is pretty solid here, but White should not be unhappy. He can always defend c3 with Bd2 and may look to meet ...Ne7 with Ne5, perhaps followed by hunting down the defender on f6 with Ng4.} b6 $6 15. Ba6 $1 Ra8 ({A fairly strong discombobulation as now} 15... Rc7 $2 16. Bf4 {would not, of course, be good for Black.}) 16. h4 $5 ({Here White settled for} 16. Qc2 {in Zelbel-De Schampheleire, Antwerp 2012, but we would prefer something more vigorous.}) {White now has ideas of not just an AlphaZeroesque h4-h5-h6, but Ng5, and we shouldn't lose sight of the fact that any ...h6 may leave Black vulnerable to a queen and bishop battery on the b1-h7 diagonal. White is surely at least slightly for choice and even more than that if Black now accepts the offer.} 16... Bxh4 $2 17. d5 $1 {A powerful and thematic breakthrough. White may now get to go d5-d6 in conjunction with Nxh4 Qxh4; Rb4, which would result in superb compensation, and in any case, we are all set to enjoy a strong initiative.} exd5 $2 18. Nxh4 Qxh4 19. Qxd5 {The defence is overloaded. Black is losing material whether on d7 or to a Bg5 or Bb7 skewer.} *

