e.} 9. O-O ({Speedy development as White keeps pieces on and directs his king's rook towards e1 (} 9. Ne5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 {would now just be very comfortable for Black thanks to the IQP).}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 {It's hard to think of a better square for the rook than this. The position can also arise from the Caro-Kann ( 1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 Nf6 4.Nc3 cxd5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.Bb5 e6 8.O-O Be7 9.d4 O-O 10.Re1 ). Black is pretty solid, but White is not without definite chances of obtaining an edge thanks to the ideas of a timely Bxc6 or Bd3 and would again welcome an exchange on c3 to strong-point d4 and increase the dynamism in his set-up yet further.} Bd7 {Black's most common choice, solidly continuing development.} 11. Bc4 $5 ({White's main move has been} 11. Bd3 {, as Magnus once used to defeat Jan Smeets, but we're quite happy with another bishop retreat. The light-squared bishop's job was clearly done on b5, with White not really interested in Bxc6 when it can be met by ...Bxc6. Instead, the bishop makes a small backwards move with tempo, angling to tempt Black into exchanging on c3.}) 11... Nf6 12. a3 {Once again, this is a handy prophylactic device to keep the knight on c6 out of b4.} Rc8 13. Qd3 {Preparing to line up the battery, and, if allowed, White might now like to improve his forces with Bf4, Rad1 and Ba2 in some order, then go Bb1.} Qb6 $5 14. Ba2 $1 {This again looks like good prophylaxis, making sure that everything is safe if White now advances with b2-b4, while also preparing Bb1 in conjunction with d4-d5 and Bg5 if Black is careless.} Rfd8 $1 15. b4 $1 ({Preparing to control the d-file after ...Be8, meaning that} 15. Bb1 {would now achieve less than nothing.}) {White finds an alternative way to expand and now very much has ideas of d4-d5 in conjunction with Be3.} 15... Be8 16. Be3 {Calmly defending d4, while preparing ideas of d4-d5 and Rac1.} Ng4 17. Na4 $1 ({Here White panicked with the mistimed} 17. d5 {in Mihok-N.Petrov, Budapest 2014, and should have preferred to make use of the useful insertion of b2-b4.}) 17... Qc7 18. Rac1 {The position is objectively speaking unclear, but White has the extra space and may press forwards with b4-b5 and/or Nc5. It may also be possible to still soften up Black's defences with the manoeuvre Bb1 g6; Ba2, looking for a timely sacrifice on e6 or d4-d5 breakthrough.} *

