e.} 9. O-O ({Speedy development as White keeps pieces on and directs his king's rook towards e1 (} 9. Ne5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 {would now just be very comfortable for Black thanks to the IQP).}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 {It's hard to think of a better square for the rook than this. The position can also arise from the Caro-Kann ( 1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 Nf6 4.Nc3 cxd5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.Bb5 e6 8.O-O Be7 9.d4 O-O 10.Re1 ). Black is pretty solid, but White is not without definite chances of obtaining an edge thanks to the ideas of a timely Bxc6 or Bd3 and would again welcome an exchange on c3 to strong-point d4 and increase the dynamism in his set-up yet further.} Bd7 {Black's most common choice, solidly continuing development.} 11. Bc4 $5 ({White's main move has been} 11. Bd3 {, as Magnus once used to defeat Jan Smeets, but we're quite happy with another bishop retreat. The light-squared bishop's job was clearly done on b5, with White not really interested in Bxc6 when it can be met by ...Bxc6. Instead, the bishop makes a small backwards move with tempo, angling to tempt Black into exchanging on c3.}) 11... Nf6 12. a3 {Once again, this is a handy prophylactic device to keep the knight on c6 out of b4.} Rc8 13. Qd3 {Preparing to line up the battery, and, if allowed, White might now like to improve his forces with Bf4, Rad1 and Ba2 in some order, then go Bb1.} Qc7 14. Ba2 $1 {Wisely moving the bishop out of harm's way.} Rfd8 15. Be3 ({A fairly modest square, but now White can go Rad1 and} 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bh4 Nh5 $1 {would seem to equalise.}) 15... Ng4 16. Rad1 Z0 ({This left Black a little passive and White with an edge in Stanescu-Pavoni, correspondence 2014. The immediate threat is to crash through with} 16... Z0 17. d5 {, with White also enjoying ideas of Bb1 and simply h2-h3, and if ...Nxe3; Qxe3, thereby maintaining good central control and still with some attacking chances.}) *

