1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 ({We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3. Now} 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 {would, of course, take us back into the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967305/#/3/w]. Black has two main alternatives, 2...Nc6 and 2...g6 , with his unusual options largely transposing to other parts of the repertoire. To stay within it, 2...b6 should be met by 3.e3 Bb7 4.b3 when after 4...e6 5.Bb2 play is either likely to enter the field of Chapter One [/variation/35967285/#/6/w] ( 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 ) or venture into the realm of the English Defence, with 5...f5 6.Nc3 seen in Chapter 7c [/variation/35967817/#/6/w]. Instead, 2...e6 3.e3 is either likely to lead to the Tarrasch Defence (we considered 3...d5 4.cxd5 exd5 5.d4 in Chapter 12 [/variation/23789957/#/5/w] of Part One of the course), or after 3...Nf6 4.Nc3 to a position we considered at the start of Chapter Two [/variation/35967305/#/3/w/1.9] in this second part of the repertoire. Finally, 2...d5?! is a premature advance White should welcome. We analysed 3.cxd5 and then 3...Qxd5 4.Nc3 and 3...Nf6 4.e4! back in the opening theory chapter [/variation/23789303/#/3/w] of the first part of the course.}) ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 e5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) 4. e3 Z0 ({Our favourite central advance, getting ready for d2-d4. Indeed,} 4... g6 $2 5. d4 {would see the centre opening faster than Black would like (White very much has ideas of dxc5, as well as a timely d4-d5). As such, Black's main move by far here is 4...Nf6 when we saw 5.d4 back in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w]. On occasion though, Black prefers something even more aggressive, 4...f5?! , which we'll check in this chapter.}) *

