1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} g6 {Black's third main option at this point, after which play is likely to transpose to the Accelerated Dragon lines we saw in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/3/b].} 3. e4 $1 ({A perhaps unexpected advance, but, worry not, the plan is not a Botvinnik formation, but rather a Maroczy Bind after all, as White plans to follow through with d2-d4 then Nc3. With this approach we avoid being move ordered by} 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {, as well as the possibility of}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 $5 {. After 3...Nc6 play might immediately transpose into the realm of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w] after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 Qa5+ {Not an especially threatening check.} 5. Nc3 ({White calmly blocks (} 5. Bd2 Qb6 6. Bc3 {is also a decent line if you're happy with an early queen exchange on d4), while intending Be2 followed by O-O or 5...Nc6?! 6.d5 .}) 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 {Naturally White keeps the knight in situ on d4 for as long as possible.} Nxd4 $6 8. Bxd4 Nf6 9. Be2 {Calmly ignoring Black while intending to castle with a typically pleasant Maroczy edge.} e5 $2 10. Be3 ({One of two semi-refutations of Black's overly ambitious last move, the other being} 10. b4 $5 {.}) 10... Nxe4 11. Qd5 $1 {The point: the double-attack compels Black to exchange queens.} Qxd5 12. Nxd5 Kd8 ({And now} 12... O-O $2 13. Nc7 {would win material in view of} Rb8 14. Bxa7 {.}) 13. Bf3 Nd6 ({Angling to pin and win with} 13... Nf6 $2 14. Bg5 {or do something similar with}) (13... f5 $2 14. Bxe4 fxe4 15. Bg5+ {.}) 14. Bg5+ {Even here, the check's a strong one.} f6 15. Nxf6 {Black can grovel on, but his position is a right wreck and both Ne4 and Nxh7+ threatened.} *

