1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} g6 {Black's third main option at this point, after which play is likely to transpose to the Accelerated Dragon lines we saw in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/3/b].} 3. e4 $1 ({A perhaps unexpected advance, but, worry not, the plan is not a Botvinnik formation, but rather a Maroczy Bind after all, as White plans to follow through with d2-d4 then Nc3. With this approach we avoid being move ordered by} 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {, as well as the possibility of}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 $5 {. After 3...Nc6 play might immediately transpose into the realm of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w] after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 Qa5+ {Not an especially threatening check.} 5. Nc3 ({White calmly blocks (} 5. Bd2 Qb6 6. Bc3 {is also a decent line if you're happy with an early queen exchange on d4), while intending Be2 followed by O-O or 5...Nc6?! 6.d5 .}) 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 {Naturally White keeps the knight in situ on d4 for as long as possible.} Nf6 8. Nb3 $1 {)} ({Black's main move, attacking the pawn on e4 which means White has no time for} 8. Be2 {.}) 8... Qd8 ({An important retreat, driving the queen backwards (} 8... Qb4 $4 9. Bc5 {would not be wise), ahead of completing development with Be2 and O-O.}) 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O {Taking stock, we find a standard Maroczy position, but with Black having lost two tempi with the queen just to drive the knight back from d4. White should not mind such a trade. He can even return the knight to d4 and transpose to normal lines, or simply aim for more, such as with Rc1 then expansion through f2-f4.} d6 11. Rc1 {Ensuring that c4 will be fully secure.} Bd7 12. f4 $5 {Black is running out of space, a factor which c4-c5 might now exploit. White can also consider going direct here with Qe1-h4.} a5 $5 13. Nd2 {Leaping out of the way of the black a-pawn. The Maroczy Bind certainly clamps down on Black's position here and White may even be able to go Qe1-h4 in conjunction with Nf3, f4-f5 and Bh6, with a strong attack brewing.} *

