1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} g6 {Black's third main option at this point, after which play is likely to transpose to the Accelerated Dragon lines we saw in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/3/b].} 3. e4 $1 ({A perhaps unexpected advance, but, worry not, the plan is not a Botvinnik formation, but rather a Maroczy Bind after all, as White plans to follow through with d2-d4 then Nc3. With this approach we avoid being move ordered by} 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {, as well as the possibility of}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 $5 {. After 3...Nc6 play might immediately transpose into the realm of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w] after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 Qb6 $5 {A more creative try than the check on a5.} 5. dxc5 $1 ({Simply does it as White establishes the Maroczy Bind after all, although creative types may wish to explore} 5. Nc3 cxd4 6. Nd5 Qa5+ {( 6...Qd8 7.Nxd4 Nf6 8.Nc3 is just a transposition to the mainline)} 7. b4 $5 {.}) 5... Qxc5 6. Be2 {White simply intends to get the king away from any checks, while waiting for ...Nf6 to go Nc3 and thereby avoid the possibility of a Nc3 Bxc3; bxc3 exchange.} Qb4+ $6 7. Nc3 $1 ({White has often preferred} 7. Nbd2 {then gradually untangled after a2-a3 and Rb1, but this is a strong pawn sacrifice, preparing to seize a strong initiative, as well as to castle.}) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 {Clearly necessary, but now just note White's lead in development. Next we'll castle, then set about trying to exploit that lead in development, be it with a quick e4-e5, Nd4-b5 or even just Rb1.} Z0 (9... Qa3 10. Nd4 $5 {Heading for b5 to seriously inconvenience the black queen.} a6 11. O-O {Calmly does it and now White might even bring the knight to its best square, d5, via c2 and e3 to emphasise Black's vulnerable dark squares.} Nf6 $6 12. Rb1 Qc5 13. Bb4 {Continuing to gain time against the pawn-grabbing, errant black queen.} Qc7 14. e5 $1 {With Re1 on the way, White enjoyed a very strong initiative whether or not Black accepted the second pawn in Verkasalo-Hentunen, Finnish League 2012.}) *

