1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} g6 {Black's third main option at this point, after which play is likely to transpose to the Accelerated Dragon lines we saw in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/3/b].} 3. e4 $1 ({A perhaps unexpected advance, but, worry not, the plan is not a Botvinnik formation, but rather a Maroczy Bind after all, as White plans to follow through with d2-d4 then Nc3. With this approach we avoid being move ordered by} 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {, as well as the possibility of}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 $5 {. After 3...Nc6 play might immediately transpose into the realm of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w] after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 Qb6 $5 {A more creative try than the check on a5.} 5. dxc5 $1 ({Simply does it as White establishes the Maroczy Bind after all, although creative types may wish to explore} 5. Nc3 cxd4 6. Nd5 Qa5+ {( 6...Qd8 7.Nxd4 Nf6 8.Nc3 is just a transposition to the mainline)} 7. b4 $5 {.}) 5... Qxc5 6. Be2 {White simply intends to get the king away from any checks, while waiting for ...Nf6 to go Nc3 and thereby avoid the possibility of a Nc3 Bxc3; bxc3 exchange.} d6 7. h3 $5 ({We quite like this prophylactic if rare advance ahead of castling. White takes control of g4 and so denies Black the chance with} 7. O-O Bg4 {to offload his potentially problematic light-squared bishop. Now 7...Nf6 8.Nc3 followed by Be3 again gives White what he wants, as will 7...Qb6 8.Qd2 , since then Nc3, O-O and Qc2 will follow ahead of Be3.}) 7... Be6 $5 8. Be3 $1 {Developing with tempo and the prelude to another fairly strong pawn sacrifice.} Qb4+ 9. Nbd2 Qxb2 ({White now has ideas of Nd4 and Rb1, as well as O-O, and} 9... Bxb2 $2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Rxb2 $1 Qxb2 12. Bd4 {wouldn't be wise.}) 10. Rb1 Qxa2 11. Nd4 {There's no rush to take on b7. Instead, White prepares to smash up Black's structure on e6, only then perhaps castle and go Rxb7.} Bd7 12. O-O {White's lead in development and queenside play supplies very promising play for the two pawns. There are even ideas of c4-c5, and if ...dxc5; Nb5, angling to land on c7 or even d6.} Qa5 {Trying to evacuate the queen from the danger zone.} 13. Rxb7 {With ideas of both Nb5 and c4-c5 dxc5; Nc4, White's initiative provides much more than enough compensation for what is now only one pawn.} *

