1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} g6 {Black's third main option at this point, after which play is likely to transpose to the Accelerated Dragon lines we saw in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/3/b].} 3. e4 $1 ({A perhaps unexpected advance, but, worry not, the plan is not a Botvinnik formation, but rather a Maroczy Bind after all, as White plans to follow through with d2-d4 then Nc3. With this approach we avoid being move ordered by} 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {, as well as the possibility of}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 $5 {. After 3...Nc6 play might immediately transpose into the realm of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w] after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 Qb6 $5 {A more creative try than the check on a5.} 5. dxc5 $1 ({Simply does it as White establishes the Maroczy Bind after all, although creative types may wish to explore} 5. Nc3 cxd4 6. Nd5 Qa5+ {( 6...Qd8 7.Nxd4 Nf6 8.Nc3 is just a transposition to the mainline)} 7. b4 $5 {.}) 5... Qxc5 6. Be2 {White simply intends to get the king away from any checks, while waiting for ...Nf6 to go Nc3 and thereby avoid the possibility of a Nc3 Bxc3; bxc3 exchange.} d6 7. h3 $5 ({We quite like this prophylactic if rare advance ahead of castling. White takes control of g4 and so denies Black the chance with} 7. O-O Bg4 {to offload his potentially problematic light-squared bishop. Now 7...Nf6 8.Nc3 followed by Be3 again gives White what he wants, as will 7...Qb6 8.Qd2 , since then Nc3, O-O and Qc2 will follow ahead of Be3.}) 7... Nc6 8. O-O {The simple plan now is Qc2 then Be3 to untangle the queenside.} Be6 9. Be3 $1 ({Grandmasters have preferred} 9. Nbd2 {, but this is again a strong concept, dangling the b4-pawn before Black.}) 9... Qb4 (9... Qa5 10. Qc2 {Calmly covering b2 while continuing to wait for ...Nf6 to go Nc3, with a quick a2-a3 also on the cards.} Nf6 11. Nc3 O-O 12. a3 $1 {Queenside expansion is especially tempting when tempi can be gained against the black queen.} Rfc8 13. b4 Qd8 14. Rad1 {With c4-c5 and e4-e5 both on the agenda, as well as the idea of Ng5 and f2-f4, White enjoyed an ideal Maroczy scenario and clear advantage in Neininger-Benninger, Frankfurt 2018.}) 10. Nbd2 {Now White might very well go Rb1, a2-a3 and b2-b4 if Black makes no attempt to justify his play.} Qxb2 {This greedy pawn snatch was seen in Kristjansson-Al Sayed, Gibraltar 2005.} 11. Rb1 $1 Qxa2 12. Ng5 $5 {White enjoys superb compensation, Black being vulnerable on not just b7, but e6, and if the bishop retreats then White will definitely go 13.c5! followed by Bc4, angling to fork the queen on a2 and f7.} *

