1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} g6 {Black's third main option at this point, after which play is likely to transpose to the Accelerated Dragon lines we saw in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/3/b].} 3. e4 $1 ({A perhaps unexpected advance, but, worry not, the plan is not a Botvinnik formation, but rather a Maroczy Bind after all, as White plans to follow through with d2-d4 then Nc3. With this approach we avoid being move ordered by} 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {, as well as the possibility of}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 $5 {. After 3...Nc6 play might immediately transpose into the realm of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w] after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 ({Establishing the Maroczy Bind. 6.Nc3 will follow, and} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 {would be an immediate transposition back into 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w].}) 6. Be3 Qb6 $5 ({Defending the knight and now play will almost always go} 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 {(and not 7.e5? Qa5+ ) or 6...d6 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Be2 when we're back in the world of 2b [/variation/35967446/#/8/b]. There are just two minor alternatives we should mention where Black aims to exploit the absence of an early ...Nf6.}) {Rauf Mamedov's pet line.} 7. Nb3 ({Retreating with tempo while keeping Black out of a5, unlike White's main alternative,} 7. Nb5 Qa5+ {when} 8. N1c3 Nf6 {may follow.}) 7... Qc7 8. Qd2 Nf6 ({Calmly avoiding any notion of doubled pawns while intending to complete development with Nc3, Be2 and O-O. Note too that} 8... Ne5 $2 {should be welcomed, not feared, as after} 9. Nc3 {the c-pawn is taboo:} Nxc4 $2 10. Nd5 {followed by carnage down the c-file.}) 9. Nc3 O-O ({Possible, as} 9... Ng4 {can simply be met by} 10. Bf4 {, which helps to explain why Black likely does better to retreat the queen to d8 in one move.}) 10. Be2 {Simply covering g4 ahead of housing the king.} b6 $5 11. O-O d6 12. Rac1 {White was now content to manoeuvre while maintaining an edge with f2-f3 and Nd4 in Noble-Sassler, correspondence 2011, but might also have looked for a more aggressive path, not least with f2-f4 and Bf3.} *

