1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} g6 {Black's third main option at this point, after which play is likely to transpose to the Accelerated Dragon lines we saw in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/3/b].} 3. e4 $1 ({A perhaps unexpected advance, but, worry not, the plan is not a Botvinnik formation, but rather a Maroczy Bind after all, as White plans to follow through with d2-d4 then Nc3. With this approach we avoid being move ordered by} 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {, as well as the possibility of}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 $5 {. After 3...Nc6 play might immediately transpose into the realm of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w] after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 ({Establishing the Maroczy Bind. 6.Nc3 will follow, and} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 {would be an immediate transposition back into 2b [/variation/35967401/#/6/w].}) 6. Be3 Qb6 $5 ({Defending the knight and now play will almost always go} 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 {(and not 7.e5? Qa5+ ) or 6...d6 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Be2 when we're back in the world of 2b [/variation/35967446/#/8/b]. There are just two minor alternatives we should mention where Black aims to exploit the absence of an early ...Nf6.}) {Rauf Mamedov's pet line.} 7. Nb3 ({Retreating with tempo while keeping Black out of a5, unlike White's main alternative,} 7. Nb5 Qa5+ {when} 8. N1c3 Nf6 {may follow.}) 7... Qd8 {The queen doesn't always retreat all the way back to base, but c7 is rarely a great square for her in Maroczy positions.} 8. Qd2 ({Declining the repetition with} 8. Nd4 {and again ensuring that there won't be any shredding of White's structure on c3.}) 8... Nf6 (8... d6 9. Nc3 {Straightforward development and White is now set to complete it with Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {We've already seen something very similar to this via a 4...Qa5+ move order. Here the white queen is on d2 and 11...Ng4 12.Bxg4 Bxg4 13.Nd4 followed by b2-b3 is nothing to fear. In any case, the knight may well return to d4, although if Black now went 11...Bd7 we would be very tempted to start getting on with things with 12.f4 .} a5 $5 12. Nd4 {Back already, but don't forget that Black has also lost time with his queen and now White is all set to take control of the position with Ndb5.} Nxd4 13. Bxd4 a4 14. h3 $5 {A familiar useful little pawn push, one which supplied a definite edge in Gokerkan-Makaraci, Ankara 2023, where one decent plan was our favourite Rad1 and f2-f4.}) 9. Nc3 {White is set to complete development with Be2 and O-O, which helps to explain why Black has often taken the chance to disrupt at this point.} Ng4 $5 10. Bf4 {Preserving the important bishop while intending Be2 and/or h2-h3.} d6 11. h3 $1 {Pushing the knight back so that White can exploit having the queen on d2 to force a positionally favourable exchange of dark-squared bishops.} Nf6 12. Bh6 {The point.} O-O 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. O-O-O $5 {With f2-f4 and g2-g4 on their way, as well as a timely Nd4, White enjoyed definite attacking prospects and was slightly for choice in Sethuraman-Vakhidov, Jerusalem 2022.} ({We should also point out though that if this seems too aggressive to you, there's also absolutely nothing wrong with} 14. Be2 {followed by O-O here.}) *

