b2-b3 is nothing to fear. In any case, the knight may well return to d4, although if Black now went 11...Bd7 we would be very tempted to start getting on with things with 12.f4 .} a5 $5 12. Nd4 {Back already, but don't forget that Black has also lost time with his queen and now White is all set to take control of the position with Ndb5.} Nxd4 13. Bxd4 a4 14. h3 $5 {A familiar useful little pawn push, one which supplied a definite edge in Gokerkan-Makaraci, Ankara 2023, where one decent plan was our favourite Rad1 and f2-f4.}) 9. Nc3 {White is set to complete development with Be2 and O-O, which helps to explain why Black has often taken the chance to disrupt at this point.} Ng4 $5 10. Bf4 {Preserving the important bishop while intending Be2 and/or h2-h3.} a5 11. Be2 ({Simple development, although we should note that the engines prefer} 11. h3 $5 Nf6 12. Nc5 $1 d6 13. N5a4 {to obstruct Black's queenside play, and it's not impossible that this is even stronger than the text move.}) 11... d6 12. Bxg4 $5 {A big decision and certainly a good one from a practical perspective. White wants to follow up by denying Black the bishop-pair with Bh6, thereby creating a square for the b3-knight on either d4 or d2.} Bxg4 13. Bh6 Bxc3 $5 14. Qxc3 f6 {The engines' preference is for this slightly ugly, but also complex choice.} 15. Nd4 Z0 ({Keeping the knight in play. The position isn't completely clear, but the bishop isn't about to get trapped (} 15... g5 {can be met by} 16. h4 {), and White is all set to regroup with Be3 and O-O, after which f2-f4 will become quite a tempting advance.}) *

