1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {after} Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+. This has only been Black's fifth most popular move and has never fully taken off, despite enjoying a pretty decent pedigree, having been used by such players as Kramnik, Anand and Caruana. e3 Our favourite advance even comes with tempo here as White avoids having the pawns doubled on f3. Nxf3+ Qxf3 g6 d4!? White's most ambitious move, seizing space, and probably the one most likely to disturb an opponent who had perhaps been looking forward to a lengthy manoeuvring battle. That said, if you don't like this aggressive choice, there's nothing at all wrong for White with the main line, b3 Bg7 Bb2} d6 {when there's a fairly pleasant choice between} 5. g3 {and 8.g4!? . cxd4?! exd4 Bg7 Be3 White's useful pawn centre and lead in development supply a pleasant early advantage. Next up will likely be Be2 and O-O, unless Black tries anything radical. Nf6 Be2 d5!? Nxd5! White ensures that while he will have to take on an isolated queen's pawn, there will at least be two of them! Nxd5 Qxd5 Continuing to force the pace while getting ready to castle. Qxd5 cxd5 Bf5 Bf3 The pawns may be doubled, but White has a clear advantage: g2-g4, Kd2 and Rhc1 will follow.} *

