1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 Nd4 $5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) {This has only been Black's fifth most popular move and has never fully taken off, despite enjoying a pretty decent pedigree, having been used by such players as Kramnik, Anand and Caruana.} 4. e3 {Our favourite advance even comes with tempo here as White avoids having the pawns doubled on f3.} Nxf3+ 5. Qxf3 g6 6. d4 $5 {White's most ambitious move, seizing space, and probably the one most likely to disturb an opponent who had perhaps been looking forward to a lengthy manoeuvring battle.} ({That said, if you don't like this aggressive choice, there's nothing at all wrong for White with the main line,} 6. b3 Bg7 7. Bb2 d6 {when there's a fairly pleasant choice between} 8. g3 {and 8.g4!? .}) 6... Bg7 {Black plays to keep White's own dark-squared bishop restricted.} 7. dxc5 $1 Bxc3+ $5 ({The correspondence world has helped to show that this is a critical capture, refusing to be concerned by the potential Irish pawns on the c-file. Black doesn't have to exchange there, but} 7... Qa5 8. e4 $1 {would offer support to c3 and then} Qxc5 9. Be2 {just looks like a pleasant Maroczy Bind edge for White.}) 8. bxc3 Qa5 9. e4 Qxc5 ({Covering c3 while making a useful gain of space. We mustn't lost sight that White's dark-squared bishop is unopposed here, and after something like} 9... Nf6 10. e5 $1 Ne4 11. Be2 {that might well quickly become a factor as White's lead in development grows.}) 10. Be3 Qc7 ({With tempo and now Black must reckon with the possibility of White clamping down on his underdeveloped position with c4-c5. As such,} 10... Qc6 {looks a little risky in view of the engines'} 11. a4 $1 {, intending} d6 $2 12. c5 $1 {when the upcoming Bb5 would be quite awkward.}) 11. Rd1 $5 Nf6 ({A sneaky suggestion by David Cummings from his ChessPublishing column, angling to break through with} 11... d6 $6 12. c5 $1 {followed by cxd6 or Bb5+.}) 12. Bd4 {Not only threatening to win a pawn, but especially helping the e4-e5 advance.} O-O $1 13. e5 $1 ({Now Black would be quite solid after} 13. Bxf6 exf6 14. Qxf6 Re8 {and ...b6, but White can do better than that.}) 13... Ne8 14. h4 $1 {The main point of Cummings's idea, leaving h4-h5 imminent and White with decent attacking prospects.} *

