1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 Nd4 $5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) {This has only been Black's fifth most popular move and has never fully taken off, despite enjoying a pretty decent pedigree, having been used by such players as Kramnik, Anand and Caruana.} 4. e3 {Our favourite advance even comes with tempo here as White avoids having the pawns doubled on f3.} Nxf3+ 5. Qxf3 g6 6. d4 $5 {White's most ambitious move, seizing space, and probably the one most likely to disturb an opponent who had perhaps been looking forward to a lengthy manoeuvring battle.} ({That said, if you don't like this aggressive choice, there's nothing at all wrong for White with the main line,} 6. b3 Bg7 7. Bb2 d6 {when there's a fairly pleasant choice between} 8. g3 {and 8.g4!? .}) 6... Bg7 {Black plays to keep White's own dark-squared bishop restricted.} 7. dxc5 $1 Bxc3+ $5 ({The correspondence world has helped to show that this is a critical capture, refusing to be concerned by the potential Irish pawns on the c-file. Black doesn't have to exchange there, but} 7... Qa5 8. e4 $1 {would offer support to c3 and then} Qxc5 9. Be2 {just looks like a pleasant Maroczy Bind edge for White.}) 8. bxc3 Qa5 9. e4 Qxc5 ({Covering c3 while making a useful gain of space. We mustn't lost sight that White's dark-squared bishop is unopposed here, and after something like} 9... Nf6 10. e5 $1 Ne4 11. Be2 {that might well quickly become a factor as White's lead in development grows.}) 10. Be3 Qa5 ({With tempo and now Black must reckon with the possibility of White clamping down on his underdeveloped position with c4-c5. As such,} 10... Qc6 {looks a little risky in view of the engines'} 11. a4 $1 {, intending} d6 $2 12. c5 $1 {when the upcoming Bb5 would be quite awkward.}) 11. Rc1 {) Calmly covering the main weakness in the white camp while intending both Bd4 and c4-c5.} Nf6 12. c5 $1 {White threatens to destabilise Black's set-up with e4-e5 and is also now all set to go Bd3 or Bc4 then O-O.} Qxa2 $5 13. e5 Nd5 14. Bh6 $5 ({This was the main reason why Black grabbed the a-pawn, but here White can aim for even more than the decent compensation that we'd get after} 14. Bd4 {, Bd3 and O-O.}) {Ensuring that Black won't be castling any time soon. Black's light-squared bishop also isn't especially happy.} 14... Nc7 15. Bd3 {Preparing after castling to take aim at b7 with Be4.} Qd5 16. Qxd5 $5 ({With such a grip on the position White can even exchange queens, although} 16. Qg3 Qxc5 17. O-O {is also quite tempting.}) 16... Nxd5 17. Kd2 {Black does have an extra and passed a-pawn, but the rest of Black's army is far from happy. With Be4, Ra1 and Rhb1 on the way, White enjoys at least full compensation for the pawn, and the engines suggest we are slightly for choice.} *

