1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 e5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) 4. e3 f5 $6 ({Our favourite central advance, getting ready for d2-d4. Indeed,} 4... g6 $2 5. d4 {would see the centre opening faster than Black would like (White very much has ideas of dxc5, as well as a timely d4-d5). As such, Black's main move by far here is 4...Nf6 when we saw 5.d4 back in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w]. On occasion though, Black prefers something even more aggressive.}) 5. d4 $1 {Our favourite central counter remains a critical one.} cxd4 $6 6. exd4 {The open nature of the position already favours White's more active pieces.} e4 7. Ne5 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2c2 , although here 7.Ng5!? is also pretty strong. The move ( 7.Ne5 threatens a certain check, as well as a timely clamp in the shape of c4-c5.} Nf6 8. Be2 ({Simply preparing to castle, although} 8. c5 $5 {might also be explored.}) 8... Bb4 9. O-O O-O 10. c5 $1 {All of a sudden Qb3+ is a definite threat.} d5 11. Bf4 Z0 ({White threatened} 11... Z0 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qa4 {and was all set to press ahead on the queenside, either down an open b-file or after getting in b2-b4, with a clear advantage in Kharitonov-Iljushin, Novgorod 1999.}) *

