1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 e5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) 4. e3 f5 $6 ({Our favourite central advance, getting ready for d2-d4. Indeed,} 4... g6 $2 5. d4 {would see the centre opening faster than Black would like (White very much has ideas of dxc5, as well as a timely d4-d5). As such, Black's main move by far here is 4...Nf6 when we saw 5.d4 back in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w]. On occasion though, Black prefers something even more aggressive.}) 5. d4 $1 {Our favourite central counter remains a critical one.} e4 {This is definitely best here.} 6. d5 $1 {Here this forcing advance is even stronger than in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/6/w].} Nb8 $5 7. Nd2 Nf6 8. f3 $1 Bd6 $5 ({A powerful advance and White's set-up is now a good one, whether Black tries to gambit the e-pawn or prefers to suffer after} 8... exf3 9. Nxf3 {followed by Bd3 and e3-e4.}) 9. fxe4 fxe4 10. Ndxe4 (10. Qc2 O-O {gave Black some compensation in Sasikiran-Harikrishna, Hastings 2001/2, but White can do much better with either 10.g4!? or simply grabbing the pawn.}) 10... Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Qh4+ {The point of Black's play, but the knight can easily drop back, thereby facilitating ideas of Qg4.} 12. Nf2 O-O 13. g3 {With Ne4 and Bg2 on the way, it's hard to detect too much compensation for Black.} *

