1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 e5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) 4. e3 f5 $6 ({Our favourite central advance, getting ready for d2-d4. Indeed,} 4... g6 $2 5. d4 {would see the centre opening faster than Black would like (White very much has ideas of dxc5, as well as a timely d4-d5). As such, Black's main move by far here is 4...Nf6 when we saw 5.d4 back in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w]. On occasion though, Black prefers something even more aggressive.}) 5. d4 $1 {Our favourite central counter remains a critical one.} e4 {This is definitely best here.} 6. d5 $1 {Here this forcing advance is even stronger than in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/6/w].} exf3 {Best. Black has also tried all the knight moves, but without much joy.} 7. dxc6 bxc6 $6 8. Qxf3 {This is yet another position where Black would prefer the pawn back on f7, not already finding itself en prise.} g6 $6 9. e4 $1 Qe7 {Black somehow won in just another 10 moves in Engelmann-Miezis, Bonn 1998, something which surely wouldn't have happen had White not opted to castle long.} 10. Bd3 {With O-O next up, the position is fast becoming a massacre. And, yes, White very much can sacrifice a piece here:} fxe4 11. Nxe4 $1 d5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. O-O {The aforementioned sacrifice, threatening ruin down the e-file after Re1.} dxe4 14. Bxe4 Rb8 15. Re1 {Faced with such threats as Bc6+ and Bf4, Black is surely never going to survive.} *

