1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 e5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) 4. e3 f5 $6 ({Our favourite central advance, getting ready for d2-d4. Indeed,} 4... g6 $2 5. d4 {would see the centre opening faster than Black would like (White very much has ideas of dxc5, as well as a timely d4-d5). As such, Black's main move by far here is 4...Nf6 when we saw 5.d4 back in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w]. On occasion though, Black prefers something even more aggressive.}) 5. d4 $1 {Our favourite central counter remains a critical one.} e4 {This is definitely best here.} 6. d5 $1 {Here this forcing advance is even stronger than in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/6/w].} exf3 {Best. Black has also tried all the knight moves, but without much joy.} 7. dxc6 dxc6 {Going for the solid option is wise when Black has already weakened their position with ...f5.} 8. Qxd8+ {Hurrying for the pleasant queenless middlegame.} Kxd8 9. gxf3 {We saw something very similar in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967486/#/9/w], but there Black hadn't weakened the position with ...f5. Also, just as there, White is all set to mobilise the queenside pieces with b2-b3, Bb2 and O-O-O.} Be6 10. b3 {Continuing the plan.} Nf6 11. Bb2 {Now White has ideas of not just O-O-O, but Ne2-f4 in conjunction with h2-h4, beginning to press against the black kingside.} Ke8 ({Here we'll see} 11... Bd6 12. O-O-O Ke7 13. h4 {in action in our mainline [/variation/35967588/#/13/w] after 9...Nf6.}) (11... Kc7 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Bd3 $5 {Opting to deploy the final piece before going Ne2-f4.} Rhe8 $6 14. Ne2 $1 g6 15. Nf4 Bf7 16. h4 $1 {White was all set to undermine the black kingside with h4-h5 and stood clearly better in Chigaev-Lorenzo de la Riva, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022.}) 12. Ne2 $1 {White wastes no time in starting the knight manoeuvre, threatening both Bxf6 with structural ruin and Nf4, and if ...Bf7; Bd3, with a rather awkward attack to deal with on f5.} Kf7 13. O-O-O Be7 14. Nf4 {White enjoyed a definite edge in Sargissian-Bernadskiy, European Championship, Vrnjacka Banja 2023, with Black either having to retreat to c8 or concede the bishop-pair. Whether White wants to exchange on e6 is a moot question though. We might prefer to, but only after first h2-h4 and Bh3, or we might prefer to keep pieces on with Nd3, highlighting the weakened c5 and e5 points.} *

