 O-O-O.} g6 {This was Black's best defensive with ...Nf6 played instead of ...f5, but now White should be able to exploit the extra weaknesses to emerge with an edge.} 10. b3 {The standard plan.} Bg7 11. Bb2 Ne7 $2 ({White is all set to go O-O-O followed by f3-f4, Bg2 and Na4, which may well cause something of a crisis on c5. we'll now see} 11... Nf6 12. Ne2 $5 {via a 9...Nf6 10.b3 g6 11.Bb2 Bg7 12.Ne2 move order [/variation/35967585/#/12/w].}) 12. O-O-O+ Ke8 13. f4 ({Fixing the kingside pawns and ensuring the long diagonal will be open for the bishop once it arrives on g2 (White can also go} 13. Bg2 {then} Z0 14. f4 {).}) 13... Rf8 14. Bg2 {With Na4 next up, Black's defence is beginning to creak.} Be6 15. Na4 $1 Bxb2+ 16. Kxb2 b6 17. Rd6 {Black was in all sorts of difficulties here in Stridde-Baramietze, Bad Zwesten 1999, thanks to the pressure against c6 and the bishop on e6. White was also all set to dominate the d-file after Rhd1 when one useful plan would be Kc2 and Nb2-d3-e5, with a huge positional advantage.} *

