1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 e5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) 4. e3 f5 $6 ({Our favourite central advance, getting ready for d2-d4. Indeed,} 4... g6 $2 5. d4 {would see the centre opening faster than Black would like (White very much has ideas of dxc5, as well as a timely d4-d5). As such, Black's main move by far here is 4...Nf6 when we saw 5.d4 back in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w]. On occasion though, Black prefers something even more aggressive.}) 5. d4 $1 {Our favourite central counter remains a critical one.} e4 {This is definitely best here.} 6. d5 $1 {Here this forcing advance is even stronger than in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/6/w].} exf3 {Best. Black has also tried all the knight moves, but without much joy.} 7. dxc6 dxc6 {Going for the solid option is wise when Black has already weakened their position with ...f5.} 8. Qxd8+ {Hurrying for the pleasant queenless middlegame.} Kxd8 9. gxf3 {We saw something very similar in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967486/#/9/w], but there Black hadn't weakened the position with ...f5. Also, just as there, White is all set to mobilise the queenside pieces with b2-b3, Bb2 and O-O-O.} Nf6 {Natural enough and Black's most common move at this juncture.} 10. b3 {As usual, White initially prioritises queenside development after the early exchanges.} g6 11. Bb2 Bg7 12. Ne2 $5 ({A small change of approach, angling to exploit one downside to ...f5 and place the knight quickly on f4. The standard plan of} 12. O-O-O+ Ke7 13. Bg2 {followed by f3-f4 and Na4 should also suffice for an edge.}) 12... Ke7 13. Nf4 Nh5 $5 {A logical attempt to free Black's position.} (13... a5 $6 14. Nd3 {A fine spot for the knight, as well as a strategic retreat which carries a certain threat.} b6 15. Bg2 $5 {White is happy enough with 15...a4 16.O-O-O , but it was also possible to begin with 15.a4 and only then go Bg2.} Bd7 16. a4 {Fixing the black queenside.} Rhd8 {This was Short-Hou Yifen, 5th matchgame, Hoogeveen 2016, where White went} 17. h4 {. We would prefer 17.f4!? The point is to follow up with Ne5, whether or not Black offers an exchange of bishops, then to go O-O-O or Rd1 and Ke2. After that Bf3 will follow with a pleasant edge and everything should then be set for a fairly powerful undermining advance in h2-h4-h5.}) 14. Bxg7 {A necessary exchange thanks to Black's temporary pressure.} Nxg7 15. Nd3 $1 {And this is a good retreat, threatening the c5-pawn while eyeing the potential outpost on e5.} Ne6 16. f4 {Clamping down on the outpost and do, as so often in this structure, note Black's lack of counterplay, since they can't easily open lines on the queenside.} a5 17. a4 $1 Bd7 18. h4 {Having kept the queenside closed, White thematically began to expand and probe in Gareyev-Sarkar, Pawtucket 2008, with a pleasant edge. Next up will be h4-h5 and Be2 in some order, after which O-O-O may follow or even Bf3 and Ke2, all the while as we await a timely moment to land our knight on e5 with some force.} *

