 O-O-O.} Nf6 {Natural enough and Black's most common move at this juncture.} 10. b3 {As usual, White initially prioritises queenside development after the early exchanges.} Bd6 ({Black's main move. Of course, this position could also arise via a 9...Bd6 10.b3 Nf6 move order, while here we saw} 10... Be6 {via a 9...Be6 10.b3 Nf6 move order [/variation/35967583/#/10/b].}) 11. Bb2 {Everything is now set for O-O-O, and after or even before that White may again consider ideas of Ne2 in conjunction with h2-h4.} Kc7 $6 {The wrong side for the king, in part because the knight on f6 now lacks protection.} 12. h4 $1 g6 $6 ({Neither does the other attempt to deter White: White threatens to clamp the black kingside with h4-h5, and} 12... h5 $2 13. Rg1 {wouldn't especially help the second player.}) 13. h5 $1 Be6 ({A powerful pawn sacrifice, since} 13... Nxh5 $2 14. Nb5+ $1 {would win the exchange and}) (13... gxh5 $2 14. Bd3 {followed by Ne2 leave Black with a horrendously shattered and vulnerable kingside.}) 14. Ne2 {Rerouting with gain of tempo.} Be7 15. Nf4 Bf7 16. O-O-O {White is in complete control and simply doing very well. Bd3 and Rdg1 may follow or even Nd3-e5. Black still can't really take on h5:} gxh5 $6 17. Bd3 Bg6 18. Ne6+ {White will regain the pawn with significant interest after Ng7.} *

