1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 e5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) 4. e3 f5 $6 ({Our favourite central advance, getting ready for d2-d4. Indeed,} 4... g6 $2 5. d4 {would see the centre opening faster than Black would like (White very much has ideas of dxc5, as well as a timely d4-d5). As such, Black's main move by far here is 4...Nf6 when we saw 5.d4 back in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w]. On occasion though, Black prefers something even more aggressive.}) 5. d4 $1 {Our favourite central counter remains a critical one.} e4 {This is definitely best here.} 6. d5 $1 {Here this forcing advance is even stronger than in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/6/w].} exf3 {Best. Black has also tried all the knight moves, but without much joy.} 7. dxc6 dxc6 {Going for the solid option is wise when Black has already weakened their position with ...f5.} 8. Qxd8+ {Hurrying for the pleasant queenless middlegame.} Kxd8 9. gxf3 {We saw something very similar in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967486/#/9/w], but there Black hadn't weakened the position with ...f5. Also, just as there, White is all set to mobilise the queenside pieces with b2-b3, Bb2 and O-O-O.} Nf6 {Natural enough and Black's most common move at this juncture.} 10. b3 {As usual, White initially prioritises queenside development after the early exchanges.} Bd6 ({Black's main move. Of course, this position could also arise via a 9...Bd6 10.b3 Nf6 move order, while here we saw} 10... Be6 {via a 9...Be6 10.b3 Nf6 move order [/variation/35967583/#/10/b].}) 11. Bb2 {Everything is now set for O-O-O, and after or even before that White may again consider ideas of Ne2 in conjunction with h2-h4.} Ke7 12. O-O-O ({A consistent approach, although White is spoilt for choice here with both} 12. Bd3 {and}) (12. h4 {also fairly promising.}) 12... Be6 ({The only real square for this bishop, thanks to the inclusion of ...f5.} 12... f4 $6 13. Bd3 {wouldn't help Black, since} fxe3 14. fxe3 {leaves White with a handy, mobile central pawn majority.}) 13. h4 $5 {White looks to squeeze with a timely h4-h5, an advance which may be prefaced by Be2 to connect the rooks and even f3-f4.} ({We prefer this set-up to} 13. Bd3 Rhd8 14. Kc2 Rd7 {, after which Black was able to hold in Giri-So, Saint Louis 2015.}) 13... Rhd8 14. h5 $1 Bf7 $5 ({Now this is possible, since} 14... g6 $6 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Na4 {would prevent ...Rh8 and prepare to invade down the h-file.}) 15. h6 $1 ({Consistently undermining Black on the long dark-square diagonal. Here} 15. Bd3 $5 Bxh5 16. Nd5+ cxd5 17. Bxf6+ Kxf6 18. Rxh5 g6 19. Rxh7 {is also quite tempting, but with opposite-coloured bishops present, Black should be able to hold - with care.}) 15... g6 16. Bd3 {Gradual does it. White may now improve the king to c2, after which it may even be possible to undertake a strong knight manoeuvre in the shape of Ne2-g1-h3-g5.} Be5 17. f4 {Ensuring that the a1-h8 diagonal will continue to be White's.} Bc7 18. Kc2 {Tidying up White's position while usefully overprotecting the bishop on d3 lest Black now doubles rooks.} Rd7 19. Rhe1 Be6 $1 ({All of a sudden White threatens to blow open the position with} 19... Z0 20. e4 {then go after the black king.}) {Sensibly blocking the e-file while freeing up a square for the king on f7.} 20. f3 {Even here White enjoys a definite pull with ideas of e3-e4. Ne2 may well help with such a plan (overprotecting f4), and White has by no means given up on the ideas of a timely Ne2-g1-h3-g5 to tie Black down to the defence of h7.} *

