{A) 15...g6? 16.hxg6+ Whoops! Only now does Black notice that 16...hxg6? would now leave the rook on d8 badly overloaded. 16...Kxg6 17.Bd3 Black's king is badly exposed and both e3-e4 and Ne2-g3 look strong for White. B 15...Bc7 16.Rdg1 Keeping all the rooks on for now while intending to plug the d-file with Kc2 then Bd3. 16...Ba5!? 17.Kc2 Rd7 18.Bd3 Rhd8 19.Rd1! Back again, but Black has been kept out of d2 and is still struggling for counterplay. The key to these positions is often not to rush as White, who is only now all set to increase the pressure with Ne2-f4, as the clamping and cramping pawn on h5 continues to play a major role.} 1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 {We decline the option of a Sicilian (2.e4), and keep play within Reti-English lines, getting ready to go 3.Nc3 or 3.e3.} Nc6 ({Black's main move and alternative to} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 e5 ({Continuing development while getting ready for both e2-e3 then d2-d4 and a transposition to the realm of Chapter Two [/variation/35967462/#/4/w] after} 3... Nf6 4. e3 {. As well as 3...Nf6 , Black has two other big main moves, 3...g6 and 3...e5. The former should be met by 4.e3 followed by d2-d4, and we saw 4...Nf6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 and then 7.h3!? back in Chapter 2c1 [/variation/35967468/#/7/w]. We should also note the rare move order that is 3...e6 4.e3 . Then 4...Nf6 5.d4 takes play into Chapter 2c3 [/variation/35967520/#/5/w], while 4...d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.d4 would be a Tarrasch [/variation/23789979/#/5/b] where White should be looking to make one of our favourite early moves there in Bb5+.}) 4. e3 f5 $6 ({Our favourite central advance, getting ready for d2-d4. Indeed,} 4... g6 $2 5. d4 {would see the centre opening faster than Black would like (White very much has ideas of dxc5, as well as a timely d4-d5). As such, Black's main move by far here is 4...Nf6 when we saw 5.d4 back in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/5/w]. On occasion though, Black prefers something even more aggressive.}) 5. d4 $1 {Our favourite central counter remains a critical one.} e4 {This is definitely best here.} 6. d5 $1 {Here this forcing advance is even stronger than in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967479/#/6/w].} exf3 {Best. Black has also tried all the knight moves, but without much joy.} 7. dxc6 dxc6 {Going for the solid option is wise when Black has already weakened their position with ...f5.} 8. Qxd8+ {Hurrying for the pleasant queenless middlegame.} Kxd8 9. gxf3 {We saw something very similar in Chapter 2c2 [/variation/35967486/#/9/w], but there Black hadn't weakened the position with ...f5. Also, just as there, White is all set to mobilise the queenside pieces with b2-b3, Bb2 and O-O-O.} Nf6 {Natural enough and Black's most common move at this juncture.} 10. b3 {As usual, White initially prioritises queenside development after the early exchanges.} Bd6 ({Black's main move. Of course, this position could also arise via a 9...Bd6 10.b3 Nf6 move order, while here we saw} 10... Be6 {via a 9...Be6 10.b3 Nf6 move order [/variation/35967583/#/10/b].}) 11. Bb2 {Everything is now set for O-O-O, and after or even before that White may again consider ideas of Ne2 in conjunction with h2-h4.} Ke7 12. O-O-O ({A consistent approach, although White is spoilt for choice here with both} 12. Bd3 {and}) (12. h4 {also fairly promising.}) 12... Be6 ({The only real square for this bishop, thanks to the inclusion of ...f5.} 12... f4 $6 13. Bd3 {wouldn't help Black, since} fxe3 14. fxe3 {leaves White with a handy, mobile central pawn majority.}) 13. h4 $5 {White looks to squeeze with a timely h4-h5, an advance which may be prefaced by Be2 to connect the rooks and even f3-f4.} ({We prefer this set-up to} 13. Bd3 Rhd8 14. Kc2 Rd7 {, after which Black was able to hold in Giri-So, Saint Louis 2015.}) 13... Rad8 14. Be2 ({Black keeps a rook on h8 so as to be able to answer} 14. h5 {with} g6 {, angling to keep the kingside as closed as possible.}) {Connecting the rooks. White may now even be able to go Rdg1, as well as h4-h5 and f3-f4.} 14... Kf7 15. h5 $1 ({This improves over the} 15. Na4 Be7 16. Rdg1 {of Nguyen-Tomczak, German Bundesliga 2021, as then} b5 $1 {would have given Black reasonable counterplay, as pointed out by David Cummings. White generally does better to only go Na4 when it attacks c5 or creates some issues down the a1-h8 diagonal and sometimes, as here, the idea would be better prepared by first Bc3 so that Na4 b5 can be met by the calm Nb2.}) 15... Z0 *

