1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 {A very popular choice at all levels, largely due to the vast number of King's Indian enthusiasts there are about, although, especially at higher levels, the Grunfeld can also be quite popular.} 3. Nc3 Z0 ({Standard enough moves for the repertoire and now} 3... c5 4. e4 {would take us back into the realm of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w]. When first planning this repertoire, we wanted to suggest another of our favourite moves in general here in the shape of 3.b4!? . This is a decent, independent, fully Reti line, but unfortunately White can be move ordered by 2...d6 ( 3.b4 e5 isn't so ideal when Black hasn't gone ...g6), and especially a 1...g6 or 1...d6 approach. Instead, after 3.Nc3 we threaten to advance with e2-e4, and now 3...Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.d4 and the King's Indian will be considered in our next theoretical section, Chapter Five. In Chapter Four we're looking at what a Grunfeld (1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5) player might do against our Reti move order. Some Grunfeldeers try a 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 move order, when we saw that 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 is not without bite back in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w]. Here we'll focus instead on the two main alternatives used by those Grunfeld players who have no desire to be dragged into King's Indian lines: 4a: 3...d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 4b: 3...Bg7 4.e4 e5 .}) *

