1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Nxc3 6. bxc3 h5 ({That leaves: This is far from forced, but we'd quite like to retain the queens and now play will usually go} 6... Bg7 7. h5 {with a transposition to our mainline [/variation/35967625/#/7/w].}) 7. Ng5 $5 {This has been pretty rare, but we quite like to exploit the weakened g5-square without delay, in a similar manner to how we will with 5...h6 6.Qb3 Nb6 7.Ng5 . Already Qb3 may be slightly annoying for Black to meet and White can also easily expand in the centre.} Bg7 8. d4 O-O 9. e3 {Here rather than e2-e4 to keep d4 secure against any ...c5 counter-thrust. The position is clearly quite Grunfeld-like, but the knight on g5 is pretty useful. Those of a very aggressive bent may even wish to consider ideas of a quick Be2 and g2-g4, but our main recommendation would be to place the light-squared bishop on c4. White will likely castle short and may also find all of a2-a4, Ba3 and especially Qb3 to be useful moves too, aiming to maintain some pressure on Black's position, not least the f7 point.} *

