1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Nxc3 6. bxc3 h6 $5 ({This is far from forced, but we'd quite like to retain the queens and now play will usually go} 6... Bg7 7. h5 {with a transposition to our mainline [/variation/35967625/#/7/w].}) 7. h5 $5 ({This isn't perhaps one of Black's better defences, but is a decent try for a Grunfeld player. White has tended to respond with} 7. e4 Bg7 8. d4 c5 {when} 9. Be2 {should be an improved version of a main-line Grunfeld for him (h6 can be attacked with tempo, a timely h4-h5 might be on).}) ({Do by all means play this way if you have some Grunfeld experience, but if you don't, we can aim to remain in independent Reti waters, whether with the positionally sensible} 7. g3 {followed by Bg2, or the following.}) 7... g5 8. d4 {Only now do we advance, with Black having sensibly elected to keep his kingside intact. The plan is to follow up not with e2-e4, but the more solid e2-e3, a policy which may even allow White to later launch a timely strike down the weakened b1-h7 diagonal.} Bg7 9. e3 {This was initially suggested by David Cummings on ChessPublishing and in his fine book 'Opening Repertoire: The English'. White wants to develop the light-squared bishop to d3 and may also find Rb1 and Ba3 to be useful moves. Indeed, Black is potentially vulnerable down the a3-f8 diagonal and on e7.} c5 10. Rb1 Qc7 ({It shouldn't now be too hard to realise the impact that Bd3-e4 might carry and meanwhile just how is Black supposed to develop the bishop from c8?} 10... b6 $2 {might look sensible, but look again and you'll likely spot} 11. Nxg5 $1 {, netting a clear pawn in view of the rook-winning threat of Qf3.}) 11. Bd3 Nd7 ({Calm development and the right square, heading for e4, even if White is some way off setting up an effective queen and bishop battery on the diagonal. Note too that} 11... cxd4 $6 12. cxd4 {only helps White to take control, since where is Black's counterplay or development after} Qc3+ $6 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Bxd2 $2) 12. O-O ({We're not too sure what} 12. Qa4 {achieved here in Rahul-Zeng, Xingtai 2019, and would prefer just to house the king.}) 12... O-O 13. c4 Z0 ({With d4-d5 then Bb2 on the cards, this feels like a pleasant version of a Grunfeld for White. Whether Black exchanges pawns on d4 or opts for something more unbalanced with} 13... e6 $5 14. d5 {, it's hard to shake off the notion that the vulnerability of his kingside won't come back to haunt them one day.}) *

