1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} h6 6. Qb3 $5 {)} Nb6 ({Forcing the pace and in a slightly awkward manner for Black, since now} 6... Nxc3 $6 {can be well met by} 7. Qxc3 {. Once again, 6.e4 Nxc3 7.bxc3 is very much an option if you have some Grunfeld experience, and here 7.dxc3!? has been tried by some strong players, but we're quite happy with the text move, increasing the pressure against d5. After 6.Qb3 , 6...c6?! 7.e4 would favourably expand and 6...Nf6?! 7.d4 then e2-e4 also leave Black with an inferior version of a Grunfeld considering the lack of activity and counterplay. As such, the knight really should make its standard retreat in these anti-Grunfeld lines.}) 7. d4 ({Straightforward development and we prefer this to} 7. h5 g5 8. e3 {and d2-d4 here in part because Black seems to struggle to get in ...c5 and develop sufficient counterplay. This time we'll even be happy to take the plunge and push e2-e4.}) 7... Be6 $6 {Grunfeld authority Emil Sutovsky once played this way, but we're not especially convinced since the bishop may become a target here for a timely d4-d5.} 8. Qc2 Bg7 ({There's no need to go all the way back to d1 when} 8... Z0 9. e4 {can follow next in any case.}) 9. e4 $1 {The point. Be3 and Rd1 will follow and any ...Nc4; Bf4 manoeuvre will only improve White's pieces, not Black's. Note too that the powerful centre is secure since d4 is taboo:} Bxd4 $4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nb5 Z0 ({Since} 11... Qb4+ {can be met by} 12. Bd2 {, the fork on c7 will decide the game.}) *

