1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} h6 6. Qb3 $5 Nb6 ({Forcing the pace and in a slightly awkward manner for Black, since now} 6... Nxc3 $6 {can be well met by} 7. Qxc3 {. Once again, 6.e4 Nxc3 7.bxc3 is very much an option if you have some Grunfeld experience, and here 7.dxc3!? has been tried by some strong players, but we're quite happy with the text move, increasing the pressure against d5. After 6.Qb3 , 6...c6?! 7.e4 would favourably expand and 6...Nf6?! 7.d4 then e2-e4 also leave Black with an inferior version of a Grunfeld considering the lack of activity and counterplay. As such, the knight really should make its standard retreat in these anti-Grunfeld lines.}) 7. d4 ({Straightforward development and we prefer this to} 7. h5 g5 8. e3 {and d2-d4 here in part because Black seems to struggle to get in ...c5 and develop sufficient counterplay. This time we'll even be happy to take the plunge and push e2-e4.}) 7... Bg7 8. e4 $1 Bg4 $1 ({A fairly strong pawn sacrifice, although White is happy to accept another if allowed and} 8... c5 $2 9. dxc5 N6d7 10. Qa3 {doesn't impress whatsoever for Black. Meanwhile Be3 is on the way to develop and shore up the centre.}) {Undermining d4 so must be critical.} 9. Ne5 $5 ({White finds a different way to attack the bishop.} 9. Nh2 {is again the alternative and was once seen in a Vallejo Pons-Mamedyarov blindfold rapid game when} Bc8 $1 {is the critical line, after which White can repeat or try} 10. d5 e6 11. h5 $5 g5 12. Bb5+ {with chances for an edge.}) ({Instead, with} 9. Ne5 {we create a double-threat and again play for the bishop-pair.}) 9... Bxe5 10. dxe5 {Clearly Black can't castle here ( 11...O-O ( 11.Bxh6 ), and 10...Nc6 would be fairly well met by 11.Bb5 (or 10...N8d7?! 11.f4 ), so pawn grabbing may again be critical.} Qd4 $1 11. Nb5 $1 (11. f4 $2 Nc6 {would leave White's position a right wreck, but the text carries a further double-threat while preparing a nifty queen manoeuvre.}) 11... Qxe5 12. Qe3 {Thanks to the pressure against h6 and with Bd2-c3 on the way, White enjoys good compensation for the pawn.} *

