chances for an edge.}) ({Instead, with} 9. Ne5 {we create a double-threat and again play for the bishop-pair.}) 9... Be6 10. d5 $1 Bxd5 ({This pawn sacrifice is the main point of White's direct play. Clearly} 10... Bc8 $2 11. Bf4 {would now just leave White in full control.}) 11. exd5 Bxe5 12. Be3 {This time Black has managed to retain their dark-squared bishop, but we still quite like White's compensation. Either Rd1 or O-O-O will support the bridgehead on d5, while on the other flank there are various tempting options, not least f2-f4 in conjunction with h4-h5.} *

