1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} h5 6. Qb3 Nb6 ({White has tested many moves here, but we're again happy to force the pace with the queen, while hoping for} 6... Nxc3 $6 7. Qxc3 {. Note too that ...h5 is by no means a risk-free advance for Black: the g5-square is effectively an outpost for White, since ...f6 would be extremely weakening, meaning that ideas of a quick Ng5 very much come into the equation.}) (6... c6 $6 7. e4 {Forcing the pace while preparing to claim a large advantage after 7...Nf4 8.d4 or 7...Nf6 8.Bc4 e6 9.d4 .} Nxc3 $6 8. Qxc3 Rg8 9. d4 {Talk about a powerful centre!} Bg7 10. Be3 {Overprotecting d4 to facilitate Ng5 possibilities is never a bad thing.} Bg4 11. Ne5 {By no means the only good option ( 11.Ng5!? is also pretty tempting), but this left White clearly better in Scherbakov-Tengis, Moscow 2019. Bc4 is a threat and after 11.Ne5 Be6 12.Be2 and O-O clearly only one king would be happy with the early exchanges.}) 7. Ng5 $5 (7. d4 {is also a good move, but it's hard to resist threatening a huge check when you have the chance!}) 7... e6 8. a4 $1 Nc6 ({White wastes no time in continuing actively, seeking to make a further positional gain in} 8... Z0 9. a5 {before going} Z0 10. d4 {.}) 9. a5 Nd5 ({Possible as} 9... Nd4 10. Qd1 {followed by e2-e3 is nothing to fear.}) 10. e3 {White has made serious inroads on both flanks and with both Bc4 and d2-d4 on the way was taking control, thereby leaving Black struggling for counterplay in Oparin-Aggelis, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022.} *

