1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} c5 6. h5 $1 ({A standard enough advance in these lines, if arguably a little premature here. Now White can do even better than} 6. e3 {.}) 6... Nxc3 ({Threatening to break up the opposition kingside with} 6... Z0 7. hxg6 fxg6 {ahead of going} 8. Qb3 {. Black has usually now opted not to allow 6...Bg7 7.h6! Bf6 8.e4 when White has made definite gains on the dark squares and positionally.}) 7. dxc3 $1 {Not our usual recapture, but an especially good one here. The combination of the weaknesses created by ...c5 and the kingside pressure ensure that White obtains a good version of the queenless middlegame.} Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Bg7 9. e4 {The king will come to c2, the dark-squared bishop to e3 or f4 and White very much has ideas too of h5-h6, since ...Bf6 would currently cost Black a piece after e4-e5.} Nc6 (9... Bg4 10. h6 $1 Bf6 11. Kc2 {Calmly unpinning while preparing to exert some pressure against c5 with Be3. Now 11...Nd7?! 12.Nh2! Be6 13.f4 Rf8 14.g4 left White doing pretty well in Cmilyte-D.Andersen, Copenhagen 2010.} Nc6 12. Be3 b6 {Here} 13. Nd2 {was thematic and fairly strong in Deac-Atanasov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022, and White actually can do even better: 13.Bb5! Bd7 14.Rhd1 Now even 14...-- 15.Rxd7! Kxd7 16.e5 is a threat. 14...e6 15.a4 White is in full control and clearly better. After 15...a6 16.Be2 will keep the bishop safe while preparing a strong manoeuvre to exploit Black's weaknesses: Nd2-c4.}) 10. Kc2 {White stays flexible with the bishops for now while freeing d1 for a rook to later use.} Bg4 11. h6 $1 {Beginning to squeeze ahead of tickling c5 with Be3.} Bf8 12. Bc4 $5 f6 ({Suddenly Black has to watch out for the threat of} 12... Z0 13. Ng5 {, and if} Ne5 14. Bd5 {or 13...e6? 14.f3 , trapping Black's bishop.}) 13. Be3 {This was already quite unpleasant for Black in Reinhart-Gleyzer, correspondence 2015, since White will be quick to increase the pressure on the queenside, most likely through a combination of Bd5, a2-a4-a5 and Nd2-c4, all the while as any exchange on f3 would just leave Black even more vulnerable on the light squares.} *

