1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Nf6 $6 {A sharp, but risky choice. Black prevents h4-h5, but does nothing to prevent White from dominating the centre.} 6. e4 $1 {Even e4-e5 may now be possible, as well as just d2-d4.} Bg7 7. d4 {Taking stock, we have a Grunfeld where all the knights are still on the board and we would claim that the pawn on h4, far from being a weakness, is actually a strength. Indeed, h4-h5 might land with some effect and the position just looks like a good combination of the Grunfeld and Harry Attack ( 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.h4!? ) from White's perspective.} O-O {Now 7...c5 8.d5 would keep lines relatively closed, seize some space and even introduce ideas of e4-e5 and h4-h5.} 8. Be2 c5 ({Calm does it. There's no need to rush with h4-h5 and now} 8... Bg4 {won't pin, but can be fairly well met by} 9. e5 {. In any case, White is all set to advance with 8...-- 9.e5 Nd5 10.h5 , hence Black's rather radical upcoming play.}) 9. d5 $1 e6 ({Keeping the centre closed. Now} 9... Z0 10. h5 Nxh5 {followed by} 11. e5 {or 11.Ng5 would already leave Black under significant pressure, as in a calmer guise would 9...h5 10.Ng5 .}) 10. h5 $1 Nxh5 ({Blasting ahead, as White introduces ideas of Bg5 and even h5-h6, as well as hxg6 and d5-d6. Now} 10... exd5 {can be met by either} 11. hxg6 {or even 11.h6! Bh8 12.exd5 followed by Bg5 and O-O with a pleasant, stable long-term advantage.}) 11. Bg5 $1 ({Here White couldn't resist} 11. g4 {in Piket-Svidler, Internet 2000, but even stronger ideas also exist.}) {With tempo. White is now ready to complete mobilisation with Qd2 and also has strong ideas in the shape of d5-d6 and e4-e5.} 11... Qa5 12. Nd2 $1 ({Even stronger than} 12. Qd2 {as the knight on h5 begins to feel the heat.}) 12... Nf6 13. Nc4 {With Qd2 on the way, followed by d5-d6, e4-e5 and/or just Bh6 and O-O-O if necessary, White simply enjoys an extremely strong attack.} *

