1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Nf6 $6 {A sharp, but risky choice. Black prevents h4-h5, but does nothing to prevent White from dominating the centre.} 6. e4 $1 {Even e4-e5 may now be possible, as well as just d2-d4.} Bg7 7. d4 {Taking stock, we have a Grunfeld where all the knights are still on the board and we would claim that the pawn on h4, far from being a weakness, is actually a strength. Indeed, h4-h5 might land with some effect and the position just looks like a good combination of the Grunfeld and Harry Attack ( 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.h4!? ) from White's perspective.} O-O {Now 7...c5 8.d5 would keep lines relatively closed, seize some space and even introduce ideas of e4-e5 and h4-h5.} 8. Be2 c5 ({Calm does it. There's no need to rush with h4-h5 and now} 8... Bg4 {won't pin, but can be fairly well met by} 9. e5 {. In any case, White is all set to advance with 8...-- 9.e5 Nd5 10.h5 , hence Black's rather radical upcoming play.}) 9. d5 $1 b5 $5 ({Keeping the centre closed. Now} 9... Z0 10. h5 Nxh5 {followed by} 11. e5 {or 11.Ng5 would already leave Black under significant pressure, as in a calmer guise would 9...h5 10.Ng5 .}) 10. e5 $1 ({Forcing the pace rather than allow Black to secure some counterplay with the standard tactical motif that would be} 10. Bxb5 Nxe4 $1 {.}) 10... Ng4 11. d6 $1 ({Tony Kosten's powerful suggested improvement over the slightly greedy} 11. Bxb5 {of Zvjaginsev-Najer, Moscow 2003. With}) (11. d6 {, White drives a powerful wedge into the middle of the black camp, threatening Bg5, as well as h4-h5, while} Nxe5 $2 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 {would drop material to} 13. Bf3 {.}) 11... exd6 12. Bg5 {Developing with tempo.} Qd7 13. exd6 {The position is a bit messy, but White does seem to be clearly for choice. Bf4 will protect the key asset on d6, the king will be quite safe on g1 and while Black can defend b5, they must very much also reckon with the powerful idea of Nd5.} *

