1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Nc6 {MVL has dabbled in this risky sideline, one which just appears to give White a number of pleasant options.} 6. e4 $1 ({Of course,} 6. h5 {can't be a bad move, but it's hard to resist kicking the black knight here in a position where the exchange on c3 should be especially promising for White.}) 6... Nxc3 $6 7. bxc3 e5 ({Black's c-pawn-obstructing knight would now just be rather misplaced after} 7... Bg7 8. d4 {, not that the alternatives are especially great either for Black.}) 8. Bc4 $1 h6 ({All of a sudden Ng5 is quite a large threat, and} 8... Bg4 {well met by} 9. Qb3 {.}) 9. Rb1 ({White now went in for} 9. h5 g5 10. Nh2 {in Petrosyan-Khusenkhojaev, Tashkent 2021, but simpler and stronger plans were available, including 9.d4 exd4 10.O-O!? and obtaining some pressure down the half-open b-file.}) 9... Z0 ({Aiming to tie down Black's light-squared bishop to the defence of b7. The dark-squared one isn't especially happy either as} 9... Be7 {will be powerfully met by} 10. d4 {and 9...Bg7 10.Ba3 is also a bit awkward for Black. Meanwhile White is all set to go O-O and d2-d4 in any case, with some advantage.}) *

