1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Nc6 {MVL has dabbled in this risky sideline, one which just appears to give White a number of pleasant options.} 6. e4 $1 ({Of course,} 6. h5 {can't be a bad move, but it's hard to resist kicking the black knight here in a position where the exchange on c3 should be especially promising for White.}) 6... Ndb4 $1 7. d3 $1 ({Prudently keeping Black out of d3, in contrast to which} 7. d4 $2 Nxd4 8. Nxd4 Qxd4 $1 {would not be so wise.}) 7... Bg4 {The point of Black's play. Otherwise, they'd have little to compensate for being pushed backwards by a2-a3 and h4-h5.} 8. a3 {Rightly forcing the pace and refusing to fear any doubled pawns.} Bxf3 9. gxf3 Na6 10. Be3 {The knight on a6 wasn't too happy and White was all set to expand with either d3-d4 or f3-f4 and h4-h5, which left him clearly for choice in Bu Xiangzhi-Xu Xiangyu, Chinese Rapid Championship, Shenyang 2019.} *

