1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg4 $6 6. Qa4+ $5 Bd7 ({Hoping that Black will blunder a piece with} 6... Qd7 $4 {before dropping back to b3. The immediate 6.Qb3 is also pretty strong.}) 7. Qb3 Nb6 ({Not for the first time we find Black reluctant to see} 7... Nxc3 8. Qxc3 {, and 7...Bc6?! 8.Ne5 would also not spell good news.}) 8. d4 Bg7 9. e4 $1 Bg4 ({Picking off d4 would be a rather risky approach for Black: With Be3 and h4-h5 on the way, this is a pretty promising version of a Grunfeld for White.} 9... Nc6 {can simply be met by} 10. d5 {.}) 10. Be3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Bxd4 ({Now} 11... Nc6 {can be well met by} 12. Bb5 {and meanwhile Rd1 or even O-O-O will be next up to secure d4.}) 12. Rd1 c5 13. h5 {With ideas of breaking up Black's queenside, as well as Nb5, White enjoys superb play for the pawn.} *

