1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nc6 $5 7. d4 $1 ({It's important to contest the centre and not fall too far behind in development here. Indeed,} 7. Qb3 $6 Be6 $1 8. Qxb7 $6 Ndb4 {would not be wise and Black also obtains good counterplay after 7.h6 Bf6 and then the slow 8.Ne4 (8.g3 is a much better approach) 8...Bf5 .}) ({Instead, with} 7. d4 {we threaten to dominate the centre and the board after e2-e4 and don't forget that Black has obstructed one major source of counterplay in ...c5.}) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 e5 9. e3 O-O ({Keeping everything secure in the centre where} 9... exd4 $6 10. cxd4 {would now leave White in control. Even worse for Black would be 9...e4? 10.Nd2 when the e-pawn is pretty weak and further weaknesses likely and meanwhile White threatens Ba3.}) 10. Be2 {Modest but good development whether White wants to cramp with h5-h6 then castle or maintain more aggressive intentions with Kf1. Ba3 is again also likely to prove useful, while the queen may come out to b3 or even a4, all the while keeping an eye open for a timely and powerful switch to the kingside.} exd4 $6 11. cxd4 Nb4 $6 12. Bd2 {With tempo. Now Rc1 is also on the way.} c5 {The point of Black's play, but the idea is flawed, in part due to White's solid centre.} 13. Rc1 {White was simply winning a pawn on c5 in Gukesh-Mikhalevski, La Roda 2022.} *

