1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nc6 $5 7. d4 $1 ({It's important to contest the centre and not fall too far behind in development here. Indeed,} 7. Qb3 $6 Be6 $1 8. Qxb7 $6 Ndb4 {would not be wise and Black also obtains good counterplay after 7.h6 Bf6 and then the slow 8.Ne4 (8.g3 is a much better approach) 8...Bf5 .}) ({Instead, with} 7. d4 {we threaten to dominate the centre and the board after e2-e4 and don't forget that Black has obstructed one major source of counterplay in ...c5.}) 7... Bf5 8. Rh4 $1 ({Highly creative play, but White wants to force through e2-e4 (} 8. e4 $2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxe4 {wins a pawn), and this looks like his best option to boot.}) ({There's also} 8. Qb3 {, but after} Be6 $1 {there may not be a better move than to go back with} 9. Qd1 {.}) 8... Bf6 {This must be critical, and White has no intention of backing down and moving the rook.} 9. g4 $1 Bxh4 10. gxf5 {And so Black has won the exchange, but their bishop is attacked, White also threatens e2-e4 and it's not hard to see the black light squares becoming rather vulnerable. All in all, White has promising compensation.} e6 $5 {This might be best, overprotecting the bishop.} 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Bh3 ({Threatening to remove a rather important pawn. White might also be able to go} 12. e4 $5 {following up with Be3.}) 12... Qe7 13. Nxd5 {This exchange ensures that Black won't be castling long for a while.} exd5 14. Bh6 {And Black won't be castling short either. With Qb3 or just Qd2 set to follow, White enjoyed full compensation for the exchange in Matlakov-Suleymenov, Abu Dhabi 2023, and note that not only may the remaining white rook be developed by castling queenside, but that Rc1-c3 may be a pretty strong manoeuvre.} *

