1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nc6 $5 7. d4 $1 ({It's important to contest the centre and not fall too far behind in development here. Indeed,} 7. Qb3 $6 Be6 $1 8. Qxb7 $6 Ndb4 {would not be wise and Black also obtains good counterplay after 7.h6 Bf6 and then the slow 8.Ne4 (8.g3 is a much better approach) 8...Bf5 .}) ({Instead, with} 7. d4 {we threaten to dominate the centre and the board after e2-e4 and don't forget that Black has obstructed one major source of counterplay in ...c5.}) 7... Bf5 8. Rh4 $1 ({Highly creative play, but White wants to force through e2-e4 (} 8. e4 $2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxe4 {wins a pawn), and this looks like his best option to boot.}) ({There's also} 8. Qb3 {, but after} Be6 $1 {there may not be a better move than to go back with} 9. Qd1 {.}) 8... Bf6 {This must be critical, and White has no intention of backing down and moving the rook.} 9. g4 $1 Bxh4 10. gxf5 {And so Black has won the exchange, but their bishop is attacked, White also threatens e2-e4 and it's not hard to see the black light squares becoming rather vulnerable. All in all, White has promising compensation.} Bf6 11. e4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 {Suddenly e4-e5 is imminent, as well as various methods to increase the pressure on the light squares, such as Qb3 or Qd3.} gxf5 $6 ({This line subsequently received a test in Sviridov-Khusenkhojaev, Pavlodar 2023, where Black lashed out:} 12... e5 $6 13. fxe6 fxe6 14. Rb1 $1 {White wants to probe on the light squares - right across the board.} O-O 15. hxg6 e5 $5 {And here there were various sensible and strong moves, including the game's} 16. d5 {and 16.Bh6!? Bg7 17.gxh7+ Kh8 18.Bxg7 Kxg7 19.h8=Q+ This deflection avoids 19.d5 Qf6! and leaves Black in some trouble with either d4-d5 or Nxe5 up next.}) 13. e5 Bxe5 14. dxe5 Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 {The king was but en route to c2 and with two unopposed bishops against the rook and pawns, White was clearly better in Giri-Svidler, Internet (blitz) 2020.} *

