1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... O-O $6 {A rather risky choice, castling into it.} 7. hxg6 hxg6 ({By no means forced, but it's hard not to want to open the h-file, especially when} 7... fxg6 $6 8. e4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {would leave Black vulnerable to Ng5 and down the a2-g8 diagonal.}) 8. Qa4 $1 (8. e4 Nxc3 9. dxc3 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 {should be a pleasant edge, but it's very hard to resist the temptation to swing the queen over to h4.}) 8... e5 $6 9. Nxd5 {Dragging the black queen away to get the white queen across to h4 after all.} Qxd5 10. Qh4 Re8 11. d3 Be6 $5 ({This threatened} 11... Z0 12. Qh7+ Kf8 13. Bh6 {to leave White clearly better in Speelman-Nadig, Gibraltar 2010 ( 11.e4!? then -- 12.d4 is also pretty tempting and dangerous). Here Black's best defence would be to offer the king some protection for if it is flushed out to e7.}) 12. g3 $1 {Calm does it. The black king isn't going anywhere, so White simply intends Bg2 and Kf1, with full control and a free attack, and only then will we consider whether to go in for Bh6 or first a Ng5-e4 manoeuvre.} *

