1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... c5 7. h6 $1 Bf6 ({Black's last would be a decent move but for this awkward prod. Now} 7... Bf8 $6 8. d4 {would quickly open the position to White's advantage, but going forwards will leave the bishop exposed.}) 8. e4 $1 {With a double threat.} Nxc3 9. dxc3 $1 ({Now} 9. bxc3 Nc6 {wouldn't be so clear, but, of course, that isn't White's only recapture.}) 9... Qc7 {Black kept the queens on so in Theodorou-Costello, Charlotte 2022, but doing so didn't have to interfere with White's standard plans in the resulting structure.} 10. Be3 {Eyeing c5 to disrupt Black's development, while also intending a strong regrouping in Nd2 followed by Nc4 and/or f2-f4.} Bg4 11. Bb5+ Bd7 $1 {Developing with tempo. Now White might even look to follow up with -- Qd5 if allowed.} 12. a4 $1 {White enjoys a very pleasant edge. An exchange on b5 would only serve to increase his queenside play, Qd5 is still an issue and the bishop can easily skip back to c4 or e2 if attacked.} *

