1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... gxh5 $6 {A capture to welcome, not worry about.} 7. Rxh5 Nxc3 $6 ({Recapturing with tempo. Now} 7... Nf6 8. Rh4 {would leave the rook well placed for any attack, as well as to help White's central pawn expansion.}) 8. bxc3 c6 9. Qb3 Z0 ({This pressed on b7 as well as f7, leaving White ready to go Ne5 or Ng5, as well as just roll the pawns and unsurprisingly clearly better in Cramling-Merkesvik, Stockholm 2014, where Black, not uniquely for someone surprised by 5.h4, suffered an extremely fast defeat. The brutal finish was} 9... h6 10. Ne5 $5 e6 $6 11. Ba3 $1 {Preventing castling while allowing White to consider Nc4 ideas.} Qa5 12. d4 Nd7 $4 13. Nxf7 $1 {1-0. The twin threats of Rxa5 and mate on e6 decide.}) *

