1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... f5 $6 {Another unexpected pawn move which White should welcome.} 7. Qb3 {) White wastes no time pressing on the weakened a2-g8 diagonal and will likely follow up with d2-d4 or even e2-e4.} c6 8. d4 Qd6 9. Bd2 $1 Z0 ({A small but strong move. White covers the b4-square and so prepares} 9... Z0 10. e4 fxe4 11. Nxe4 {, as well as O-O-O, which all added up to an early initiative and clear advantage in Ftacnik-Kouatly, Thessaloniki Olympiad 1984.}) *

