1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nxc3 ({One of two especially important and common moves here, the other being rapid development with} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. bxc3 e5 ({White enjoys ideas of h5-h6 in conjunction with e2-e4, as well as of just d2-d4 and may even consider a timely Qb3, not least in the event of something like} 7... Bf5 $6 8. Qb3 {.}) 8. e4 {Ensuring that the e4-square will remain White's while preparing to prevent castling with Ba3, with Bc4 and Rb1 also likely to be useful moves.} Nc6 9. Ba3 Bf8 ({Now} 9... Bg4 $6 10. Qb3 {once left a young Praggnanandhaa in some trouble and in any case the queen may well be heading for b3.}) 10. Bxf8 {Ensuring that Black won't be castling kingside.} Rxf8 11. Rb1 {This pressed against b7 and left White all set to expand with d2-d4, either before or after Qa4, as Black found himself somewhat on the back foot in Wei Yi-Huang Renjie, Chinese League 2023.} *

