1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nxc3 ({One of two especially important and common moves here, the other being rapid development with} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. bxc3 O-O ({White enjoys ideas of h5-h6 in conjunction with e2-e4, as well as of just d2-d4 and may even consider a timely Qb3, not least in the event of something like} 7... Bf5 $6 8. Qb3 {.}) 8. hxg6 {The standard drill against Black's brave decision to castle, although there's a small twist ahead.} hxg6 9. Ba3 $5 ({As} 9. Qa4 e5 {wouldn't lead anywhere, White first pins the pawn on e7, in the process cutting out ...c5 ideas, and so intends Qa4-h4 after all.}) 9... Re8 $1 10. e4 $1 ({A somewhat stronger concept than} 10. Qa4 e5 {. White plays to generate some pressure against f7 with Bc4 and may still take over the centre with d2-d4 and perhaps even e4-e5 if allowed. One other idea which may be useful is that of keeping the bishop on a3 involved with Bc5-e3.}) 10... Nd7 $6 {This was seen in Carlsen-Artemiev, Chessable Masters (rapid) 2020, no less where White should have been direct.} 11. Ng5 $1 Nb6 ({Threatening Qf3 as well as Qg4, and} 11... Nf6 $2 12. Bc4 {wouldn't be at all easy for Black to deal with.}) 12. f4 $5 Z0 ({Useful preparation for Qf3 or} 12... f6 13. Nf3 {. With good central control and a free attack, White stands clearly better.}) *

