1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nxc3 ({One of two especially important and common moves here, the other being rapid development with} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. bxc3 c5 ({White enjoys ideas of h5-h6 in conjunction with e2-e4, as well as of just d2-d4 and may even consider a timely Qb3, not least in the event of something like} 7... Bf5 $6 8. Qb3 {.}) {Black has tended to fight for the centre in this way.} 8. Qa4+ $5 ({This check has recently been seen causing Black some problems, since all of the ways to block it have their downsides. This is though a rare position in this second part of the Modern Reti repertoire where you actually have a choice, as} 8. e3 {would take play back into the realm of Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967340/#/8/w].}) 8... Nc6 $6 {This has also been quite common, but it allows White to seize an early initiative.} 9. Ba3 $1 Qb6 $6 ({Not for the first time, the pawn on c5 proves more of a target than a strength. If} 9... Bd7 {White can calmly annex it with} 10. Bxc5 {.}) 10. Ng5 $1 {A powerful leap, threatening Qc4, as well as Ne4. There's just no good way for Black to avoid losing a pawn.} O-O $6 11. hxg6 {Naturally White is delighted to open the h-file so.} hxg6 12. Qc4 $1 ({This is more clear-cut than the immediate} 12. Rh8+ $6 Bxh8 13. Qh4 Kg7 {. White keeps that idea and Qh4 in general in reserve while threatening Bxc5.}) 12... Ne5 $6 13. Rh8+ $1 {Now it works, and how!} Bxh8 14. Qh4 Kg7 {A second fairly essential move.} 15. Bxc5 $1 Qb2 ({Exploiting the fork that would be} 15... Qxc5 16. Qh7+ Kf6 17. Ne4+ {to bring the bishop into the attack.}) 16. Rd1 Z0 ({White is a rook down, but in view of the threats of Bxe7 and Bd4 enjoys a decisive attack. For example:} 16... Bg4 17. Bd4 Bh5 18. Bxe5+ $1 {It's now just an exchange and there's still nothing even coming close to resembling a satisfactory defence.} f6 19. g4 fxe5 20. gxh5 {The light-squared bishop will join the fray after e2-e3 or even via g2 or h3 and either h5-h6+ or hxg6 will quickly clean Black up.}) *

