1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nxc3 ({One of two especially important and common moves here, the other being rapid development with} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. bxc3 c5 ({White enjoys ideas of h5-h6 in conjunction with e2-e4, as well as of just d2-d4 and may even consider a timely Qb3, not least in the event of something like} 7... Bf5 $6 8. Qb3 {.}) {Black has tended to fight for the centre so.} 8. Qa4+ $5 ({This check has recently been seen causing Black some problems, since all of the ways to block it have their downsides. This is though a rare position in this second part of the Modern Reti repertoire where you actually have a choice, as} 8. e3 {would take play back into the realm of Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967340/#/8/w].}) 8... Nd7 9. e4 {Logical expansion with Black struggling to untangle his queenside unless he wants to brave castling.} Qc7 10. h6 $1 {It's also possible to retain the tension, but sooner or later White should make this fairly strong cramping advance, claiming a long-term advantage on the kingside ahead of expanding in the centre.} Bf6 11. Rb1 {Played not just to pressure b7, but especially to prepare d2-d4 which will no longer walk into a devastating ...Qc3+.} O-O 12. d4 cxd4 13. cxd4 {Threatening to entomb Black's dark-squared bishop with e4-e5.} e5 14. d5 {White enjoyed control and a fairly pleasant edge in Niemann-Madaminov, Astana 2023. It may be possible to make inroads via Ba3 and Qb4, but there's also the simple and strong approach that would be Be3, Be2 and Nd2-c4, while the queen will travel across to c4 or c2, pinning in the event of any ...Nc5.} *

