1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nxc3 ({One of two especially important and common moves here, the other being rapid development with} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. bxc3 c5 ({White enjoys ideas of h5-h6 in conjunction with e2-e4, as well as of just d2-d4 and may even consider a timely Qb3, not least in the event of something like} 7... Bf5 $6 8. Qb3 {.}) {Black has tended to fight for the centre so.} 8. Qa4+ $5 ({This check has recently been seen causing Black some problems, since all of the ways to block it have their downsides. This is though a rare position in this second part of the Modern Reti repertoire where you actually have a choice, as} 8. e3 {would take play back into the realm of Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967340/#/8/w].}) 8... Bd7 9. Qc4 ({Here White made a decent case for} 9. Qf4 $5 Nc6 10. e4 {in Wojtaszek-Mikhalevski, European Team Championship, Terme Catez 2021, and it's also possible to go after both c5 and f7 once more.}) 9... Qc7 10. Ng5 {Another thematic move, as suggested by David Cummings in his excellent Flank Openings column on ChessPublishing.} e6 11. Ne4 Na6 ({Keeping up the threats. Now White might even meet} 11... b6 {with} 12. h6 {, and if} Be5 13. d4 {, preparing to swap queens having made some definite long-term gains.}) 12. Rb1 $1 Z0 ({With the knight defending the queen on c7, an h5-h6 and d2-d4 plan is no longer so good, but this strong move both prevents} 12... b5 {(} 13. Rxb5 $1 {) and threatens Rxb7. Cummings ended his analysis here and so shall we. Throw Ba3 into the mix and it should be clear that White has every chance of emerging in front from the early skirmishes.}) *

