1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 $1 {Consistent with our approach in Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967336/#/7/w] ( 2...c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.bxc3 g6 7.h4 ), and a very well-established choice these days at this point, with even Magnus having appeared on the white side. The idea is simple: to exert early kingside pressure with h4-h5. Instead, 5.d4 would just be a standard Grunfeld, but if you like to explore complex sidelines away from the beaten track, you may wish to look into 5.Qb3 Nb6 and only then 6.h4!? .} Bg7 {Black's most common response, retaining the tension, although a great many moves have actually been tried here - testament to the strength as well as one-time surprise factor of 5.h4.} 6. h5 ({Needless to say, we press ahead when allowed, introducing ideas of h5-h6 and e2-e4, as well as hxg6, although it should be noted that the calm} 6. e4 $5 Nxc3 7. dxc3 {is also quite a good option.}) 6... Nxc3 ({One of two especially important and common moves here, the other being rapid development with} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. bxc3 c5 ({White enjoys ideas of h5-h6 in conjunction with e2-e4, as well as of just d2-d4 and may even consider a timely Qb3, not least in the event of something like} 7... Bf5 $6 8. Qb3 {.}) {Black has tended to fight for the centre so.} 8. Qa4+ $5 ({This check has recently been seen causing Black some problems, since all of the ways to block it have their downsides. This is though a rare position in this second part of the Modern Reti repertoire where you actually have a choice, as} 8. e3 {would take play back into the realm of Chapter 2a1 [/variation/35967340/#/8/w].}) 8... Qd7 {Black's most popular and probably best defence.} 9. Qc4 {Levon Aronian and Peter Wells have been happy to go to h4 with the queen, but we're happy with the usual square, pressing against c5 while also keeping an eye on f7.} b6 10. Ng5 {The standard follow-up, forcing Black to weaken to defend f7, that is unless they prefer to castle into a huge attack.} e6 11. Qh4 $1 {The queen's business done on c4, she swings across to the kingside and now White has ideas of not just Ne4, but also hxg6 and a certain sacrifice.} Qe7 {Engine-approved, if also quite a risky choice, not least from a practical perspective.} 12. hxg6 $1 {The prelude to a dangerous queen sacrifice.} hxg6 13. Qxh8+ Bxh8 14. Rxh8+ Kd7 15. d4 $1 {Overprotecting the knight and thereby threatening Rh7. White also has ideas of Ne4 and Bg5, and overall excellent compensation. We'll return to this position in Rallabandi-Rawlings [/variation/35967901/#/15/w], English Correspondence Championship Final 2021.} *

