1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 $1 {)} ({Perhaps not the obvious choice for a Grunfeld player, if a move recommended on Peter Svidler's Grunfeld course. Black still hopes for} 4. d4 d5 {and isn't about to go in for a King's Indian in the event of 4.e4.}) 4... c6 ({Preparing d2-d4 now that ...d5 has been ruled out, while also threatening e4-e5. Here play will most often go} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {or}) (4... d6 5. d4 O-O {, taking play into the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/35967649/#/5/w]. There is though one important independent line which we will now cover.}) 5. e5 $5 ({Here you actually have quite a pleasant choice, since} 5. d4 {is likely to lead after} O-O {( 5...d5?! 6.e5 is just very nice for White, and if 6...Ne4 7.Bd3 ) to a position we'll consider via a 4...O-O 5.e4 c6 move order [/variation/35967649/#/5/b].}) 5... Ng4 {Otherwise White would simply expand with d2-d4 and Bf4, with a pleasant edge.} 6. d4 c5 $1 ({White still hopes to take full control of the position with} 6... Z0 7. h3 Nh6 8. Bf4 {, so Black pretty much must react.}) 7. dxc5 $1 {Simple chess. White is happy to give up the pawn on e5 for easy development and now Be2 and O-O may quickly follow, as well as Bf4.} Nxe5 8. Be2 {The dark-squared bishop will come to e3 or f4, White can exchange knights on e5 if we wish and simply enjoys a pleasant edge because as much as in spite of the doubled c-pawns. White has complete control of d5 and pressure down the d-file, the e-file too quite possibly after O-O and Re1, and Black's only real attempt to disrupt things isn't particularly impressive.} Qa5 $6 9. O-O $1 {Ideas of Be3, and if ...Ng4; Bd4, as well as Nd5 loom.} Qxc5 $6 10. Nd5 $1 {White's lead in development and initiative are both pretty significant (we're at '+2' in engine speak). As well as the ideas of Be3 then Nd4 and Nxe5 Bxe5; Bh6, White would especially like to go Bf4 then b2-b4 as the c7-square becomes a major source of concern for Black.} *

