1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 $1 ({Perhaps not the obvious choice for a Grunfeld player, if a move recommended on Peter Svidler's Grunfeld course. Black still hopes for} 4. d4 d5 {and isn't about to go in for a King's Indian in the event of 4.e4.}) 4... e5 $5 ({Preparing d2-d4 now that ...d5 has been ruled out, while also threatening e4-e5. Here play will most often go} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {or}) (4... d6 5. d4 O-O {, taking play into the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/35967649/#/5/w]. There is though one important independent line which we will now cover.}) {As recommended on the largely excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: Peter Svidler's Grunfeld' course (Part Two).} 5. Nxe5 {The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating. White will now drop the knight back to f3 if attacked and would also like to expand with d2-d4.} ({Should you really not want to go a pawn up and would prefer to attack, then} 5. d4 $5 exd4 6. Nxd4 {can be considered, which is likely to lead to either a pleasant Maroczy Bind style advantage or after the critical} O-O 7. Be3 c6 $1 {to chaos after} 8. e5 $1 Ne8 9. h4 {.}) 5... Nxe4 {Regaining the pawn without delay, but White should be quite happy to see this since he now obtains easy development.} 6. Nxe4 {Acceptance is again critical. Now d2-d4 will come with tempo.} Bxe5 7. d4 Bg7 8. Bg5 $1 {A further precise move, forcing Black to weaken their kingside before dropping the bishop back to e3.} f6 9. Be3 {White's knight will redeploy to c3, controlling the d5-square, and it may even be possible to go Qd2 and O-O-O, looking to launch an early assault against Black's weakened kingside with h2-h4-h5.} O-O 10. Nc3 $1 {Dropping the knight back before it has to retreat, to prevent such moves as ...d5 from arriving with tempo.} Nc6 $6 11. h4 $5 ({Both} 11. d5 {and}) (11. Qd2 {are also good moves, but it's quite possible to begin the kingside assault without delay. Now h4-h5 will exploit the hook on g6, while Qd2 then O-O-O are still on the way.}) 11... d6 12. h5 {Even Qf3 in conjunction with Bd3 could now be a strong possibility, hence Black's next move.} f5 13. g3 $1 ({Calmly preventing ...f4, and} 13. Qd2 $5 {is also a good option if you really want to be aggressive.}) 13... Re8 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. Be2 Z0 ({Having opened the h-file towards Black's king, White continued to play against ...f4 ideas in Laan-Leijen, correspondence 2017. With Qd2 and O-O-O on the way, White is clearly better and in the game Black couldn't find anything better than the rather desperate} 15... f4 $6 16. gxf4 Bf5 {, when} 17. d5 Nb4 18. Rc1 {was simple and strong.}) *

