1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 $1 ({Perhaps not the obvious choice for a Grunfeld player, if a move recommended on Peter Svidler's Grunfeld course. Black still hopes for} 4. d4 d5 {and isn't about to go in for a King's Indian in the event of 4.e4.}) 4... e5 $5 ({Preparing d2-d4 now that ...d5 has been ruled out, while also threatening e4-e5. Here play will most often go} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {or}) (4... d6 5. d4 O-O {, taking play into the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/35967649/#/5/w]. There is though one important independent line which we will now cover.}) {As recommended on the largely excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: Peter Svidler's Grunfeld' course (Part Two).} 5. Nxe5 {The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating. White will now drop the knight back to f3 if attacked and would also like to expand with d2-d4.} ({Should you really not want to go a pawn up and would prefer to attack, then} 5. d4 $5 exd4 6. Nxd4 {can be considered, which is likely to lead to either a pleasant Maroczy Bind style advantage or after the critical} O-O 7. Be3 c6 $1 {to chaos after} 8. e5 $1 Ne8 9. h4 {.}) 5... Qe7 {This too will regain the pawn, but the queen isn't brilliantly placed and this is another line White should be pretty happy to see.} 6. d4 {Thematic expansion ahead of dropping the knight back to f3.} d6 7. Nf3 Nxe4 8. Nd5 $1 {An effective leap. White wants to keep pieces on, with the plan being Bd3, O-O and quick pressure down the e-file if suitable.} Qd8 9. Bd3 O-O $5 ({Now} 9... Nf6 $6 10. Nxf6+ {(or even 10.Qe2+ ) 10...Bxf6 11.Bh6 would mess up Black's development, so opponents are likely to castle here and offer a temporary piece sacrifice.}) 10. Bxe4 {White has more often castled here, but there's no good reason not to take the piece and only then castle.} Re8 11. O-O $1 Rxe4 12. Bg5 $1 ({Here} 12. Re1 {sufficed for an edge in Eisenbeiser-Kessler, Austrian League 2014, but White can do better than that.}) {Forcing a weakness after all, as Black surely doesn't want to lose control of the f6-square.} 12... f6 13. Qd3 {Completing development with tempo.} Bf5 14. Bd2 {Wisely retaining the bishop and leaving the e3-square free for the knight.} Nc6 15. Qb3 {White threatens to take on b7 and enjoys a pleasant edge, with the queen also well placed from the perspective of the a2-g8 diagonal. Ne3 will follow, either mashing up Black's pawns on the kingside or leaving White in full control after Bc3.} *

