1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 $1 ({Perhaps not the obvious choice for a Grunfeld player, if a move recommended on Peter Svidler's Grunfeld course. Black still hopes for} 4. d4 d5 {and isn't about to go in for a King's Indian in the event of 4.e4.}) 4... e5 $5 ({Preparing d2-d4 now that ...d5 has been ruled out, while also threatening e4-e5. Here play will most often go} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {or}) (4... d6 5. d4 O-O {, taking play into the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/35967649/#/5/w]. There is though one important independent line which we will now cover.}) {As recommended on the largely excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: Peter Svidler's Grunfeld' course (Part Two).} 5. Nxe5 {The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating. White will now drop the knight back to f3 if attacked and would also like to expand with d2-d4.} ({Should you really not want to go a pawn up and would prefer to attack, then} 5. d4 $5 exd4 6. Nxd4 {can be considered, which is likely to lead to either a pleasant Maroczy Bind style advantage or after the critical} O-O 7. Be3 c6 $1 {to chaos after} 8. e5 $1 Ne8 9. h4 {.}) 5... O-O $5 {Black's main try these days, playing for compensation down the e-file.} 6. Nf3 $1 {A useful retreat, as White threatens e4-e5, as well as Be2 and d2-d4.} Nxe4 $2 7. Nxe4 Re8 8. d3 {Calmly holding on to the piece for now while introducing the possibility of a rapid and pretty disruptive Bg5.} f5 9. Bg5 $1 Bf6 10. Be2 {Blocking the e-file and so threatening to move the knight.} fxe4 11. dxe4 Z0 ({As} 11... Bxg5 {will be met by} 12. Qd5+ {White isn't losing a piece and is just doing pretty well, with the safer king, a handy lead in development and ideas of both O-O and h2-h4.}) *

