{A fine spot indeed for the knight and with such moves as Qd2, Rac1 and Bf4 on the way, it's hard to find too much compensation for Black.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 $1 ({Perhaps not the obvious choice for a Grunfeld player, if a move recommended on Peter Svidler's Grunfeld course. Black still hopes for} 4. d4 d5 {and isn't about to go in for a King's Indian in the event of 4.e4.}) 4... e5 $5 ({Preparing d2-d4 now that ...d5 has been ruled out, while also threatening e4-e5. Here play will most often go} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {or}) (4... d6 5. d4 O-O {, taking play into the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/35967649/#/5/w]. There is though one important independent line which we will now cover.}) {As recommended on the largely excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: Peter Svidler's Grunfeld' course (Part Two).} 5. Nxe5 {The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating. White will now drop the knight back to f3 if attacked and would also like to expand with d2-d4.} ({Should you really not want to go a pawn up and would prefer to attack, then} 5. d4 $5 exd4 6. Nxd4 {can be considered, which is likely to lead to either a pleasant Maroczy Bind style advantage or after the critical} O-O 7. Be3 c6 $1 {to chaos after} 8. e5 $1 Ne8 9. h4 {.}) 5... O-O $5 {Black's main try these days, playing for compensation down the e-file.} 6. Nf3 $1 {A useful retreat, as White threatens e4-e5, as well as Be2 and d2-d4.} Re8 {Black should press against e4 so.} 7. d3 {Holding on to the pawn in this way must be critical, effectively asking Black to prove their compensation.} ({The alternative is} 7. Bd3 $5 {, intending} Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Bxc3 9. dxc3 Rxe4+ 10. Be3 {, when White's game is slightly the easier to play with the unopposed dark-squared bishop.}) 7... d5 $1 {Black pretty much must break open the centre before White goes Be2, O-O and is just a clear pawn to the good.} 8. cxd5 {Dealing with the threat to e4 in simple fashion. White would now quite like just to go Be2 and O-O.} Nxd5 9. Bd2 ({Shoring up c3 makes Black's life harder than} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Be2 Qd6 11. O-O c5 $1 {would do, when the central clamp on the d4-square provides reasonable compensation.}) 9... c5 10. Be2 Nb4 ({Naturally White takes a step towards evacuating the king to the kingside, and now Black must move his knight. Going back to c7 would appear logical, but then} 10... Nc7 11. Be3 {would hit c5 and after} Ne6 {as well as} 12. O-O {, White might even consider 12.h4!? .}) 11. Bg5 $1 {White begins to untangle their position with tempo.} Qd6 12. a3 {Another tempo gain and, of course, Black can't have both the knights on c6.} N4a6 13. O-O Nc6 14. Nb5 $5 ({Here} 14. Rc1 {was pretty sensible in L.Van Foreest-Papadiamandis, Plovdiv 2021, but White might prefer to conquer an inviting square.}) *

