ovides reasonable compensation.}) 9... Qd6 $5 10. Rc1 c5 ({Ever a good move in these structures, preparing potential pressure against a pawn on c5, while intending} 10... Z0 11. Be2 {when} Nf4 $2 {would run into} 12. Nb5 {.}) 11. Be2 ({Calm does it, as White gets ready to castle, although we also can't help wondering about} 11. h4 $5 {here, and if} h5 12. Ng5 {.}) 11... Nf4 {The point of Black's play, but White need not panic.} 12. O-O $1 Nxe2+ $5 ({Now} 12... Nxd3 $2 13. Be3 {would be very good for White, since} c4 14. Nb5 {leaves Black's position on the brink of collapse.}) 13. Qxe2 b6 14. b4 $1 Ba6 ({White plays not only to weaken c5, but for tricks on c7 (} 14... cxb4 $2 15. Nb5 {).}) 15. b5 {The other point behind White's last, closing a key diagonal while making a handy gain of space.} Bb7 16. Be3 {With ...Nc6-d4 off the table and ideas of both d3-d4, and if ...cxd4; Rfd1, and Nd2-c4 in conjunction with a2-a4, we'd definitely prefer to take White, even if Black's bishop-pair must offer them a bit of compensation for the pawn.} *

