1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 $1 ({Perhaps not the obvious choice for a Grunfeld player, if a move recommended on Peter Svidler's Grunfeld course. Black still hopes for} 4. d4 d5 {and isn't about to go in for a King's Indian in the event of 4.e4.}) 4... e5 $5 ({Preparing d2-d4 now that ...d5 has been ruled out, while also threatening e4-e5. Here play will most often go} 4... O-O 5. d4 d6 {or}) (4... d6 5. d4 O-O {, taking play into the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/35967649/#/5/w]. There is though one important independent line which we will now cover.}) {As recommended on the largely excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: Peter Svidler's Grunfeld' course (Part Two).} 5. Nxe5 {The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating. White will now drop the knight back to f3 if attacked and would also like to expand with d2-d4.} ({Should you really not want to go a pawn up and would prefer to attack, then} 5. d4 $5 exd4 6. Nxd4 {can be considered, which is likely to lead to either a pleasant Maroczy Bind style advantage or after the critical} O-O 7. Be3 c6 $1 {to chaos after} 8. e5 $1 Ne8 9. h4 {.}) 5... O-O $5 {Black's main try these days, playing for compensation down the e-file.} 6. Nf3 $1 {A useful retreat, as White threatens e4-e5, as well as Be2 and d2-d4.} Re8 {Black should press against e4 so.} 7. d3 {Holding on to the pawn in this way must be critical, effectively asking Black to prove their compensation.} ({The alternative is} 7. Bd3 $5 {, intending} Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Bxc3 9. dxc3 Rxe4+ 10. Be3 {, when White's game is slightly the easier to play with the unopposed dark-squared bishop.}) 7... d5 $1 {Black pretty much must break open the centre before White goes Be2, O-O and is just a clear pawn to the good.} 8. cxd5 {Dealing with the threat to e4 in simple fashion. White would now quite like just to go Be2 and O-O.} Nxd5 9. Bd2 ({Shoring up c3 makes Black's life harder than} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Be2 Qd6 11. O-O c5 $1 {would do, when the central clamp on the d4-square provides reasonable compensation.}) 9... Bg4 {By far Black's main move, playing for control of d4, if by no means forced.} 10. Be2 {)} Bxf3 $1 ({Calmly breaking the pin. Now} 10... Nb4 11. Be3 {would let White retain a fair degree of control.}) 11. gxf3 $1 ({Slightly ugly, although you might also think of it as a dynamic recapture. In any case, if we want to set Black any problems, we must avoid} 11. Bxf3 Nb4 {.}) 11... Nb4 12. Be3 {Calmly supporting the extra pawn. White's king should be fairly safe in the centre and we will now play to combine maintaining control with kingside expansion. Yes, Harry does yet have a role to play!} N8c6 13. h4 $5 {Beginning the aforementioned expansion and intending h4-h5 if allowed.} ({Another decent idea here is} 13. a3 Na6 14. Nb5 $5 {, offering the pawn on b2 to activate White's forces, as in Indjic-Djukic, Ohrid 2023.}) 13... Nd4 14. Rc1 {It's rather important to keep c2 covered.} Qd7 $5 {This might be a better try, although thanks to the inclusion of h2-h4 there clearly aren't going to be any ...Qh3 ideas to worry about.} 15. a3 {Kicking the knight back ahead of expansion on the kingside with h4-h5 and f3-f4, while even b2-b4 may be quite a useful advance.} Na6 ({Not such a strange square when you consider that after} 15... Nbc6 16. h5 {what do Black's nice looking pieces actually achieve? White can always recapture with the king on e2.}) 16. b4 $1 {Fighting to keep the knight sidelined.} c6 17. f4 {White was set to press with h4-h5 and was definitely for choice in Ludwig-Gomila Marti, correspondence 2019. It may then be possibly to expand further with e4-e5 and/or activate the final minor piece with Bg4.} Z0 ({For example:} 17... Nc7 18. h5 a5 {As recommended by Svidler.} 19. e5 {A natural gain of space intending Bg4, although the engines also quite like 19.bxa5!? Rxa5 20.a4 .} Nxe2 20. Qxe2 axb4 21. axb4 Ra3 {Peter Svidler writes: 'And we have enough pesky counterthreats to make White's extra pawn feel very far from decisive.' That may well be true, but we certainly wouldn't be at all unhappy as White.} 22. Ne4 {Threatening h5-h6, as well as a timely Nc5.} Nd5 23. Kf1 {The position still isn't too clear, but at least White is a pawn up and has potential threats on the kingside (not least} Nxb4 24. h6 {). Both Rd1 and Kg2 may well prove useful, while extensive analysis with the engines demonstrated that a plan of Rh4 (potentially preparing to double as well as offering indirect cover to b4) and Ng3 can often be a decent one. Tests are required, as they say!}) *

