ovides reasonable compensation.}) 9... Bg4 {By far Black's main move, playing for control of d4, if by no means forced.} 10. Be2 Bxf3 $1 ({Calmly breaking the pin and now} 10... Nb4 11. Be3 {would retain a fair degree of control for White.}) 11. gxf3 $1 ({Slightly ugly, although you might also think of it as a dynamic recapture. In any case, if we want to set Black any problems, we must avoid} 11. Bxf3 Nb4 {.}) 11... Nb4 12. Be3 {Calmly supporting the extra pawn. White's king should be fairly safe in the centre and we will now play to combine maintaining control with kingside expansion. Yes, Harry does yet have a role to play!} N8c6 13. h4 $5 ({Beginning the aforementioned expansion and intending h4-h5 if allowed. Another decent idea here is} 13. a3 Na6 14. Nb5 $5 {, offering the pawn on b2 to activate White's forces, as in Indjic-Djukic, Ohrid 2023.}) 13... Nd4 14. Rc1 {It's rather important to keep c2 covered.} Qd6 15. a3 {)} Na6 ({Kicking the knight back and now} 15... Nbc6 16. f4 {would leave White with sufficiently strong control of the central situation.}) 16. f4 {Now e4-e5 is high on the agenda, as well as h4-h5 and even b2-b4 might be quite a useful advance.} Rad8 17. e5 $1 ({Matters weren't completely clear after} 17. b4 c5 $1 18. e5 Qe7 {and Black went on to pull off an upset in Niemann-Woodward, World Junior Championship, Mexico City 2023, so here White should likely be more aggressive.}) ({Forcing the pace while preparing to bring the knight to e4. There's also} 17. h5 $5 Nc5 {when we suspect that White is better after both} 18. Nb5 {and 18.h6 , but the resulting sacrificial play from Black does leave the position pretty murky and not so easy to handle.}) 17... Qb6 18. Ne4 $5 {Returning the pawn to activate the white army. Thanks to White's control of c5, b2-b4 is now a definite threat and h4-h5 is also imminent.} ({If, though, you're happy to gradually consolidate then} 18. Na4 Qe6 19. Bg4 $1 {should also be a little better for White, and if 18...f5 19.Be2 .}) 18... Qxb2 19. h5 {Now h5-h6 is something of a problem for Black, since either his bishop must become entombed in the corner or they have to allow Nf6+. White is also set to continue the activation policy with Bg4 and O-O, and like the engines, we quite like White's chances in no small part due to control of the c-file and that most strong central bridgehead supplied by the well supported pawn on e5 and knight just behind it.} *

