{White's basic idea is simple: to overprotect e4 and so claim that 6...e5 7.d5 is a superior version of the Petrosian variation 6.Be2 e5 7.d5. In practice Black's two most common moves by far have been 6...e5 and 6...Nbd7 , and here we'll especially focus on: 5a: 6...c5 5b: 6...e5 5c: 6...Bg4 . Note that 6...Nbd7 almost always transposes into Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] after 7.O-O e5 8.d5 . Likewise, 6...Na6 and 6...c6 tend to transpose there after 7.O-O e5 .} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 ({Having seen Black's various attempts to play a Grunfeld, we now come on to a defence popular at all levels of chess against 1.d4, 1.c4 and 1.Nf3, the King's Indian. We should also mention that here} 4... c5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 {would once again take play back into the Maroczy Bind world of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967414/#/7/w].}) ({Invariably played, although as White risks overextension after} 4... O-O 5. e5 {, Black can also delay ...d6 by a move.}) 5. d4 O-O ({Invariably played, in part because the immediate} 5... e5 $2 {would just drop a pawn to} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Nxe5 {.}) ({Other moves are very likely to transpose once Black castles: for example,} 5... Nbd7 6. Bd3 e5 7. d5 {when} O-O 8. O-O {would be an immediate transposition to Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] and after 7...Nc5 8.Bc2 a5 9.O-O Black has almost always gone 9...O-O , transposing after all.}) ({Finally, we should just mention that} 5... Bg4 {can be met by either} 6. Be3 {or 6.Be2 when White may well find himself a tempo up on Chapter 5c [/variation/35967697/#/7/w]!}) 6. Bd3 $5 ({Many King's Indian players aren't even aware that this move exists and} 6. Bd3 {has been about 50 times less common than the Classical main line,}) (6. Be2 {. The move has been around for a long time - it was even seen in a series of games between Cochrane and Bonnerjee at Calcutta in 1855 - but it only really became popular during the Covid era, in part due to Daniil Dubov's defeat of Magnus Carlsen. Since then Carlsen and Nakamura have been seen on the white side, as has the great hope of Belgian chess, Daniel Dardha.}) 6... Z0 *

