1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 O-O ({Having seen Black's various attempts to play a Grunfeld, we now come on to a defence popular at all levels of chess against 1.d4, 1.c4 and 1.Nf3, the King's Indian. We should also mention that here} 4... c5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 {would once again take play back into the Maroczy Bind world of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967414/#/7/w].}) 5. d4 c6 $6 ({Completing the perfect pawn centre and now Black really should, and almost always does, transpose to the main line with} 5... d6 {.}) 6. Bd3 {This is a particularly good square for the light-squared bishop if Black now goes in for a misguided double-advance of the d-pawn.} d5 $6 7. e5 {Exploiting White's control of e4 to pretty much force the knight backwards.} Ne8 ({Best as} 7... Nfd7 $6 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. h4 $1 {just gives White a strong early initiative, in view of} h5 $6 10. e6 $1 {.}) 8. cxd5 {Fixing the central structure as White begins to deny Black counterplay.} cxd5 9. h3 $1 ({Restricting the prospects of the bishop on c8, although as fans of the Harry Attack, your authors would also be tempted even here to at least strongly consider} 9. h4 $5 {.}) 9... Nc6 10. O-O {A pretty safe spot for the king. Now White can look to complete development with Re1 and Bf4.} f6 $5 {The obvious break. Otherwise just how would Black free their position and fight against the bridgehead on e5?} 11. exf6 ({The simple approach, weakening Black's kingside, although} 11. Re1 $5 {also comes into the equation. In any case, Re1 is likely to be fairly high on White's agenda.}) 11... Nxf6 12. Be3 {A more secure spot for the bishop than f4 here. Enjoying good central control, White will next be able to improve the rooks to c1 and e1 as the position begins to take on several French Tarrasch connotations.} Nh5 13. Rc1 {Now Black must even watch out that White doesn't obtain too strong a central grip after Bb5, and avoid falling for a Nxd5 tactic.} Kh8 14. Re1 Z0 ({With} 14... e5 $2 {running into} 15. Bg5 {and both Bb5 and Na4 on their way, White was in control and clearly for choice in Vasquez Schroder-Pantsulaia, Mumbai 2019.}) *

