1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 ({Having seen Black's various attempts to play a Grunfeld, we now come on to a defence popular at all levels of chess against 1.d4, 1.c4 and 1.Nf3, the King's Indian. We should also mention that here} 4... c5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 {would once again take play back into the Maroczy Bind world of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967414/#/7/w].}) ({Invariably played, although as White risks overextension after} 4... O-O 5. e5 {, Black can also delay ...d6 by a move.}) 5. d4 {and after Nc5 Bc2} a5 {O-O Black has almost always gone O-O , transposing after all. Finally, we should just mention that Bg4 can be met by either} 6. Be3 {or 6.Be2 when White may well find himself a tempo up on Chapter 5c [/variation/35967697/#/7/w]! Bd3!? Many King's Indian players aren't even aware that this move exists and Bd3 has been about 50 times less common than the Classical main line, Be2 . The move has been around for a long time - it was even seen in a series of games between Cochrane and Bonnerjee at Calcutta in 1855 - but it only really became popular during the Covid era, in part due to Daniil Dubov's defeat of Magnus Carlsen. Since then Carlsen and Nakamura have been seen on the white side, as has the great hope of Belgian chess, Daniel Dardha. Nc6!? White's basic idea is simple: to overprotect e4 and so claim that 6...e5 7.d5 is a superior version of the Petrosian variation (6.Be2 e5 7.d5). In practice Black's two most common moves by far have been 6...e5 and 6...Nbd7 , and here we'll especially focus on: 5a: 6...c5 5b: 6...e5 5c: 6...Bg4 . Note that 6...Nbd7 almost always transposes into Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] after 7.O-O e5 8.d5 . Likewise, 6...Na6 and 6...c6 tend to transpose there after 7.O-O e5 . d5 Prodding the knight rather than allow Black to increase the pressure against d4 with} {As well as 6...Bg4 , Black has one other way of aiming for quick counterplay against d4.} O-O {Bg4 , and now 7...Ne5?! 8.Nxe5 dxe5 9.O-O followed by Be3 would just be a pleasant edge for White. Nb8?! This retreat is sometimes seen in analogous Pirc positions, but here White's centre is stronger (the pawn on c4), and Black may become rather cramped. h3! Ruling out ...Bg4 for good. White will castle, probably play Re1 and then find a good square for the dark-squared bishop: probably e3 or f4 if Black has played ...c6, g5 if Black instead goes for an ...e6 set-up. e6 O-O Re8 Bg5! Angling to provoke a small weakness while intending to take control of the position with Qd2 and Rfe1. h6 Be3 A safer retreat square thanks to the inclusion of h2-h3. Nbd7 Qd2 This attacked h6 and left White with a very pleasant edge in Dardha-Lorenzo de la Riva, Barcelona 2021. All of Rac1, Rfe1 and b2-b4 may quickly prove useful moves, and White can also consider switching the structure with dxe6, either obtaining Maroczy Bind control or a dangerous initiative if ...fxe6; e4-e5.} *

