1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 ({Having seen Black's various attempts to play a Grunfeld, we now come on to a defence popular at all levels of chess against 1.d4, 1.c4 and 1.Nf3, the King's Indian. We should also mention that here} 4... c5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 {would once again take play back into the Maroczy Bind world of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967414/#/7/w].}) ({Invariably played, although as White risks overextension after} 4... O-O 5. e5 {, Black can also delay ...d6 by a move.}) 5. d4 O-O ({Invariably played, in part because the immediate} 5... e5 $2 {would just drop a pawn to} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Nxe5 {.}) ({Other moves are very likely to transpose once Black castles: for example,} 5... Nbd7 6. Bd3 e5 7. d5 {when} O-O 8. O-O {would be an immediate transposition to Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] and after 7...Nc5 8.Bc2 a5 9.O-O Black has almost always gone 9...O-O , transposing after all.}) ({Finally, we should just mention that} 5... Bg4 {can be met by either} 6. Be3 {or 6.Be2 when White may well find himself a tempo up on Chapter 5c [/variation/35967697/#/7/w]!}) 6. Bd3 $5 ({Many King's Indian players aren't even aware that this move exists and} 6. Bd3 {has been about 50 times less common than the Classical main line,}) (6. Be2 {. The move has been around for a long time - it was even seen in a series of games between Cochrane and Bonnerjee at Calcutta in 1855 - but it only really became popular during the Covid era, in part due to Daniil Dubov's defeat of Magnus Carlsen. Since then Carlsen and Nakamura have been seen on the white side, as has the great hope of Belgian chess, Daniel Dardha.}) 6... Nc6 $5 {White's basic idea is simple: to overprotect e4 and so claim that 6...e5 7.d5 is a superior version of the Petrosian variation (6.Be2 e5 7.d5). In practice Black's two most common moves by far have been 6...e5 and 6...Nbd7 , and here we'll especially focus on: 5a: 6...c5 5b: 6...e5 5c: 6...Bg4 . Note that 6...Nbd7 almost always transposes into Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] after 7.O-O e5 8.d5 . Likewise, 6...Na6 and 6...c6 tend to transpose there after 7.O-O e5 .} {As well as 6...Bg4 , Black has one other way of aiming for quick counterplay against d4.} 7. d5 ({Prodding the knight rather than allow Black to increase the pressure against d4 with} 7. O-O Bg4 {, and now 7...Ne5?! 8.Nxe5 dxe5 9.O-O followed by Be3 would just be a pleasant edge for White.}) 7... Nb4 8. Bb1 $5 {)} ({A maximalist move, keeping e4 secure and intending to seize some useful space with a2-a3 followed by arranging b2-b4.} 8. Be2 {, as played by Jan Timman amongst others, also offers decent chances of an edge.}) 8... e6 9. a3 Na6 10. O-O Re8 ({Having kicked the knight back, White wisely evacuates the king from the e-file. Now h2-h3 and Re1 may follow, or if} 10... exd5 11. cxd5 {(11.exd5 is also an option)} Re8 12. Be3 $5 {(12.Re1 would be our mainline here), fighting against} Nc5 {with} 13. e5 $1 {.}) 11. h3 {Taking control of g4 is often a choice in such positions: it facilitates Be3 and also creates potential problems for the bishop on c8.} Nc5 12. Re1 a5 ({Securing e4 and so enabling White to meet} 12... exd5 {with} 13. cxd5 {.}) 13. Bc2 {Taking control of a4 for now as White hints at expansion with Rb1 and b2-b4.} Bd7 14. Bg5 $5 ({A slightly more ambitious choice than} 14. Be3 exd5 15. exd5 Nfe4 $1 {, which seemed fine for Black at this stage in Bernadskiy-Warmerdam, Bassano del Grappa 2020. The text pins and threatens to seize the initiative with e4-e5.}) 14... exd5 15. exd5 ({The calm choice, preparing Qd2. You may also wish to explore the somewhat more complex and unclear} 15. cxd5 $5 h6 16. Bf4 b5 17. e5 $5 {.}) 15... Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 Qf8 17. Qd2 {Black is very solid here and objectively must be OK, but we still wouldn't be too unhappy as White with either Re1 or Be3, Rc1 and a queenside advance set to follow. Ideally Nd4-b5 may also cause some problems.} *

