1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 ({Having seen Black's various attempts to play a Grunfeld, we now come on to a defence popular at all levels of chess against 1.d4, 1.c4 and 1.Nf3, the King's Indian. We should also mention that here} 4... c5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 {would once again take play back into the Maroczy Bind world of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967414/#/7/w].}) ({Invariably played, although as White risks overextension after} 4... O-O 5. e5 {, Black can also delay ...d6 by a move.}) 5. d4 O-O ({Invariably played, in part because the immediate} 5... e5 $2 {would just drop a pawn to} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Nxe5 {.}) ({Other moves are very likely to transpose once Black castles: for example,} 5... Nbd7 6. Bd3 e5 7. d5 {when} O-O 8. O-O {would be an immediate transposition to Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] and after 7...Nc5 8.Bc2 a5 9.O-O Black has almost always gone 9...O-O , transposing after all.}) ({Finally, we should just mention that} 5... Bg4 {can be met by either} 6. Be3 {or 6.Be2 when White may well find himself a tempo up on Chapter 5c [/variation/35967697/#/7/w]!}) 6. Bd3 $5 ({Many King's Indian players aren't even aware that this move exists and} 6. Bd3 {has been about 50 times less common than the Classical main line,}) (6. Be2 {. The move has been around for a long time - it was even seen in a series of games between Cochrane and Bonnerjee at Calcutta in 1855 - but it only really became popular during the Covid era, in part due to Daniil Dubov's defeat of Magnus Carlsen. Since then Carlsen and Nakamura have been seen on the white side, as has the great hope of Belgian chess, Daniel Dardha.}) 6... Nc6 $5 {White's basic idea is simple: to overprotect e4 and so claim that 6...e5 7.d5 is a superior version of the Petrosian variation (6.Be2 e5 7.d5). In practice Black's two most common moves by far have been 6...e5 and 6...Nbd7 , and here we'll especially focus on: 5a: 6...c5 5b: 6...e5 5c: 6...Bg4 . Note that 6...Nbd7 almost always transposes into Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] after 7.O-O e5 8.d5 . Likewise, 6...Na6 and 6...c6 tend to transpose there after 7.O-O e5 .} {As well as 6...Bg4 , Black has one other way of aiming for quick counterplay against d4.} 7. d5 ({Prodding the knight rather than allow Black to increase the pressure against d4 with} 7. O-O Bg4 {, and now 7...Ne5?! 8.Nxe5 dxe5 9.O-O followed by Be3 would just be a pleasant edge for White.}) 7... Nb4 8. Bb1 $5 ({A maximalist move, keeping e4 secure and intending to seize some useful space with a2-a3 followed by arranging b2-b4.} 8. Be2 {, as played by Jan Timman amongst others, also offers decent chances of an edge.}) 8... Bg4 $5 9. O-O {Calm does it. With Black's knight over on b4, h2-h3 can easily wait a move.} c6 10. h3 Bxf3 ({Now} 10... Bd7 $6 11. a3 Na6 12. Be3 {would quickly see White taking control, so Black should cede the bishop-pair.}) 11. Qxf3 {If allowed, White may now reset with Qe2, a2-a3, Bc2 and Bg5 or Be3.} Nd7 $1 12. Bd2 ({Beginning some counterplay on the dark squares. White now kicked the knight with} 12. a3 {in Carrera-Yanez Garcia, correspondence 2018, but didn't need to rush with that.}) {A modest move, but White is now all set to expand with a2-a3, Ba2 and b2-b4.} 12... Nc5 13. Qe2 ({Avoiding} 13. a3 $2 Nb3 $1 {, but now 13...-- 14.a3 may well be possible (does Black really want a knight on a1 even in return for the exchange?), and White may also look to maintain decent central control, as with Rd1 and Be3.}) *

