1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 ({Having seen Black's various attempts to play a Grunfeld, we now come on to a defence popular at all levels of chess against 1.d4, 1.c4 and 1.Nf3, the King's Indian. We should also mention that here} 4... c5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 {would once again take play back into the Maroczy Bind world of Chapter 2b [/variation/35967414/#/7/w].}) ({Invariably played, although as White risks overextension after} 4... O-O 5. e5 {, Black can also delay ...d6 by a move.}) 5. d4 O-O ({Invariably played, in part because the immediate} 5... e5 $2 {would just drop a pawn to} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Nxe5 {.}) ({Other moves are very likely to transpose once Black castles: for example,} 5... Nbd7 6. Bd3 e5 7. d5 {when} O-O 8. O-O {would be an immediate transposition to Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] and after 7...Nc5 8.Bc2 a5 9.O-O Black has almost always gone 9...O-O , transposing after all.}) ({Finally, we should just mention that} 5... Bg4 {can be met by either} 6. Be3 {or 6.Be2 when White may well find himself a tempo up on Chapter 5c [/variation/35967697/#/7/w]!}) 6. Bd3 $5 ({Many King's Indian players aren't even aware that this move exists and} 6. Bd3 {has been about 50 times less common than the Classical main line,}) (6. Be2 {. The move has been around for a long time - it was even seen in a series of games between Cochrane and Bonnerjee at Calcutta in 1855 - but it only really became popular during the Covid era, in part due to Daniil Dubov's defeat of Magnus Carlsen. Since then Carlsen and Nakamura have been seen on the white side, as has the great hope of Belgian chess, Daniel Dardha.}) 6... Nc6 $5 {White's basic idea is simple: to overprotect e4 and so claim that 6...e5 7.d5 is a superior version of the Petrosian variation (6.Be2 e5 7.d5). In practice Black's two most common moves by far have been 6...e5 and 6...Nbd7 , and here we'll especially focus on: 5a: 6...c5 5b: 6...e5 5c: 6...Bg4 . Note that 6...Nbd7 almost always transposes into Chapter 5b [/variation/35967689/#/8/w] after 7.O-O e5 8.d5 . Likewise, 6...Na6 and 6...c6 tend to transpose there after 7.O-O e5 .} {As well as 6...Bg4 , Black has one other way of aiming for quick counterplay against d4.} 7. d5 ({Prodding the knight rather than allow Black to increase the pressure against d4 with} 7. O-O Bg4 {, and now 7...Ne5?! 8.Nxe5 dxe5 9.O-O followed by Be3 would just be a pleasant edge for White.}) 7... Nb4 8. Bb1 $5 ({A maximalist move, keeping e4 secure and intending to seize some useful space with a2-a3 followed by arranging b2-b4.} 8. Be2 {, as played by Jan Timman amongst others, also offers decent chances of an edge.}) 8... a5 (8... c5 $6 9. a3 {This could also have waited as the knight is doing little on b4.} Na6 10. O-O Nc7 11. Re1 {Lining up the key pawn break, e4-e5. Black doesn't have a particularly good version of a Benoni, but could now have restricted White to an edge with 11...Bg4 12.h3 Bxf3 13.Qxf3 .} a6 12. e5 $1 {With} dxe5 13. Nxe5 {or 12...Nfe8 13.h3 on the way, White was in full control in Barua-Cuijpers, Dortmund 1980.}) 9. h3 $5 {White has more often preferred to castle, but once again we quite like the idea of cutting out ...Bg4 ideas while White can.} e6 10. O-O {White is now ready to go Re1 and Be3 or Bg5, and with e4 secure should be able to meet ...exd5 with cxd5.} exd5 11. cxd5 $1 Re8 12. Be3 $5 (12. Re1 {is a good move, but so is the text. White is set to increase his grip with Re1 and Qd2, and also has ideas of a3 Na6; Bc2, possibly even followed by Nd4. Black's position is fairly solid, but just where is their counterplay?}) 12... c6 $5 13. a3 {Kicking the knight so that it won't be able to recapture on c6 next move.} Na6 14. dxc6 $5 bxc6 15. Ba2 $5 ({Here} 15. e5 dxe5 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Nxe5 Bb7 {wasn't too bad for Black in Prohaszka-J.Van Foreest, Ajka (rapid) 2023, but White didn't need to rush.}) {Activating the bishop so definitely adds a fair degree of oomph to e4-e5 and White is also set to go on the front foot with Qa4. As such, we undoubtedly have an edge and have also set a small trap.} 15... Nxe4 $2 16. Nxe4 Rxe4 17. Bxf7+ $1 {Clearly the bishop is untouchable unless Black wishes to lose the exchange.} Kh8 18. Rc1 {White enjoys the initiative, as well as the safer king. One threat is clearly Rxc6, Bg5 or Ng5-e6 may also be awkward for Black and even Qd3 followed by Rfd1 may not be trivial to meet.} *

