1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... Bg4 8. h3 {Challenging the bishop without delay.} Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6 $5 10. O-O exd5 11. exd5 {Not forced, but our usual recapture in these ...c5 lines, maintaining the symmetry.} Nbd7 12. Qd1 $1 Z0 ({A useful retreat so as to be able to meet} 12... Ne5 $6 {with} 13. Be2 {. With 13.Bg5 or 13.Bf4 set to follow, the bishop-pair and a small space advantage, White is slightly better.}) *

