1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... Bg4 8. h3 {Challenging the bishop without delay.} Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nbd7 10. Qd1 $1 e6 ({A useful bishop-retaining retreat once again, facilitating} 10... Ne5 $6 11. Be2 {.}) 11. O-O exd5 ({Getting the king off the e-file before it opens. White will follow up with Bg5 or even the initially more restrained Bd2 and Qc2, not least in the event of} 11... Ne8 {.}) 12. exd5 $1 {Denying Black any asymmetry and thereby making it harder for them to obtain counterplay.} Ne8 13. Bd2 Z0 ({This avoided any notion of doubled pawns as White enjoyed a pleasant edge in Spassky-Fischer, 26th matchgame, Belgrade 1992. It's worth seeing just a few more moves as they were definitely thematic:} 13... Ne5 $6 14. Be2 f5 15. f4 $1 Nf7 16. g4 $1 {White has well and truly seized the initiative and it wasn't long before he followed up Kg2 with g4-g5, thereby leaving Fischer's position beginning to run low on oxygen.}) *

