1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... e5 {A Czech Benoni style counter.} 8. h3 $1 {This is an especially strong advance here, not only keeping Black out of g4, but also preparing g2-g4 which can leave Black cramped and struggling to be able to satisfactorily free his position (unsurprisingly, ...f5 becomes extremely risky, if it can even be arranged).} Nbd7 $6 9. g4 {A very useful gain of space.} Ne8 10. Bg5 $5 {Probing, facilitating Qd2 and preparing to drop the bishop back to e3 if challenged by its counterpart or the f-pawn.} Qb6 11. Qd2 f6 12. Be3 {White was in full control and stood clearly better in Valenzuela Gomez-Iljin, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, with Black a long way from arranging ...f5 and h3-h4 imminent.} *

