1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... e5 {A Czech Benoni style counter.} 8. h3 $1 {This is an especially strong advance here, not only keeping Black out of g4, but also preparing g2-g4 which can leave Black cramped and struggling to be able to satisfactorily free his position (unsurprisingly, ...f5 becomes extremely risky, if it can even be arranged).} Nh5 $5 9. g3 {)} ({Continuing the prophylaxis to keep Black's knight out of f4 (} 9. Bg5 $5 f6 10. Be3 {is also a decent option, so long as White then goes} Nf4 11. Bf1 {and g2-g3).}) ({The move} 9. g3 {prepares to drive Black backwards with Be2 then Nd2 or Nh2, after which the knight make well travel via f1 to a pretty decent post on e3.}) 9... f5 $6 10. exf5 $1 ({This forcing choice is even stronger here than Bacrot's calm} 10. Qe2 {. Already ideas of g3-g4, Ng5 and even Nh4 loom.}) 10... gxf5 11. Nh4 $1 Nf4 $5 ({Clearly if the knight retreats, White will just pocket f5 and} 11... Qe8 $2 12. Nb5 {would also be very bad for Black.}) 12. Bxf4 $1 {An unstereotyped but strong exchange.} exf4 13. Qh5 {Clearly f5 is collapsing, gxf4 also a threat and the engines feel that White is clearly better, in part because White's king will be quite safe after O-O or Kd2, in large contrast to its counterpart.} *

