{Tying Black down to d6 while taking control of e5. White enjoys a very pleasant edge with Qd2, Rab1, a2-a3 and b2-b4 the plan.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... e6 {Black usually challenges so in Modern Benoni fashion.} 8. h3 $1 {Useful prophylaxis again as White reminds Black that the light-squared bishop can often become something of a problem piece in the Benoni.} a6 9. O-O ({There's no need for} 9. a4 {here, as now 9...b5 10.cxb5 axb5 11.Bxb5 doesn't look like the best version of a Benko for Black, with White having developed smoothly and with ...e6 played.}) 9... exd5 10. exd5 {Our standard recapture, denying Black a mobile queenside majority and leaving them a little cramped.} Ne8 11. Re1 {A fine file for the rook. Bf4 or a discombobulating Bg5 will likely follow.} Nd7 12. Bf4 ({White now went for} 12. Bg5 {in Prohaszka-Sourath, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, but if Black is possibly going to play ...f6 anyhow, we can do without it.}) *

