g to leave Black rather tied down after Raf1 then Ng5.} Ng8 $5 15. Raf1 f6 16. Ne4 $1 {Exploiting the absence of e3-e4 to pressure d6 and also make Nfg5 a definite threat.} Ne5 17. Nxe5 {Naturally White wants to open lines.} Rxe5 18. Nxf6 $1 {Breaking through and the prelude to a strong exchange sacrifice.} Nxf6 19. Rxf6 Bf5 20. R6xf5 $1 gxf5 21. Bxf5 {With two pawns for the exchange, a mighty bishop on f5, the black king exposed and both e3-e4 and Rf4 on their way, White was clearly better in Jovanovic-Gruic, Belgrade 1991.} *

