y Nb5, which can cause problems for Black if they're trying to sit with a knight on d7 and queen on e7.} a6 14. Qd2 Qe7 15. Qh6 $1 ({This seems even stronger than the somewhat more popular} 15. Rf2 {. White will only go Rf2 next and is also ready to keep up the pressure with 15...Qf8 16.Qh4 or 15...Nh5?! 16.g4! .}) 15... Ne5 $2 16. Ng5 $1 {White should be happy to give up material to crash through down the f-file.} Nxd3 17. Rxf6 $1 Qxf6 18. Qxh7+ Kf8 19. Rf1 Nf4 ({Black now failed to survive against the deadly queen and double-knight combination after} 19... Qxf1+ 20. Kxf1 Ne5 21. Ne2 {and Nf4 in Campos-Sanchez Guirado, Valencia 1989, where blocking too would have been insufficient.}) 20. Qh4 Qd4+ 21. Kh1 {The right square for the king with g2-g4 imminent.} Nh5 22. g4 $1 Z0 ({White is winning by force since} 22... Nf6 {is cleaned up by} 23. Rxf6 $1 {.}) *

