1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... e6 {Black usually challenges so in Modern Benoni fashion.} 8. h3 $1 {Useful prophylaxis again as White reminds Black that the light-squared bishop can often become something of a problem piece in the Benoni.} exd5 {Black usually exchanges so, although on occasion an opponent may prefer to retain the tension.} 9. exd5 $1 ({This recapture, rather than} 9. cxd5 {and the Modern mainline of the Benoni. White gets ready to castle, then go Re1 and Bf4, with smooth and easy development. This position can come about from a number of move orders and for several decades now has generally been considered pleasantly better for White.}) 9... Re8+ 10. Be3 (10. Kf1 {isn't ridiculous, but the sensible}) (10. Be3 {gets ready to castle after all.}) 10... Bh6 {This has actually been Black's most common move in practice, partly due to the fact that non-titled players have tended to shy away from the long-term exchange sacrifice.} 11. O-O $1 Bxe3 ({White should be happy to gambit a pawn to speed up our development and now} 11... Rxe3 $6 12. fxe3 Bxe3+ 13. Kh1 {shouldn't give Black enough compensation, and if} Nh5 14. Qe1 {.}) 12. fxe3 Nbd7 ({White would now like to push e3-e4, go Qd2 and then double rooks on the half-open f-file. As such, White will meet} 12... Qe7 {with} 13. e4 {then go Qd2 and Rf2.}) 13. e4 {White is now ready to go Qd2, after which Qh6 might be possible, as well as Rf2 and Raf1. Do look out too for ideas of a timely Nb5, which can cause problems for Black if they're trying to sit with a knight on d7 and queen on e7.} a6 14. Qd2 Kg7 15. Rf2 {All is now set for Raf1, after which White would be threatening the classic breakthrough e4-e5 dxe5; Ng5 with tremendous pressure.} Ng8 $5 16. a3 {Spreading the play to stretch Black's still quite undeveloped position.} Ne5 17. Nxe5 Rxe5 18. b4 {With Black still low on counterplay, White enjoyed a pleasant edge in Gupta-Pridorozhni, Moscow 2012, where Raf1 wasn't any longer White's only idea, since Rb1 and Na4 might quickly lead to inroads on the queenside.} *

