1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... e6 {Black usually challenges so in Modern Benoni fashion.} 8. h3 $1 {Useful prophylaxis again as White reminds Black that the light-squared bishop can often become something of a problem piece in the Benoni.} exd5 {Black usually exchanges so, although on occasion an opponent may prefer to retain the tension.} 9. exd5 $1 ({This recapture, rather than} 9. cxd5 {and the Modern mainline of the Benoni. White gets ready to castle, then go Re1 and Bf4, with smooth and easy development. This position can come about from a number of move orders and for several decades now has generally been considered pleasantly better for White.}) 9... Re8+ 10. Be3 (10. Kf1 {isn't ridiculous, but the sensible}) (10. Be3 {gets ready to castle after all.}) 10... Bf5 $5 {Another radical idea, which is perhaps a sign of how unpleasant the defence can be for Black if they proceed along conventional lines. White can now castle or opt for something fairly critical.} 11. Bxf5 gxf5 12. O-O Ne4 {The point of Black's play.} 13. Ne2 $1 {Retaining the knights reveals the downside to Black's approach. White is quite happy to trade b2 for b7 and Black's kingside won't look so attractive once the knight lands on f4.} Nd7 14. Qc2 {Holding everything together and beginning to eye the weakness on f5, which a plan of Rae1 and Ng3 will be quick to target.} Rb8 15. Rae1 $1 b5 $5 16. cxb5 $1 {In conjunction with White's next, the best way to keep Black's counterplay under control on the queenside.} Rxb5 17. b3 {With Ng3 set to follow and ideas too of Nd2-c4, White was clearly for choice in Khairullin-Kislinsky, Legnica 2013.} *

