1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... e6 {Black usually challenges so in Modern Benoni fashion.} 8. h3 $1 {Useful prophylaxis again as White reminds Black that the light-squared bishop can often become something of a problem piece in the Benoni.} exd5 {Black usually exchanges so, although on occasion an opponent may prefer to retain the tension.} 9. exd5 $1 ({This recapture, rather than} 9. cxd5 {and the Modern mainline of the Benoni. White gets ready to castle, then go Re1 and Bf4, with smooth and easy development. This position can come about from a number of move orders and for several decades now has generally been considered pleasantly better for White.}) 9... Re8+ 10. Be3 (10. Kf1 {isn't ridiculous, but the sensible}) (10. Be3 {gets ready to castle after all.}) 10... b5 $6 11. Nxb5 {Pretty much a free pawn here.} Ne4 12. Bxe4 {Forcing the pace, ahead of covering b2 and c4.} Rxe4 13. Qb3 {The knight should now be able to drop back to c3, White is all set to castle then challenge the e-file and Black surely doesn't have anything like enough for a pawn.} *

