1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... e6 {Black usually challenges so in Modern Benoni fashion.} 8. h3 $1 {Useful prophylaxis again as White reminds Black that the light-squared bishop can often become something of a problem piece in the Benoni.} exd5 {Black usually exchanges so, although on occasion an opponent may prefer to retain the tension.} 9. exd5 $1 ({This recapture, rather than} 9. cxd5 {and the Modern mainline of the Benoni. White gets ready to castle, then go Re1 and Bf4, with smooth and easy development. This position can come about from a number of move orders and for several decades now has generally been considered pleasantly better for White.}) 9... Re8+ 10. Be3 (10. Kf1 {isn't ridiculous, but the sensible}) (10. Be3 {gets ready to castle after all.}) 10... Rxe3+ $5 {Black's most ambitious approach, sacrificing the exchange for a decent grip on the dark squares.} 11. fxe3 Nfd7 $5 12. O-O {Housing the king so that White can meet ...Ne5 with an exchange of knights and without running into any annoying checks.} Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Qf3 $1 {Preparing to triple on the f-file.} Qe7 15. Rf2 Nd7 {This was all quite critical in Gavrilov-Chigaev, Voronezh 2016, where White should have been consistent.} 16. Raf1 Bxc3 ({The defence now begins to creek - if} 16... f6 17. g4 {or 16...f5? 17.Bxf5! gxf5 18.Qxf5 with a very strong attack.}) 17. bxc3 Ne5 18. Qg3 $1 {With Be2 then h3-h4-h5 on the way, we'd certainly prefer to take White despite Black's firm grip on e5. And, yes, the bishop on d3 is taboo:} Nxd3 $2 19. Rxf7 $1 Qxf7 20. Rxf7 Kxf7 21. Qxd6 {With Black lacking a safe square for his bishop, the extra queen allied to White's central majority will prove far, far too strong.} *

