1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 {A Benoni-esque challenge to the white centre.} 7. d5 ({Taking the space on offer. If you really like your Maroczy Binds, by all means consider} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {and then} 9. Nc2 {or 9.Nde2!? , but not 9.Be3? Ng4 .}) ({After} 7. d5 {we should note that thanks to White's sixth move, the Benko isn't an option for Black:} b5 $2 8. Nxb5 {is just a safe extra pawn. Likewise, while you may wish to meet 7...a6 with 8.a4 , 8.O-O is very much an option too, and if 8...b5 9.cxb5 axb5 10.Nxb5 .}) 7... e6 {Black usually challenges so in Modern Benoni fashion.} 8. h3 $1 {Useful prophylaxis again as White reminds Black that the light-squared bishop can often become something of a problem piece in the Benoni.} exd5 {Black usually exchanges so, although on occasion an opponent may prefer to retain the tension.} 9. exd5 $1 ({This recapture, rather than} 9. cxd5 {and the Modern mainline of the Benoni. White gets ready to castle, then go Re1 and Bf4, with smooth and easy development. This position can come about from a number of move orders and for several decades now has generally been considered pleasantly better for White.}) 9... Re8+ 10. Be3 (10. Kf1 {isn't ridiculous, but the sensible}) (10. Be3 {gets ready to castle after all.}) 10... Rxe3+ $5 {Black's most ambitious approach, sacrificing the exchange for a decent grip on the dark squares.} 11. fxe3 Qe7 {Invariably played, if not completely forced.} 12. O-O $1 {Once again we see White happy to give up e3 to open lines and fight for the initiative.} Nbd7 13. Qe1 $5 ({A change from the standard} 13. Qd2 {. White frees d1 for the rook and prepares to bring the queen to f2 or h4.}) 13... Ne8 14. Rd1 {Completing mobilisation and the rook may yet land up on the f-file after all, just via d2 then f2.} Ne5 15. Nxe5 ({A standard reaction, although the engines slightly prefer the immediate} 15. Rd2 $5 {, which also makes good sense.}) 15... Bxe5 16. Rd2 $1 {Preparing to double rooks.} Bd7 17. Rdf2 {Threatening to exchange twice on f7 and then activate with Ne4.} f5 18. g4 $5 fxg4 ({The most aggressive choice, preparing to invade down the f-file after all or to expand with} 18... Qg5 19. Rg2 fxg4 20. Ne4 {and hxg4 . This may be even stronger than returning the extra material for a structural edge with 18.e4 , as White did in Salem-Indjic, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023.}) 19. Rf8+ $1 Qxf8 20. Rxf8+ Kxf8 21. hxg4 {Dragging Black's light-squared bishop slightly offside.} Bxg4 22. Ne4 $1 Z0 ({Black does have rook, bishop and pawn for the queen, but like the engines we would definitely prefer to take White with ideas of Qh4 or b2-b4 set to quickly place Black under some pressure, as would} 22... Bf5 23. Nf2 {.}) *

