1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} a5 {The other fairly common move, playing just as Black does with 6.Be2 e5 7.d5 a5 .} 8. O-O ({Natural and sensible, if by no means forced. We also examined} 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 Na6 10. Nd2 {which doesn't appear to give White an improved version of the main lines of the Petrosian, but you may also wish to look into the Makogonov-like 8.h3!? when 8...Nh5 9.g3!? was played by Nakamura in the 2022 World Rapid Championship.}) 8... Na6 9. a3 c5 $6 ({White prepares to take advantage of the situation down the a-file to threaten b2-b4. Now Black will almost always transpose to our mainline [/variation/35967693/#/10/w] (7...Nbd7 8.O-O Nc5 9.Bc2 a5 10.a3) after} 9... Nc5 10. Bc2 {.}) {This attempted to seal up the queenside in Getman-Yip, Mexico City 2023, where White mistakenly exchanged on c6. Denoting such a natural move as dubious may seem harsh, but just look at what follows!} 10. Ne1 Ne8 ({A fairly natural regrouping, freeing the f-pawn for duty, possibly heading for c2 with the knight to support b2-b4 and preparing to meet} 10... Nh5 {with} 11. g3 $1 {, thereby fully taking the wind out of the sails of ...f5 ideas.}) 11. f3 $5 {A devious little move. Perhaps quite remarkably, White would now like to go g2-g4 followed by Ng2 - it's all about White's full control of e4 in the event of pawn exchanges after ...f5.} f5 12. exf5 $1 gxf5 ({Now} 12... Bxf5 13. Ra2 $5 {followed by b2-b3 then probably g2-g3 would leave White in full control of the position due to our firm control of the key e4 point.}) 13. g4 $1 ({A radical follow-up to the logical exchange on f5, and perhaps unsurprisingly, engine-approved (they also quite like the more restrained} 13. g3 $5 {followed by Ng2 and an eventual g3-g4). There's no good reason why White too shouldn't look to play on the kingside here, thereby making good use of the bishop being on d3. Now 13...f4 14.Qc2 would leave White in full control (Ng2, Bd2, Rae1 and a kingside advance might follow), or White could switch back at some stage to arranging b2-b4.}) 13... fxg4 {Attempting to disrupt.} 14. fxg4 Qh4 ({Now} 14... Rxf1+ 15. Bxf1 {retains sufficient control (} Qh4 {can be met by} 16. h3 {and 15...e4!? 16.Nxe4 Bd4+ 17.Kh1 leaves Black with clearly insufficient compensation with their own king and kingside still not exactly safe).}) 15. Rxf8+ ({The simplest way of keeping control, although interestingly the engines also quite like} 15. Nf3 $5 Qxg4+ 16. Kh1 {.}) 15... Bxf8 16. g5 {With Ng2 and Ne4 on the way, Black's queen is, if anything, misplaced and White simply doing pretty well thanks to our superior coordination.} *

