1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} a5 {The other fairly common move, playing just as Black does with 6.Be2 e5 7.d5 a5 .} 8. O-O ({Natural and sensible, if by no means forced. We also examined} 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 Na6 10. Nd2 {which doesn't appear to give White an improved version of the main lines of the Petrosian, but you may also wish to look into the Makogonov-like 8.h3!? when 8...Nh5 9.g3!? was played by Nakamura in the 2022 World Rapid Championship.}) 8... Nfd7 $5 9. a3 $5 f5 ({White makes a useful move and provokes ...f5, while preparing to meet} 9... Nc5 {with} 10. Bc2 {and we slightly prefer this approach to the immediate 9.Bc2 of Lupulescu-Saric, Zagreb (rapid) 2023.}) 10. Bg5 ({Forcing the pace. The engines also quite like} 10. exf5 $5 gxf5 11. Bc2 {followed by Rb1 and a timely Ng5.}) 10... Nf6 11. exf5 $5 ({Preparing to counter on the kingside. The alternative is to plough straight ahead with} 11. c5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. b4 {, which is probably good for White.}) 11... gxf5 12. Nh4 h6 ({The point of White's play. Now} 12... e4 $6 13. Bc2 {followed by f2-f3 and possibly a timely g2-g3 would leave us doing well.}) 13. Bd2 {Retaining an important piece.} Ne4 $5 14. Bxe4 Qxh4 ({Clearly the right way to capture. Now} 14... fxe4 $2 15. Qh5 {would leave White doing very well.}) 15. g3 Qe7 16. Bc2 {White isn't about to get mated, can take control of the central situation with Qe2 and f2-f3, and should be slightly for choice, with a subsequent b2-b4 or even g2-g4 on the cards.} *

