1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} a5 {The other fairly common move, playing just as Black does with 6.Be2 e5 7.d5 a5 .} 8. O-O ({Natural and sensible, if by no means forced. We also examined} 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 Na6 10. Nd2 {which doesn't appear to give White an improved version of the main lines of the Petrosian, but you may also wish to look into the Makogonov-like 8.h3!? when 8...Nh5 9.g3!? was played by Nakamura in the 2022 World Rapid Championship.}) 8... Nh5 9. Bc2 ({Getting out of the way of ...Nf4 before looking for the thematic queenside roller with a2-a3 and b2-b4. Another fascinating option here is the positional pawn sacrifice} 9. Bg5 Qe8 10. c5 $5 dxc5 11. Qd2 {from Karpanov-Tripp, correspondence 2017.}) 9... Nf4 10. Be3 {Possible now that ... Nxd3 isn't on. Here White is ready for both Qd2 and a2-a3 followed by b2-b4.} f5 $2 11. exf5 $1 gxf5 ({A well-timed exchange, prior to looking for another one on f4. Now} 11... Bxf5 12. Bxf5 gxf5 13. g3 $1 Nh3+ 14. Kg2 {would keep Black fully at bay on the kingside and White doing pretty well with c4-c5 imminent.}) 12. Bxf4 $5 exf4 13. Rb1 {Black's King's Indian bishop is currently looking pretty good, but White is doing well with Ne2 on the way followed by Nxf4 or Ned4 and Re1, beginning to dominate the position.} *

