1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} a5 {The other fairly common move, playing just as Black does with 6.Be2 e5 7.d5 a5 .} 8. O-O ({Natural and sensible, if by no means forced. We also examined} 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 Na6 10. Nd2 {which doesn't appear to give White an improved version of the main lines of the Petrosian, but you may also wish to look into the Makogonov-like 8.h3!? when 8...Nh5 9.g3!? was played by Nakamura in the 2022 World Rapid Championship.}) 8... Nh5 9. Bc2 ({Getting out of the way of ...Nf4 before looking for the thematic queenside roller with a2-a3 and b2-b4. Another fascinating option here is the positional pawn sacrifice} 9. Bg5 Qe8 10. c5 $5 dxc5 11. Qd2 {from Karpanov-Tripp, correspondence 2017.}) 9... Nf4 10. Be3 {Possible now that ... Nxd3 isn't on. Here White is ready for both Qd2 and a2-a3 followed by b2-b4.} Nd7 11. Qd2 Nc5 $5 12. Kh1 $1 ({Development complete, White starts to switch which side of the board we want to play on, beginning to borrow ideas from the not unrelated 5.Bd3 Nc6 6.Nge2 Seirawan system. Rather than allow Black full dark-square compensation for the pawn after} 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. Qxf4 {,White intends to fight back on the kingside with g2-g3 and Nh4.}) (12. Kh1 {also begins to introduce ideas of a timely Nxe5 - not least in the event of} Bg4 $2 13. Nxe5 $1 {- and do please note that 12.Bxc5? dxc5 13.Nxe5?? would not have been at all wise due to 13...Qg5 .}) 12... b6 {Overprotection of c5 against White's Nxe5 ideas.} 13. g3 Nh3 ({Kicking the annoying enemy knight away ahead of moving the knight from f3 to h4 or back to g1 in the event of} 13... Bg4 14. Ng1 {.}) 14. Nh4 $5 {By no means has White fully given up on queenside play, but for now the priority is to frustrate Black on the kingside. Note how the knight on h4 helps to fight for the f5-square, as well as that White would now quite like to mobilise the troops with Rae1, f2-f3 and Qg2. Another possibility is Ng2 then f2-f4, striking out on the kingside.} f5 $6 {Natural, if likely premature here.} 15. exf5 $1 gxf5 16. Rae1 f4 $2 ({White is all now set to take control of the position with} 16... Z0 17. f4 {, and if} exf4 {( 17...e4?? 18.Qg2 picks up the stray knight)} 18. Bxf4 Nxf4 19. Qxf4 {, leaving Black's position rather riddled with weaknesses. As such, Black might try to beat White to that advance.}) 17. Bxc5 {A fairly forced but strong exchange.} bxc5 18. Qd3 {The knight on h4 really makes its presence felt as White creates a direct and rather strong threat.} Ng5 19. Ne4 $1 {Black is in serious trouble on the light squares and kingside in general.} *

