1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} Ne8 8. h4 $5 ({A very tempting advance here (the alternative would be} 8. O-O f5 9. exf5 gxf5 10. Bc2 {), simply intending to ram the black kingside with h4-h5. White will meet 8...Bg4 with 9.Be2 , which would also be a good response to 8...Nf6 , while 8...h5 9.Ng5 would immediately exploit the weakened black kingside.}) 8... h6 $2 {A clear positional mistake, seen in Tikhonov-Ziatdinov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023.} 9. h5 $1 g5 10. Nh2 $1 {White gets ready to seal the kingside and Black is left with just a choice of evils. If g2-g4 occurs, White will then manoeuvre the knight on h2 to g2 via f1 and should win the game on the queenside thanks to the c4-c5 and/ or b2-b4 advances, all the while as Black is deprived of their natural counterplay on the kingside.} f5 $5 11. exf5 {Opening lines to exploit White's resulting control of the key e4-square.} Bxf5 12. Bxf5 Rxf5 13. Qc2 {With Be3 and Nf1-g3 set to follow, White is clearly better with Black again rather lacking counterplay and having certain kingside weaknesses.} *

