1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} Ne8 8. h4 $5 ({A very tempting advance here (the alternative would be} 8. O-O f5 9. exf5 gxf5 10. Bc2 {), simply intending to ram the black kingside with h4-h5. White will meet 8...Bg4 with 9.Be2 , which would also be a good response to 8...Nf6 , while 8...h5 9.Ng5 would immediately exploit the weakened black kingside.}) 8... f5 9. h5 $1 {) Preparing to quickly ramp up the pressure against g6 and f5 with Nh4.} f4 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Bd2 Z0 ({The engines are surely right that White is doing pretty well. One plan is a quick c4-c5, not least with} 11... Nf6 12. c5 {, the other Qe2 and O-O-O, after which Rdg1 followed by g2-g3 might well leave Black rather feeling the heat on the kingside.}) *

