1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} c6 {A move popular back in Calcutta in 1855!} 8. O-O {Calm does it as White should not mind an exchange on d5: ...cxd5; cxd5 supplies the same largely favourable structure that c4-c5xd6 does.} Na6 9. Rb1 Nc5 10. Bc2 {Retaining a useful piece while renewing the threat of b2-b4.} a5 11. Be3 cxd5 ({White has a definite pull with ideas of not just} 11... Z0 12. Nxe5 {, but 12.Bxc5 dxc5 13.dxc6 , thereby rather destroying Black's structure.}) 12. cxd5 {Rightly refusing to unbalance the structure.} Bd7 $6 13. Nxe5 $1 {Overloading the defender on d6 to win a pawn.} Nfxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe5 15. f4 $1 Z0 ({Once the bishop retreats,} 15... Z0 16. Nxd6 {will leave White a clear pawn to the good.}) *

