1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} h6 8. O-O ({A simple approach, although the Makogonov-esque} 8. h3 $5 {is also pretty tempting here, intending} Ne8 9. g4 {and 8...Nh5! 9.g3 f5? 10.Nh4 . Instead, 8.O-O gets ready to advance with Bd2 (or even Be3), and b2-b4.}) 8... a5 9. a3 ({Here} 9. h3 {was seen in Moksh-Mikhalsky, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where White also could have initially focussed on the queenside.}) {All is now set for Rb1 and b2-b4.} 9... Ne8 ({Probably a better way of preparing ...f5 than} 9... Nh5 10. Bc2 {when Black must be wary of Nxe5 tactics.}) 10. Rb1 {White gets ready to launch the b- and c-pawns.} f5 11. exf5 $5 {Again we see White playing to keep Black's counterplay under control, not just hurtle into a race situation.} gxf5 12. Bc2 f4 $6 ({Good prophylaxis. Clearly} 12... e4 {will be well met by} 13. Nd4 {and meanwhile White is all set to fight back on the kingside with g2-g3 then Nh4. Note too that once again Black's other advance should not be feared.}) 13. Qe2 ({With full control of e4 and b2-b4 on the way, White is definitely for choice and here more aggressive types even have an alternative in the highly modern} 13. Kh1 $5 {, intending Rg1 and g2-g3, demonstrating that White too can play on the kingside.}) *

