1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} Nbd7 {Natural development and one of two popular choices for Black here.} 8. O-O {Not forced, but the king should be fairly safe here and now a2-a3 and b2-b4 will follow, as well as Bc2 if the bishop is challenged.} Nh5 9. Bg5 $5 f6 ({Discombobulating as White drags a black piece to f6 (} 9... Qe8 $2 10. Nb5 {wouldn't be wise), ahead of dropping the bishop back to e3.}) 10. Be3 f5 $2 ({Now} 10... Nf4 11. Bc2 {should retain sufficient control and meanwhile White is set to expand with b2-b4 or regroup with Ne1, all the while as we aim to provoke a certain break.}) 11. exf5 $1 ({This natural but misguided break was met by} 11. Ng5 {in Golombek-Hindle, Ilford 1964, where} Nc5 {wouldn't have been so clear.}) 11... gxf5 12. Ng5 Ndf6 ({This is the way to do things. Both} 12... Z0 13. Qxh5 {and 13.Ne6 are suddenly quite large threats.}) 13. Ne6 $1 Bxe6 14. dxe6 {Black's light squares have pretty much gone as they find themselves clearly worse, with White threatening both Bxf5 and Be2.} *

