1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} Nbd7 {Natural development and one of two popular choices for Black here.} 8. O-O {Not forced, but the king should be fairly safe here and now a2-a3 and b2-b4 will follow, as well as Bc2 if the bishop is challenged.} h6 $5 {Once tried by Movsesian, this prepares ...Nh7 then ...f5.} 9. Kh1 $5 {Decent prophylaxis. White can now still play on the queenside, but also gets ready to regroup with Ng1.} Nh7 10. Ng1 f5 ({Once again, the battle will in part revolve around the f5-square, whether Black breaks straight away or after} 10... Nc5 11. Bc2 {.}) 11. exf5 ({A clear improvement on the} 11. f4 $2 exf4 {of Trimborn-Atkins, Amsterdam 1899.}) 11... gxf5 12. f3 $1 {It's useful to take control of e4 here and White should be slightly better. Nge2 and Be3 will likely follow, after which White might play on the queenside after all (b2-b4 and c4-c5), look to disrupt Black's coordination with an attack on f5 through Qc2, or counter in the centre and on the kingside with f3-f4.} *

