1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} Nbd7 {Natural development and one of two popular choices for Black here.} 8. O-O {Not forced, but the king should be fairly safe here and now a2-a3 and b2-b4 will follow, as well as Bc2 if the bishop is challenged.} Nc5 {A natural follow-up, if not forced.} 9. Bc2 {Preserving the bishop and thereby setting up b2-b4.} a5 {Obvious you might well think, although not quite everyone has played this way as Black.} (9... Bd7 $6 10. b4 Na6 11. a3 {Stabilising the queenside situation; 11.Rb1 would also be a good choice.} Ne8 12. Re1 $5 {Strong-pointing e4 while increasing White's options in the event of ...f5.} f5 13. exf5 {13.c5!? This is even stronger in the view of the engines, in part because 13...f4 would run into 14.c6! . 13...dxc5 14.b5 Nb8 15.Bg5 A most disruptive hit due to White's ideas of Nxe5, d5-d6 and 15...Qc8 16.Be7 . 15...Bf6 16.Bxf6 Qxf6 17.d6! Crunch. White threatens not only exf5, but Qd5+ and Qxb7*, with Black's centre completely collapsing in the event of 17...Nxd6 18.Nd5 . 17...Qxd6 18.exf5 Not only attacking e5, but allowing White to contemplate increasing the pressure with Qe2 and Rad1. 18...Qxd1 19.Raxd1 Bxf5 20.Bb3+ Kg7 21.Rxe5 White's initiative is simply far too powerful.} gxf5 14. Bg5 Nf6 15. Qd2 {With ideas of all of Nh4, Rad1 and c4-c5, White was in control and clearly for choice in Dearnley-Crook, correspondence 1999.}) 10. a3 Ne8 ({White gets ready for Rb1 and b2-b4 to drive Black back on the queenside. Now} 10... b6 11. Rb1 h6 {would be rather slow and we'll then see White doing well after} 12. b4 {in Smyslov-Karadzhaev, USSR Team Championship, Moscow 1959, while we've already noted that White shouldn't mind 10...c6 11.Be3 when 11...cxd5 12.cxd5 will be followed by b2-b4 or 12...Ng4 13.Bxc5! dxc5 14.Re1 with full control.}) {This prepared ...f5 in Mikaelyan-Su, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020.} 11. Rb1 {White wastes no time getting on with things.} f5 12. exf5 $1 {An important exchange ahead of going b2-b4 which can no longer be met by ...Nxe4.} gxf5 13. b4 axb4 ({Now} 13... Na6 {can be well met by} 14. Ng5 {or even 14.Ne2!? , heading for g3.}) 14. axb4 e4 15. Bg5 $1 {An important intermezzo, looking to get in Nd4 under pretty favourable conditions.} Bf6 16. Bxf6 ({Simply does it, although} 16. bxc5 $5 Bxg5 17. Nxg5 Qxg5 18. Rb3 {is also tempting.}) 16... Qxf6 17. Nd4 Z0 ({White has a definite edge being all set to maintain his grip on the position after} 17... Z0 18. Nce2 {.}) *

