1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 e5 {Black's most natural and common response to our slightly trendy set-up.} 7. d5 {Once again, White keeps the centre closed and the position unsurprisingly has several similarities with the Petrosian variation, where White's bishop would be on e2, not d3.} Nbd7 {Natural development and one of two popular choices for Black here.} 8. O-O {Not forced, but the king should be fairly safe here and now a2-a3 and b2-b4 will follow, as well as Bc2 if the bishop is challenged.} Nc5 {A natural follow-up, if not forced.} 9. Bc2 {Preserving the bishop and thereby setting up b2-b4.} a5 {Obvious you might well think, although not quite everyone has played this way as Black.} (9... Bd7 $6 10. b4 Na6 11. a3 {Stabilising the queenside situation; 11.Rb1 would also be a good choice.} Ne8 12. Re1 $5 {Strong-pointing e4 while increasing White's options in the event of ...f5.} f5 13. exf5 {13.c5!? This is even stronger in the view of the engines, in part because 13...f4 would run into 14.c6! . 13...dxc5 14.b5 Nb8 15.Bg5 A most disruptive hit due to White's ideas of Nxe5, d5-d6 and 15...Qc8 16.Be7 . 15...Bf6 16.Bxf6 Qxf6 17.d6! Crunch. White threatens not only exf5, but Qd5+ and Qxb7*, with Black's centre completely collapsing in the event of 17...Nxd6 18.Nd5 . 17...Qxd6 18.exf5 Not only attacking e5, but allowing White to contemplate increasing the pressure with Qe2 and Rad1. 18...Qxd1 19.Raxd1 Bxf5 20.Bb3+ Kg7 21.Rxe5 White's initiative is simply far too powerful.} gxf5 14. Bg5 Nf6 15. Qd2 {With ideas of all of Nh4, Rad1 and c4-c5, White was in control and clearly for choice in Dearnley-Crook, correspondence 1999.}) 10. a3 Bd7 ({White gets ready for Rb1 and b2-b4 to drive Black back on the queenside. Now} 10... b6 11. Rb1 h6 {would be rather slow and we'll then see White doing well after} 12. b4 {in Smyslov-Karadzhaev, USSR Team Championship, Moscow 1959, while we've already noted that White shouldn't mind 10...c6 11.Be3 when 11...cxd5 12.cxd5 will be followed by b2-b4 or 12...Ng4 13.Bxc5! dxc5 14.Re1 with full control.}) ({Black plays for a queenside clamp with ...a4. The immediate} 10... a4 $6 {would leave that pawn looking pretty weak after} 11. Be3 {.}) 11. Re1 $5 ({Overprotecting e4 in a bid to encourage ...a4. The alternatives are the natural} 11. b3 {and the}) (11. Be3 Ng4 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Ba4 $1 {of Paravyan-Murzin, Cheboksary 2021, where} Bc8 $1 {would have been critical. If after 11.Re1 Black proceeds slowly, White may well go -- 12.Be3 under favourable circumstances.}) 11... c6 {Black angles for play on the queenside after an exchange on d5, but White is fairly well placed to react.} 12. dxc6 $1 (12. Be3 {can't be terrible here, but this is a well-timed exchange, exploiting the weakness on d6 to pretty much make Black recapture with the bishop.}) 12... Bxc6 13. b3 {Now ...a4 will always run into b3-b4 and in any case, Rb1 then b3-b4 may quickly occur.} Qc7 14. Rb1 $1 ({A consistent choice, and one we prefer to the arguably-too-clever} 14. Bg5 {of Kienel-Koehl, correspondence 2020. All is now set for b3-b4 followed by Bd3 to secure c4, although thanks to the control supplied by the Maroczy Bind, White may first prefer to make some useful moves, such as h2-h3 and Bd2.}) *

