1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} c5 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) {This has also gained some adherents, but as so often, White should not mind a Benoni structure.} 8. d5 {Claiming the space on offer.} b5 $2 {This may also seem fairly natural and the question mark perhaps a bit harsh, but the Benko works much better when Black has their queen's bishop on the queenside.} 9. cxb5 a6 10. O-O axb5 ({Maintaining the queenside tension, in part because} 10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 axb5 12. Nxb5 {is on with e4 still defended. Note too that this position might also come about via an 8...a6 9.O-O b5 10.cxb5 move order.}) 11. Bxb5 Na6 12. h3 {It makes reasonable sense to break the pin before ...Nd7 is played.} Bd7 {Presumably trying to keep White out of c6.} 13. Bc4 {With Bf4 and Qe2 on the way, lining up for the key e4-e5 breakthrough, White was pretty much just a clear pawn to the good in Dardha-Mohammad, Sitges 2021.} *

