1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} c5 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) {This has also gained some adherents, but as so often, White should not mind a Benoni structure.} 8. d5 {Claiming the space on offer.} e6 {A thematic counter, just like in Chapter 5a.} 9. O-O {As we saw in Chapter 5a [/variation/35967662/#/9/w], getting the king away from the e-file is often a good idea in such positions and here too White wants to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn.} exd5 10. exd5 Nfd7 $6 {Possibly played to try and wreck White's queenside, but it's not too hard to sidestep such an approach.} 11. Bg5 $1 Qb6 ({Now} 11... Bf6 12. Bf4 {will pressure d6 and also take control of e5, leaving Black unlikely to want to part with bishop for knight on c3.}) 12. Qd2 Re8 13. h3 $1 ({White now offered some support to c4 with} 13. Rac1 {in Dardha-Sadikhov, European Individual Championship, Vrnjacka Banja 2023, where a simpler approach would have been to take the bishop-pair.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {White may now reset with Be2, thereby keeping c4 secure, ahead of beginning to go forwards on the kingside with f2-f4 and in any case, it isn't clear where Black's counterplay is set to come from.} *

