1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} c5 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) {This has also gained some adherents, but as so often, White should not mind a Benoni structure.} 8. d5 {Claiming the space on offer.} e6 {A thematic counter, just like in Chapter 5a.} 9. O-O {As we saw in Chapter 5a [/variation/35967662/#/9/w], getting the king away from the e-file is often a good idea in such positions and here too White wants to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn.} exd5 10. exd5 Re8 11. h3 {) Playing to obtain the bishop-pair ahead of getting in Bf4.} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nbd7 13. Bf4 ({With a threat. Now White may look to complete development with Qc2 and Rfe1 (the immediate} 13. Qc2 {then} a6 14. Bf4 {also led to a pleasant edge and eventual successful grind in Giri-Mamedov, FIDE Grand Swiss, Douglas 2023).}) 13... Ne5 14. Be2 a6 15. a4 {Having retained an important bishop, White ruled out ...b5 for good and enjoyed a small but pleasant edge in Dardha-Erigaisi, Peniche 2021. One good way to mobilise the white forces would be Qc2, Bd2 and Rae1 followed by advancing the f- and perhaps also g-pawns.} *

