1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} e5 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) 8. d5 {Naturally White closes the centre. Now Black has to be a little careful: if their light-squared bishop is exchanged off, it's going to be very hard to mate White on the kingside - just think of all those classic Classical King's Indians decided by a ...Bxh3 blow.} a5 9. Be3 {Already White hints at c4-c5 and now that the bishop has been developed, a thematic regrouping may begin with Nd2.} Na6 10. Nd2 $1 {White might have lost a tempo, but is already doing quite well - or at least Black faces a choice of evils.} Bd7 11. g4 $1 ({A key advance as White exploits the fact our king is still on e1 to suddenly go forwards on the kingside (} 11. h4 $5 h5 12. f3 {is another idea). Now g4-g5 and h2-h4 may well be quick to follow.}) 11... Nxg4 $5 12. Bxg4 f5 13. exf5 $1 {Opening lines before Black regains the piece.} gxf5 14. Bh3 f4 15. Bxd7 {Almost always a favourable trade for White in the King's Indian.} Qxd7 16. Rg1 {Reminding Black that his king may become an issue ahead of installing a knight on e4.} fxe3 17. fxe3 {The King's Indian bishop might be unopposed and the position a bit messy, but even here White is undoubtedly for choice with Nde4 and Qh5, Qg4 or Qe2 on the way ahead of getting the king to safety on the queenside.} *

