1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} e5 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) 8. d5 {Naturally White closes the centre. Now Black has to be a little careful: if their light-squared bishop is exchanged off, it's going to be very hard to mate White on the kingside - just think of all those classic Classical King's Indians decided by a ...Bxh3 blow.} a5 9. Be3 {Already White hints at c4-c5 and now that the bishop has been developed, a thematic regrouping may begin with Nd2.} Na6 10. Nd2 $1 {White might have lost a tempo, but is already doing quite well - or at least Black faces a choice of evils.} Bxe2 11. Qxe2 Nd7 12. g4 $1 ({Aggression is fully justified here and somewhat stronger than just taking an edge with} 12. O-O f5 13. f3 {. All is now set for h2-h4 and O-O-O, with White's position also looking somewhat the easier to handle.}) 12... Ndc5 13. O-O-O Qd7 14. h4 Na4 ({Everything is set for a direct assault with h4-h5, f2-f3 and Qh2, while after} 14... f5 {the engines indicate that even} 15. Rdg1 $5 {(15.exf5 would be simpler, and also fairly strong)} f4 16. Bxc5 Nxc5 17. g5 $1 {should be somewhat better for White.}) 15. Ndb1 $1 {This kept the queenside situation fully under control, leaving White clearly for choice with our kingside play. In Carlsen-Nakamura, SpeedChess Championship (blitz) 2022, Black was forced into closing the kingside, after which Carlsen calmly walked his king back across to the kingside, broke through in classic fashion on the queenside and Nakamura was rather fortunate to eventually escape with a draw.} *

