1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} Nbd7 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) 8. Be3 ({Simple development. White has tended to prefer} 8. Ng1 $5 Bxe2 9. Ngxe2 {, which is a good trade in general, but here} e5 10. d5 Nh5 $1 {may not be too bad for Black.}) 8... e5 9. d5 {Getting set for a thematic and fairly strong regrouping with Nd2.} Nc5 10. h3 $1 ({Forcing the bishop backwards (unless Black wants to concede the bishop-pair), as White avoids walking into} 10. Nd2 Nd3+ {.}) 10... Bd7 11. Nd2 {With b2-b4 or g2-g4 on the way, White already looks to be doing pretty well.} *

