1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} Nfd7 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) {Thematically increasing the pressure against d4 and this is how Black often plays when White has the extra move (after 6.Be2 Bg4) Be3 in.} 8. Be3 {Sensible development as White keeps open options of castling on either side depending on what Black gets up to.} c5 9. d5 {Thematically closing the centre and White may now have ideas of h2-h4 and Qd2, as well as just h2-h3.} Qa5 (9... Na6 10. h3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 $5 {Eschewing a small edge with 11.Bxf3 Nc7 12.Be2 to play for more.} Nc7 12. h4 $1 a6 13. a4 {Pretty much ruling out ...b5 for the time being.} Re8 14. h5 {White was clearly for choice in Stukan-Dimic, Belgrade 2021, with hxg6 and f3-f4 on the way and ...e6 able to be met with the slightly awkward (for Black) exchange on e6.}) 10. Bd2 $5 Qd8 ({Retaining control. Now} 10... e6 11. Ng5 {would be a little embarrassing for Black.}) 11. h3 ({A calm approach, although we dare say that} 11. h4 $5 {is also possible.}) 11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 e6 13. O-O {White will recapture on d5, if Black exchanges, with the e-pawn and will likely drop the bishop back to e2 at some point soon with a pleasant edge. Qc2 and Rae1 may then follow, after which it might finally be time to think about expansion and f2-f4.} *

