{With Harry set to advance and White's centre quite secure, we'd definitely prefer to take White in this admittedly quite unbalanced and complex position.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} Nfd7 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) {Thematically increasing the pressure against d4 and this is how Black often plays when White has the extra move (after 6.Be2 Bg4) Be3 in.} 8. Be3 {Sensible development as White keeps open options of castling on either side depending on what Black gets up to.} a6 {Black angles for an improved version of a ...c5 line.} 9. d5 $1 {Seizing space before Black can get in ...c5 then ...b5. If Black now proceeds slowly White may go h2-h4 and Qd2 or just h2-h3 and O-O.} c5 10. a4 {Clamping down on Black's ideal break to leave their queenside places slightly clumsily placed.} Bxf3 11. gxf3 $5 ({Angling for} 11. Bxf3 Qa5 12. Qd2 Qb4 {, which White can allow or go:}) *

