1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} Nfd7 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) {Thematically increasing the pressure against d4 and this is how Black often plays when White has the extra move (after 6.Be2 Bg4) Be3 in.} 8. Be3 {Sensible development as White keeps open options of castling on either side depending on what Black gets up to.} Bxf3 $5 9. Bxf3 {Note that the move order 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 tends to be followed by 8...Nfd7 9.Be3 , transposing to here.} c5 10. d5 {Naturally White keeps lines closed and denies Black the opportunity to increase the pressure with ...Nd4.} Na6 11. Be2 ({Prophylaxis, ensuring that ...Ne5 will now run into f2-f4, although the more aggressive} 11. h4 $5 {also looks pretty tempting.}) 11... Nc7 12. O-O a6 13. a4 {This continued to deny Black counterplay and left White with a pleasant edge in D.Dardha-A.Salem, World Rapid Championship, Samarkand 2023, where Qd2 was on the way and Rfe1 followed by Bf1 a potential good regrouping.} *

