1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} Nfd7 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) {Thematically increasing the pressure against d4 and this is how Black often plays when White has the extra move (after 6.Be2 Bg4) Be3 in.} 8. Be3 {Sensible development as White keeps open options of castling on either side depending on what Black gets up to.} Bxf3 $5 9. Bxf3 {Note that the move order 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 tends to be followed by 8...Nfd7 9.Be3 , transposing to here.} Nc6 10. h4 $5 ({Here} 10. O-O e5 11. d5 Nd4 $1 {wasn't too clear in Dardha-Reuker, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022, but White also has some other options.}) ({Exploiting the absence of the knight from f6 (} 10. d5 Na5 11. Be2 {would be the calmer approach), and now 10...h5? 11.g4! would not be wise for Black.}) 10... e5 11. d5 Nd4 12. h5 {The position isn't completely clear, but White can ignore the knight on d4 and with the options of Ne2 and Qd2, or even Bg4, may still be slightly for choice.} c5 {Gawain Jones ends his coverage here, noting that Black can play for ...f5 or ...b5, and this position is still in need of a test or three! While we both rather like Gawain's King's Indian repertoire, we would also be quite happy as White here.} 13. hxg6 hxg6 ({Now} 13... fxg6 14. Bg4 {would leave Black a little weak on the light squares. You might also wish to consider the immediate 13.Bg4!? , aiming to provoke 13...f5 when 14.Bh3 could leave Black's kingside potentially a little brittle.}) 14. Kf1 {White wants to castle by hand after g2-g3 and Kg2 when we may yet be able to use the h-file. we'll likely also meet ...a6 with a2-a4 when even Ra3 could become a possibility, angling to get in an eventual Rah3.} *

