1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 $5 {Black aims to take advantage of the one downside to playing 6.Bd3, instead of 6.Be2: the d-pawn is somewhat less well defended.} 7. Be2 $1 {Giving up a whole tempo, but breaking the pin and engine-approved. Black is now a move up on the sideline 6.Be2 Bg4, but that has long not enjoyed the best of reputations. It turns out that even with an extra move, Black may not be able to equalise.} Nfd7 ({Note too that once again,} 7... Nc6 {would now be fairly well met by} 8. d5 {, and that we'll see 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nfd7 (Gawain Jones's recommendation on his excellent 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defence' course) 9.Be3 via a 7...Nfd7 8.Be3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 move order.}) {Thematically increasing the pressure against d4 and this is how Black often plays when White has the extra move (after 6.Be2 Bg4) Be3 in.} 8. Be3 {Sensible development as White keeps open options of castling on either side depending on what Black gets up to.} e5 {Again, we see this very natural King's Indian move and, again, it's one which White should largely welcome.} (8... Nc6 9. Ng1 $5 {A decent alternative to 9.d5 here now that White has sufficient control of d4.} Bxe2 10. Ngxe2 e5 {Here White strangely castled in Dardha-Bazakutsa, Cambridge 2023, rather than pushing on now that Black can no longer really invade on d4.} 11. d5 Ne7 12. f3 f5 13. O-O {Since White shouldn't get mated in the absence of the light-squared bishops, we definitely have an edge and might prepare the key c4-c5 break with Nc1-d3.}) 9. d5 {Once again, correctly closing the centre ahead of going Nd2, h2-h4 or even Ng5.} a5 10. Ng5 $5 ({Playing for even more than} 10. Nd2 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 f5 12. f3 {with an edge and later a notable result for White in Dubov-Carlsen [/variation/35967903/#/12/w], Steinitz Memorial (blitz) 2020, which we'll see in the illustrative games section.}) 10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 Na6 12. g4 $1 ({We prefer this immediate advance to the} 12. O-O-O {of Jacobson-Aravindh, Sant Ferran de ses Roques 2023, with White now all set to go h2-h4-h5.}) 12... h6 {Slightly weakening, but also necessary preparation if Black ever wants to go ...f5.} 13. Nf3 {The plan is h2-h4-h5 and if then ...g5 White will castle kingside and gradually win the game on the queenside, preparing first then b2-b4 break then the c4-c5 one, all the while as Black lacks any counterplay on the other flank.} f5 $2 14. gxf5 {Beginning to open lines.} gxf5 15. exf5 $1 {With control of e4 and both Rg1 and O-O-O imminent, White simply enjoys an ideal attacking set-up.} *

