1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 {here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options. f5 This move orders us out of our proposed anti-Dutch lines in Chapter Seven, but a simple solution is at hand. Nc3! Obstructing the c-pawn it's true, but White wants to break quickly with e2-e4 to exploit a weakening downside to the early ...f5. Nf6 Bg5 d5!? Continuing to play for control of e4. White has scored well from here.} e6 4. e4 {fxe4} Nxe4 {is a pleasant edge, 4...g6?! 5.Bxf6 exf6 6.d5! positionally grim for Black, and so too is 4...Ne4?! 5.Nxe4 fxe4 6.Nd2 . e3 A necessary change of approach, but White should not be unhappy with control of e5 and this version of a Stonewall. There are two main plans to be aware of: Bd3, Ne2 and c2-c4 to exert some central pressure; and g2-g4 to undermine Black on the kingside. e6 g4! A powerful advance here, playing to undermine d5 as well as f5. Not only is gxf5 a threat, but White may now be quick to seize an early initiative with such moves as Bd3 and Rg1. fxg4 Ne5 White will regain the pawn on g4 and must be doing well thanks to the half-open g-file and potential pressure down the b1-h7 diagonal.} *

