1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 ({A fairly rare, but not unimportant move order, and one which both your authors have used on occasion. Black prepares ...e5, and so this is a rare position where we do not advocate} 2. c4 {.}) ({The best move order for the purpose of our repertoire, although you can also prefer} 2. c4 e5 3. d4 {if you don't mind playing against Black's space advantage after} e4 4. Ng5 {.}) ({The move} 2. d4 {simply intends c2-c4, Nc3 and e2-e4 and now play will usually transpose to either our mainline [/variation/35967728/#/3/w] here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options.}) 2... f5 {This move orders us out of our proposed anti-Dutch lines in Chapter Seven, but a simple solution is at hand.} 3. Nc3 $1 {Obstructing the c-pawn it's true, but White wants to break quickly with e2-e4 to exploit a weakening downside to the early ...f5.} Nf6 4. Bg5 d5 $5 ({Continuing to play for control of e4. White has scored well from here.} 4... e6 5. e4 fxe4 6. Nxe4 {is a pleasant edge, 4...g6?! 5.Bxf6 exf6 6.d5! positionally grim for Black, and so too is 4...Ne4?! 5.Nxe4 fxe4 6.Nd2 .}) 5. e3 {A necessary change of approach, but White should not be unhappy with control of e5 and this version of a Stonewall. There are two main plans to be aware of: Bd3, Ne2 and c2-c4 to exert some central pressure; and g2-g4 to undermine Black on the kingside.} Nbd7 6. Bd3 e6 7. Ne2 {With both Nf4 and c2-c4 on their way, as well as simply O-O, it's not hard to conclude that White enjoys a pleasant edge.} *

