1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 ({A fairly rare, but not unimportant move order, and one which both your authors have used on occasion. Black prepares ...e5, and so this is a rare position where we do not advocate} 2. c4 {.}) ({The best move order for the purpose of our repertoire, although you can also prefer} 2. c4 e5 3. d4 {if you don't mind playing against Black's space advantage after} e4 4. Ng5 {.}) ({The move} 2. d4 {simply intends c2-c4, Nc3 and e2-e4 and now play will usually transpose to either our mainline [/variation/35967728/#/3/w] here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options.}) 2... Bg4 {The Wade Defence, named after the legendary Kiwi-English IM, analyst, coach and writer. It used to be a fairly popular choice, but is nowadays rarely seen, quite possibly as engines have affected our views on the bishop-pair and a space advantage,} 3. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although} 3. e4 {is also a decent option if you have some 1.e4 experience, here followed by Nc3 and h2-h3. The text move simply intends to continue with 4.Nc3 after all, as we provoke and welcome rather than fear the doubled f-pawns.}) 3... Nd7 {Actually Black's most common choice at this juncture, retaining the tension for now.} 4. Nc3 c6 ({White continues not to fear the doubled pawns. Now} 4... Bxf3 5. exf3 {followed by d4-d5, Bd3 and O-O would be our standard plan from the 3...Bxf3 4.exf3 lines.}) 5. d5 Ngf6 ({Our favourite advance in these lines. Now Black should probably go in for} 5... Bxf3 6. exf3 {after all, otherwise they may find their bishop rather floating in thin air.}) 6. Nd4 $1 Ne5 ({Not only attacking c6, but preparing some rather useful expansion in the shape of} 6... Z0 7. f3 {followed by e2-e4 or g2-g4, or even 7.h3 Bh5 8.g4 , an easy and strong plan White can also carry out if now 6...c5 7.Nc2 .}) 7. h3 Bd7 ({Of course,} 7... Bh5 $2 8. g4 Bg6 9. f4 {would now cost Black a piece, so the bishop must go all the way back.}) 8. e4 {Thanks to the bridgehead on d5 White enjoys a definite edge and may simply continue with Be2, O-O and Be3, although there are also some aggressive ideas revolving around f2-f4 which may be pretty tempting too.} *

