1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 ({A fairly rare, but not unimportant move order, and one which both your authors have used on occasion. Black prepares ...e5, and so this is a rare position where we do not advocate} 2. c4 {.}) ({The best move order for the purpose of our repertoire, although you can also prefer} 2. c4 e5 3. d4 {if you don't mind playing against Black's space advantage after} e4 4. Ng5 {.}) ({The move} 2. d4 {simply intends c2-c4, Nc3 and e2-e4 and now play will usually transpose to either our mainline [/variation/35967728/#/3/w] here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options.}) 2... Bg4 {The Wade Defence, named after the legendary Kiwi-English IM, analyst, coach and writer. It used to be a fairly popular choice, but is nowadays rarely seen, quite possibly as engines have affected our views on the bishop-pair and a space advantage,} 3. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although} 3. e4 {is also a decent option if you have some 1.e4 experience, here followed by Nc3 and h2-h3. The text move simply intends to continue with 4.Nc3 after all, as we provoke and welcome rather than fear the doubled f-pawns.}) 3... Nd7 {Actually Black's most common choice at this juncture, retaining the tension for now.} 4. Nc3 e5 ({White continues not to fear the doubled pawns. Now} 4... Bxf3 5. exf3 {followed by d4-d5, Bd3 and O-O would be our standard plan from the 3...Bxf3 4.exf3 lines.}) 5. h3 $5 ({Angling for a ...Bxf3 exf3 structure, even at the cost of a tempo. If you have some experience of kingside fianchettos, you may though prefer} 5. g3 {followed by Bg2 and O-O, also with a pleasant edge.}) 5... Bh5 $6 6. g4 $1 {This would also be a good response to 5...Bf5?! , expanding with tempo.} Bg6 7. Bg2 {A fine spot for this bishop. White may now play for pressure against b7 with Qb3 or angle to make life uncomfortable for the bishop on g6 with h3-h4.} c6 8. d5 $1 ({White couldn't now resist} 8. h4 $5 {in Loetscher-A.Orlov, Dortmund 2012, where matters wouldn't have been too clear after 8...h6 , but it's also quite possible to continue a light-square policy.}) 8... Be7 ({White hopes for} 8... Ngf6 9. Nh4 {and may also improve the kingside pieces with a quick Nd2.}) 9. Nd2 {This looks like a pretty pleasant edge to us and not a particularly good version of an Old Indian for Black. White's control of f5 is pretty useful, Nde4 is on the way, dxc6 an immediate threat and White can recapture with a piece in the event of any exchange on d5.} *

