1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 ({A fairly rare, but not unimportant move order, and one which both your authors have used on occasion. Black prepares ...e5, and so this is a rare position where we do not advocate} 2. c4 {.}) ({The best move order for the purpose of our repertoire, although you can also prefer} 2. c4 e5 3. d4 {if you don't mind playing against Black's space advantage after} e4 4. Ng5 {.}) ({The move} 2. d4 {simply intends c2-c4, Nc3 and e2-e4 and now play will usually transpose to either our mainline [/variation/35967728/#/3/w] here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options.}) 2... Bg4 {The Wade Defence, named after the legendary Kiwi-English IM, analyst, coach and writer. It used to be a fairly popular choice, but is nowadays rarely seen, quite possibly as engines have affected our views on the bishop-pair and a space advantage,} 3. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although} 3. e4 {is also a decent option if you have some 1.e4 experience, here followed by Nc3 and h2-h3. The text move simply intends to continue with 4.Nc3 after all, as we provoke and welcome rather than fear the doubled f-pawns.}) 3... Nd7 {Actually Black's most common choice at this juncture, retaining the tension for now.} 4. Nc3 e5 ({White continues not to fear the doubled pawns. Now} 4... Bxf3 5. exf3 {followed by d4-d5, Bd3 and O-O would be our standard plan from the 3...Bxf3 4.exf3 lines.}) 5. h3 $5 ({Angling for a ...Bxf3 exf3 structure, even at the cost of a tempo. If you have some experience of kingside fianchettos, you may though prefer} 5. g3 {followed by Bg2 and O-O, also with a pleasant edge.}) 5... Bxf3 6. exf3 {White won't be going Bd3 in a hurry here, but should find e2 a decent spot for this unopposed piece.} Ngf6 7. Be2 ({Simple chess, preparing to castle then break with f3-f4, although} 7. Be3 {must also be a good option, retaining some more aggressive ideas.}) 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 {Preparing to undouble the pawns. White may now exchange twice on e5 or just continue in unhurried fashion with Be3.} exd4 10. Qxd4 c6 11. Bf3 {Clamping down on the d5-square with a pleasant edge. A draw was actually agreed here in Lalic-Scalcione, Cutro 2010, but White should really have continued. The queen can drop back to d2 or via d3 to c2 if needed, Rd1 is imminent and White may then go Be3 or fianchetto on the queenside, thereby leaving Black fairly solid, but also quite cramped.} *

