1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 ({A fairly rare, but not unimportant move order, and one which both your authors have used on occasion. Black prepares ...e5, and so this is a rare position where we do not advocate} 2. c4 {.}) ({The best move order for the purpose of our repertoire, although you can also prefer} 2. c4 e5 3. d4 {if you don't mind playing against Black's space advantage after} e4 4. Ng5 {.}) ({The move} 2. d4 {simply intends c2-c4, Nc3 and e2-e4 and now play will usually transpose to either our mainline [/variation/35967728/#/3/w] here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options.}) 2... Bg4 {The Wade Defence, named after the legendary Kiwi-English IM, analyst, coach and writer. It used to be a fairly popular choice, but is nowadays rarely seen, quite possibly as engines have affected our views on the bishop-pair and a space advantage,} 3. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although} 3. e4 {is also a decent option if you have some 1.e4 experience, here followed by Nc3 and h2-h3. The text move simply intends to continue with 4.Nc3 after all, as we provoke and welcome rather than fear the doubled f-pawns.}) 3... Bxf3 4. exf3 $1 {The right recapture, opening a path for the unopposed light-squared bishop.} g6 5. Bd3 $5 ({A simple way to play, prioritising kingside development and here there’s actually no need to block the e-file with Be2.} 5. Nc3 {has been much more popular when there are a few aggressive ideas if you prefer, including} Bg7 6. h4 $5 {.}) 5... Bg7 6. O-O Nd7 ({Possible, as the d4-pawn isn't hanging in view of} 6... Bxd4 $4 7. Be4 {. White is now set to seize a space advantage with d4-d5 then begin to clamp down on Black's possibilities for counterplay with Re1 and Bf1. Note too that 6...e6 7.d5! e5 8.f4! would undouble the pawns and also generate early pressure.}) 7. d5 $1 Ngf6 ({A consistent advance. Now if} 7... Nc5 {White can either retain the bishop with} 8. Bc2 {or obtain something of a bind with 8.Nc3 Nxd3 9.Qxd3 followed by Bg5 and Rfe1.}) 8. Nc3 {There isn't going to be a better square for the knight than here and now, of course, Black isn't in a position to double White's c-pawns too.} O-O 9. Re1 {Clamping down on e7 ahead of regrouping with Bf1. Observe, too, the cramping strength of the bridgehead on d5.} c6 10. Bf1 $1 {Not such a strange manoeuvre when you realise that White wants to retain the bishop-pair for later, the first goal being to maintain a pawn on d5 while denying Black easy counterplay. Now Be3 and Qd2 will follow, after which White will expand on one flank or the other.} Nc5 11. Be3 ({Retaining control is a much better choice than allowing Black to create a mess with} 11. b4 $6 Nfe4 $1 {.}) 11... Nfd7 12. Qd2 {With the knight on c3 overprotected, everything is now set for expansion with b2-b4.} a5 13. h4 $1 Z0 ({White was in control and now starting to expand in I.Sokolov-Van der Wiel, Dutch Championship, Rotterdam 1998. The simple plan is h4-h5 when White will either cramp Black with h5-h6 ahead of pushing the front f-pawn or go hxg6 then f3-f4. Meanwhile Rad1 will centralise the final piece, and note too that} 13... h5 $6 14. f4 {would only serve to weaken Black's kingside yet further.}) *

