1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 ({A fairly rare, but not unimportant move order, and one which both your authors have used on occasion. Black prepares ...e5, and so this is a rare position where we do not advocate} 2. c4 {.}) ({The best move order for the purpose of our repertoire, although you can also prefer} 2. c4 e5 3. d4 {if you don't mind playing against Black's space advantage after} e4 4. Ng5 {.}) ({The move} 2. d4 {simply intends c2-c4, Nc3 and e2-e4 and now play will usually transpose to either our mainline [/variation/35967728/#/3/w] here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options.}) 2... Bg4 {The Wade Defence, named after the legendary Kiwi-English IM, analyst, coach and writer. It used to be a fairly popular choice, but is nowadays rarely seen, quite possibly as engines have affected our views on the bishop-pair and a space advantage,} 3. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although} 3. e4 {is also a decent option if you have some 1.e4 experience, here followed by Nc3 and h2-h3. The text move simply intends to continue with 4.Nc3 after all, as we provoke and welcome rather than fear the doubled f-pawns.}) 3... Bxf3 4. exf3 $1 {The right recapture, opening a path for the unopposed light-squared bishop.} Nd7 {Staying flexible, but now White can grab some useful space.} 5. d5 $1 {we saw via a} g6 6. Bd3 Bg7 7. O-O {Nd7 d5 move order. An ill-timed break. dxe6! White wastes no time weakening Black on the colour complex which they don't have a bishop for, the light squares. fxe6 g3! The unopposed bishop will clearly be very well placed on g2 (f3-f4 is imminent) or h3. Qf6 Nc3 Hinting at a possible Nb5 now that the queen has moved to try to cover some of Black's light-square weaknesses. O-O-O!? Bg2 With O-O then f3-f4 imminent, only one king was safe and White clearly better in Benjamin-Balinas, Philadelphia 1994, where he would quickly made good use of rushing the a-pawn up the board.} *

