1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 ({A fairly rare, but not unimportant move order, and one which both your authors have used on occasion. Black prepares ...e5, and so this is a rare position where we do not advocate} 2. c4 {.}) ({The best move order for the purpose of our repertoire, although you can also prefer} 2. c4 e5 3. d4 {if you don't mind playing against Black's space advantage after} e4 4. Ng5 {.}) ({The move} 2. d4 {simply intends c2-c4, Nc3 and e2-e4 and now play will usually transpose to either our mainline [/variation/35967728/#/3/w] here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options.}) 2... Bg4 {The Wade Defence, named after the legendary Kiwi-English IM, analyst, coach and writer. It used to be a fairly popular choice, but is nowadays rarely seen, quite possibly as engines have affected our views on the bishop-pair and a space advantage,} 3. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although} 3. e4 {is also a decent option if you have some 1.e4 experience, here followed by Nc3 and h2-h3. The text move simply intends to continue with 4.Nc3 after all, as we provoke and welcome rather than fear the doubled f-pawns.}) 3... Bxf3 4. exf3 $1 {The right recapture, opening a path for the unopposed light-squared bishop.} e6 5. Nc3 {Logical development as well as support for any early d4-d5 advance.} g6 6. d5 $1 exd5 ({Threatening light-square ruin after all and here ideas of h2-h4-h5 are very much on the agenda, as well as} 6... e5 7. f4 {.}) 7. cxd5 ({Here White opted for} 7. Nxd5 $5 {and a pull in Smejkal-Miles, Ter Apel 1987, but retaining a bridgehead on d5 was very much possible too.}) 7... Bg7 8. Be2 {With the e-file open, there's no real need to place the bishop on d3 here as White gets ready to castle.} Nf6 9. O-O O-O 10. Qb3 $1 {Pressing on b7 and leaving White with a pretty pleasant edge. Rd1 then Be3 will maintain full control after which White can look to expand and/or attack on the queenside, possibly prefaced by tidying up the kingside with Bf1, g2-g3 and Bg2.} *

