1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 $1 ({A fairly rare, but not unimportant move order, and one which both your authors have used on occasion. Black prepares ...e5, and so this is a rare position where we do not advocate} 2. c4 {.}) ({The best move order for the purpose of our repertoire, although you can also prefer} 2. c4 e5 3. d4 {if you don't mind playing against Black's space advantage after} e4 4. Ng5 {.}) ({The move} 2. d4 {simply intends c2-c4, Nc3 and e2-e4 and now play will usually transpose to either our mainline [/variation/35967728/#/3/w] here after} Nf6 3. c4 {or to the realm of 6b [/variation/35967761/#/4/w] after 2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.c4 . There are though two independent options.}) 2... Bg4 {The Wade Defence, named after the legendary Kiwi-English IM, analyst, coach and writer. It used to be a fairly popular choice, but is nowadays rarely seen, quite possibly as engines have affected our views on the bishop-pair and a space advantage,} 3. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although} 3. e4 {is also a decent option if you have some 1.e4 experience, here followed by Nc3 and h2-h3. The text move simply intends to continue with 4.Nc3 after all, as we provoke and welcome rather than fear the doubled f-pawns.}) 3... Bxf3 4. exf3 $1 {The right recapture, opening a path for the unopposed light-squared bishop.} c6 {Black's most popular choice, trying to retain a fair degree of flexibility.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 ({Clearly the best square for this knight as White again looks towards a cramping early d4-d5 advance, such as with} 5... g6 6. d5 {(6.h4!? is also pretty tempting)} Bg7 7. Bd3 {followed by O-O, Re1 and Bf1 a la Ivan Sokolov.}) 6. d5 $1 ({Consistent and good, although here the engines confirm that even} 6. g4 $5 {is a pretty decent move - space and freedom to manoeuvre matter!}) 6... g6 7. Bd3 {Keeping the bishop as active as possible while preparing to press down the e-file after O-O and Re1.} Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 a6 $5 ({Completing the ideal set-up and now} 9... Nbd7 10. Bf1 {would take us back into Sokolov-Van der Wiel and a position [/variation/35967724/#/10/w] we considered via a 4...g6 5.Bd3 move order.}) 10. Bf1 $1 ({This hinted at expansion with ...b5 in Illescas Cordoba-Spangenberg, Buenos Aires 1993, and now} 10. a4 $6 a5 {would fix the queenside in a way only likely to help Black.}) 10... b5 $5 ({Consistent and also a good way to shore up d5. Now} 10... cxd5 11. cxd5 b5 12. a3 $1 {followed by Be3 should be quite pleasant for White - just think of the havoc a knight coming to d4 could wreak.}) 11. Qb3 $5 cxd5 ({Cutting out ...b4 ideas, threatening dxc6 all while supporting d5, and it would now take a brave opponent to allow} 11... bxc4 $6 12. Qb7 $1 Nbd7 13. dxc6 {.}) 12. cxb5 $1 {The star point of White's last, threatening Nxd5 and especially radically arguing that White's queenside play is stronger than anything Black can muster in the centre. That shouldn't be too big a surprise considering that the d-pawns are doubled and the e4-square in White's control. Now a2-a4 and even Bf4 may follow, while ...d4 can be met by Ne4.} axb5 13. Nxb5 $1 {The most useful recapture. The engines like White and so do we, with the simple plan of Bd2, a2-a4 and Rec1 leaving White pretty well placed on the queenside, as well as with two handy connected passed pawns for a little later in the game.} *

