1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Bf5 $5 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {This creative, independent choice has enjoyed some relative fashionability over the past 15 or so years.} 4. Nc3 g6 ({Sticking with sensible development. If Black now does something strange, White can continue with Qb3, and note too that} 4... Nbd7 $2 {would no longer be especially wise on account of} 5. Nh4 $1 {followed by} Be4 6. f3 {or 5...Bg4 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 with a clear early advantage for White.}) {Black's standard follow-up, going in for King's Indian-like play after all.} 5. Qb3 {As so often, the main downside to the early ...Bf5 proves to be an attack on b7.} b6 6. h3 $1 {This advance is especially tempting when Black has weakened the long light-square diagonal. White simply wants to obtain a souped-up fianchetto type set-up with g2-g4 followed by Bg2.} c5 $6 7. g4 {Expanding with tempo ahead of closing the centre with d4-d5.} Bd7 8. d5 $1 {This may seem inconsistent with the long diagonal, but think too about what White has gained! This is quite simply a pretty bad version of a Benoni for Black, and already e2-e4-e5 might quickly land.} Bg7 9. e4 e5 $5 10. Be3 {White was clearly for choice in Vinchev-Saviano, correspondence 2012, having the option of gradually expanding on the queenside with b2-b4 while keeping Black squeezed on the kingside, a sector of the board in which White may expand too, with Be2 and Nd2 likely to be useful moves in any case.} *

