1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Bf5 $5 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {This creative, independent choice has enjoyed some relative fashionability over the past 15 or so years.} 4. Nc3 g6 ({Sticking with sensible development. If Black now does something strange, White can continue with Qb3, and note too that} 4... Nbd7 $2 {would no longer be especially wise on account of} 5. Nh4 $1 {followed by} Be4 6. f3 {or 5...Bg4 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 with a clear early advantage for White.}) {Black's standard follow-up, going in for King's Indian-like play after all.} 5. Qb3 {As so often, the main downside to the early ...Bf5 proves to be an attack on b7.} b6 6. h3 $1 {This advance is especially tempting when Black has weakened the long light-square diagonal. White simply wants to obtain a souped-up fianchetto type set-up with g2-g4 followed by Bg2.} Nc6 7. d5 $5 {)} ({White has usually gone} 7. g4 {here, but kicking the c6-knight is quite tempting and if Black is now careless, White might get to play g2-g4 at an opportune moment.}) 7... Na5 8. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 ({A discombobulating check as} 8... Qd7 9. Qd1 {would slightly misplace the black queen and leave g2-g4 imminent after all, or if} Nxc4 $2 10. e4 {.}) 9. Qc2 Bg7 ({Nothing is now going to prevent White from expanding with e2-e4. Note that the c-pawn is taboo here, with the greedy} 9... Nxc4 $6 10. e4 {unwise for Black, and if} Na5 $2 11. b4 Nb7 12. Nb5 {.}) 10. e4 {White must be slightly for choice. It's once again not too clear what the knight on a5 is doing, while White will complete development with Be2, O-O and Be3 or Bg5. Sooner or later Black will surely have to go ...c6 before they are overrun after b2-b4 on the queenside, following which White can either maintain the bridgehead on d5 or exchange on c6 with a fairly decent Maroczy Bind set-up.} *

