1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Bf5 $5 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {This creative, independent choice has enjoyed some relative fashionability over the past 15 or so years.} 4. Nc3 g6 ({Sticking with sensible development. If Black now does something strange, White can continue with Qb3, and note too that} 4... Nbd7 $2 {would no longer be especially wise on account of} 5. Nh4 $1 {followed by} Be4 6. f3 {or 5...Bg4 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 with a clear early advantage for White.}) {Black's standard follow-up, going in for King's Indian-like play after all.} 5. Qb3 {As so often, the main downside to the early ...Bf5 proves to be an attack on b7.} b6 6. h3 $1 {This advance is especially tempting when Black has weakened the long light-square diagonal. White simply wants to obtain a souped-up fianchetto type set-up with g2-g4 followed by Bg2.} Bg7 {Consistent, if not forced.} 7. g4 {Thematic expansion ahead of obtaining a big centre with e2-e4.} Bd7 8. e4 {) Once again it's a pretty impressive centre and Black must even watch out that he doesn't find himself badly suffocated after e4-e5.} O-O {Wisely freeing e8 for the knight in the event of e4-e5.} 9. Be3 {It definitely doesn't do any harm to overprotect d4 and so take some of the wind out of the sails of any ...Nc6 approach.} Nc6 $6 10. Qd1 $5 ({As tried in Lazavik-Ibarra Jerez, Chessable Masters Play-In (rapid) 2023, where White was happy to go} 10. d5 {and gain an edge. We might even play for more.}) {Everything is secure in the centre. White may follow up with Bg2 and O-O or even look for something more aggressive after Be2 and Qd2.} 10... e5 {Presumably the point of Black's play, but this won't be a great version of a King's Indian for them.} 11. d5 Ne7 12. Be2 {White will continue with Nd2 and Qc2, meeting any ...Ne8 and ...f5 break with f2-f3. As White hasn't castled short, this is a good version of a King's Indian for us. The king will come to the queenside, after which White may look to go forwards on the kingside, while if Black does ever go in for ...f4; Bf2, White's long-term advantage on the queenside with b2-b4 and c4-c5 will be a major factor even if we have already castled long.} *

