1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Bf5 $5 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {This creative, independent choice has enjoyed some relative fashionability over the past 15 or so years.} 4. Nc3 g6 ({Sticking with sensible development. If Black now does something strange, White can continue with Qb3, and note too that} 4... Nbd7 $2 {would no longer be especially wise on account of} 5. Nh4 $1 {followed by} Be4 6. f3 {or 5...Bg4 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 with a clear early advantage for White.}) {Black's standard follow-up, going in for King's Indian-like play after all.} 5. Qb3 {As so often, the main downside to the early ...Bf5 proves to be an attack on b7.} b6 6. h3 $1 {This advance is especially tempting when Black has weakened the long light-square diagonal. White simply wants to obtain a souped-up fianchetto type set-up with g2-g4 followed by Bg2.} Bg7 {Consistent, if not forced.} 7. g4 {Thematic expansion ahead of obtaining a big centre with e2-e4.} Bd7 8. e4 {Once again it's a pretty impressive centre and Black must even watch out that he doesn't find himself badly suffocated after e4-e5.} O-O {Wisely freeing e8 for the knight in the event of e4-e5.} 9. Be3 {It definitely doesn't do any harm to overprotect d4 and so take some of the wind out of the sails of any ...Nc6 approach.} c5 $5 10. Qc2 $5 (10. d5 e6 {has twice led to quite a murky position in practice, so we'd prefer to drop the queen back to a safe spot, waiting for 10...Nc6 before going 11.d5 while preparing another Maroczy style set-up.}) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nc6 12. O-O-O $1 Z0 ({The position isn't completely clear, but we'd prefer to be White who has kept d4 secure and will meet} 12... Nxd4 {with} 13. Bxd4 {. The king should be pretty safe on b1 and it's not at all hard to imagine Black quickly being overrun in the centre (e4-e5) and on the kingside once White has got in f2-f4 and Be2.}) *

