1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Bf5 $5 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {This creative, independent choice has enjoyed some relative fashionability over the past 15 or so years.} 4. Nc3 g6 ({Sticking with sensible development. If Black now does something strange, White can continue with Qb3, and note too that} 4... Nbd7 $2 {would no longer be especially wise on account of} 5. Nh4 $1 {followed by} Be4 6. f3 {or 5...Bg4 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 with a clear early advantage for White.}) {Black's standard follow-up, going in for King's Indian-like play after all.} 5. Qb3 {As so often, the main downside to the early ...Bf5 proves to be an attack on b7.} Qc8 {This is arguably less weakening and has been fractionally more popular than advancing the b-pawn.} 6. h3 $5 {Preparing to drive Black backwards with g2-g4.} h5 $6 {Preventing g2-g4, but also weakening the g5-square.} 7. c5 $1 {A perhaps unexpected, but also strong advance. Not for the first time in this repertoire, we'll see White aiming to quickly exploit the main downside to ...h5 by landing a knight on g5.} Bg7 8. Ng5 {With a certain threat.} O-O 9. e4 {Another good point behind having the knight on g5 is quick to reveal itself.} Bd7 10. Be3 {This left White somewhat for choice in Korobov-Mikhailovsky, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023. White will simply recapture in the event of an exchange on c5 and will likely develop the light-squared bishop to c4, thereby increasing the pressure against f7. With Black having weakened their kingside, O-O-O followed by a kingside pawn advance is tempting, although White might also just castle short and then advance with f2-f4.} *

