1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Bf5 $5 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {This creative, independent choice has enjoyed some relative fashionability over the past 15 or so years.} 4. Nc3 g6 ({Sticking with sensible development. If Black now does something strange, White can continue with Qb3, and note too that} 4... Nbd7 $2 {would no longer be especially wise on account of} 5. Nh4 $1 {followed by} Be4 6. f3 {or 5...Bg4 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 with a clear early advantage for White.}) {Black's standard follow-up, going in for King's Indian-like play after all.} 5. Qb3 {As so often, the main downside to the early ...Bf5 proves to be an attack on b7.} Qc8 {This is arguably less weakening and has been fractionally more popular than advancing the b-pawn.} 6. h3 $5 {Preparing to drive Black backwards with g2-g4.} Bg7 {In the fairly limited testing thus far of this position, Black has tended to continue development so.} (6... c5 7. d5 {Denying Black any central counterplay ahead of expanding on the kingside.} Bg7 8. g4 Bd7 9. e4 O-O 10. Bf4 {Once again White stood clearly better in Radjabov-Volokitin, Cap d'Agde (rapid) 2006, being all set to complete development with Be2 and probably O-O, while already the key pawn break e4-e5 was hanging over Black like the sword of Damocles.}) 7. g4 {Pushing Black backwards as White again succeeds in conquering the e4-square.} Bd7 8. e4 h5 $6 ({Once again White constructs a pretty impressive array of pawns. Now Be3 then Be2 or Bg2 will follow, that is assuming Black deals with the immediate threat of} 8... Z0 9. e5 {.}) {Attempting to close the kingside, but the knight won't be especially happy once chased back to h7.} 9. g5 ({Even stronger than} 9. e5 $5 {here, as White plays to suffocate the black position.}) 9... Nh7 10. Be3 {Black is pretty cramped, something which White certainly isn't, and now everything is set for White to castle queenside.} O-O 11. O-O-O c5 $5 {White was content to exchange on c5 here in Szymanski-Haeusler, correspondence 2009, but we'd prefer to keep Black out of the d4-square for good.} 12. d5 $1 {While Black does have the ...b5 break to play for, White should be able to ignore that and meanwhile Nh4 and f2-f4 will be a pretty powerful advance on the other wing followed by Qc2 or Bd3 and f4-f5.} *

