{Activating the dormant rook adds strength to the e4-e5 push and with Bh6 also on the cards, White is surely in control and somewhat for choice.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Bf5 $5 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {This creative, independent choice has enjoyed some relative fashionability over the past 15 or so years.} 4. Nc3 g6 ({Sticking with sensible development. If Black now does something strange, White can continue with Qb3, and note too that} 4... Nbd7 $2 {would no longer be especially wise on account of} 5. Nh4 $1 {followed by} Be4 6. f3 {or 5...Bg4 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 with a clear early advantage for White.}) {Black's standard follow-up, going in for King's Indian-like play after all.} 5. Qb3 {As so often, the main downside to the early ...Bf5 proves to be an attack on b7.} Qc8 {This is arguably less weakening and has been fractionally more popular than advancing the b-pawn.} 6. h3 $5 {Preparing to drive Black backwards with g2-g4.} Bg7 {In the fairly limited testing thus far of this position, Black has tended to continue development so.} (6... c5 7. d5 {Denying Black any central counterplay ahead of expanding on the kingside.} Bg7 8. g4 Bd7 9. e4 O-O 10. Bf4 {Once again White stood clearly better in Radjabov-Volokitin, Cap d'Agde (rapid) 2006, being all set to complete development with Be2 and probably O-O, while already the key pawn break e4-e5 was hanging over Black like the sword of Damocles.}) 7. g4 {Pushing Black backwards as White again succeeds in conquering the e4-square.} Bd7 8. e4 O-O ({Once again White constructs a pretty impressive array of pawns. Now Be3 then Be2 or Bg2 will follow, that is assuming Black deals with the immediate threat of} 8... Z0 9. e5 {.}) 9. Be3 ({Enabling White to consider castling queenside and this tension-retaining developing move seems even better than going in for} 9. e5 Ne8 {.}) 9... Nc6 (9... c5 $6 10. dxc5 $1 {Even stronger than 10.d5 in this particular case, since White threatens to win a pawn and hasn't forgotten about the key e4-e5 break.} dxc5 $2 11. e5 $1 Ne8 12. Nd5 {Without a good way to defend e7 due to the pressure against c5, Black was simply getting crushed in Kazhgaleyev-Wang Hao, Almaty (blitz) 2016.}) 10. Be2 {Sensible development. There's no need to rush to castle long until we've seen how Black is going to set up and attempt to break free.} a5 {Angling for ...a5-a4.} 11. Qd1 $1 {Wisely regrouping the queen who will head to d2. Now White will always be able to keep the right lines closed on the queenside.} a4 12. Qd2 a3 13. b3 Nb4 ({Keeping the position closed, just as} 13... e5 14. d5 {now would. White may still play for a d4-d5 and c4-c5 advance, although it should also be possible to place the king on f1 and look to attack on the kingside.}) 14. Rd1 $1 ({White now decided that it was time to get on with things and went} 14. e5 $5 Ne8 15. Ne4 {in Eljanov-Volokitin, Dagomys 2008. A calmer approach would also have been quite sensible.}) *

