e and this tension-retaining developing move seems even better than going in for} 9. e5 Ne8 {.}) 9... Nc6 (9... c5 $6 10. dxc5 $1 {Even stronger than 10.d5 in this particular case, since White threatens to win a pawn and hasn't forgotten about the key e4-e5 break.} dxc5 $2 11. e5 $1 Ne8 12. Nd5 {Without a good way to defend e7 due to the pressure against c5, Black was simply getting crushed in Kazhgaleyev-Wang Hao, Almaty (blitz) 2016.}) 10. Be2 {Sensible development. There's no need to rush to castle long until we've seen how Black is going to set up and attempt to break free.} e5 $6 {The obvious try, but unfortunately for Black, White is ready for it.} 11. d5 $1 Nd4 $5 ({The usual riposte to ...e5. Now} 11... Ne7 {would be well met by} 12. Nd2 {or even 12.O-O-O!? with a pretty good version of a King's Indian for White.}) 12. Nxd4 {White should not be bluffed and should just take the pawn.} exd4 13. Bxd4 Nxe4 $6 {The point of Black's play, but there's a flaw.} 14. Bxg7 Nc5 15. Qd1 Kxg7 16. b4 $1 ({Here} 16. Qd4+ {was pretty strong in Lalic-Scalcione, Trieste 2008, and there was something even better.}) {Clearly Black can't come to a4 this way.} 16... Na6 17. Qd4+ f6 18. c5 {Black's queenside pieces are clumsily placed, leaving White doing extremely well, being ready to castle then crash through with c5-c6.} *

