1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Nbd7 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {Black insists on ...e5 after all, and goes for an Old Indian Defence.} 4. Nc3 e5 ({Natural development, as well as necessary preparation for e2-e4. Now} 4... g6 5. e4 {would take play back into King's Indian waters after all.}) {The Old Indian response and now Black will likely follow up with ...Be7, ...c6 and ...O-O.} 5. e4 Be7 ({Thematic play. Now Black's second most popular move has actually been} 5... g6 {when} 6. Bd3 $5 {would take play back towards the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/b/1.1].}) ({The most common choice, although play is very similar after} 5... c6 {. Then} 6. Bd3 $5 {is again a rare choice, not least compared to the standard move 6.Be2, but one in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian. Now} g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. d5 {would be very King's Indianesque, and we'll see 6...Be7 7.O-O by transposition in our mainline [/variation/35967743/#/7/w].}) 6. Bd3 $5 {Our favourite square for the bishop in such structures, if also quite an unusual choice here. White may now follow up with d4-d5, since ...Nc5 can be met by Bc2, although it's also very possible to maintain the tension, which will usually lead to Black exchanging on d4 and a Maroczy Bind set-up occurring.} h6 {Black hints at Black Lion style expansion with ...g5, but such a policy works better when White's centre is a less impressive one with the c-pawn still back on c2.} 7. O-O {Staying calm and refusing to fear any kingside advance.} g5 $6 8. Be3 c6 ({Pretty much completing development and now Black would gain little from} 8... Ng4 9. Bd2 {. Meanwhile, White may play for centralisation with Qc2 and Rad1, after which the c4-c5 break may be on, or simply expand on the queenside with Rb1 and b2-b4.}) 9. Qc2 ({Here White went} 9. a4 {in Radhey Derling-M.Jones, correspondence 2019, where} a5 $1 {would have been a thematic and good response.}) 9... Nh5 $5 ({Maintaining the tension (} 9... exd4 $6 10. Nxd4 {would leave Black looking rather weak on f5), while freeing d1 for the queen's rook. Note too that 9...g4? 10.Nh4! would be very good for White, since the tactics backfire for Black on d6 after 10...Nxe4? 11.Nxe4 .}) {Attempting to intimidate White on the kingside.} 10. Rad1 Nf4 ({But White can be resolute and stick to the task. Now c4-c5 is on, since ...dxc5; dxe5 would be a favourable line-opening trade for White, and} 10... g4 11. Nd2 {is nothing to fear.}) 11. c5 $1 Z0 ({Ignoring Black's play to open up the centre. Now} 11... Z0 12. cxd6 Bxd6 13. Ne2 {is the plan, opening the position to exploit White's lead in development while beginning to quickly undermine Black's grip on the f4-square. White stands at least clearly better.}) *

