1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Nbd7 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {Black insists on ...e5 after all, and goes for an Old Indian Defence.} 4. Nc3 e5 ({Natural development, as well as necessary preparation for e2-e4. Now} 4... g6 5. e4 {would take play back into King's Indian waters after all.}) {The Old Indian response and now Black will likely follow up with ...Be7, ...c6 and ...O-O.} 5. e4 Be7 ({Thematic play. Now Black's second most popular move has actually been} 5... g6 {when} 6. Bd3 $5 {would take play back towards the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/b/1.1].}) ({The most common choice, although play is very similar after} 5... c6 {. Then} 6. Bd3 $5 {is again a rare choice, not least compared to the standard move 6.Be2, but one in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian. Now} g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. d5 {would be very King's Indianesque, and we'll see 6...Be7 7.O-O by transposition in our mainline [/variation/35967743/#/7/w].}) 6. Bd3 $5 {Our favourite square for the bishop in such structures, if also quite an unusual choice here. White may now follow up with d4-d5, since ...Nc5 can be met by Bc2, although it's also very possible to maintain the tension, which will usually lead to Black exchanging on d4 and a Maroczy Bind set-up occurring.} O-O ({A sensible choice, as would be} 6... c6 7. O-O O-O {with a transposition.}) 7. O-O ({Maintaining the tension, although if you quite like an early closed centre,} 7. d5 Nc5 8. Bc2 a5 9. O-O {is also a reasonable option.}) 7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Re8 ({As so often, the Maroczy Bind denies Black easy counterplay and now White can preserve the light-squared bishop with Bc2 (or with} 8... Ne5 9. Be2 {), may well find h2-h3 a useful move to keep Black out of g4 and can then begin to expand with f2-f4.}) 9. h3 $5 ({This was seen back in Shoosmith-Nimzowitsch, Ostend 1907, no less where} 9. b3 {was pretty sensible and so would have been taking control of g4.}) 9... Ne5 10. Be2 {Preserving the bishop and keeping pieces on will in general help to keep Black a little cramped.} c5 $5 11. Nf5 $5 ({A thematic advance in such positions, often associated with the ...b5 advance, but here White is better after} 11. Nc2 {or going forwards.}) 11... Bxf5 ({Now if} 11... Bf8 {White may reset with Ng3 followed by a later f2-f4, so Black might prefer to exchange.}) 12. exf5 {White has a definite edge, in part thanks to the hole on d5. There's always Be3 to cover d4 if needed and meanwhile g2-g4 will be a pretty strong advance. If White could then get in g4-g5 and f2-f4 followed by Nd5 Black's position would quickly become rather critical.} *

