1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Nbd7 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {Black insists on ...e5 after all, and goes for an Old Indian Defence.} 4. Nc3 e5 ({Natural development, as well as necessary preparation for e2-e4. Now} 4... g6 5. e4 {would take play back into King's Indian waters after all.}) {The Old Indian response and now Black will likely follow up with ...Be7, ...c6 and ...O-O.} 5. e4 Be7 ({Thematic play. Now Black's second most popular move has actually been} 5... g6 {when} 6. Bd3 $5 {would take play back towards the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/b/1.1].}) ({The most common choice, although play is very similar after} 5... c6 {. Then} 6. Bd3 $5 {is again a rare choice, not least compared to the standard move 6.Be2, but one in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian. Now} g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. d5 {would be very King's Indianesque, and we'll see 6...Be7 7.O-O by transposition in our mainline [/variation/35967743/#/7/w].}) 6. Bd3 $5 {Our favourite square for the bishop in such structures, if also quite an unusual choice here. White may now follow up with d4-d5, since ...Nc5 can be met by Bc2, although it's also very possible to maintain the tension, which will usually lead to Black exchanging on d4 and a Maroczy Bind set-up occurring.} O-O ({A sensible choice, as would be} 6... c6 7. O-O O-O {with a transposition.}) 7. O-O ({Maintaining the tension, although if you quite like an early closed centre,} 7. d5 Nc5 8. Bc2 a5 9. O-O {is also a reasonable option.}) 7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Nc5 ({As so often, the Maroczy Bind denies Black easy counterplay and now White can preserve the light-squared bishop with Bc2 (or with} 8... Ne5 9. Be2 {), may well find h2-h3 a useful move to keep Black out of g4 and can then begin to expand with f2-f4.}) 9. Bc2 {) Preserving a useful piece. Now White may expand with not only h2-h3, f2-f4 and Qf3, but even b2-b4 if allowed.} c6 10. b4 $5 Na6 $5 ({Here} 10... Ne6 11. Nf5 {left White in control and doing well in Ravizza-Bericat, correspondence 1969, so Black should possibly try a more critical retreat.}) 11. Rb1 $1 c5 $5 ({The other possible transition of the position is also not to be feared: Improving the rook. White might well now manage to get something going on the kingside in the event of} 11... Nxb4 12. Rxb4 c5 13. Rb3 {.}) 12. bxc5 Nxc5 ({Opening the b-file and hoping to take full control of the position after} 12... dxc5 13. Ndb5 $1 {.}) 13. Bb2 {Even here White is hardly doing badly from a control perspective. The bishops on b2 and c2 bristle with potential attacking menace and White would like to expand on the kingside with f2-f4 and Qf3, after which a well-prepared e4-e5 might wreak mayhem.} *

