1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d6 {A fairly unusual choice at this point, but it might be used by opponents who meet 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 with 2...d6 . Now we'd again like to prevent ...e5.} 3. d4 Nbd7 ({This advance is in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian and now White would again ignore} 3... Bg4 {with} 4. Nc3 {. The majority of your games will likely go 3...g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 when we're back in the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/w].}) {Black insists on ...e5 after all, and goes for an Old Indian Defence.} 4. Nc3 e5 ({Natural development, as well as necessary preparation for e2-e4. Now} 4... g6 5. e4 {would take play back into King's Indian waters after all.}) {The Old Indian response and now Black will likely follow up with ...Be7, ...c6 and ...O-O.} 5. e4 Be7 ({Thematic play. Now Black's second most popular move has actually been} 5... g6 {when} 6. Bd3 $5 {would take play back towards the realm of Chapter Five [/variation/36296491/#/5/b/1.1].}) ({The most common choice, although play is very similar after} 5... c6 {. Then} 6. Bd3 $5 {is again a rare choice, not least compared to the standard move 6.Be2, but one in keeping with our approach against the King's Indian. Now} g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. d5 {would be very King's Indianesque, and we'll see 6...Be7 7.O-O by transposition in our mainline [/variation/35967743/#/7/w].}) 6. Bd3 $5 {Our favourite square for the bishop in such structures, if also quite an unusual choice here. White may now follow up with d4-d5, since ...Nc5 can be met by Bc2, although it's also very possible to maintain the tension, which will usually lead to Black exchanging on d4 and a Maroczy Bind set-up occurring.} O-O ({A sensible choice, as would be} 6... c6 7. O-O O-O {with a transposition.}) 7. O-O ({Maintaining the tension, although if you quite like an early closed centre,} 7. d5 Nc5 8. Bc2 a5 9. O-O {is also a reasonable option.}) 7... c6 {Black's main choice by some margin, maintaining the tension while playing all the standard Old Indian moves.} ({After} 7... Re8 {the reply} 8. Re1 {is very likely after} c6 {to transpose to our mainline [/variation/35967748/#/8/b] with 7...c6 8.Re1 Re8, but with the rook committed to e8 and the pawn still on c7, White might also be tempted to close the centre with 8.d5!? a5 9.h3 Keeping Black out of g4 and so facilitating Be3 when ...Ng4 will no longer be possible. 9...h6 10.Be3 Nh7 11.a3 Beginning the thematic queenside advance, although the engines' preference for 11.Kh2!? should also be noted, intending 11...Ng5 12.Ng1! , which should keep Black fully at bay on the kingside. 11...Ng5 12.Ne1! Keeping pieces on, thereby continuing to leave Black's position a little congested. 12...Nf8 This saw Black limbering up for ...Ng6 and a sacrifice on h3 in Nikologorsky-L.Ivanovic, Herceg Novi 2008. Of course, White wants to advance on the queenside with b2-b4 and c4-c5, but that doesn't have to be rushed and here a prophylactic approach would have been effective: 13.h4! Ngh7 14.g3 The knight can come to g2 and there's always f2-f3 if required to help the defence too. This rather stymies Black's knights and kingside play in general, leaving White clearly for choice thanks to the queenside roller.}) 8. Re1 ({Maintaining the tension and reinforcing e4 in the event of any exchange on d4. It should be said that this is not White's only good plan, with} 8. b3 {followed by Bb2 one decent alternative and there's always}) (8. d5 {too, of course, if you prefer to play with a closed centre.}) 8... a6 9. d5 $1 ({Black prepares ...b5 and would also quite like to see} 9. a4 a5 {, fixing the queenside, after which ...exd4; Nxd4 Nc5 would likely follow.}) {It's high time to close the centre and so delay ...b5 by a move.} 9... Nc5 10. Bc2 ({White elected to keep the bishop in touch with potential developments on both flanks with} 10. Bf1 $5 {in Zubov-Vasiliev, Rodatychi 2006, where the more standard retreat was also possible.}) 10... cxd5 11. cxd5 {The standard recapture, not allowing the structure to become unbalanced.} b5 $6 12. b4 $1 {A powerful advance as White seizes the initiative on the queenside.} Ncd7 13. a4 Z0 ({Black is already under some pressure, with b5 en prise and} 13... bxa4 14. Bxa4 {set to eye up the weakness of the c6-square.}) *

