ld Indian moves.} ({After} 7... Re8 {the reply} 8. Re1 {is very likely after} c6 {to transpose to our mainline [/variation/35967748/#/8/b] with 7...c6 8.Re1 Re8, but with the rook committed to e8 and the pawn still on c7, White might also be tempted to close the centre with 8.d5!? a5 9.h3 Keeping Black out of g4 and so facilitating Be3 when ...Ng4 will no longer be possible. 9...h6 10.Be3 Nh7 11.a3 Beginning the thematic queenside advance, although the engines' preference for 11.Kh2!? should also be noted, intending 11...Ng5 12.Ng1! , which should keep Black fully at bay on the kingside. 11...Ng5 12.Ne1! Keeping pieces on, thereby continuing to leave Black's position a little congested. 12...Nf8 This saw Black limbering up for ...Ng6 and a sacrifice on h3 in Nikologorsky-L.Ivanovic, Herceg Novi 2008. Of course, White wants to advance on the queenside with b2-b4 and c4-c5, but that doesn't have to be rushed and here a prophylactic approach would have been effective: 13.h4! Ngh7 14.g3 The knight can come to g2 and there's always f2-f3 if required to help the defence too. This rather stymies Black's knights and kingside play in general, leaving White clearly for choice thanks to the queenside roller.}) 8. Re1 ({Maintaining the tension and reinforcing e4 in the event of any exchange on d4. It should be said that this is not White's only good plan, with} 8. b3 {followed by Bb2 one decent alternative and there's always}) (8. d5 {too, of course, if you prefer to play with a closed centre.}) 8... Re8 9. h3 $5 {Continuing to maintain the tension while facilitating Be3 with ...Ng4 cut out.} Qc7 10. d5 $1 {Closing the centre only now that Black's queen is a potential target on the c-file. White would love to follow up with Be3, b2-b4, Qb3 and Rac1, thereby generating potential heavy pressure on the queenside.} c5 11. Be3 Nf8 12. a3 $1 Ng6 ({It's high time to begin the thematic queenside advance. And note that} 12... a5 $6 13. b4 $1 {would powerfully open lines after all.}) 13. b4 b6 14. Rb1 {White enjoyed a pleasant edge in Martinovic-Goric, Zenica 2009, where he was always able to meet ...Nf4 with Bf1 (if not Bxf4 exf4; e4-e5), thereby keeping everything under control on the kingside. On the other flank, a probing Qa4 may be useful, as can be Bc2-a4 if there's time (the prophylactic Kh2 and g2-g3 isn't a ridiculous idea on the kingside), and there's absolutely no need to rush with an exchange on c5, which may even be useful prefaced by Re2-b2.} *

