1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Nf6 $6 {A premature involvement of the knight, if a surprise choice which you may get to face at blitz or rapid.} 3. e5 $1 {Taking up the challenge.} Nd5 4. c4 ({Now} 4. d4 d6 {would be a well-established line of the Alekhine, but White can exploit the move order to do better than that.}) {Driving the knight onwards while intending to follow up with d2-d4 unless there's c4-c5 available with tempo.} 4... Nb6 5. c5 $1 {A strong advance, refusing to allow the knight any respite.} Nd5 6. Bc4 {White enjoys free and easy development and is already doing pretty well, with d2-d4 and/or Nc3 set to follow, all the while as the pawn on g6 looks rather out of place.} c6 7. Nc3 $1 Nxc3 $2 ({Continuing to force the pace. Now} 7... d6 8. exd6 exd6 9. O-O $1 {would give White a large lead in development and dangerous initiative, but the alternative is even worse for Black.}) 8. dxc3 $1 {Opening lines and increasing the central pressure is more important than recapturing towards the centre in this case.} Bg7 9. Ng5 $1 O-O ({Now} 9... e6 10. Ne4 {would be positionally atrocious for Black, but the alternative allows a tactic.}) 10. Nxf7 $1 {Cashing in by exploiting the pressure down the d-file.} Rxf7 11. e6 Rf8 12. exd7+ Kh8 13. dxc8=Q Qxd1+ 14. Kxd1 Rxc8 15. Be3 {The forcing sequence came to an end, leaving White a pawn to the good and with a mighty unopposed bishop to boot in Martinez Ramirez-Avila Pavas, Havana 2018.} *

