1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Nf6 $6 {A premature involvement of the knight, if a surprise choice which you may get to face at blitz or rapid.} 3. e5 $1 {Taking up the challenge.} Nd5 4. c4 ({Now} 4. d4 d6 {would be a well-established line of the Alekhine, but White can exploit the move order to do better than that.}) {Driving the knight onwards while intending to follow up with d2-d4 unless there's c4-c5 available with tempo.} 4... Nb6 5. c5 $1 {A strong advance, refusing to allow the knight any respite.} Nd5 6. Bc4 {White enjoys free and easy development and is already doing pretty well, with d2-d4 and/or Nc3 set to follow, all the while as the pawn on g6 looks rather out of place.} e6 7. d4 {Threatening positional ruin with Bxd5 then Bg5.} d6 8. Bxd5 $5 {A simple approach. White continues to play for Bg5 and a fairly large positional plus.} exd5 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Bxe7 {Consistent while also usefully denying Black use of the bishop-pair.} Qxe7 11. Nc3 Be6 12. Qb3 {With pressure against b7 and d5, as well as ideas of cxd6 cxd6; Nb5 White, who can easily castle kingside at a moment's notice, stood clearly better in Eingorn-Kupreichik, Muenster 1996.} *

