1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Nf6 $6 {A premature involvement of the knight, if a surprise choice which you may get to face at blitz or rapid.} 3. e5 $1 {Taking up the challenge.} Nh5 {The North Sea Defence, a sometime favourite of the world number one's at blitz and bullet.} 4. d4 {Classical play as White helps himself to the control of the centre on offer.} d6 5. Bc4 $1 c6 ({White's best move, generating some pressure against f7 and so enabling us to meet} 5... Bg7 $6 {with} 6. Ng5 {, threatening both Nxf7 and g2-g4.}) 6. O-O ({White has often proved unable to resist} 6. Ng5 {, but the calm}) (6. O-O {is at least as good, continuing to offer Black the opportunity to err with} Bg7 7. Ng5 {.}) 6... d5 7. Bd3 {Cutting out any ...Bf5 possibilities for now while intending not just h2-h3, but to fight for the initiative with c2-c4.} Bg4 8. h3 {Forcing the pace as White doesn't mind the queen being developed.} Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Ng7 ({And now} 9... Bg7 $2 10. g4 {would be embarrassing for Black.}) 10. Nd2 Z0 ({The queen will drop back to e2 (or head to e3 if} 10... Ne6 11. Qe3 {), after which Nf3 will leave White with a harmonious set-up and pleasant edge.}) *

