1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Nf6 $6 {A premature involvement of the knight, if a surprise choice which you may get to face at blitz or rapid.} 3. e5 $1 {Taking up the challenge.} Nh5 {The North Sea Defence, a sometime favourite of the world number one's at blitz and bullet.} 4. d4 {Classical play as White helps himself to the control of the centre on offer.} d6 5. Bc4 $1 Nc6 ({White's best move, generating some pressure against f7 and so enabling us to meet} 5... Bg7 $6 {with} 6. Ng5 {, threatening both Nxf7 and g2-g4.}) 6. Qe2 $1 {)} Bg7 $5 ({Offering support to the bridgehead on e5, one which White would like to maintain. Note too that} 6... Bg4 $2 {is most certainly not a problem here due to} 7. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 8. Ng5+ {and -- Qxg4 .}) 7. h3 $1 {White was happy to castle in Giri-Svidler, Internet (blitz) 2020, but this looks much stronger. White is in control and the threat of g2-g4 not so easy for Black to deal with.} dxe5 8. dxe5 Nd4 $5 9. Qe4 {Activating the queen with tempo while renewing the threat of g2-g4.} Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 $1 Z0 ({Threatening f7 as well as g2-g4. Now} 10... f5 11. O-O {would leave Black in a pretty bad way indeed.}) *

