een a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) {Increasing the pressure against d4.} 6. dxe5 $1 {A timely exchange, as played by Sam Shankland. You might be wondering: why exchange now and not a move earlier? The answer lies in the c6-square, where Black now has a knight and so can no longer cover d5 so easily with a pawn.} ({Instead, play tends to go} 6. Bg5 f6 7. Be3 {these days, but we weren't sure that 6...Nge7 was so clear in this sequence and, in any case, 6.dxe5 looks like a good try for a pleasant edge.}) 6... Nxe5 7. Nxe5 ({Consistently playing for a possible queen exchange, although here} 7. Be2 {is also a decent option, with a Maroczy edge.}) 7... dxe5 8. Qxd8+ {Naturally we exchange queens ahead of gaining a couple of useful tempi.} Kxd8 9. Bg5+ $1 f6 10. O-O-O+ {The second tempo gain. Now Black must block the check, otherwise they would find c7 coming under rapid attack.} Bd7 11. Be2 {Completing development while setting a little trap as the bishop turns out to be taboo. If you added knights on f3 and b8, Black would likely be fine here, but with the kingside pawns unimpeded, White has good chances of emerging with even more than an edge, such as after Be3 and f2-f4.} h5 12. Be3 {White is all set to seize a strong initiative with either g2-g4 or c4-c5 and Bc4.} Bh6 {This was the second point behind 11...h5, but it won't solve Black's difficulties.} 13. Bxh6 {Dragging one of Black's pieces to a slightly strange place ahead of doubling on the d-file and/or going c4-c5.} Rxh6 14. Rd2 $1 ({This simple move looks to be even stronger than the} 14. c5 {of Budisavljevic-Drazic, Paracin 2021, since now 14...Ne7?? would lose to 15.Rhd1 . In any case that is a threat and White will also be able to increase the pressure with Nd5 or c4-c5 and Bc4.}) *

