1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 e5 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) {Here too Black plays for pressure against d4 and with the f-pawn obstructed, White absolutely should not exchange on e5 and d8 - the resulting positions are at least easier for Black to handle.} 5. Nc3 Nc6 ({Sensibly keeping the tension while getting ready for a Maroczy situation in the event of an exchange on d4. Here Black's main choice is to take on d4, a line which used to be seen a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) {Increasing the pressure against d4.} 6. dxe5 $1 {A timely exchange, as played by Sam Shankland. You might be wondering: why exchange now and not a move earlier? The answer lies in the c6-square, where Black now has a knight and so can no longer cover d5 so easily with a pawn.} ({Instead, play tends to go} 6. Bg5 f6 7. Be3 {these days, but we weren't sure that 6...Nge7 was so clear in this sequence and, in any case, 6.dxe5 looks like a good try for a pleasant edge.}) 6... dxe5 7. Qxd8+ {Pretty much forcing Black to recapture with the king.} Kxd8 8. Bg5+ ({Provoking a weakness unless Black wants to run into a very powerful Nd5 or O-O-O+ (Sam Shankland was to prefer} 8. Be3 {in the 2020 Online Olympiad, which should also lead to an edge).}) 8... f6 $1 9. Rd1+ $5 {Electing to keep the king in the centre may seem a bit strange, but there is a tactical point to it, as we're about to see, and this way White won't need to spend a tempo on h2-h3.} Ke8 $2 {This is possible after 9.O-O-O+, but not here.} 10. Nb5 $1 {Obviously there's no way to defend c7. Now Black's counterplay will be too slow.} fxg5 11. Nxc7+ Ke7 12. Nxa8 {The knight will be able to make it out via c7 and d5, while its colleague can drop back to d2 or even g1 if attacked by ...g4.} Nf6 13. Nc7 Z0 ({White is a clear exchange ahead and doing pretty well. With the white king on c1,} 13... Nxe4 {would be quite awkward, but here it can be easily and well met by} 14. Bd3 {.}) *

