een a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) {Increasing the pressure against d4.} 6. dxe5 $1 {A timely exchange, as played by Sam Shankland. You might be wondering: why exchange now and not a move earlier? The answer lies in the c6-square, where Black now has a knight and so can no longer cover d5 so easily with a pawn.} ({Instead, play tends to go} 6. Bg5 f6 7. Be3 {these days, but we weren't sure that 6...Nge7 was so clear in this sequence and, in any case, 6.dxe5 looks like a good try for a pleasant edge.}) 6... dxe5 7. Qxd8+ {Pretty much forcing Black to recapture with the king.} Kxd8 8. Bg5+ ({Provoking a weakness unless Black wants to run into a very powerful Nd5 or O-O-O+ (Sam Shankland was to prefer} 8. Be3 {in the 2020 Online Olympiad, which should also lead to an edge).}) 8... f6 $1 9. Rd1+ $5 {Electing to keep the king in the centre may seem a bit strange, but there is a tactical point to it, as we're about to see, and this way White won't need to spend a tempo on h2-h3.} Bd7 10. Be3 {Keeping the bishop safe, introducing ideas of c4-c5 and Bc4, and encouraging Black to play as they might were the king on c1.} Nh6 $6 11. c5 $1 Kc8 ({A powerful advance. There's no need to go h2-h3 here when} 11... Ng4 {can now be met by simply} 12. Bc1 {and then} Z0 13. h3 {.}) 12. Bb5 $5 ({An alternative approach to} 12. Bc4 {. White plays to generate some pressure with Nd5.}) 12... Be6 13. Nd5 Nf7 14. O-O ({Calmly does it, although} 14. h4 $5 {is also quite tempting, unlike}) (14. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 {when Black would be back in charge of the key d5 point. The text move was seen in Atalik-Safranska, Bangkok 2014, where doubling rooks on the d-file was one plan, a queenside pawn advance based around b2-b4 another.}) 14... f5 {Black's only real attempt at counterplay, but not an advance to be feared.} 15. exf5 $1 gxf5 16. Rfe1 {Black's hanging pawns don't look like an especially great asset here. White is in control, enjoys the more active pieces and may play to increase the pressure with Bc4 and/or Ng5.} *

