seen a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) 6. Nxd4 {Setting up one of our favourite structures. White will continue with Be3 and may then go Be2 or prefer a more aggressive set-up with Qd2 and/or h2-h4.} Ne7 ({Note too that} 6... Nf6 7. Be2 {would keep Black out of g4 and gives White an improved version of the lines we’ll now see, with Bg5 an option, as well as just Be3.}) 7. h4 $5 O-O ({With Black having elected to retain an unobstructed bishop by placing the knight on e7, this is always going to be a tempting advance. White prepares h4-h5 and now} 7... Nbc6 8. Be3 {would transpose to the standard 6...Nc6 7.Be3 lines [/variation/35967775/#/8/w].}) 8. h5 {If White now had time to go Be3, Qd2 and Bh6, Black might be in pretty big trouble.} c5 $5 9. Ndb5 $1 {Taking up the challenge and going after the weak pawn on d6.} Nbc6 10. Bf4 $5 {One of a few tempting options, calmly increasing the pressure against d6.} Qa5 $6 11. Qd2 {) Breaking the pin while overprotecting the knight on c3 ahead of finally pocketing d6.} a6 12. Nxd6 {This left White pretty much just a pawn to the good in Krizsany-Balduan, Pecs 1997. We would suggest following up with Rd1 and Be2, perhaps even in conjunction with a cramping h5-h6 and O-O.} *

