1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 e5 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) {Here too Black plays for pressure against d4 and with the f-pawn obstructed, White absolutely should not exchange on e5 and d8 - the resulting positions are at least easier for Black to handle.} 5. Nc3 exd4 ({Sensibly keeping the tension while getting ready for a Maroczy situation in the event of an exchange on d4. Here Black's main choice is to take on d4, a line which used to be seen a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) 6. Nxd4 {Setting up one of our favourite structures. White will continue with Be3 and may then go Be2 or prefer a more aggressive set-up with Qd2 and/or h2-h4.} Nc6 ({Note too that} 6... Nf6 7. Be2 {would keep Black out of g4 and gives White an improved version of the lines we’ll now see, with Bg5 an option, as well as just Be3.}) 7. Be3 {Calmly retaining control of the d4 point.} Nf6 8. Be2 {An important move, just like it would be were Black's c-pawn instead on e7 (compare with this position in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967446/#/8/w]), taking control of the g4-square.} O-O 9. Qd2 $5 ({Slightly unusual at this point. There's absolutely nothing wrong with} 9. O-O {and you may prefer it, but after} Re8 10. f3 {play has transposed to a sideline of the Classical King's Indian ( 6.Be2 - instead of our 6.Bd3 - 6...e5 7.O-O exd4 8.Nxd4 Re8 9.f3 Nc6 10.Be3 ). The move 9.Qd2 retains the option of castling long, although White may still go short.}) 9... Re8 10. f3 Nh5 $5 ({Protecting the key e-pawn. Now after} 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {White will likely go short then centralise with Rad1, thereby enjoying a typical Maroczy edge.}) {One of Black's main options when White has castled instead of going Qd2.} 11. Nxc6 $1 ({The maximalist choice. White avoids the possibility of} 11. O-O-O Nf4 {and so prepares to drive the knight back from the rim with g2-g4.}) 11... bxc6 12. g4 Nf6 ({The knight must now go back as, of course,} 12... Qh4+ $4 13. Bf2 {would be most unwise.}) 13. O-O-O {Housing the king to pretty much take ...d5 ideas off the table ahead of launching the h-pawn.} Be6 14. h4 {Already the attack looks pretty fearsome.} Qb8 15. h5 {White would now love to be allowed to exchange off the black king's principal defender with Bh6.} Qb4 {White was now content to exchange on g6 in Chovan-Jacko, Slovakian League 2017, where it was also possible to be more direct.} 16. Bh6 $1 Bh8 ({The threat of} 16... Z0 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. hxg6 fxg6 19. Qh6+ Kg8 20. g5 Nh5 21. Rxh5 $1 {ensures there's no time for Black to take on c4.}) 17. Qc2 $1 Z0 ({Stepping away from the dark squares, but also leaving White in control and clearly for choice.} 17... Bxc4 {can be met by at least an exchange on g6 then Rd4, and White would like to go Bd2 followed by Na4 and Bc3, which would comprehensively deal with any threats against b2 while enabling White to continue his own attack.}) *

