seen a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) 6. Nxd4 {Setting up one of our favourite structures. White will continue with Be3 and may then go Be2 or prefer a more aggressive set-up with Qd2 and/or h2-h4.} Nc6 ({Note too that} 6... Nf6 7. Be2 {would keep Black out of g4 and gives White an improved version of the lines we’ll now see, with Bg5 an option, as well as just Be3.}) 7. Be3 {Calmly retaining control of the d4 point.} Nf6 8. Be2 {An important move, just like it would be were Black's c-pawn instead on e7 (compare with this position in Chapter 2b [/variation/35967446/#/8/w]), taking control of the g4-square.} O-O 9. Qd2 $5 ({Slightly unusual at this point. There's absolutely nothing wrong with} 9. O-O {and you may prefer it, but after} Re8 10. f3 {play has transposed to a sideline of the Classical King's Indian ( 6.Be2 - instead of our 6.Bd3 - 6...e5 7.O-O exd4 8.Nxd4 Re8 9.f3 Nc6 10.Be3 ). The move 9.Qd2 retains the option of castling long, although White may still go short.}) 9... Re8 10. f3 Nh5 $5 ({Protecting the key e-pawn. Now after} 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {White will likely go short then centralise with Rad1, thereby enjoying a typical Maroczy edge.}) {One of Black's main options when White has castled instead of going Qd2.} 11. Nxc6 $1 ({The maximalist choice. White avoids the possibility of} 11. O-O-O Nf4 {and so prepares to drive the knight back from the rim with g2-g4.}) 11... bxc6 12. g4 Nf6 ({The knight must now go back as, of course,} 12... Qh4+ $4 13. Bf2 {would be most unwise.}) 13. O-O-O {Housing the king to pretty much take ...d5 ideas off the table ahead of launching the h-pawn.} Qe7 14. h4 {) Everything is now set for the good, old plan in such positions: h4-h5 and Bh6.} a5 15. h5 Bxg4 $2 16. hxg6 $1 ({Under pressure on the kingside, this was an understandable bid to muddy the waters (} 16. fxg4 $2 Nxe4 {would be most unclear) in Wells-Jones, London 2007, but it was to run into a forcing refutation.}) 16... fxg6 17. e5 $1 Qxe5 ({The problem:} 17... dxe5 18. fxg4 {would just be a clear extra piece, with lines now closed.}) 18. Bd4 Qe6 19. fxg4 {And by now White was just a clear piece to the good.} *

