1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 e5 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) {Here too Black plays for pressure against d4 and with the f-pawn obstructed, White absolutely should not exchange on e5 and d8 - the resulting positions are at least easier for Black to handle.} 5. Nc3 exd4 ({Sensibly keeping the tension while getting ready for a Maroczy situation in the event of an exchange on d4. Here Black's main choice is to take on d4, a line which used to be seen a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) 6. Nxd4 {Setting up one of our favourite structures. White will continue with Be3 and may then go Be2 or prefer a more aggressive set-up with Qd2 and/or h2-h4.} Nc6 ({Note too that} 6... Nf6 7. Be2 {would keep Black out of g4 and gives White an improved version of the lines we’ll now see, with Bg5 an option, as well as just Be3.}) 7. Be3 {Calmly retaining control of the d4 point.} Nge7 {Black's standard approach, keeping the a1-h8 diagonal open.} 8. h4 $1 {By no means forced, but a very tempting try to take advantage of the absence of a knight from f6 and to make early gains on the kingside.} h5 $5 ({This looks like a better try than} 8... h6 {to keep lines fairly closed on the kingside, although it does, once again, also weaken the g5-square.}) 9. Qd2 Ne5 ({Facilitating queenside castling lest Black does anything slow. White is especially likely to castle long in the event of} 9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O 12. O-O-O {when the black king position appears a little airy.}) 10. f3 {Wisely keeping Black out of g4.} c6 11. O-O-O a6 ({White is now ready to meet} 11... O-O {with} 12. Bh6 {and the king should be safe enough on b1.}) 12. Kb1 $1 O-O ({Good prophylaxis.} 12... b5 {can now be well met by} 13. Nc2 {or 13.c5!? dxc5 14.Ndxb5! , and if 14...Qxd2 15.Nc7+ Kd8 16.Nxa8 (neatly exploiting the pin on the d-file) 16...Qxd1+ 17.Nxd1 followed by Nb6 with much the better structure.}) 13. Nc2 $1 ({This looks even better than the} 13. Nb3 {of Rowson-McNab, Scottish Championship, Edinburgh 2009.}) 13... Be6 14. Bh6 $1 Nxc4 $2 ({Resisting the d-pawn to launch a strong attack. White wants to exchange on g7 then go f3-f4 and the tactics work for him, as can be seen from} 14... Bxc4 $2 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. f4 {and the following line.}) 15. Bxc4 {Hoping to win a piece with the fork on d4.} Bxh6 16. Qxh6 Bxc4 17. Ne3 Be6 18. g4 $1 {The attack is crushing.} *

