1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 e5 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) {Here too Black plays for pressure against d4 and with the f-pawn obstructed, White absolutely should not exchange on e5 and d8 - the resulting positions are at least easier for Black to handle.} 5. Nc3 exd4 ({Sensibly keeping the tension while getting ready for a Maroczy situation in the event of an exchange on d4. Here Black's main choice is to take on d4, a line which used to be seen a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) 6. Nxd4 {Setting up one of our favourite structures. White will continue with Be3 and may then go Be2 or prefer a more aggressive set-up with Qd2 and/or h2-h4.} Nc6 ({Note too that} 6... Nf6 7. Be2 {would keep Black out of g4 and gives White an improved version of the lines we’ll now see, with Bg5 an option, as well as just Be3.}) 7. Be3 {Calmly retaining control of the d4 point.} Nge7 {Black's standard approach, keeping the a1-h8 diagonal open.} 8. h4 $1 {By no means forced, but a very tempting try to take advantage of the absence of a knight from f6 and to make early gains on the kingside.} f5 {Black's most common choice, one fully in keeping with their piece set-up and need for some sort of counterplay.} 9. h5 $1 O-O ({Wasting no time in consistently turning the pressure dial up a notch on the kingside. Now} 9... f4 $2 10. Nxc6 {and} Z0 11. Bxf4 {will cost Black a pawn and meanwhile a timely hxg6 hangs over their whole position.}) 10. hxg6 {Naturally White begins the policy of opening lines, aiming to gradually exploit the exposed situation of the black king.} hxg6 11. Nxc6 ({Continuing to clear lines as White spies a potential weakness on the a2-g8 diagonal to exploit (} 11. Nf3 $5 {, heading for g5, also looks quite promising).}) 11... Nxc6 12. c5 $1 {Threatening a rather nasty check.} Be6 13. exf5 $1 gxf5 ({White is alert to the threat of ...f4 and now} 13... Rxf5 14. Bd3 {would leave only one king not feeling overly happy.}) 14. cxd6 $5 ({Here one of the strongest correspondence players ever was happy to take control of f4 with} 14. g3 {and an edge in Van Oosterom-Umansky, correspondence 2006, and White may be able to do even better than that.}) {Playing for a structural plus, while keeping ideas of both g2-g3 and Qh5 in reserve. White is also provoking a certain advance:} 14... f4 15. Bd3 $1 Bxc3+ $1 ({The point. The threat of} 15... Z0 16. Bh7+ {, and if} Kf7 17. Qh5+ Kf6 18. Ne4# {is not so easy for Black to prevent.}) 16. bxc3 Qf6 17. Bd4 Nxd4 18. cxd4 {The pawn on d4 is clearly taboo and White is doing well. Not only can we continue with Qh5, but we shouldn't forget that such sensible moves as O-O and Rc1 are very much still possible.} *

