seen a fair amount in grandmaster chess, but which is currently pretty unfashionable, largely due to White's central clamp, spatial plus and mobile h-pawn. Black can also retain the tension with} 5... Nd7 {, reaching a position we'll discuss via a 4...Nd7 5.Nc3 e5 move order [/variation/35967782/#/5/b].}) 6. Nxd4 {Setting up one of our favourite structures. White will continue with Be3 and may then go Be2 or prefer a more aggressive set-up with Qd2 and/or h2-h4.} Nc6 ({Note too that} 6... Nf6 7. Be2 {would keep Black out of g4 and gives White an improved version of the lines we’ll now see, with Bg5 an option, as well as just Be3.}) 7. Be3 {Calmly retaining control of the d4 point.} Nge7 {Black's standard approach, keeping the a1-h8 diagonal open.} 8. h4 $1 {By no means forced, but a very tempting try to take advantage of the absence of a knight from f6 and to make early gains on the kingside.} f5 {Black's most common choice, one fully in keeping with their piece set-up and need for some sort of counterplay.} 9. h5 $1 fxe4 ({Wasting no time in consistently turning the pressure dial up a notch on the kingside. Now} 9... f4 $2 10. Nxc6 {and} Z0 11. Bxf4 {will cost Black a pawn and meanwhile a timely hxg6 hangs over their whole position.}) 10. Nxe4 $1 ({White has scored well with this tension-retaining alternative to the more popular} 10. hxg6 {. Now 11.h6 is a threat and Black may also still find themselves being hit by a timely hxg6 too.}) 10... Bf5 $6 11. h6 {Powerful use of Harry, the h-pawn.} Be5 12. Nxf5 $1 {A strong exchange, preparing to land the queen with some effect on d5 or h5.} Nxf5 13. Bg5 {Not forgetting to gain a useful tempo against the black queen while taking control of f6.} Qd7 14. Qd5 $1 Nfe7 ({Black was unable to castle and suffering in Parligras-Pancevski, Kraljevo 2014, and continued to after} 14... Bxb2 15. Rb1 Be5 16. Rxb7 {. Black can instead get castled, but not solve their problems.}) 15. Qd3 O-O-O 16. O-O-O {White is in full control with his bishops and such moves as Kb1, g2-g3 and Bg2 will but serve to increase our grip on the position.} *

