1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 Nd7 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) 5. Nc3 {A very natural response to Black's ... e5-preparing last.} e5 6. d5 $5 ({Just a quick reminder that this position can also come about via a 4...e5 5.Nc3 Nd7 move order. Now} 6. dxe5 $6 dxe5 {would be very comfortable for Black with the queens staying on the board.}) ({Closing the centre ahead of going Bd3. Arguably} 6. Be2 {followed by Be3 is more critical and do please play this way if such set-ups in the Classical King's Indian are also in your repertoire (}) (6. Be2 Ngf6 {is, of course, a King's Indian).}) ({After} 6. d5 {,} Ngf6 7. Bd3 {and a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 5 [/variation/36296491/#/5/b/1.3] is also very possible, although Black does have a number of independent, Modern ideas.}) 6... a5 $5 {Played to ensure that ...Nc5 won't run into b2-b4.} 7. Bd3 {Our favourite development. Even here Black may hold back on ...Ngf6.} Nc5 8. Bc2 {Keeping the bishop safe while intending Be3, after which a quick a2-a3 and b2-b4 may well be quick to happen.} Bh6 $5 {Giving up a tempo, but exchanging off the bad bishop and before White gets to go Be3 when ...Bh6 might well run into Bxc5 dxc5; Nxe5.} 9. Bxh6 Nxh6 10. Qd2 {Developing with tempo.} Ng4 11. h3 $5 ({Kicking the knight back ahead of castling queenside. Here} 11. O-O {is also very much an option, perhaps looking to gradually expand with b2-b3, a2-a3 and only then b3-b4.}) 11... Nf6 12. O-O-O ({This side to avoid coming under an attack after} 12. O-O Nh5 $1 {.}) 12... Nh5 13. Ne1 $1 Z0 ({White prepares to meet} 13... Nf4 {with} 14. h4 {then g2-g3 and should be slightly for choice. As well as g2-g3, Nd3 is on the way and while White's king should be pretty safe on b1, its counterpart may yet land up feeling the heat, such as if White is able to get in a timely f2-f4 or meet ...f5 with exf5 and g2-g4.}) *

