1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 Nd7 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) 5. Nc3 {A very natural response to Black's ... e5-preparing last.} e5 6. d5 $5 ({Just a quick reminder that this position can also come about via a 4...e5 5.Nc3 Nd7 move order. Now} 6. dxe5 $6 dxe5 {would be very comfortable for Black with the queens staying on the board.}) ({Closing the centre ahead of going Bd3. Arguably} 6. Be2 {followed by Be3 is more critical and do please play this way if such set-ups in the Classical King's Indian are also in your repertoire (}) (6. Be2 Ngf6 {is, of course, a King's Indian).}) ({After} 6. d5 {,} Ngf6 7. Bd3 {and a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 5 [/variation/36296491/#/5/b/1.3] is also very possible, although Black does have a number of independent, Modern ideas.}) 6... a5 $5 {Played to ensure that ...Nc5 won't run into b2-b4.} 7. Bd3 {Our favourite development. Even here Black may hold back on ...Ngf6.} Nc5 8. Bc2 {Keeping the bishop safe while intending Be3, after which a quick a2-a3 and b2-b4 may well be quick to happen.} f5 9. Be3 $5 {)} Ne7 $2 ({Calmly ignoring Black's attempt to disrupt as now} 9... Nxe4 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Ng5 {would be a pretty pleasant edge and 9...f4?! 10.Bxc5! dxc5 11.Ba4+ a potential positional disaster for Black.}) 10. Bxc5 $1 {White instead captured on f5 in Ungureanu-Ciocaltea, Timisoara 1977, missing a good moment to make a different exchange.} dxc5 11. Ba4+ $1 Kf8 ({Black's problem is that} 11... c6 {will be well met by} 12. d6 $1 {, and if} fxe4 13. Nxe4 {, while 11...Bd7 12.Bxd7+ creates weaknesses on the light squares which can be exploited with 12...Qxd7 13.Ng5 .}) 12. Qd2 {Despite his unopposed dark-squared bishop or even because of it, Black is in serious early trouble. White just wants to go O-O-O followed by crashing through with d5-d6 and also has various kingside options available, not least h2-h4-h5.} *

