1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 Nd7 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) 5. Nc3 {A very natural response to Black's ... e5-preparing last.} e5 6. d5 $5 ({Just a quick reminder that this position can also come about via a 4...e5 5.Nc3 Nd7 move order. Now} 6. dxe5 $6 dxe5 {would be very comfortable for Black with the queens staying on the board.}) ({Closing the centre ahead of going Bd3. Arguably} 6. Be2 {followed by Be3 is more critical and do please play this way if such set-ups in the Classical King's Indian are also in your repertoire (}) (6. Be2 Ngf6 {is, of course, a King's Indian).}) ({After} 6. d5 {,} Ngf6 7. Bd3 {and a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 5 [/variation/36296491/#/5/b/1.3] is also very possible, although Black does have a number of independent, Modern ideas.}) 6... Nh6 7. Bd3 ({Keeping control (the immediate} 7. h4 $5 {is also pretty good), while angling to win a pawn with 7...f5? 8.Bxh6! Bxh6 9.exf5 or to usefully discombobulate in the event of 7...Nc5 8.Bc2 f5?! 9.Bg5 .}) 7... O-O 8. h4 $1 {This sounded the charge in Kamsky-Terry, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022, where Black tried to break out.} f5 9. h5 $1 {A strong advance, threatening to take on g6, as well as to open lines in general towards the black king.} f4 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Bc2 $1 Z0 ({Prophylaxis against ...Nc5 (} 11... Nc5 12. b4 $1 {) as we find Black having closed the kingside earlier than they might wish. White may simply continue with Bd2, Qe2 and O-O-O, although we may do even better with a quick Nh4, and if ...g5; Nf5. Finally, do note that once White has caught up a bit in development that the g2-g3 break may well land up packing a certain punch on the kingside.}) *

