y this way if such set-ups in the Classical King's Indian are also in your repertoire (}) (6. Be2 Ngf6 {is, of course, a King's Indian).}) ({After} 6. d5 {,} Ngf6 7. Bd3 {and a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 5 [/variation/36296491/#/5/b/1.3] is also very possible, although Black does have a number of independent, Modern ideas.}) 6... Ne7 $6 {Black's most popular choice at this stage, if also a line White should be pretty happy to see.} 7. h4 $1 {Sounding the charge as White aims to cause early problems once again on the kingside with Harry.} O-O $6 8. h5 {Already White is all set to open lines on the kingside and may even have something of a strong positional threat in the shape of h5-h6 followed by g2-g4.} f5 9. hxg6 hxg6 10. g4 $5 ({Here} 10. Bd3 {was simple and strong in Krutko-Merino Garcia, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where White might also have been more direct.}) 10... fxg4 ({Aiming to either open the g-file or usefully control the f5-square in the event of} 10... fxe4 11. Ng5 {.}) 11. Ng5 Nc5 12. Be2 {Black is under very heavy pressure on the light squares and kingside, and only able to prevent Bxg4 at the cost of a rather unconvincing exchange sacrifice on f4.} *

