1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 Bg4 $5 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) {The most popular of Black's independent options, going for immediate counterplay against d4.} 5. Be2 {Breaking the pin while also facilitating castling as well as Nc3.} Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {Not forced, but there's no need to compromise the pawn structure at this early stage.} e5 7. d5 a5 8. Nc3 h5 $5 {We've followed Sos Andreu-Luque Saiz, Guardamar del Segura 2023, where again White didn't need to fear an early exchange of dark-squared bishops.} 9. O-O (9. h4 $5 {and a plan involving queenside castling is a decent alternative, but the text can hardly be bad and White is now all set to go a2-a3 and b2-b4.}) 9... Bh6 $5 10. c5 $1 {This temporary pawn sacrifice gives White the initiative and a definite edge. We'll recapture on c1 with the rook and the queen is coming to b3.} dxc5 $6 11. Qb3 b6 ({Attacking b7 and now} 11... Qc8 $6 12. Nb5 {would menace a rather nasty breakthrough in the shape of d5-d6.}) 12. Be2 $5 {Black's light squares are shot and White enjoys superb play for the pawn. The main idea is Nb5 followed by Bc4, Rad1 and d5-d6 in some order, although Bb5+ followed by an exchange of dark-squared bishops and f2-f4 can also be quite strong so long as it doesn't allow Black to entrench a knight on e5.} *

