1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 Bg4 $5 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) {The most popular of Black's independent options, going for immediate counterplay against d4.} 5. Be2 {Breaking the pin while also facilitating castling as well as Nc3.} Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {Not forced, but there's no need to compromise the pawn structure at this early stage.} Nc6 7. d5 $5 {with Nc6 Nbd2. Nd4 Nc3 Calmly ignoring Black as White begins to play around the knight on d4. e5 dxe6 fxe6 Changing the structure in accordance with the policy begun by 7.d5. Now Nxe6 Be3 should be a pleasant enough Maroczy style edge for White. O-O White is ready to increase the pressure with e4-e5 or Bg4 and Be3. Ne7 Be3 c5! The position isn't completely clear, but White definitely has chances to be better, as is definitely the case after} e5 {Nd5 or 11...Nec6 12.Bg4 and f2-f4. Bg4 Threatening Bxd4. The immediate Bxd4!? Bxd4} 8. Bg4 {very much comes into the equation too. Nec6 f4 Black has a firm grip on d4, but White has decent central control otherwise and an unopposed light-squared bishop. One plan would be Qd2, a2-a3, Rab1 and b2-b4, another to tidy the kingside with g2-g3, looking to expand at a favourable moment with h2-h4.} *

