1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 Bg4 $5 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) {The most popular of Black's independent options, going for immediate counterplay against d4.} 5. Be2 {Breaking the pin while also facilitating castling as well as Nc3.} Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {Not forced, but there's no need to compromise the pawn structure at this early stage.} Nc6 7. d5 $5 ({Avoiding the structure which arises after} 7. Be3 e5 8. d5 Nd4 {, just as we'll also do in our main line [/variation/35967793/#/6/w] with 5...Nc6 6.Nbd2.}) 7... Nd4 8. Nc3 {Calmly ignoring Black as White begins to play around the knight on d4.} c5 9. O-O Nf6 ({Housing the king. Now if} 9... e5 {White will again go} 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. Be3 {.}) 10. Be3 Nd7 ({Forcing Black to either offer a pawn on d4 for some dark-squared compensation (would it really be enough if White managed to reset with, say, Be2, g2-g3, Kg2 and f2-f4?), or to allow White to activate the dark-squared bishop (} 10... Nxf3+ $6 11. Qxf3 {followed by Qe2 and f2-f4 would be a pleasant edge).}) 11. Bg4 $1 {White was slightly for choice despite the outpost on d4 in Burmakin-Lorenzo de la Riva, Montcada 2013, with the plans of b2-b4 and Ne2.} Ne5 12. Be2 {Retaining the bishop. White may now edge forwards with f2-f4 then Bd3 and/or continue to angle for the b2-b4 break.} *

