1. Nf3 g6 {The Modern Defence, although in practice this flexible move order from Black will often lead to the King's Indian.} 2. e4 $1 ({Like 1.Nf3 d6 2.d4 this is a perhaps unexpected choice, but it avoids being move ordered into something we don't want. Indeed,} 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 {would see Black having tricked us into a Grunfeld after all, while 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 can be annoyingly met by 3...c5 . If your opponent isn't a Grunfeld or Symmetrical English player, you may not need to worry and so can allow those options, but the text move, intending d2-d4 and only then c2-c4 is the best route towards a King's Indian transposition or lines of the Modern not unacceptable to White. Note, too, that now 2...c5 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 followed by -- 5.c4 would take us back into the Maroczy Bind world of 2b [/variation/35967401/#/4/w].}) 2... Bg7 ({Black's usual choice at this point (} 2... d6 3. d4 Bg7 {would transpose).}) 3. d4 d6 ({Invariably played as Black has no desire to allow} 3... Nf6 $6 4. e5 {.}) 4. c4 Bg4 $5 ({At last the pawn reaches c4. Now Black's most common choice in practice has been} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {when we're back in a King's Indian Defence after all. There are though three important Modern alternatives, which we'll explore here. We should mention too that 4...c5 5.d5 (5.dxc5 is also possible) is likely after 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Bd3 to transpose back into the world of 5a [/variation/35967662/#/7/w], while 4...Nc6 doesn't make too much sense with the d4-square firmly under White's control and 5.d5 Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 7.Bd3 followed by Nc3 and O-O supplies a fairly pleasant edge.}) {The most popular of Black's independent options, going for immediate counterplay against d4.} 5. Be2 {Breaking the pin while also facilitating castling as well as Nc3.} Nc6 {Black's usual choice, increasing the pressure against d4.} 6. Nbd2 $5 e5 ({As used by Boris Gelfand, White plays to retain a knight on f3 and control of d4. Of course, that pawn isn't hanging in view of} 6... Nxd4 $4 7. Nxd4 Bxe2 8. Nxe2 {. White much more often prefers 6.Be3 when the main line revolves around 6...e5 7.d5 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nd4 . That may be slightly better for White, but there's no need to allow Black into d4 so.}) 7. d5 {Closing the centre with tempo after which White will always be able to follow up with at least h2-h3.} Bxf3 $5 8. Nxf3 {Black is determined to invade on d4, but White need not panic.} Nd4 9. Nxd4 $1 ({This is a good version of the structure with a black pawn on d4 thanks to White's free and easy development. Instead,} 9. Be3 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Bh6 $1 {would be less effective.}) 9... exd4 10. O-O {Clearly the right side for the king to go as White may look to expand on the other flank.} Ne7 11. Bd3 {White enjoyed a pleasant edge with Black low on counterplay in Holt-Saveliev, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023. Expansion with f2-f4, Qf3 and Bd2 is one good plan, pressing ahead on the queenside with Bd2 and b2-b4 another.} *

