.. Nxd4 $4 7. Nxd4 Bxe2 8. Nxe2 {. White much more often prefers 6.Be3 when the main line revolves around 6...e5 7.d5 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nd4 . That may be slightly better for White, but there's no need to allow Black into d4 so.}) 7. d5 {Closing the centre with tempo after which White will always be able to follow up with at least h2-h3.} Nce7 8. h3 {Asking the question. White should be quite happy to be given the bishop-pair and also very much has ideas of a quick c4-c5.} Bc8 9. c5 $1 Nf6 ({The key break and} 9... dxc5 10. Nc4 {would leave White in full control.}) 10. Qa4+ $5 {By no means forced, but a notable idea. White seeks to discombobulate ahead of dropping the queen back to a3 or b3.} Nd7 11. cxd6 cxd6 12. Qa3 {With the c-file open and O-O and Nc4 on the way, White enjoyed a promising version of a King's Indian in Gelfand-Tukhaev, World Blitz Championship, St. Petersburg 2018.} *

