... Nxd4 $4 7. Nxd4 Bxe2 8. Nxe2 {. White much more often prefers 6.Be3 when the main line revolves around 6...e5 7.d5 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nd4 . That may be slightly better for White, but there's no need to allow Black into d4 so.}) ({This and} 6... e5 {are roughly level in the popularity stakes.}) 7. d5 {Advancing with tempo as White helps himself to the extra space on offer.} Nb8 8. Qc2 $1 ({Gelfand's choice and preferable to the more popular} 8. O-O {. After}) (8. Qc2 {White simply wants to be able to go} Z0 9. h3 {, and if} Bxf3 10. Nxf3 {.}) 8... c6 9. h3 {Consistently angling for a small but pleasant edge with the bishop-pair.} Bd7 $5 10. Nb1 $1 {A retrograde choice, but also a good one. Having dealt with the early pressure, White has time to improve the queen's knight and bring it to its ideal post on c3.} cxd5 11. cxd5 {Maintaining the structure while intending to complete development with Nc3, O-O and Be3.} Na6 12. Nc3 Nc5 13. O-O {Mission largely accomplished and do note, despite their seemingly decent piece development, Black's lack of counterplay.} Rc8 14. Qb1 $1 {This stepped away from the gaze of the black rook to leave White with small but definite edge in Wharrier-Cleto Junior, correspondence 2017. Be3 will follow, after which White may even already be in a position to expand with b2-b4.} *

