... Nxd4 $4 7. Nxd4 Bxe2 8. Nxe2 {. White much more often prefers 6.Be3 when the main line revolves around 6...e5 7.d5 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Nd4 . That may be slightly better for White, but there's no need to allow Black into d4 so.}) ({This and} 6... e5 {are roughly level in the popularity stakes.}) 7. d5 {Advancing with tempo as White helps himself to the extra space on offer.} Nb8 8. Qc2 $1 ({Gelfand's choice and preferable to the more popular} 8. O-O {. After}) (8. Qc2 {White simply wants to be able to go} Z0 9. h3 {, and if} Bxf3 10. Nxf3 {.}) 8... Na6 (8... O-O 9. h3 Bd7 {This was Gordievsky-Matlakov, Sochi (blitz) 2018, where} 10. Rb1 {wasn't the best use of that particular square. But after 10.Nb1! , tThanks to the bridgehead on d5 and with Nc3, O-O and Be3 on their way, White again enjoys decent control and a definite edge.}) 9. h3 {Consistently challenging the bishop, a piece Black would really like to retain.} Bd7 10. Nb1 $1 {Another of our favourite moves in this line, switching the knight round to its best square.} Nb4 11. Qb3 {Not exactly a bad square for the queen.} a5 12. Nc3 $1 {A good move. There's absolutely no need to rush with a2-a3 here and so drive Black's knight round to c5.} e6 13. O-O O-O 14. Be3 b6 ({Completing development, pretty harmonious development at that, and now with White controlling the c5-square, a2-a3 is a definite threat. Here} 14... exd5 15. cxd5 {would open the c-file for White, when a2-a3 will follow and there’s always Nd2 to cover e4 if needed.}) 15. dxe6 $5 Bxe6 ({By no means forced, but a decent way to transform the position and now} 15... fxe6 $6 16. e5 $1 {would not be good news for Black's structure.}) 16. Nd4 Z0 ({The Maroczy Bind supplied a pretty pleasant edge in Gelfand-Nepomniachtchi, Internet (blitz) 2020, where White was even able to consider expansion with f2-f4 and Bf3, and neatly reset in the game with} 16... Nd7 17. Qd1 $1 {followed by Qd2.}) *

