1. Nf3 Z0 ({Before we delve too deeply into the main lines of this chapter characterised by an early ...f5, the Dutch Defence, let's pause to consider} 1... e6 {, which after 1...f5 is the most common of Black's first moves we're yet to discuss. Against 1.Nf3 it is, though, pretty much just a transpositional tool, as after}) (1... e6 2. c4 {we have the following options: 2...d5 3.e3 takes play back into the anti-Queen's Gambit and Part One of the course; 2...Nf6 3.e3 was seen in Chapter One here [/variation/35973664/#/3/w]; 2...c5 3.e3 may well become a Symmetrical English; and both 2...f5 3.e3 and 2...b6 3.Nc3 will transpose to lines considered in Chapter Seven here. Moving on to the Dutch and we'll analyse: 7a: The Stonewall Dutch (...e6 and ...d5) 7b: The Classical Dutch (...e6 and ...d6) 7c: Lines with an early ...b6 (including 1...b6) 7d: The Leningrad Dutch (...g6 set-ups). Before delving into those lines, we should just mention one other option.}) *

