1. Nf3 f5 ({Before we delve too deeply into the main lines of this chapter characterised by an early ...f5, the Dutch Defence, let's pause to consider} 1... e6 {, which after 1...f5 is the most common of Black's first moves we're yet to discuss. Against 1.Nf3 it is, though, pretty much just a transpositional tool, as after}) (1... e6 2. c4 {we have the following options: 2...d5 3.e3 takes play back into the anti-Queen's Gambit and Part One of the course; 2...Nf6 3.e3 was seen in Chapter One here [/variation/35973664/#/3/w]; 2...c5 3.e3 may well become a Symmetrical English; and both 2...f5 3.e3 and 2...b6 3.Nc3 will transpose to lines considered in Chapter Seven here. Moving on to the Dutch and we'll analyse: 7a: The Stonewall Dutch (...e6 and ...d5) 7b: The Classical Dutch (...e6 and ...d6) 7c: Lines with an early ...b6 (including 1...b6) 7d: The Leningrad Dutch (...g6 set-ups). Before delving into those lines, we should just mention one other option.}) 2. c4 Nc6 $6 3. d4 ({Threatening to transpose to reversed Grand Prix lines after} 3. Z0 e5 {, but...}) {This simple and strong retort leaves the knight misplaced on c6.} 3... e6 {This is actually a known position to theory, but with Black to move! That's when White loses a tempo with 2.d3 Nc6 3.c4 e6 4.d4 , and with the extra move White should be pretty happy.} 4. d5 $1 ({One of two good moves, and likely even better than . After} 4. d5 {,} Bb4+ {is best according to the engines, but} 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 {leaves White doing pretty well in any case with the key anti-Dutch break e2-e4 imminent.}) 4... exd5 5. cxd5 Nce7 6. d6 $1 {Destroying Black's position at a very early stage.} cxd6 7. Nc3 {With e2-e4 imminent and ideas too of Bg5 or simply g2-g3 and Bg2, White already enjoyed a large advantage in Gelman-Daianu, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020.} *

