1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 ({You may have a pet line(s) you're happy with against the Dutch, in which case go} 2. d4 {and there's also the fashionable}) (2. d3 {, but our favourite second move remains a good choice here.}) 2... e6 {As we'll see further in 7b, this is also a common move order.} 3. e3 d5 ({Another of our favourite moves and now play would, of course, transpose to the main line after} 3... Nf6 4. b3 {.}) 4. cxd5 {Making the exchange so early slightly goes against conventional Stonewall wisdom (White should be happy after ...c6 then cxd5 if Black takes back with the c-pawn), but here it looks like a simple and decent choice.} exd5 5. b3 Be7 ({Preparing to bring the bishop to a fine diagonal on b2. Now play would be very likely to transpose to the main line after} 5... Nf6 6. Bb2 {. There's only one other way we can really see for Black to try and develop the kingside.}) 6. Bb2 Bf6 $6 {Already we're in pretty much totally uncharted waters.} 7. Nc3 $5 Ne7 ({Keeping the bishops on for now. White wants to exchange them, but on his terms. Now Qc2 will follow unless Black weakens further and allows us to speed up our development with} 7... c5 $6 8. Bb5+ {.}) 8. Qc2 ({The immediate} 8. d4 {followed by Bd3 also looks like a pretty good version of a Stonewall for White with Black having misplaced their kingside pieces, but so does}) (8. Qc2 {which carries the positional threat of Ne2.}) 8... O-O 9. Ne2 $1 {Thematically swapping off Black's good bishop to only leave them with a potentially bad light-squared one.} Bxb2 10. Qxb2 {With Nf4 in conjunction with h2-h4 on the way, White enjoys full control. Be2 and O-O may follow or even something more aggressive such as h4-h5 and Rh3-g3.} *

