1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 ({You may have a pet line(s) you're happy with against the Dutch, in which case go} 2. d4 {and there's also the fashionable}) (2. d3 {, but our favourite second move remains a good choice here.}) 2... e6 {As we'll see further in 7b, this is also a common move order.} 3. e3 d5 ({Another of our favourite moves and now play would, of course, transpose to the main line after} 3... Nf6 4. b3 {.}) 4. cxd5 {Making the exchange so early slightly goes against conventional Stonewall wisdom (White should be happy after ...c6 then cxd5 if Black takes back with the c-pawn), but here it looks like a simple and decent choice.} exd5 5. b3 Be7 ({Preparing to bring the bishop to a fine diagonal on b2. Now play would be very likely to transpose to the main line after} 5... Nf6 6. Bb2 {. There's only one other way we can really see for Black to try and develop the kingside.}) 6. Bb2 Bf6 $6 {Already we're in pretty much totally uncharted waters.} 7. Nc3 $5 Ne7 ({Keeping the bishops on for now. White wants to exchange them, but on his terms. Now Qc2 will follow unless Black weakens further and allows us to speed up our development with} 7... c5 $6 8. Bb5+ {.}) 8. Qc2 ({The immediate} 8. d4 {followed by Bd3 also looks like a pretty good version of a Stonewall for White with Black having misplaced their kingside pieces, but so does}) (8. Qc2 {which carries the positional threat of Ne2.}) 8... Nbc6 $5 9. d4 $1 ({Intending ...f4 while setting a small trap. Please do not fall for} 9. Ne2 $4 Nb4 $1 {when the weakness of d3 is already game ending.}) {Clamping down in the centre to leave a Stonewall where the black knights are on rather strange squares. White may now still go Ne2-f4 and h2-h4 to reinforce our grip on the position.} 9... f4 $5 10. e4 $1 Nxd4 ({Seizing the initiative with} 10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 {or a quick O-O-O.}) 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 12. O-O-O {White's pressure down the d-file supplies excellent compensation for the pawn.} c5 $1 13. Kb1 $1 {There's no need to rush to take on d5. Only now does White want to favourably regain the pawn with Nxd5 then Bxd4 and Rxd4.} dxe4 $6 14. Nxe4 {Threatening Nxc5 and with Bb5+ also on the way to pose serious questions, it's not a surprise to use that the engines already assess White's initiative as being over '+2'.} *

