1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 ({You may have a pet line(s) you're happy with against the Dutch, in which case go} 2. d4 {and there's also the fashionable}) (2. d3 {, but our favourite second move remains a good choice here.}) 2... Nf6 {Black is likely to make this move at any early point.} 3. e3 {Remaining flexible and waiting to see which set-up Black is going to go in for.} e6 4. b3 {With Black not looking like contesting the a1-h8 diagonal, unlike in Chapter 7d, it makes good sense to place the bishop on a fine spot on b2, a square where it will be especially well placed if Black now goes in for a Stonewall set-up, weakening the e5 point in the process.} Be7 {A flexible move order, keeping Black's options of ...d6, ...b6 and ...d5 open.} 5. Bb2 {Completing the fianchetto and waiting for Black to show his hand, although they can continue to delay doing so for one more move.} O-O 6. Nc3 {Staying flexible with the d-pawn and this is pretty much the latest moment at which a Stonewall Dutch opponent is likely to go in for their favourite set-up.} d5 7. cxd5 {Forcing the pace in the centre ahead of going in for a double fianchetto with g2-g3.} Nxd5 $5 8. Nxd5 exd5 ({By no means White's only good move, but a simple and effective choice, in part because} 8... Qxd5 $6 9. Bc4 {would now make little sense for Black from a positional and developmental perspective.}) 9. g3 {Consistent with our general set-up in this system. White simply wants to fianchetto then castle short.} c6 10. Bg2 Nd7 11. O-O {White makes all the useful moves to complete kingside development and will now look for a quick d2-d3 and e3-e4 break if Black is careless.} Nf6 12. d3 {White controls a number of key central squares and it's not completely obvious what Black's plan should be. In contrast, White will aim to expand on the queenside with a2-a3 and b3-b4 or Qd2 and Bc3 if needed should Black flick in ...a5.} *

