{Keeping Black out of d3 and so securing an edge as Black begins to look a little overextended. White will castle and then look to regroup in some order with d2-d3, Ne2 and b3-b4, thereby beginning to drive Black backwards while continuing to leave them struggling slightly for a good plan.} 1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 ({You may have a pet line(s) you're happy with against the Dutch, in which case go} 2. d4 {and there's also the fashionable}) (2. d3 {, but our favourite second move remains a good choice here.}) 2... Nf6 {Black is likely to make this move at any early point.} 3. e3 {Remaining flexible and waiting to see which set-up Black is going to go in for.} e6 4. b3 {With Black not looking like contesting the a1-h8 diagonal, unlike in Chapter 7d, it makes good sense to place the bishop on a fine spot on b2, a square where it will be especially well placed if Black now goes in for a Stonewall set-up, weakening the e5 point in the process.} Be7 {A flexible move order, keeping Black's options of ...d6, ...b6 and ...d5 open.} 5. Bb2 {Completing the fianchetto and waiting for Black to show his hand, although they can continue to delay doing so for one more move.} O-O 6. Nc3 {Staying flexible with the d-pawn and this is pretty much the latest moment at which a Stonewall Dutch opponent is likely to go in for their favourite set-up.} d5 7. cxd5 {Forcing the pace in the centre ahead of going in for a double fianchetto with g2-g3.} exd5 8. g3 {White goes for the same set-up with Bg2 and O-O we'll see Zhao Jun deploying in our mainline with 4...d5 5.Bb2. Here White has already committed to Nc3, but the knight supports the e3-e4 break and may also deploy via e2 to f4.} Nbd7 9. Bg2 {Consistent play as White gets ready to castle.} Nc5 10. Qc2 $1 ({Here} 10. d3 {was logical enough in Krawinkel-Buchholz, Wesel 1997, but wouldn't have been completely clear after} f4 $1 {.}) *

