[ECO "A04"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 ({You may have a pet line(s) you're happy with against the Dutch, in which case go} 2. d4 {and there's also the fashionable}) (2. d3 {, but our favourite second move remains a good choice here.}) 2... Nf6 {Black is likely to make this move at any early point.} 3. e3 {Remaining flexible and waiting to see which set-up Black is going to go in for.} e6 4. b3 {With Black not looking like contesting the a1-h8 diagonal, unlike in Chapter 7d, it makes good sense to place the bishop on a fine spot on b2, a square where it will be especially well placed if Black now goes in for a Stonewall set-up, weakening the e5 point in the process.} d5 5. cxd5 exd5 ({Playing to either leave Black slightly strangely placed in the centre, such as after} 5... Nxd5 6. Bb2 {(what is the pawn doing on f5?), or to ensure White will definitely be facing a Stonewall scenario. Another good approach here is 5.Be2 c6 6.O-O Nd6 7.Ba3! , swapping off Black's better bishop as recommended by Axel Smith in his fascinating book 'e3 Poison'.}) 6. Bb2 {A fine diagonal indeed for the dark-squared bishop.} c6 7. g3 $1 {This whole approach for White has been extremely rare, but Vincent Keymer has been known to follow up e2-e3 and b2-b3 by going in for a double fianchetto when Black's pawn is back on f7, so this must surely be an improved version with Black having made the rather committal ...f5 advance.} Bd6 ({The ideal spot for this bishop in a Stonewall structure, if not forced here. Instead,} 7... Be7 8. Bg2 {is likely to transpose to the lines which we examined via a 4...Be7 move order [/variation/35967806/#/8/w].}) 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O {White's set-up may be rare, but it's certainly harmonious and both we and the engines like it. Moreover, it was once used by the future 2600+ Chinese GM Zhao Jun back when he was a strong IM. White may either route the queen's knight around to f4 via e2 after all, as the engines quite like to, or simply develop with d2-d3 and Nbd2.} Nbd7 10. d3 {Going for a Nbd2 approach. If Black now reacts slowly White may get to favourably break with e3-e4 after Nbd2 and Qc2; we shouldn't forget that ...f5 has potentially weakened Black in the centre and on the kingside. Another decent plan is to begin to expand on the queenside with a2-a3 and b3-b4.} Ng4 $5 11. Nbd2 Nge5 12. Qc2 Z0 ({This left White with a pleasant edge in Zhao Jun-Wang Yue, Seville 2003. Already} 12... Z0 13. e4 {is a threat and White may also increase the pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal while supporting a queenside advance with Bc3 and Qb2.}) *

