[Result "*"]
[ECO "A04"]
[PlyCount "25"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. b3 {Heading for our favourite Reti set-up with the white dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} Be7 ({Black's standard move order in the normal Classical Dutch, i.e. 1.d4 f5 2.c4 Nf6, etc, but here they might also begin with} 4... d6 {, angling for a quick ...e5 at the cost of a tempo. White can cut out such ideas with} 5. d4 {when} Be7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Nc3 {would take us back into the current trainable.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 {White keeps the d-pawn flexible while getting ready for cxd5 and g2-g3 in the event of a Stonewall.} d6 {Angling to break out with ...e5.} 7. d4 {Slamming the brakes on Black's idea. We're now into a conventional Dutch, although it should be said that this is another pretty unusual move order and has rarely occurred via a 1.d4 f5 move order.} Ne4 {This is another common idea in the Classical Dutch, freeing f6 for the bishop on e7.} 8. Bd3 Nxc3 ({White should immediately challenge the knight so. Now} 8... d5 9. O-O {would leave Black a tempo down on a not particularly great type of Stonewall, one where White will be quick to look to improve the knights with Ne2-f4 and Ne5.}) 9. Bxc3 {All is now set for White's main pawn break in the Dutch, e3-e4. Note too White's easier development and flexibility: we might wish to castle short then expand with b3-b4 or prefer to follow up Qc2 with O-O-O and kingside ambitions,} Nd7 10. e4 $1 ({Here White was content to go} 10. Qc2 Nf6 11. O-O {and emerged with an edge in Yaran-Novikova, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where the key break might well have been implemented right away.}) 10... Nf6 ({Clearly White's bishops would breathe fire. Black's position look quite precarious if now} 10... fxe4 $6 11. Bxe4 Nf6 12. Bc2 {.}) {The lesser evil.} 11. exf5 {Usefully opening the e-file ahead of castling.} exf5 12. O-O Ne4 13. Bb2 {Black's knight may look active, but it can easily be challenged and meanwhile the holes created by ...f5 will persist for a long time. White will follow up with Qc2 and then go d4-d5 and/or Rae1, with a very pleasant edge indeed.} *

