1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. b3 {Heading for our favourite Reti set-up with the white dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} Be7 ({Black's standard move order in the normal Classical Dutch, i.e. 1.d4 f5 2.c4 Nf6, etc, but here they might also begin with} 4... d6 {, angling for a quick ...e5 at the cost of a tempo. White can cut out such ideas with} 5. d4 {when} Be7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Nc3 {would take us back into the current trainable.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 {White keeps the d-pawn flexible while getting ready for cxd5 and g2-g3 in the event of a Stonewall.} d6 {Angling to break out with ...e5.} 7. d4 {Slamming the brakes on Black's idea. We're now into a conventional Dutch, although it should be said that this is another pretty unusual move order and has rarely occurred via a 1.d4 f5 move order.} Nc6 {Looking for ...e5, but the knight is a target here.} 8. d5 $1 {With tempo and now Black may well have to nurse a long-term weakness on e6.} Ne5 9. Nd4 {The early skirmishes have gone well for White. Black is under pressure on e6, may also find f5 being targeted after Qc2 and White's king will be quite safe on the kingside after Be2 and O-O.} *

