1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. b3 {Heading for our favourite Reti set-up with the white dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} Be7 ({Black's standard move order in the normal Classical Dutch, i.e. 1.d4 f5 2.c4 Nf6, etc, but here they might also begin with} 4... d6 {, angling for a quick ...e5 at the cost of a tempo. White can cut out such ideas with} 5. d4 {when} Be7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Nc3 {would take us back into the current trainable.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 {White keeps the d-pawn flexible while getting ready for cxd5 and g2-g3 in the event of a Stonewall.} d6 {Angling to break out with ...e5.} 7. d4 {Slamming the brakes on Black's idea. We're now into a conventional Dutch, although it should be said that this is another pretty unusual move order and has rarely occurred via a 1.d4 f5 move order.} b6 $6 8. Bd3 $1 {Once again, not forgetting that the main pawn break is e3-e4.} Bb7 $2 {This doesn't work well here in conjunction with the early ...d6, for the instructive reason we're about to see.} 9. d5 $1 Z0 ({Breaking Black's position in two with some effect. Nd4 is a big threat and} 9... e5 10. Bxf5 {would just be a clear extra pawn for White.}) *

