1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. b3 {Heading for our favourite Reti set-up with the white dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} Be7 ({Black's standard move order in the normal Classical Dutch, i.e. 1.d4 f5 2.c4 Nf6, etc, but here they might also begin with} 4... d6 {, angling for a quick ...e5 at the cost of a tempo. White can cut out such ideas with} 5. d4 {when} Be7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Nc3 {would take us back into the current trainable.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 {White keeps the d-pawn flexible while getting ready for cxd5 and g2-g3 in the event of a Stonewall.} d6 {Angling to break out with ...e5.} 7. d4 {Slamming the brakes on Black's idea. We're now into a conventional Dutch, although it should be said that this is another pretty unusual move order and has rarely occurred via a 1.d4 f5 move order.} Qe8 {Black's most common choice according to ChessBase in the limited practice with this position so far, angling for an early kingside attack, just as Classical Dutch players often like to do.} 8. Qc2 $1 {This looks like the right way to support the key e4 break. White may even be able to follow up with Bd3, and if ...Nc6 then a2-a3.} ({Stuart Conquest, though, was once happy just to calmly go} 8. Be2 {followed by O-O, and}) (8. Bd3 {can hardly be terrible, even if here} Nc6 $5 9. d5 Ne5 {is more murky than usual due to Black's ideas of ...Nxd3+ and ...Qg6.}) 8... Qh5 $6 9. Be2 ({Black hopes for} 9. e4 $6 Nc6 $1 {, but White doesn't need to rush with the advance.}) 9... Qg6 ({Threatening to seize a strong initiative with} 9... Z0 10. d5 exd5 11. Nd4 $1 {.}) 10. h4 $1 ({White was now content to go} 10. g3 {in Trifan-Ventura Bolet, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where it was also very possible to be more aggressive.}) 10... Ne4 $2 ({Directed against ...Ne4 ideas and, of course,} 10... Qxg2 $4 11. Rg1 Qh3 12. Rg3 {would trap the black queen.}) 11. h5 Qxg2 $2 ({Either winning a pawn, as with} 11... Qg4 12. Nh4 {and} Z0 13. Nxe4 {, or forcing Black into a rather risky venture.}) 12. Rh2 $1 {Chasing the queen back while covering f2.} Qg4 13. O-O-O {What a superb position for White, with Rg1 a big threat and that fianchettoed bishop on b2 ideally placed for the upcoming attack on g7.} *

