1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. b3 {Heading for our favourite Reti set-up with the white dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} Be7 ({Black's standard move order in the normal Classical Dutch, i.e. 1.d4 f5 2.c4 Nf6, etc, but here they might also begin with} 4... d6 {, angling for a quick ...e5 at the cost of a tempo. White can cut out such ideas with} 5. d4 {when} Be7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Nc3 {would take us back into the current trainable.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 {White keeps the d-pawn flexible while getting ready for cxd5 and g2-g3 in the event of a Stonewall.} d6 {Angling to break out with ...e5.} 7. d4 {Slamming the brakes on Black's idea. We're now into a conventional Dutch, although it should be said that this is another pretty unusual move order and has rarely occurred via a 1.d4 f5 move order.} Qe8 {Black's most common choice according to ChessBase in the limited practice with this position so far, angling for an early kingside attack, just as Classical Dutch players often like to do.} 8. Qc2 $1 {This looks like the right way to support the key e4 break. White may even be able to follow up with Bd3, and if ...Nc6 then a2-a3.} ({Stuart Conquest, though, was once happy just to calmly go} 8. Be2 {followed by O-O, and}) (8. Bd3 {can hardly be terrible, even if here} Nc6 $5 9. d5 Ne5 {is more murky than usual due to Black's ideas of ...Nxd3+ and ...Qg6.}) 8... d5 $6 9. Bd3 {Increasing the pressure against d5 and f5.} c6 10. O-O ({Calmly does it, although an aggressive player might want to make} 10. h3 $5 {followed by g2-g4 work.}) 10... Ne4 11. Ne2 $1 {Keeping the knights on to leave Black with a fairly bad version of a Stonewall, one where White is set to improve their grip on the position with Ne5 followed by Nf4 and/or f2-f3.} *

