1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. b3 {Heading for our favourite Reti set-up with the white dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} Be7 ({Black's standard move order in the normal Classical Dutch, i.e. 1.d4 f5 2.c4 Nf6, etc, but here they might also begin with} 4... d6 {, angling for a quick ...e5 at the cost of a tempo. White can cut out such ideas with} 5. d4 {when} Be7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Nc3 {would take us back into the current trainable.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 {White keeps the d-pawn flexible while getting ready for cxd5 and g2-g3 in the event of a Stonewall.} d6 {Angling to break out with ...e5.} 7. d4 {Slamming the brakes on Black's idea. We're now into a conventional Dutch, although it should be said that this is another pretty unusual move order and has rarely occurred via a 1.d4 f5 move order.} Qe8 {Black's most common choice according to ChessBase in the limited practice with this position so far, angling for an early kingside attack, just as Classical Dutch players often like to do.} 8. Qc2 $1 {This looks like the right way to support the key e4 break. White may even be able to follow up with Bd3, and if ...Nc6 then a2-a3.} ({Stuart Conquest, though, was once happy just to calmly go} 8. Be2 {followed by O-O, and}) (8. Bd3 {can hardly be terrible, even if here} Nc6 $5 9. d5 Ne5 {is more murky than usual due to Black's ideas of ...Nxd3+ and ...Qg6.}) 8... Qg6 {Fighting for the e4-square while obtaining some pressure against g2.} 9. h4 $5 Nc6 ({Pretty much taking} 9... Ne4 {off the table due to} 10. h5 {. White now wants to castle queenside and may be able to consider too bringing a piece over to the kingside with tempo in the shape of Ne2-f4. The related 9.Rg1 was preferred in McMichael-Meyer, Ghent 1998, where 9...Ne4 10.Bd3 Nxc3?! (10...Nc6 would restrict White to an edge) 11.Bxc3 Nd7 12.g4! was already excellent for White.}) {Angling for counterplay with ...e5.} 10. O-O-O ({Refusing to fear ...e5 and leaving White doing fairly well, unlike} 10. d5 $6 Nb4 $1 {. Now a2-a3 may follow, after which d4-d5 and/or h4-h5 will become quite strong positional threats. Unfortunately too for Black the obvious remedy is worse than the disease.}) 10... e5 $2 11. dxe5 $1 dxe5 ({Favourably opening lines, as we can quickly tell from a glance at} 11... Nxe5 12. Nb5 {.}) 12. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 ({Attacking c7 as well as e5 and now} 12... Bd6 {can at least be met by} 13. c5 {.}) 13. cxd5 Nb4 14. Nxe5 Z0 ({A clear pawn to the good, White is quite happy to trade queens, as well as to meet} 14... Qd6 {with} 15. Nc4 {.}) *

