1. Nf3 b6 ({The English Defence. Note that the resulting play may well quickly become rather Dutch-like against our favourite set-up for White:} 1... f5 2. c4 Nf6 {(or 2...e6 3.e3 b6 4.b3 Bb7 5.Bb2 ) 3.e3 e6 4.b3 Be7 5.Bb2 O-O 6.Nc3 b6 7.g3 Bb7 8.Bg2 transposes to our mainline here.}) 2. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although if you have some 1.e4 experience you may prefer} 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {and to take on Owen's Defence.}) 2... Bb7 3. e3 ({Starting with} 3. Nc3 {can hardly be terrible, but there's no need to allow Black the opportunity of doubling the f-pawns.}) 3... e6 {We'll now focus on Black's most flexible and common choice here in 3...e6 , but do note that 3...Nf6 would return play to the realm of Chapter 1c [/variation/35967270/#/3/b], while we considered 3...c5 4.b3 Nf6 5.Nc3 d5 6.cxd5 at the start of Chapter Two [/variation/35967310/#/6/w].} 4. b3 f5 ({Going for our favourite fianchetto. In practice Black has almost always now made either the Dutch advance or gone in for} 4... Nf6 5. Bb2 {, with a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 1 [/variation/35973664/#/5/w].}) 5. Bb2 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Keeping the light-squared bishop and d-pawn flexible while waiting to see what set-up Black is going for.} Bb4 7. Be2 ({This way ahead of castling, not to g2, as here} 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2 Bxc3 $5 9. Bxc3 a5 10. O-O d6 {looks like a fairly harmonious set-up for Black.}) ({White could also ask the question straight away with} 7. a3 {, but there's no need to rush with that and a careless opponent may even get into trouble with their bishop on b4.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O d6 $6 9. Nb5 $1 {All of a sudden Black's bishop finds itself precariously floating in mid-air on b4.} d5 10. Rc1 {White's pressure against c7 and e6 after Nbd4 (Ng5 may follow) already supplies a clear advantage.} *

