1. Nf3 b6 ({The English Defence. Note that the resulting play may well quickly become rather Dutch-like against our favourite set-up for White:} 1... f5 2. c4 Nf6 {(or 2...e6 3.e3 b6 4.b3 Bb7 5.Bb2 ) 3.e3 e6 4.b3 Be7 5.Bb2 O-O 6.Nc3 b6 7.g3 Bb7 8.Bg2 transposes to our mainline here.}) 2. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although if you have some 1.e4 experience you may prefer} 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {and to take on Owen's Defence.}) 2... Bb7 3. e3 ({Starting with} 3. Nc3 {can hardly be terrible, but there's no need to allow Black the opportunity of doubling the f-pawns.}) 3... e6 {We'll now focus on Black's most flexible and common choice here in 3...e6 , but do note that 3...Nf6 would return play to the realm of Chapter 1c [/variation/35967270/#/3/b], while we considered 3...c5 4.b3 Nf6 5.Nc3 d5 6.cxd5 at the start of Chapter Two [/variation/35967310/#/6/w].} 4. b3 f5 ({Going for our favourite fianchetto. In practice Black has almost always now made either the Dutch advance or gone in for} 4... Nf6 5. Bb2 {, with a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 1 [/variation/35973664/#/5/w].}) 5. Bb2 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Keeping the light-squared bishop and d-pawn flexible while waiting to see what set-up Black is going for.} g6 $5 {A change of approach as Black goes for a hybrid of all the types of Dutch bar the Stonewall.} 7. d4 {It makes sense to bring a pawn on to the long dark-square diagonal now that Black is surely going to be fianchettoing on it.} Bg7 8. Be2 ({Straightforward development to be consistent with our anti-Leningrad approach, although this another position where you may prefer} 8. g3 {and a double fianchetto approach.}) 8... O-O 9. b4 $5 {White is now a tempo down on the positions we reach in Chapter 7d, but on the other hand, Black has gone ...e6 and also in for a queenside fianchetto. White will castle short, may find Qb3 a useful move and would love to get in a cramping a2-a4-a5 if somehow allowed. We should also mention that after ...d6, Ng5 may become a decent possibility, intending ...Qe7; Bf3 to swap off Black's more active bishop.} a5 $5 10. b5 {Seizing the space on offer, just as White can do after 9...Qe7 with 10.b5 .} d6 11. Ng5 {An aforementioned manoeuvre.} Qe7 12. Bf3 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 ({The right way to recapture.} 13. Qxf3 Nbd7 14. Qc6 {just doesn't seem to achieve all that much.}) 13... Nbd7 14. O-O Z0 ({Objectively Black may be OK here, but White should not be too unhappy. Qc2 then Rad1 and e3-e4 would be the ideal continuation, while} 14... e5 {can be well enough met by} 15. Qb3 {, with ideas of both c4-c5+ and a timely exchange on e5.}) *

