1. Nf3 b6 ({The English Defence. Note that the resulting play may well quickly become rather Dutch-like against our favourite set-up for White:} 1... f5 2. c4 Nf6 {(or 2...e6 3.e3 b6 4.b3 Bb7 5.Bb2 ) 3.e3 e6 4.b3 Be7 5.Bb2 O-O 6.Nc3 b6 7.g3 Bb7 8.Bg2 transposes to our mainline here.}) 2. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although if you have some 1.e4 experience you may prefer} 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {and to take on Owen's Defence.}) 2... Bb7 3. e3 ({Starting with} 3. Nc3 {can hardly be terrible, but there's no need to allow Black the opportunity of doubling the f-pawns.}) 3... e6 {We'll now focus on Black's most flexible and common choice here in 3...e6 , but do note that 3...Nf6 would return play to the realm of Chapter 1c [/variation/35967270/#/3/b], while we considered 3...c5 4.b3 Nf6 5.Nc3 d5 6.cxd5 at the start of Chapter Two [/variation/35967310/#/6/w].} 4. b3 f5 ({Going for our favourite fianchetto. In practice Black has almost always now made either the Dutch advance or gone in for} 4... Nf6 5. Bb2 {, with a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 1 [/variation/35973664/#/5/w].}) 5. Bb2 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Keeping the light-squared bishop and d-pawn flexible while waiting to see what set-up Black is going for.} Bd6 $6 {A rather ambitious set-up, hoping to land a quick kingside attack.} 7. Be2 {Calm development. White need not overly fear the attack, but also doesn't have to rush to castle. First all of a2-a3, d2-d4 and b3-b4 may well be useful advances, as even could be a timely Nb5.} a6 8. a3 ({This cut out Nb5 possibilities for good in Janz-Buhmann, Austrian League 2002, where White went} 8. d3 {.}) {Beginning to advance the pawns.} 8... O-O 9. d4 {Here before b3-b4 as now Black must reckon with the possibility of d4-d5, which would rather cut his position in two.} Nc6 10. b4 $1 ({Angling to meet} 10. d5 {with} Ne5 {and a rather unclear scenario.}) {A strong advance, cutting out any ...Ne7 regrouping ideas due to the threat of c4-c5. In any case White is ready with that advance, after which the b-file may open (... bxc5; bxc5) or White may be able to exchange on b6 then break after all with d4-d5.} 10... Qe8 {Going for a kingside attack while freeing d8 for the knight.} 11. O-O ({The immediate} 11. c5 {is also possible, but}) (11. O-O {aims to lure Black into being too ambitious, while preparing to meet} Nd8 {with} 12. Ne5 {.}) 11... Qg6 $6 12. c5 $1 bxc5 13. bxc5 Be7 14. d5 $1 {A powerful break, just as it would have been without the exchange on c5. Black was dreaming of an attack, but now the initiative well and truly belongs to White.} exd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5+ Qe6 17. Bc4 {One of a few good moves. White will bring the rooks to c1 and d1 and definitely exerts quite strong pressure.} *

