1. Nf3 b6 ({The English Defence. Note that the resulting play may well quickly become rather Dutch-like against our favourite set-up for White:} 1... f5 2. c4 Nf6 {(or 2...e6 3.e3 b6 4.b3 Bb7 5.Bb2 ) 3.e3 e6 4.b3 Be7 5.Bb2 O-O 6.Nc3 b6 7.g3 Bb7 8.Bg2 transposes to our mainline here.}) 2. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although if you have some 1.e4 experience you may prefer} 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {and to take on Owen's Defence.}) 2... Bb7 3. e3 ({Starting with} 3. Nc3 {can hardly be terrible, but there's no need to allow Black the opportunity of doubling the f-pawns.}) 3... e6 {We'll now focus on Black's most flexible and common choice here in 3...e6 , but do note that 3...Nf6 would return play to the realm of Chapter 1c [/variation/35967270/#/3/b], while we considered 3...c5 4.b3 Nf6 5.Nc3 d5 6.cxd5 at the start of Chapter Two [/variation/35967310/#/6/w].} 4. b3 f5 ({Going for our favourite fianchetto. In practice Black has almost always now made either the Dutch advance or gone in for} 4... Nf6 5. Bb2 {, with a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 1 [/variation/35973664/#/5/w].}) 5. Bb2 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Keeping the light-squared bishop and d-pawn flexible while waiting to see what set-up Black is going for.} Be7 {This Classical Dutch style deployment has been Black's most common choice by some margin in practice, but isn't forced.} 7. g3 $5 ({Not for the first time in this section we see White going for a double fianchetto, here in part to compete on the long light-square diagonal.} 7. Be2 {has been more popular and is also a decent choice, but why not make even greater use of that piece?}) 7... O-O 8. Bg2 e5 $6 ({The pawn on e3 may look a little strange, but it helps to rule out an ...f4 advance and White may use the e2-square for the queen or knight, not least in the event of} 8... Ne4 9. Ne2 $1 {followed by O-O and d2-d3, or if} Ng5 10. Nf4 {. White is now set to castle and may then continue in English style with d2-d3, a2-a3 and ideally b3-b4, or advance in the centre after all with d2-d4.}) {This advance has tempted a couple of strong players, but while the pawn is clearly taboo White should still be fairly happy.} 9. O-O d6 ({Threatening Nxe5. Now} 9... e4 $2 10. Nd4 g6 11. d3 {would leave Black badly overextended.}) 10. Qc2 $5 ({This may be even stronger than the immediate} 10. d4 {of Yilmazyerli-Haznedaroglu, Turkish Team Championship 2010. White continues to force concessions, tempt 10...e4 11.Nd4 and just seems to be doing fairly well with d2-d4 likely up next, after which ...e4 may even run into the strong concept that is Ng5 in conjunction with d4-d5.}) *

