re after all with d2-d4.}) ({Going for a standard Dutch-type build-up while trying to avoid falling for a common type of trap in such positions with} 8... d6 9. O-O Nbd7 $4 10. Ng5 {when Black's position implodes on e6.}) 9. O-O d6 ({Refusing to fear the attack, while now} 9... Ne4 {can be met by} 10. Ne2 {or even 10.Nb5!? then d2-d3.}) 10. d3 $1 ({This seems even more promising than} 10. Ng5 {with a likely edge, as White takes control of e4.}) 10... Nbd7 {Here White began to play on the queenside in Ott-Weigand, Wuerttemberg 2001, a logical enough choice, but he might have preferred to react in the centre.} 11. e4 $1 {With the rather large threat of Nd4.} fxe4 12. Nd4 Qf7 13. dxe4 {White has cleverly established a Maroczy Bind and strong knight on d4. We might proceed slowly to retain control with Qe2, Rad1 and h2-h3, although a quick f2-f4 looking for f4-f5 and light-square chaos is also pretty tempting.} *

