{Overprotecting the knight on c3 while bringing the rook to a good square and thereby facilitating Ba3, which won't be too easy for Black to meet.} 1. Nf3 b6 ({The English Defence. Note that the resulting play may well quickly become rather Dutch-like against our favourite set-up for White:} 1... f5 2. c4 Nf6 {(or 2...e6 3.e3 b6 4.b3 Bb7 5.Bb2 ) 3.e3 e6 4.b3 Be7 5.Bb2 O-O 6.Nc3 b6 7.g3 Bb7 8.Bg2 transposes to our mainline here.}) 2. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although if you have some 1.e4 experience you may prefer} 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {and to take on Owen's Defence.}) 2... Bb7 3. e3 ({Starting with} 3. Nc3 {can hardly be terrible, but there's no need to allow Black the opportunity of doubling the f-pawns.}) 3... e6 {We'll now focus on Black's most flexible and common choice here in 3...e6 , but do note that 3...Nf6 would return play to the realm of Chapter 1c [/variation/35967270/#/3/b], while we considered 3...c5 4.b3 Nf6 5.Nc3 d5 6.cxd5 at the start of Chapter Two [/variation/35967310/#/6/w].} 4. b3 f5 ({Going for our favourite fianchetto. In practice Black has almost always now made either the Dutch advance or gone in for} 4... Nf6 5. Bb2 {, with a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 1 [/variation/35973664/#/5/w].}) 5. Bb2 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Keeping the light-squared bishop and d-pawn flexible while waiting to see what set-up Black is going for.} Be7 {This Classical Dutch style deployment has been Black's most common choice by some margin in practice, but isn't forced.} 7. g3 $5 ({Not for the first time in this section we see White going for a double fianchetto, here in part to compete on the long light-square diagonal.} 7. Be2 {has been more popular and is also a decent choice, but why not make even greater use of that piece?}) 7... O-O 8. Bg2 Qe8 $5 ({The pawn on e3 may look a little strange, but it helps to rule out an ...f4 advance and White may use the e2-square for the queen or knight, not least in the event of} 8... Ne4 9. Ne2 $1 {followed by O-O and d2-d3, or if} Ng5 10. Nf4 {. White is now set to castle and may then continue in English style with d2-d3, a2-a3 and ideally b3-b4, or advance in the centre after all with d2-d4.}) ({Going for a standard Dutch-type build-up while trying to avoid falling for a common type of trap in such positions with} 8... d6 9. O-O Nbd7 $4 10. Ng5 {when Black's position implodes on e6.}) 9. O-O Na6 ({Refusing to fear the attack, while now} 9... Ne4 {can be met by} 10. Ne2 {or even 10.Nb5!? then d2-d3.}) {Trying to develop the knight without blocking the fianchettoed bishop or weakening e6. It does, though, create a slightly strange impression.} 10. d4 $1 {)} Ng4 $6 ({Keeping the knight on the rim for now, although White might let it off to carry out a d4-d5 breakthrough. There are very much ideas too of a2-a3 and b3-b4, as well as of meeting} 10... Ne4 {with} 11. Ne5 $5 d6 12. Nd3 {to retain control and an edge.}) 11. h3 {Wasting no time in kicking the knight away.} Nh6 12. d5 $1 {A powerful advance to cut Black's position in two and leave White with the strong possibilities of Nd4 and e3-e4.} Bf6 13. Rc1 ({Here} 13. Nd4 e5 $1 14. Ndb5 {was only a little better for White in Taimanov-Steffens, Fuerth 1999, and we might aim for more.}) *

