1. Nf3 b6 ({The English Defence. Note that the resulting play may well quickly become rather Dutch-like against our favourite set-up for White:} 1... f5 2. c4 Nf6 {(or 2...e6 3.e3 b6 4.b3 Bb7 5.Bb2 ) 3.e3 e6 4.b3 Be7 5.Bb2 O-O 6.Nc3 b6 7.g3 Bb7 8.Bg2 transposes to our mainline here.}) 2. c4 ({Our favourite advance, although if you have some 1.e4 experience you may prefer} 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {and to take on Owen's Defence.}) 2... Bb7 3. e3 ({Starting with} 3. Nc3 {can hardly be terrible, but there's no need to allow Black the opportunity of doubling the f-pawns.}) 3... e6 {We'll now focus on Black's most flexible and common choice here in 3...e6 , but do note that 3...Nf6 would return play to the realm of Chapter 1c [/variation/35967270/#/3/b], while we considered 3...c5 4.b3 Nf6 5.Nc3 d5 6.cxd5 at the start of Chapter Two [/variation/35967310/#/6/w].} 4. b3 f5 ({Going for our favourite fianchetto. In practice Black has almost always now made either the Dutch advance or gone in for} 4... Nf6 5. Bb2 {, with a transposition back to the realm of Chapter 1 [/variation/35973664/#/5/w].}) 5. Bb2 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Keeping the light-squared bishop and d-pawn flexible while waiting to see what set-up Black is going for.} Be7 {This Classical Dutch style deployment has been Black's most common choice by some margin in practice, but isn't forced.} 7. g3 $5 ({Not for the first time in this section we see White going for a double fianchetto, here in part to compete on the long light-square diagonal.} 7. Be2 {has been more popular and is also a decent choice, but why not make even greater use of that piece?}) 7... O-O 8. Bg2 Qe8 $5 ({The pawn on e3 may look a little strange, but it helps to rule out an ...f4 advance and White may use the e2-square for the queen or knight, not least in the event of} 8... Ne4 9. Ne2 $1 {followed by O-O and d2-d3, or if} Ng5 10. Nf4 {. White is now set to castle and may then continue in English style with d2-d3, a2-a3 and ideally b3-b4, or advance in the centre after all with d2-d4.}) ({Going for a standard Dutch-type build-up while trying to avoid falling for a common type of trap in such positions with} 8... d6 9. O-O Nbd7 $4 10. Ng5 {when Black's position implodes on e6.}) 9. O-O Qh5 ({Refusing to fear the attack, while now} 9... Ne4 {can be met by} 10. Ne2 {or even 10.Nb5!? then d2-d3.}) {Very aggressive and possibly also overly ambitious.} 10. d4 $1 d6 ({Seizing some useful space, threatening d4-d5. Now} 10... Ng4 $6 {can be well met by} 11. h3 {or even 11.d5 .}) 11. d5 $5 ({Even here this is a fairly strong advance (} 11. Ne1 {would be a good, positional alternative, forcing favourable exchanges), and now 11...exd5? 12.cxd5 followed by Nd4 would be positional suicide for Black.}) 11... e5 $1 12. Nxe5 $1 {The point of White's play, exploiting the potential tactics down the long diagonal to force some fairly favourable simplification.} dxe5 13. Qxh5 Nxh5 14. d6 {White is currently a piece down, but both black bishops hang and his rook on f8 is about to be hit.} Bxg2 15. dxe7 Bxf1 16. exf8=Q+ Kxf8 17. Kxf1 ({With Rd1 on the way, the superior minor piece and Black potentially vulnerable on d5 (even} 17. Nd5 $5 {was an option), White enjoys a definite edge and went on to convert in Welin-Brontz, Swedish League 2001.}) *

