1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} d6 4. d4 e6 ({As ever, we don't really want to allow ...e5 and a reversed Sicilian when it's easy to avoid. Now} 4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {would transpose to our main line after 3...g6.}) {Have we been move-ordered into a type of Classical Dutch we had been avoiding?} 5. Nc3 {Well, yes and no to answer that question! White simply proceeds with straightforward development. Bd3 will follow and Black won't land up with a particularly great version of the Classical Dutch.} Be7 6. Bd3 {Already the key e3-e4 pawn break looms.} d5 7. Qc2 {Threatening to take on f5 as White is, of course, a tempo up on the normal lines of the Stonewall Dutch.} c6 8. O-O O-O 9. b3 {White's simplest plan and one which supplies a clear edge here. Bb2 and Ne2 will follow, after which White may head forwards with Ne5, being then ready to evict any black knight on e4 with f2-f3.} *

