1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} d6 4. d4 e6 ({As ever, we don't really want to allow ...e5 and a reversed Sicilian when it's easy to avoid. Now} 4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {would transpose to our main line after 3...g6.}) {Have we been move-ordered into a type of Classical Dutch we had been avoiding?} 5. Nc3 {Well, yes and no to answer that question! White simply proceeds with straightforward development. Bd3 will follow and Black won't land up with a particularly great version of the Classical Dutch.} Be7 6. Bd3 {Already the key e3-e4 pawn break looms.} O-O 7. e4 {There's no good reason to delay the break, although you can also castle first.} Nc6 $6 8. exf5 {Forcing a pretty favourable structure for White.} exf5 9. O-O {Black is vulnerable on the e-file and also devoid of counterplay. White will follow up with Re1 then perhaps Bd2 and Nd5 or just a2-a3 and b2-b4.} d5 $5 {A radical try for freedom.} 10. Re1 {Calmly continuing to take control of key squares.} Nb4 11. Bf1 $1 {Preserving this important piece left White clearly better in Korobkov-Golinka, Kharkov 2004. The bishop can still recapture on c4 and White is all set to further increase the pressure with a2-a3 and/or Bg5 or even just Bf4.} *

