1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} d6 4. d4 e6 ({As ever, we don't really want to allow ...e5 and a reversed Sicilian when it's easy to avoid. Now} 4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {would transpose to our main line after 3...g6.}) {Have we been move-ordered into a type of Classical Dutch we had been avoiding?} 5. Nc3 {Well, yes and no to answer that question! White simply proceeds with straightforward development. Bd3 will follow and Black won't land up with a particularly great version of the Classical Dutch.} Be7 6. Bd3 {Already the key e3-e4 pawn break looms.} O-O 7. e4 {There's no good reason to delay the break, although you can also castle first.} fxe4 8. Nxe4 {White can castle next and may then begin to look to exploit the favourable situation with Qc2.} Nxe4 9. Bxe4 d5 {The engines strangely suggest this may be the best of Black's possible central reactions, but it's not a break that comes anywhere close to equalising.} 10. Bd3 {White would love an IQP scenario with heavy pressure against e6, and may now go O-O then Qc2 or even start an attack straight away with h2-h4.} *

