1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} d6 4. d4 e6 ({As ever, we don't really want to allow ...e5 and a reversed Sicilian when it's easy to avoid. Now} 4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 {would transpose to our main line after 3...g6.}) {Have we been move-ordered into a type of Classical Dutch we had been avoiding?} 5. Nc3 {Well, yes and no to answer that question! White simply proceeds with straightforward development. Bd3 will follow and Black won't land up with a particularly great version of the Classical Dutch.} Be7 6. Bd3 {Already the key e3-e4 pawn break looms.} O-O 7. e4 {There's no good reason to delay the break, although you can also castle first.} fxe4 8. Nxe4 {White can castle next and may then begin to look to exploit the favourable situation with Qc2.} Nc6 9. O-O Qe8 10. Ng3 $5 ({White was better here after} 10. Bd2 {in Ott-Hausner, German League 2016, but it was also possible to aim for more with}) (10. Re1 {or the following idea.}) {Useful prophylaxis to leave Black quite cramped. Re1 will follow unless Black now reacts in the centre.} 10... e5 11. d5 $1 {Forcing the pace as White prepares to press on the light squares and kingside.} Nb4 12. Bb1 {White is doing well thanks to controlling e4. Now a2-a3 and Qc2 may follow and/or Ng5 and f2-f4, as Black begins to come under definite pressure.} *

