1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... d6 6. Be2 Nc6 $5 ({Consistent with 5...O-O 6.Be2 and now play usually transposes after} 6... O-O {. Likewise,}) (6... c6 7. b4 {also very likely to transpose after} O-O 8. O-O {, and 6...a5 is nothing to fear since after 7.O-O O-O 8.a3 White should be able to force through b2-b4 after all.}) 7. d5 ({Preventing} 7. b4 $6 {due to a small tactical point:} Nxb4 $1 8. Qa4+ Nc6 9. d5 $2 Nxd5 $1 {.}) {Forcing the pace before Black can get in ...e5.} 7... Ne5 8. Nxe5 $5 ({This might well be even stronger than} 8. Nd4 {here.}) 8... dxe5 9. b4 ({Consistently seizing space without delay.} 9. e4 $5 {also looks quite promising.}) 9... O-O 10. Qb3 {This structure is known when White has a bishop on g2, but this looks like a good version for White, since it's not so easy for Black to open lines. O-O then Rd1 will support White's queenside play (c4-c5), while the dark-squared bishop will head to b2 or even a3 after a2-a4.} *

