1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} a5 $5 {A rare choice in practice, if also Michiel Abeln's recommendation to prevent b2-b4 in his 'Leningrad Dutch: An Uncompromising, Attacking Opening' course. If you really want to avoid this sideline, then by all means do consider beginning with 5.b4 .} 7. O-O b6 ({Calmly housing the king. Now if} 7... d6 {White can either go} 8. b3 {and Bb2 or 8.a3!? , angling for Rb1 and b2-b4 after all.}) 8. b3 ({Abeln's preferred set-up. Now} 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. d5 e6 10. Rd1 {quickly became quite unclear in Eynullayev-N.Petrov, Mersin 2019.}) 8... Bb7 9. Ba3 $5 Na6 ({A slightly strange square for the bishop, but at least it stops Abeln's preferred set-up with . Now} 9... d6 $6 10. Ng5 {surely can't be good for Black with d4-d5 on the way.}) 10. Qd2 Z0 ({White continues to inhibit ...e6 and ...d6 ideas, and will reset after} 10... Nb4 {with} 11. Bb2 {. Meanwhile Rac1 or Rad1 will follow, sensibly getting off the a1-h8 diagonal and so enabling White to consider d4-d5 ideas, as well as even the engines' preference for Ng5!? and Bf3.}) *

