1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} Qe8 8. O-O {Not forced, but it makes sense to play the moves you definitely want to make first and here White certainly wants to castle. We are now ready to exchange in the event of ...e5, as well as to continue the queenside advance, with Bb2, a2-a4 and c4-c5 in some order.} h6 9. a4 $5 {Wasting no time getting going on the queenside, in part because any 'attack' on the kingside should not be feared.} g5 10. Ba3 Kh8 ({The bishop doesn't have to go to b2 and will be well placed here to support White's advance, be it with b4-b5 and c4-c5 or} 10... e5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. b5 {.}) 11. b5 Nbd7 12. c5 $1 {White was clearly for choice in Gorbatov-Dubinsky, Moscow 1996, with Black not up to much and Bd3 or Qc2 set to increase the pressure.} *

