1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} Qe8 8. O-O {Not forced, but it makes sense to play the moves you definitely want to make first and here White certainly wants to castle. We are now ready to exchange in the event of ...e5, as well as to continue the queenside advance, with Bb2, a2-a4 and c4-c5 in some order.} Kh8 $6 9. Bb2 c6 ({Pretty much cutting out} 9... e5 $6 {in view of} 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nb5 {, with a double attack on c7 and e5.}) 10. a4 {The queenside juggernaut rolls on with both a4-a5 and b4-b5 set to follow in short order.} Be6 11. b5 Bg8 $5 12. a5 $1 {One of the heroes of the white system, the Polish GM Zbigniew Pakleza, was doing pretty well here in Pakleza-Bartel, Budva 2003 being all set to make long-term gains with a5-a6 and/or to recapture if required with the knight on b5.} *

