1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} Qe8 8. O-O {Not forced, but it makes sense to play the moves you definitely want to make first and here White certainly wants to castle. We are now ready to exchange in the event of ...e5, as well as to continue the queenside advance, with Bb2, a2-a4 and c4-c5 in some order.} e5 ({The natural break, if one White is ready for. Of Black's slower moves, note that we'll consider} 8... c6 {via a 7...c6 8.O-O Qe8 9.a4 move order [/variation/35967840/#/9/w].}) 9. dxe5 {Opening the centre; there's absolutely no reason to allow Black to close things up with ...e4.} dxe5 10. b5 $1 ({This natural advance, intending Ba3 and Qb3, seems even more clear-cut than the Dangerous Weapons book recommendation of} 10. Nd5 {.}) 10... e4 $5 11. Nd4 {Black may have got in ...e4 after all, but only at the cost of driving the white knight to an excellent square. The plan is now Ba3, Qb3 followed by Nd5 or c4-c5, and unfortunately for Black, it's not so easy to challenge the dominant knight on d4.} c5 $6 12. bxc6 {Naturally White continues to open lines.} Nxc6 13. Ba3 $1 {Forcing the pace and so making Ncb5 an even stronger manoeuvre than it already is.} Nxd4 14. exd4 Rf7 15. Nb5 {Black was in big trouble on d6 and in general in Meier-Kindermann, German Bundesliga 2018.} *

