1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} c6 8. O-O {Again White starts with a definitely useful move and now Black should probably try to get ...e5 in after all.} Ne4 $6 {Thematic enough, but it runs into an unusually strong exchange.} 9. Nxe4 $1 fxe4 10. Nd2 {White simply wants to go after e4 and is already doing pretty well, as Richard had realised all the way back in 2009.} d5 11. Qb3 $5 e5 $5 ({Keeping the tension threatens} 11... Z0 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nxe4 {while supporting the b4-b5 advance.}) 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. Rb1 {A simple and strong approach, renewing the threat in the centre to leave Black in trouble there and on the queenside.} *

