1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} c6 8. O-O {Again White starts with a definitely useful move and now Black should probably try to get ...e5 in after all.} a5 $6 9. b5 $1 {Pressing straight ahead and preparing to increase the queenside pressure with Rb1.} e5 $6 10. dxe5 $1 {White's standard reaction to ...e5 and an especially strong one here.} dxe5 11. Ba3 {Forcing the pace. Now a subsequent Na4 will underline just how vulnerable on the dark squares Black already is.} Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 Re8 13. Na4 $1 Z0 ({As pointed out by David Vigorito, White is already doing extremely well. Black can cover b6 with} 13... Nbd7 {, but how will he then ever manage to untangle after} 14. Rac1 $2) *

