1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} c6 8. O-O {Again White starts with a definitely useful move and now Black should probably try to get ...e5 in after all.} Qe8 9. a4 $5 ({Here too Black has been known to move the queen to support ...e5 and now White can do even better than} 9. Bb2 {. 8...Na6 9.Qb3 Shoring up b4, supporting the queenside advance and again hoping for 9...e5? 10.c5+ . 9...Kh8 10.Bb2 Nc7 11.a4 a6 12.d5!? This switch to central play prepared to leave Black rather tied up if 12...cxd5 13.cxd5 , but otherwise White was ready to exchange on c6 and then increase the pressure with Rfd1 and/ or a4-a5, leaving him definitely for choice in Sjugirov-Bajarani, Baku 2016.}) ({White prepares to advance further both the a- and b-pawns while tempting the natural break. Both} 9. Qb3 {and}) (9. b5 $5 {also appear fairly promising.}) 9... e5 10. dxe5 {Our favourite line-opening exchange.} Ne4 $5 11. Bb2 {Keeping everything under control; Qc2 or even b4-b5 will follow.} a5 12. b5 {Thematic, if not the only decent choice here.} Nd7 13. bxc6 $5 ({Black has played to obtain control over c5, but is still to fully quell the early pressure and worse after} 13. Qc2 {or a more forcing option.}) 13... bxc6 14. Nb5 $1 {This idea from 2009 has held up well. Thanks to the loose rook on a8, the knight is taboo and White doing well with Nc7 next up.} *

