1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} c6 8. O-O {Again White starts with a definitely useful move and now Black should probably try to get ...e5 in after all.} e5 9. dxe5 {The standard reaction, opening lines ahead of placing the queen on b3.} Ng4 $5 10. Qc2 {Covering the knight on c3 while freeing d1 for a rook.} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Rd1 {Even here White has a definite pull with b4-b5 followed by Bf3 and/or Rb1 high on the agenda.} *

