1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} a5 $6 8. b5 {White can hardly mind being encouraged to advance like this and is now ready for our favourite central plan, as well as to usefully complete development with O-O, Qc2, Ba3 and Rad1.} e5 9. dxe5 $1 Nfd7 $5 10. O-O {Getting ready to go Ba3 and Nd5 if Black doesn't hurry to recoup the pawn.} Nxe5 11. Nd4 {A fine spot for the knight. White is again doing well and will follow up with Ba3 and Qb3, looking to force through c4-c5.} *

