1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} c5 $5 8. bxc5 dxc5 ({Exchanging must be critical. Now} 8... Ne4 {can be largely defanged by simply} 9. Bb2 {.}) 9. O-O ({This seems even stronger than the} 9. Bb2 {of Townsend-Tsilidis, Heraklion 2010. White gets ready to increase his grip with Qc2 and Bb2 while preparing a perhaps unexpected recapture on d4.}) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 $1 {With Bf3, Qb3, Rb1 and Rfd1 on their way, the c4-pawn is much more of an asset than a weakness and Black set to quickly come under pressure, not least on b7 and down the d-file.} *

