1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} Nbd7 $5 8. c5 $5 ({Here} 8. O-O e5 9. a4 {didn't seem especially clear in Pakleza-Aizenberg, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, so perhaps White should try to force things.}) 8... e6 ({Threatening Qb3+ and Ng5, and now} 8... d5 9. b5 {doesn't look like an especially great form of a Stonewall for Black.}) 9. cxd6 {Beginning to open lines ahead of pressing against e6.} cxd6 10. Qb3 Nb6 11. a4 {With the queenside pawns advancing and development set to be completed by O-O and Bb2, White surely enjoys a pleasant edge.} *

