1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} e5 {Critical and Black's most common reaction in practice, if by no means forced.} 8. dxe5 {Thematically opening the centre before Black can get in ...e4.} Nfd7 $6 9. Qd5+ $1 ({This seems even stronger than} 9. Bb2 {, as played by Kempinski (and, likewise, 8...Ng4?! 9.Qd5+ works and is likely to transpose).}) 9... Kh8 10. Bb2 Nxe5 11. h4 $1 {White enjoys an early initiative and likely has at least an edge. The queen can drop back to d2 if attacked and h4-h5 doesn't look especially easy for Black to meet.} *

