1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} e5 {Critical and Black's most common reaction in practice, if by no means forced.} 8. dxe5 {Thematically opening the centre before Black can get in ...e4.} dxe5 9. Qb3 {)} ({This simple recapture is definitely best, hoping for} 9. Nxe5 $4 Ne4 {.}) {Overprotecting the knight on c3 to threaten Nxe5, with Ba3 another important idea at White's disposal.} 9... Kh8 $6 10. Bb2 ({Hoping for} 10. Nxe5 Ne4 {which isn't so clear here, but White can reinforce the capture on e5 by either castling or developing the remaining bishop.}) 10... Qe7 11. Nd5 $1 {Seizing the initiative since Black must now exchange knights and open the c-file, otherwise e5 or c7 would fall.} Nxd5 12. cxd5 {With Rc1 on the way, White was doing well in Chekhov-Djurhuus, Gausdal 1991. We are most likely to go short, although a quick h2-h4-h5 is also pretty tempting.} *

