1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} e5 {Critical and Black's most common reaction in practice, if by no means forced.} 8. dxe5 {Thematically opening the centre before Black can get in ...e4.} dxe5 9. Qb3 ({This simple recapture is definitely best, hoping for} 9. Nxe5 $4 Ne4 {.}) {Overprotecting the knight on c3 to threaten Nxe5, with Ba3 another important idea at White's disposal.} 9... e4 $1 ({Black should push on so, since} 9... Qe8 10. b5 {, and if} e4 11. Nd4 {, is all just rather too easy for White.}) 10. Nd4 c6 ({Beginning to eye the e6-square (naturally} 10... Nbd7 $4 {- once somehow suggested in Informator -} 11. Ne6 {would be pretty embarrassing for Black), while also assisting with the queenside juggernaut: Ba3 and c4-c5 are imminent.}) 11. O-O ({An approach consistent with our 7...c6 8.O-O policy, although here both} 11. c5+ {and}) (11. Ba3 $5 {are also pretty tempting and quite strong.}) 11... Re8 12. a4 Nbd7 {This was preferred by a great Leningrad Dutch player in Chekhov-Malaniuk, Palma de Mallorca 1989, where White should have continued the queenside advance.} 13. a5 $5 {Chekhov later suggested this idea in Informator, threatening to break up the black queenside with a5-a6.} Ne5 14. c5+ Kh8 15. b5 $5 ({This might be even better than} 15. a6 {here. After}) (15. b5 {,} Z0 16. a6 bxa6 17. bxc6 {is a threat, Bb2 also on the way and 15...a6 would badly weaken the b6 point which the knight on c3 would be quick to invade.}) *

