1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} e5 {Critical and Black's most common reaction in practice, if by no means forced.} 8. dxe5 {Thematically opening the centre before Black can get in ...e4.} dxe5 9. Qb3 ({This simple recapture is definitely best, hoping for} 9. Nxe5 $4 Ne4 {.}) {Overprotecting the knight on c3 to threaten Nxe5, with Ba3 another important idea at White's disposal.} 9... e4 $1 ({Black should push on so, since} 9... Qe8 10. b5 {, and if} e4 11. Nd4 {, is all just rather too easy for White.}) 10. Nd4 c6 ({Beginning to eye the e6-square (naturally} 10... Nbd7 $4 {- once somehow suggested in Informator -} 11. Ne6 {would be pretty embarrassing for Black), while also assisting with the queenside juggernaut: Ba3 and c4-c5 are imminent.}) 11. O-O ({An approach consistent with our 7...c6 8.O-O policy, although here both} 11. c5+ {and}) (11. Ba3 $5 {are also pretty tempting and quite strong.}) 11... Qe7 12. Ba3 Re8 13. b5 $1 ({Here} 13. c5+ {was pretty good in Durak-Zeidler, British League (4NCL) 2023, and so would have been the following.}) 13... c5 ({Preparing to land the bishop on d6 if now} 13... Qf7 {, with both bxc6 and Rfd1 also high on the agenda.}) 14. Nd5 $1 {Exploiting the pin to the maximum to rather overload the defence.} Qd6 15. Rad1 {Threatening to take on f6, then pocket a pawn on c5 or f5.} b6 16. f4 $1 {Due to his light-squared weaknesses and development, taking en passant would cost Black material and so White is in complete control. We will double rooks and drop the knight back to c2 should all the routes towards e5 be closed to it.} *

