1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} e5 {Critical and Black's most common reaction in practice, if by no means forced.} 8. dxe5 {Thematically opening the centre before Black can get in ...e4.} dxe5 9. Qb3 ({This simple recapture is definitely best, hoping for} 9. Nxe5 $4 Ne4 {.}) {Overprotecting the knight on c3 to threaten Nxe5, with Ba3 another important idea at White's disposal.} 9... e4 $1 ({Black should push on so, since} 9... Qe8 10. b5 {, and if} e4 11. Nd4 {, is all just rather too easy for White.}) 10. Nd4 c5 $6 ({Beginning to eye the e6-square (naturally} 10... Nbd7 $4 {- once somehow suggested in Informator -} 11. Ne6 {would be pretty embarrassing for Black), while also assisting with the queenside juggernaut: Ba3 and c4-c5 are imminent.}) 11. bxc5 Nc6 $6 ({Accepting the pawn, one which White may even fight to hang on to in the event of} 11... Na6 12. Qa3 {.}) 12. O-O $1 ({As played in Kempinski-Nijboer, Warsaw 2005, where White returned the pawn with} 12. Bb2 {and had an even better option.}) 12... Nxd4 ({Now} 12... f4 $6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. exf4 {is nothing to fear, but, yes, d4 is hanging...}) 13. exd4 Qxd4 14. Rb1 $1 {Jumping off the dangerous diagonal and preparing to take over the initiative. Indeed, White is clearly for choice with all of Rd1, Ba3 and Nd5 on their way.} *

