1. Nf3 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. e3 {Our standard move order, of course, although we won't now rush into a queenside fianchetto if Black elects to make one of their own on the kingside.} g6 4. d4 {A logical advance with a black bishop en route to the long dark-square diagonal.} Bg7 5. Nc3 ({Straightforward development, although with this move order Robert Kempinski's pet line} 5. b4 $5 {is also quite a tempting choice.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {Conventional development thus far, but White is about to strike out on the queenside should Black continue with his standard Leningrad development.} d6 7. b4 $5 {Richard first became aware of the strength of this Leningrad sideline back in 2009 when researching 'Dangerous Weapons: The Dutch'. Fast forward 14 years and David Vigorito's old favourite still appears to pose some problems for Black.} e5 {Critical and Black's most common reaction in practice, if by no means forced.} 8. dxe5 {Thematically opening the centre before Black can get in ...e4.} dxe5 9. Qb3 ({This simple recapture is definitely best, hoping for} 9. Nxe5 $4 Ne4 {.}) {Overprotecting the knight on c3 to threaten Nxe5, with Ba3 another important idea at White's disposal.} 9... e4 $1 ({Black should push on so, since} 9... Qe8 10. b5 {, and if} e4 11. Nd4 {, is all just rather too easy for White.}) 10. Nd4 Nc6 $5 ({Beginning to eye the e6-square (naturally} 10... Nbd7 $4 {- once somehow suggested in Informator -} 11. Ne6 {would be pretty embarrassing for Black), while also assisting with the queenside juggernaut: Ba3 and c4-c5 are imminent.}) {A rare choice, but this suggestion of Valeri Beim's in 'Understanding the Leningrad Dutch' appears best.} 11. Nxc6 $5 ({Attempting to improve over} 11. c5+ {, as seen in the only test of 10...Nc6 which we could find, in Grebennikov-Sofieva, Leningrad 1990.}) 11... bxc6 12. Ba3 {This is why we refrained from c4-c5+. White still very much has designs of b4-b5 and also facilitates Rd1.} Be6 13. b5 Rf7 14. Rd1 {Continuing the plan and not rushing to take on c6, thereby helping to deny Black counterplay.} Qe8 15. O-O Z0 ({White may be slightly for choice and in any case, our play appears the easier. Bc5-d4 may be a good manoeuvre and White is now ready to head forwards with} 15... Z0 16. bxc6 Qxc6 17. Nd5 {.}) *

