1. Nf3 h6 {Hinting at a reversed Grob (or Borg) style set-up with ...g5.} (1... e5 $2 2. Nxe5 {There goes a clear pawn, and in a position where White will be able to get in at least one of d2-d4 and e2-e4.} Nc6 3. d4 $5 {Refusing to back down so and retreat the knight until attacked by a pawn is generally a good approach in such positions. White may now follow up with some combination of Bf4, Nc3 and e2-e4.} Nxe5 4. dxe5 d6 {This was Demidov-Shirazi, Internet (blitz) 2021, where Black's compensation was virtually non-existent. After} 5. Bf4 {White is simply a clear pawn up and may even meet} g5 $5 {with the super cool} 6. Bc1 {.}) (1... g5 $2 2. Nxg5 {The knight will drop back to f3 if attacked, once again both d2-d4 and e2-e4 are imminent, and Black must even watch out that they don't run into an awkward attack on f7 after Qh5.} e5 3. d4 $1 {Challenging in the centre without delay.} h6 4. Nf3 e4 5. Ng1 $5 {Undeveloping, but the knight is bound for e2 and Black's kingside hardly a pretty sight (5.Nfd2 is also somewhat better for White).} d5 {In Chigaev-Beerdsen, Internet (blitz) 2021, White was now content with} 6. e3 {and a pawn-up version of a French. It's also possible to aim for even more with 6.Bf4 White is a clear pawn up, with e2-e3 set to follow and then the c2-c4 break.}) 2. c4 a6 {The so-called Creeply-Crawly, another favourite of the late, great Mike Basman along with the Borg.} 3. Nc3 e6 ({Keeping all options open in the centre, while asking Black what they're up to. Is the plan really to sacrifice a pawn with} 3... b5 {or enter a Borg after all where ...a6 might not be too useful?}) 4. e4 $5 ({Of course,} 4. e3 {can't be a bad move, but there's no need to allow} d5 {here. Now 4...Nf6 can be well met by 5.e5 and 4...c5 5.d4 should be a pretty reasonable version of a Maroczy Bind for White.}) 4... Bb4 5. Qc2 ({You may well be happy with} 5. d4 {here, but White can even avoid any doubled pawns. 6.a3 will follow and perhaps even then b2-b4 and Bb2 with a souped-up sort of English Opening.}) *

