{Now White can exchange knights if the queen is attacked and meanwhile threatens both Nxg4 and to take a certain grip on the position with g2-g3.} 1. Nf3 h6 {Hinting at a reversed Grob (or Borg) style set-up with ...g5.} (1... e5 $2 2. Nxe5 {There goes a clear pawn, and in a position where White will be able to get in at least one of d2-d4 and e2-e4.} Nc6 3. d4 $5 {Refusing to back down so and retreat the knight until attacked by a pawn is generally a good approach in such positions. White may now follow up with some combination of Bf4, Nc3 and e2-e4.} Nxe5 4. dxe5 d6 {This was Demidov-Shirazi, Internet (blitz) 2021, where Black's compensation was virtually non-existent. After} 5. Bf4 {White is simply a clear pawn up and may even meet} g5 $5 {with the super cool} 6. Bc1 {.}) (1... g5 $2 2. Nxg5 {The knight will drop back to f3 if attacked, once again both d2-d4 and e2-e4 are imminent, and Black must even watch out that they don't run into an awkward attack on f7 after Qh5.} e5 3. d4 $1 {Challenging in the centre without delay.} h6 4. Nf3 e4 5. Ng1 $5 {Undeveloping, but the knight is bound for e2 and Black's kingside hardly a pretty sight (5.Nfd2 is also somewhat better for White).} d5 {In Chigaev-Beerdsen, Internet (blitz) 2021, White was now content with} 6. e3 {and a pawn-up version of a French. It's also possible to aim for even more with 6.Bf4 White is a clear pawn up, with e2-e3 set to follow and then the c2-c4 break.}) 2. c4 g5 3. Nc3 $5 {Again, we develop the knights before the central pawns, aiming especially here to lure Black forwards on the kingside.} Bg7 4. d4 c5 $6 ({Continuing to try and tempt Black into} 4... g4 $6 5. Nh4 {while beginning to occupy the centre.}) 5. dxc5 $1 Bxc3+ ({Yes, the pawn can very much be taken and now} 5... Qa5 6. Bd2 Qxc5 7. Nd5 $1 {gives White a strong early initiative and even more than that after} Qxc4 $2 8. Rc1 {.}) 6. bxc3 Qa5 7. h4 $5 ({Wasting no time undermining the black kingside and a tempting option, if not the only good one with} 7. Rb1 {also quite attractive.}) 7... g4 8. Qd4 $1 Nf6 9. Ne5 ({Here White went} 9. Nd2 {and later won in Agdestein-Hodgson, Hastings 1991/92, where he might instead have continued to force the pace.}) *

