1. Nf3 b5 $5 {Thanks to our first move this doesn't need any preparation, but is still quite an ambitious and positionally risky advance.} 2. e3 ({A modest approach, if one fully in keeping with our repertoire. It's also been used by some fairly strong players over the years, despite} 2. e4 {and}) (2. d4 {being much more common.}) 2... b4 $6 3. a3 $1 e6 ({White wastes no time in undermining, exploiting the fact that ...a5 isn't, of course, yet possible. Now} 3... bxa3 4. Nxa3 {would already yield a structural advantage and very pleasant edge.}) 4. d4 {Logical expansion. White may now follow up with Bd3, O-O and perhaps even e3-e4.} Bb7 5. axb4 $1 {Exchanging before ...a5 arrives.} Bxb4+ 6. Nbd2 {By no means forced, but an especially good way to block here. White may even be able to follow up c2-c3 by clamping down on the black queenside with Nb3.} Nf6 7. Bd3 d5 8. O-O {With kingside development complete White was all set to go Nb3 or even c2-c3, b2-b4 then Nb3 and was definitely for choice in Teverovski-Domingo Gadea, correspondence 2017.} *

