1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d6 3. c4 ({Simple chess as we angle for a good version of a 1...d6 2. d4 or 1...Nf6 2.c4 d6 3.d4 line (} 3. d5 Ne5 4. Nxe5 dxe5 5. e4 {is also a fairly pleasant edge). White will follow up with Nc3, e2-e4 and a timely d4-d5.}) 3... e5 4. d5 Nce7 5. e4 {Not only are Nc3 and Bd3 on their way, but already c4-c5 is a threat, undermining the black pawn chain. Already we might safely say that White has a promising version of a Modern or King's Indian position.} f5 $5 6. Nc3 {Maintaining control of e4.} Nf6 7. exf5 $1 Bxf5 $6 ({A timely exchange. If now} 7... Nxf5 {White will maintain control of e4 and a pleasant plus with} 8. Bd3 {, and there's also 8.h4!? if you're feeling more aggressive.}) 8. Bg5 $1 {Disrupting Black's smooth development and threatening Nh4.} Ng6 9. h4 $1 Z0 ({A final powerful move to remember. White is clearly better with} 9... Z0 10. h5 Ne7 11. Nh4 {back on the cards and also the simple idea of Bd3 to retake control of e4.}) *

