1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... Nf6 $6 {Based on your authors' simul experiences, this move is surprisingly common at lower club level.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 ({White wastes no time taking over the centre, getting ready for e2-e4 or if} 4... Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qa5 6. Bd2 {.}) 5. e4 $1 Nb6 ({Now} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bg4 {runs into} 7. d5 {, and the other retreat isn't all that much better for Black.}) 6. Nc3 {Simple chess, keeping d4-d5 in reserve. White may now continue development with Be3 or look to disrupt with Bb5 and/or d4-d5.} Bg4 $6 7. d5 $1 Ne5 $4 ({Now} 7... Bxf3 8. gxf3 $1 {with a huge centre and the two bishops is an important idea to remember. Similar positions are also discussed in Chapter 2 [/variation/23789319/#/7/w] of Part 1 of this LTR. Better that for Black or 7...Nb8 8.h3 than the attempt to exploit the pin, though.}) 8. Nxe5 $1 {A devastating queen sacrifice.} Bxd1 9. Bb5+ {Clearly Black will come out a clear piece down if the knight now retreats, but in any case there's already no defence.} c6 10. dxc6 Z0 ({The threats of} 10... Z0 11. c7+ {and 11.cxb7+ , as well as the possibility of 10...bxc6 11.Bxc6+ should spell an early resignation from Black.}) *

