1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... e6 4. e3 ({Playing by analogy with Part One of the course, although you may prefer} 4. Nc3 {followed by Bf4 or Bg5 In any case, Black's c-pawn-obstructing knight is slightly misplaced.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 ({Good, classical development as we wait to see what Black will do with the bishop on f8. Probably its best squares are b4 and e7, as we’ll now see, since} 5... Bd6 {offers White the chance to go} 6. c5 $5 {( 6.b3 is also fine) followed by Bb5 or Rb1 and b2-b4.}) 6. b3 ({Consistent with our anti-QGD lines (} 6. a3 $5 {is also a decent move), beginning a queenside fianchetto.}) 6... O-O 7. Bb2 {Both recaptures on c4 look reasonable if Black exchanges, while White is now ready to complete development with Rc1, Bd3 and O-O.} b6 8. cxd5 {Exchanging before Black can consider any ...Ba6 ideas in a bid to then go ...Na5 and make some use of the knight being on c6.} exd5 9. Rc1 {A fine spot for the rook. White should be slightly better and will continue with Bd3, O-O and maybe h2-h3. Two ideas to then bear in mind are seizing the initiative with Ne5 and improving the knight from c3 with Ne2 then Ng3 or Nf4.} *

