1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... e6 4. e3 ({Playing by analogy with Part One of the course, although you may prefer} 4. Nc3 {followed by Bf4 or Bg5 In any case, Black's c-pawn-obstructing knight is slightly misplaced.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 ({Good, classical development as we wait to see what Black will do with the bishop on f8. Probably its best squares are b4 and e7, as we’ll now see, since} 5... Bd6 {offers White the chance to go} 6. c5 $5 {( 6.b3 is also fine) followed by Bb5 or Rb1 and b2-b4.}) {The active course, taking play into an unusual type of Bogo-Indian.} 6. Bd2 O-O ({Calmly breaking the pin and so enabling White to meet} 6... Ne4 $6 {with} 7. Nxe4 {.}) 7. a3 $1 Bxc3 ({Angling to drive the bishop backwards. White might even be able to meet} 7... Bd6 {with} 8. c5 {.}) 8. Bxc3 {The bishop on c3 might not be especially active, but if White could get in b2-b3, Bd3 and O-O, our central control would surely supply a pleasant edge.} Ne4 9. Qc2 {Avoiding doubled pawns while preparing to challenge on the b1-h7 diagonal with Bd3.} f5 $6 10. Bd3 {There's no need to fear such a Stonewall set-up, especially when Black hasn't got a dark-squared bishop sitting on d6.} Bd7 11. O-O {Completing development ahead of beginning to attack on the queenside.} Be8 {A standard Stonewall manoeuvre to bring the bad bishop into play.} 12. cxd5 $1 {A timely exchange as White prepares to obtain some pressure down the c-file.} exd5 13. b4 {The Minority Attack begins, with already b4-b5 followed by Bb4 something of a threat.} Bh5 14. Ne5 $1 {A powerful leap to both defuse the kingside pressure and increase White's own pressure on the c-file.} Nxe5 15. dxe5 {With Bd4 or f2-f4 on their way, as well as pressure against c7 and the standard, undermining b4-b5 advance after ...c6, White stands clearly better.} *

