1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... e6 4. e3 ({Playing by analogy with Part One of the course, although you may prefer} 4. Nc3 {followed by Bf4 or Bg5 In any case, Black's c-pawn-obstructing knight is slightly misplaced.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 ({Good, classical development as we wait to see what Black will do with the bishop on f8. Probably its best squares are b4 and e7, as we’ll now see, since} 5... Bd6 {offers White the chance to go} 6. c5 $5 {( 6.b3 is also fine) followed by Bb5 or Rb1 and b2-b4.}) {The active course, taking play into an unusual type of Bogo-Indian.} 6. Bd2 O-O ({Calmly breaking the pin and so enabling White to meet} 6... Ne4 $6 {with} 7. Nxe4 {.}) 7. a3 $1 Bxc3 ({Angling to drive the bishop backwards. White might even be able to meet} 7... Bd6 {with} 8. c5 {.}) 8. Bxc3 {The bishop on c3 might not be especially active, but if White could get in b2-b3, Bd3 and O-O, our central control would surely supply a pleasant edge.} Ne4 9. Qc2 {Avoiding doubled pawns while preparing to challenge on the b1-h7 diagonal with Bd3.} Qf6 $5 10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 {Keeping the pawns intact while retaining control of e5.} Re8 12. O-O {White is ready to expand with b2-b4 or Rad1 and e3-e4, and even the main pawn break won't bring Black close to equality.} dxc4 13. Bxc4 e5 14. d5 $1 {This was a pretty useful gain of space in David-Abergel, Paris 2004; Nd2 and Rac1 will follow leaving Black somewhat worse down the c-file and in the centre.} *

