1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... e5 $5 4. Nxe5 $1 ({A radical attempt to break out and reach an Albin Countergambit after} 4. dxe5 d4 {.}) {White ensures that any Albin will be an improved version since the exchange of pieces costs Black some dynamism.} 4... Nxe5 5. dxe5 d4 ({Now} 5... dxc4 {can be well met by} 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. e4 {, so Black is likely to press ahead in the centre.}) 6. g3 {Preparing to place the light-squared bishop on a rather fine diagonal.} c6 7. Bg2 $1 {White is now all set to castle and need not fear either check which can be met, comfortably enough, by Nbd2.} Qa5+ 8. Nd2 Qxe5 9. Nf3 {With d4 so vulnerable, Black is going to have to contort if they want to try and hang on to the pawn.} Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qb6 11. O-O $1 ({Here} 11. Qb3 {was scarcely a bad choice in Sarkar-Rodriguez Fontecha, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, but White can also play more actively.}) {White is now set to seize a strong initiative with b2-b4 and/or e2-e3.} 11... Qxb2 $2 {This greedy choice only serves to make matters even worse for Black.} 12. Rb1 $1 Qxa2 $6 13. Nxd4 {Talk about a lead in development! Black might be a pawn up, but Qc1 followed by Ra1 is one big threat, Nxc6 another, a tactic which will occur even if Black now swipes c4.} *

