1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... e5 $5 4. Nxe5 $1 ({A radical attempt to break out and reach an Albin Countergambit after} 4. dxe5 d4 {.}) {White ensures that any Albin will be an improved version since the exchange of pieces costs Black some dynamism.} 4... Nxe5 5. dxe5 d4 ({Now} 5... dxc4 {can be well met by} 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. e4 {, so Black is likely to press ahead in the centre.}) 6. g3 {Preparing to place the light-squared bishop on a rather fine diagonal.} Ne7 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O $5 {The simplest use of the extra pawn is to return it for a lead in development and pleasant edge.} Nxe5 9. Na3 $1 ({Here} 9. e3 $5 {was pretty dangerous in Hebden-Williams, Hastings 2007/08, since it seems that Black must be brave and exchange on e3 to avoid being worse. Objectively speaking, White can do even better with a knight leap which has scored very well in practice.}) 9... Bxa3 $6 ({Heading for b5 or c2 to support b2-b4 in the event of} 9... c6 {.}) 10. Qa4+ {The other point to White's play. The pawns will not get doubled since a strong pawn sacrifice lies in waiting.} c6 11. Qxa3 $1 Nxc4 12. Qc5 {Now any knight move will be favorably answered by 13.Qe5+, attacking the g7-pawn.} Be6 13. b3 Z0 ({With Ba3 or Bb2 as well as Rfd1 on the way, White was doing very well in Volodin-Vihmand, Puhajarve (rapid) 2013, where he regained the pawn with some interest after} 13... Qd6 14. Qg5 $1 {.}) *

