1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... e5 $5 4. Nxe5 $1 ({A radical attempt to break out and reach an Albin Countergambit after} 4. dxe5 d4 {.}) {White ensures that any Albin will be an improved version since the exchange of pieces costs Black some dynamism.} 4... Nxe5 5. dxe5 d4 ({Now} 5... dxc4 {can be well met by} 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. e4 {, so Black is likely to press ahead in the centre.}) 6. g3 {Preparing to place the light-squared bishop on a rather fine diagonal.} Ne7 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O $5 {The simplest use of the extra pawn is to return it for a lead in development and pleasant edge.} Nxe5 9. Na3 $1 ({Here} 9. e3 $5 {was pretty dangerous in Hebden-Williams, Hastings 2007/08, since it seems that Black must be brave and exchange on e3 to avoid being worse. Objectively speaking, White can do even better with a knight leap which has scored very well in practice.}) 9... Be7 ({Heading for b5 or c2 to support b2-b4 in the event of} 9... c6 {.}) 10. Nb5 {)} O-O ({Pressing on not just d4, but also c7. Now} 10... c5 $6 11. Bf4 Bf6 12. e3 $1 {would give White a pretty useful initiative.}) 11. Nxd4 Nxc4 12. Qd3 $5 ({A possible small improvement on the} 12. b3 {of Ivanchuk-Morozevich, World Blitz Championship, Astana 2012. White is happy to exchange pieces in the centre and will meet 12...Ne5 with 13.Qe4 . In any event, our fine bishop on g2 (the other one may be pretty good too on f4) and slightly more active pieces should leave us slightly for choice.}) *

