1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... Bg4 {Black's main move by some margin, getting the bishop outside the pawn chain before going ...e6, if clearly not forced.} 4. Nc3 {Increasing the pressure against d5, an important square in the upcoming struggle.} Bxf3 $6 5. exf3 ({Simple chess to activate the unopposed bishop and keep up the pressure on the light squares, although} 5. gxf3 $5 {may appeal to fans of big centres.}) 5... e6 6. cxd5 {The key concept is to develop the bishop as actively as possible, i.e. to b5.} exd5 7. Bb5 $1 Bb4 ({The pin poses Black a number of problems, as does White's swift development with O-O up next, i.e.} 7... Nge7 8. O-O {would only leave one side with pieces flowing to good squares. The white queen may also have an important role to play, be it from a4 or e2.}) {Black's most common approach, going for a counter-pin. Plenty of other moves have been tried too, but none have come even close to helping Black reach equality.} 8. Bxc6+ {Damaging the pawns before Black can get ...Ne7 in.} bxc6 9. Qa4 Bxc3+ ({With a double attack and in a position where} 9... Qd6 {can be met by the sneaky} 10. Bf4 $1 {.}) 10. bxc3 Ne7 11. O-O {With Ba3 and Rfe1 on the way, Black was set to lose c6 after all in Bellon Lopez-Carlstrom, Tylosand 2019.} *

