1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... Bg4 {Black's main move by some margin, getting the bishop outside the pawn chain before going ...e6, if clearly not forced.} 4. Nc3 {Increasing the pressure against d5, an important square in the upcoming struggle.} dxc4 $2 {This is another line which may be surprisingly common at lower levels. Black's moves individually all make some sense, but collectively do not combine at all well.} 5. d5 {The semi-refutation, since Ne5 will follow if the black knight retreats.} Bxf3 6. exf3 {White's initiative is already of '+3' bounds, which shouldn't be such a surprise and here there are two ideas worth knowing:} Na5 7. Qa4+ $1 {Beginning to embarrass the knight on the rim.} c6 8. b4 $1 cxb3 ({Trapping and winning the knight, although after} 8... b5 $5 {White may prefer} 9. Nxb5 cxb5 10. Qxb5+ Qd7 11. Qxa5 {to taking the piece and allowing Black a certain clump of pawns.}) 9. axb3 e6 {A briefly sneaky defence, hoping for a fork on b4.} 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. Bd2 {It turns out that the knight is trapped after all, since retreating it would only make matters even worse for Black.} b6 $2 12. b4 Nb7 13. Qxc6+ Qd7 14. Bb5 {Once again we find Black completely undone on the light squares.} *

