1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... Bg4 {Black's main move by some margin, getting the bishop outside the pawn chain before going ...e6, if clearly not forced.} 4. Nc3 {Increasing the pressure against d5, an important square in the upcoming struggle.} e6 5. cxd5 exd5 ({Forcing the pace. Now} 5... Bxf3 6. exf3 exd5 7. Bb5 $1 {would once again be very pleasant for White.}) 6. Qb3 $5 ({This move lags some way behind} 6. Bf4 {in the popularity stakes, but increasing the pressure against d5 and b7 is certainly thematic with Black's bishop away from c8. White is also setting a little trap.}) 6... Bb4 7. e3 ({Simple chess to secure d4 and so threaten Ne5 (} 7. Ne5 $5 Nxd4 $1 8. Qd1 Nc6 9. Nxg4 h5 10. Ne3 d4 {doesn't seem so clear).}) 7... Nge7 8. Be2 {Now White won't even have to play with doubled pawns and both h2-h3 and a2-a3 will ask questions of Black's bishops.} O-O 9. h3 Be6 10. a3 Bxc3+ ({Beginning to eye b7, although White might meet} 10... Ba5 {with just the calm} 11. Bd2 {.}) 11. Qxc3 a6 12. O-O {With Bd2 and Rfc1 up next, White's compact position and gradual queenside play was worth an edge in Sumets-Bednarich, Luxembourg 2012.} *

