1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... Bg4 {Black's main move by some margin, getting the bishop outside the pawn chain before going ...e6, if clearly not forced.} 4. Nc3 {Increasing the pressure against d5, an important square in the upcoming struggle.} e6 5. cxd5 exd5 ({Forcing the pace. Now} 5... Bxf3 6. exf3 exd5 7. Bb5 $1 {would once again be very pleasant for White.}) 6. Qb3 $5 ({This move lags some way behind} 6. Bf4 {in the popularity stakes, but increasing the pressure against d5 and b7 is certainly thematic with Black's bishop away from c8. White is also setting a little trap.}) 6... Bxf3 {Black's most logical continuation, looking to counter against d4.} 7. exf3 $1 {The right way to recapture as we dangle d4 before Black.} Bb4 8. Bb5 $1 {Even with the queen on b3, this is quite an effective pin, one which creates a immediate threat.} Qd6 9. O-O Nge7 10. g3 $1 ({Axel Smith's suggested improvement over} 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Ne2 {, not that that was exactly bad in Smith-Sobjerg, Danish League 2008.}) 10... Ba5 11. Bxc6+ $5 ({Here} 11. Bg5 {was rather inconsistent with White's previous move in Giemsa-Haessler, German League 2009.}) (11. Bf4 {is, of course, one improvement, forcing the pace another.}) {Angling to cause trouble with Re1.} 11... bxc6 12. Re1 {With Bf4 next up and then a timely Qa3 very possible, Black is again clearly worse.} *

