1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... Bg4 {Black's main move by some margin, getting the bishop outside the pawn chain before going ...e6, if clearly not forced.} 4. Nc3 {Increasing the pressure against d5, an important square in the upcoming struggle.} e6 5. cxd5 exd5 ({Forcing the pace. Now} 5... Bxf3 6. exf3 exd5 7. Bb5 $1 {would once again be very pleasant for White.}) 6. Qb3 $5 ({This move lags some way behind} 6. Bf4 {in the popularity stakes, but increasing the pressure against d5 and b7 is certainly thematic with Black's bishop away from c8. White is also setting a little trap.}) 6... Bxf3 {Black's most logical continuation, looking to counter against d4.} 7. exf3 $1 {The right way to recapture as we dangle d4 before Black.} Nxd4 $2 8. Qa4+ $1 ({Black only reckons on} 8. Qxb7 {, underestimating a certain check.}) {A much, much stronger choice than taking on b7 due to our next move.} 8... Nc6 9. Ba6 $1 ({The star tactic and an easy move to overlook. Back in 2017, Swedish Grandmaster Smith wrote that 'Since learning about} 9. Ba6 $1 {in 2004, I have dreamt about playing it in a game.' We hope that his wish has or will soon come true!}) 9... Qc8 {Poleaxed in Teschke-Reyer, Nakenstorf 2008, Black actually resigned here, possibly only seeing 9...bxa6? 10.Qxc6+ and 9...Rb8? 10.Bxb7! , and we find the fact that a few correspondence players have reached this position more than a little strange.} ({In view of} 9... Qb8 $2 10. Qb5 $1 {, the only other move not to lose on the spot.}) 10. O-O {The moves Re1 and Nxd5 loom. Black pretty much has to return the pawn and accept a pretty miserable grovel.} d4 $2 11. Re1+ Be7 12. Nd5 {The bishop on a6 remains taboo and now Bf4 will quickly increase the pressure.} Kf8 13. Bf4 Bd6 14. Rac1 $1 {Threatening Rxc6 as Black's position is already borderline resignable.} *

