1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 ({Black gets ready to meet our favourite} 2. c4 {with} e5 {and a reversed Sicilian.}) {Just like against 1...d6, this is a good response, cutting out ...e5 in its entirety while threatening to push on to d5.} 2... d5 {Invariably played to compete for the centre.} 3. c4 ({Accepting the transposition to a Chigorin Defence where White has decent prospects of emerging with an edge. If you might prefer something independent, both the London style} 3. Bf4 {and Colle-esque}) (3. e3 $5 {are decent alternatives.}) 3... Bg4 {Black's main move by some margin, getting the bishop outside the pawn chain before going ...e6, if clearly not forced.} 4. Nc3 {Increasing the pressure against d5, an important square in the upcoming struggle.} e6 5. cxd5 exd5 ({Forcing the pace. Now} 5... Bxf3 6. exf3 exd5 7. Bb5 $1 {would once again be very pleasant for White.}) 6. Qb3 $5 ({This move lags some way behind} 6. Bf4 {in the popularity stakes, but increasing the pressure against d5 and b7 is certainly thematic with Black's bishop away from c8. White is also setting a little trap.}) 6... Bxf3 {Black's most logical continuation, looking to counter against d4.} 7. exf3 $1 {The right way to recapture as we dangle d4 before Black.} Nxd4 $2 8. Qa4+ $1 ({Black only reckons on} 8. Qxb7 {, underestimating a certain check.}) {A much, much stronger choice than taking on b7 due to our next move.} 8... Nc6 9. Ba6 $1 ({The star tactic and an easy move to overlook. Back in 2017, Swedish Grandmaster Smith wrote that 'Since learning about} 9. Ba6 $1 {in 2004, I have dreamt about playing it in a game.' We hope that his wish has or will soon come true!}) 9... Qe7+ $1 {Poleaxed in Teschke-Reyer, Nakenstorf 2008, Black actually resigned here, possibly only seeing 9...bxa6? 10.Qxc6+ and 9...Rb8? 10.Bxb7! , and we find the fact that a few correspondence players have reached this position more than a little strange.} 10. Kf1 {Clearly the safer side for the king to step.} Qb4 {The point of Black's play, not that White objects to the queen exchange.} 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. Bxb7 {Regaining the pawn and preparing to annex a second on d5.} Rd8 ({After} 12... Rb8 13. Bxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 {White is a pawn up, and can also very much continue to fight for the initiative.} Bd6 15. g3 {Preparing to untangle the kingside.} Ne7 16. Ne3 $1 {Keeping pieces on looks like the right call here. With Nc4 followed by Be3 and Kg2 on the way, it felt like White was more than just a pawn up in Bat-Bon, Avoine 2023.}) 13. a3 {Forcing the pace as White continues to target d5.} Nc2 14. Bc6+ $1 ({Here} 14. Rb1 {was seen in Leemans-Blass, correspondence 2011, where the 2603-rated black player eventually escaped with a draw after much suffering and 44 moves.}) {Axel Smith's recommendation.} 14... Ke7 15. Ra2 $5 ({One of two good moves, the other being Smith's} 15. Rb1 {. The move}) (15. Ra2 {threatens all of} Z0 16. Bxd5 {, 16.Nxd5+ Kd6 17.Ba4 , and 16.b4 .}) 15... d4 16. Be4 dxc3 ({It's high time to pick up the knight, either next move or after} 16... d3 17. Nd5+ {.}) 17. Bxc2 cxb2 18. Rxb2 {The material count might be level, but just look at White's initiative and mighty bishops. The immediate threat is Rb7 and after g2-g3 and Kg2 to involve the other rook, just how happy will the black king feel?} *

