1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. b3 ({There's absolutely nothing wrong with this, but just a quick reminder that} 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 {is our recommended move order when} c5 6. Nc3 {transposes to the game.}) 3... b6 4. Bb2 Bb7 5. Nc3 c5 {Black elects to compete for the d4-square after all, and now Simon, in true modern Reti fashion, opens a path for his light-squared bishop on the f1-a6 diagonal, rather than fianchetto it along more traditional Reti lines.} 6. e3 Be7 7. g4 $5 ({True to style, Simon opts for the more aggressive choice rather than the straightforward} 7. Be2 {, as he is quick to want to make use of his fianchettoed bishop on b2 and the now undefended g7-pawn.}) 7... O-O {This is by no means forced, as we saw back in Chapter 1b [/variation/35967297/#/7/w], but bravely castling so is a fairly critical test of White's approach.} 8. g5 {Consistently pressing ahead as White aims to secure an early initiative.} Ne4 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Rg1 $6 {Sensibly stepping off the long diagonal, but Black counters this slightly too optimistic plan in strong fashion.} (10. d3 $1 {is the correct choice, as we saw in our theoretical coverage in chapter 1b [/variation/35967303/#/10/w]. Now if 10...Bb7 White will advance with 11.h4 . Going to g6 would be somewhat more risky than in the game:} Bg6 $6 11. h4 $1 {Making full use of the rook still being on h1 to threaten the desirable h4-h5 - and with tempo.} Bh5 12. Be2 {White enjoys promising attacking chances, being all set to drop the knight back to h2, exchange bishops on e2, castle long and then head forwards on the kingside with Ng4 and f2-f4.}) 10... Nc6 $1 {The bishop isn't any longer able to retreat to base camp, but Black wants to react in classical fashion in the centre to the flank attack, be it with ...d5 or ...f6.} 11. d3 Bg6 12. h4 d5 13. Nh2 $5 {Simon doesn't back down and is threatening h4-h5 (White would also still like to get in f2-f4 and Ng4), so he must have at least slightly scared his Indian GM opponent, who now appeared to panic to some extent.} f5 $2 14. f4 $1 ({Closing lines (} 14. gxf6 $2 Bxf6 {would only give Black the initiative), but stabilising the position also gives White time to coordinate. 13...dxc4! 14.bxc4 Nb4 Consistently trying to invade on d3 would have retained the upper hand for Black, even if White now tried to confuse the issue: 15.Ng4!? b5! This perhaps unexpected blow retains the initiative, as with 16.cxb5 c4 . 15...Bxd3 16.Be2! Bg6 17.a3! Nc2+ 18.Kf1 Nxa1 19.Qxa1 This is the sort of position Simon was hoping for even after a trade on c4: White's pressure down the long diagonal supplies full compensation for the exchange. 15...Nxd3+ 16.Bxd3 Qxd3 17.Qxd3 Bxd3 18.h5! This would also just have been extremely unclear, with h5-h6 next up and taking on g5 set to leave both black bishops hanging: 18...Bxg5 19.Ne5 Bc2 20.Rxg5 f6 21.Rg3 fxe5 22.Bxe5 White's powerful dark-squared bishop this time gives him enough for the sacrificed pawn.}) {A powerful advance, preventing ...f4 and thereby keeping both of Black's bishops out of the game.} 14... Qd6 $6 (14... d4 15. Bg2 Be8 $1 16. Qe2 {This would simply have been pretty unclear, with Black having managed to get in his ideal ...d4 advance and White having made significant inroads on the kingside, whereas now in the game Simon is able to expand with tempo.}) 15. h5 Be8 16. h6 $1 {Never forgetting that the initial idea behind 7.g4 and White's attack was to make good use of that fine bishop on b2 while targeting g7.} gxh6 $6 {A rather risky choice.} (16... g6 17. Qe2 {With Nf3 and O-O-O on the way, White must be somewhat for choice, but at least this way Black would have kept lines closed on the kingside.}) 17. gxh6+ Bg6 18. Qh5 $1 {Threatening to take on g6 and win on the spot, hence Black's next.} Kf7 $1 19. Qh3 $1 {Keeping the queen active and allowing White to consider ideas of Be2-h5, as well as of O-O-O.} d4 $5 {Black's ideal advance as the battle hangs on a knife-edge.} 20. O-O-O $2 {Very natural, but the black knight was actually the key piece to deal with.} Bf6 $2 ({20...dxe3? 21.Bxc6! Qxc6 22.Qxe3 Black is devoid of counterplay and positionally lost, as White simply goes O-O-O and Nf3. O-O-O Now} 20... dxe3 21. Qxe3 {will keep d3 secure, and in any case, Black just seems to be struggling. For example: 21...Nxa2+!? 22.Kb1 Nc3+ 23.Bxc3 dxc3 24.Bxa8 Rxa8 25.Nf3 White's king should be safe enough on c2, he is the exchange up and can always bring his queen back into play via h1.}) ({Now the knight will be targeted after all.} 20... dxe3 $1 21. Qxe3 Nd4 {This just would have been very unclear, since Black's dark-squared bishop is no mug and is en route to f6. For instance:} 22. Nf3 Nxf3 23. Qxf3 Bf6 24. Bxf6 Kxf6 25. d4 $5 cxd4 26. Kb2 {White definitely has enough for the pawn, but probably no more than that.}) 21. Bg2 $1 Rad8 22. Bxc6 Qxc6 23. Nf3 {Just compare the knight on f3 with the bishop on g6. White would now quite like to trade pawns on d4, maybe make the king slightly safer on b1, and then begin to play down the e-file after Rde1.} b5 $5 24. exd4 cxd4 25. Rge1 {This rook is also pretty good on the half-open central file!} Kg8 (25... a5 $5 26. Ne5+ Bxe5 27. Rxe5 bxc4 28. dxc4 a4 29. Rxd4 Rxd4 30. Bxd4 {Even here, White should be winning - with care - since the bishop on g6 remains rather out of play and the white queen is an excellent defender.}) 26. Ne5 Qd6 27. Rd2 $1 {One of several good moves as Simon finds a neat way to bring a rook to the g-file while keeping the other one supporting the knight on e5.} Kh8 28. Rg2 a5 29. Qf3 $1 {Bringing the queen fully back into play as White prepares to decisively crash through on g6.} a4 (29... Rg8 $2 30. Rxg6 $1 {And the threat of Nf7+ decides proceedings.}) 30. Rxg6 $1 hxg6 31. Nxg6+ Kh7 32. Qb7+ $1 {A neat finish. 32...Kxg6 33.Rg1+ And the queen will pirouette back to h1 to force mate.  32...Kxh6 33.Rh1+ Kxg6 34.Qh7 .} 1-0

