1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 (2... c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nc6 {would be our usual route to the game position.}) 3. Nc3 $5 ({Not} 3. e3 {as White was presumably happy to debate the Nimzoesque lines that now arise after} Bb4 {when} 4. g4 $5 {is one fascinating possibility.}) 3... d5 4. e3 {We're now briefly back in the territory of Part One of the Modern Reti.} c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 (5... exd5 6. d4 {would be a Tarrasch option, but instead the Swiss IM elects to transpose into our coverage in Part Two of this Reti LTR.}) 6. Nxd5 $5 {Forcing the pace as White holds back on d2-d4, having another pawn advance in mind.} exd5 7. b4 {The aforementioned advance and quite a challenging gambit to meet, especially for the uninitiated.} cxb4 8. Bb2 {White develops rapidly, freeing c1 for the rook, and talk about a fine spot for the bishop!} Nc6 9. Rc1 {Preparing to increase the pressure with Bb5 followed by Ne5 or Nd4.} Be6 {A slightly unusual choice.} (9... f6 10. Nd4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Be6 12. Bd3 {This would be our usual route to the position reached at move 12 in the game.}) 10. Nd4 $5 (10. Bb5 $1 {This consistent choice would have been an even stronger option.} Rc8 11. O-O {Calmly does it. White only wants to go Ne5 when he can support the knight if required with f2-f4. The text move also introduces another of our favourite ideas in Re1 followed by e3-e4, and appears stronger than 11.Ne5 Qb6.} a6 12. Ba4 {Black remains under pressure on g7, as well as having to deal with the twin ideas of Ne5 and Re1. In short, White enjoys promising compensation and should not mind the light-squared bishop being driven backwards.} b5 13. Bb3 {White's fine dark-squared bishop continues to wreak havoc and Black is surely worse, with White all set to either take control of the board with Nd4 or obtain a strong initiative after Rfe1 and e3-e4.}) 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {Continuing to rake power down the long diagonal, hence Black's next move.} f6 12. Bd3 $5 {There's no rush to check on b5 here, as White instead supports Qh5+ ideas.} Bd6 13. Qh5+ {Disturbing the black king ahead of likely completing development with O-O, after which f2-f4 may well be a useful advance.} Bf7 {Black is determined to castle, and White can actually let him.} 14. Qg4 $5 {Moving the queen to g4 rather than h3, as White has a tactical idea in mind should Black now castle. And surely he should castle, with g7 attacked and White enjoying the superior coordination, which even allows him to consider ideas of O-O then Bc5.} O-O 15. Qf5 {The point of White's play, threatening mate. Black must now return the extra pawn on f6 or see d5 fall.} g6 ({After} 15... Bg6 16. Qxd5+ {White would love to exchange on g6 and then swing a rook with Rc4, so Black should probably go back with the bishop.} Bf7 17. Qe4 {With b7 loose and Bc4 on the way, White must be at least slightly for choice.}) 16. Qxf6 {Reclaiming the pawn as White refuses to fear an exchange of queens.} Qxf6 17. Bxf6 {This most unbalanced position isn't completely clear, and the engines helpfully proclaim '0.00', but we would certainly prefer to be on the white side. Why? Well, Bd4 and Ke2 will tidy things up, and while Black's queenside majority must be respected, his kingside weaknesses should be noted too, ones White would love to exploit with h2-h4-h5.} d4 $6 {An understandable bid for freedom before Bd4 left the bishop on f7 suffering, but it does cost Black a pawn.} (17... Rfe8 $6 18. Ke2 {18.h4!? This also looks pretty tempting with f2-f3 and g2-g4 set to follow.} Rac8 {Black changes course, having realised that a bishop exchange on e5 would allow White's rook into c7.} 19. Bb5 $1 {Forcing the pace ahead of expanding on the kingside.} Rxc1 20. Rxc1 Ra8 21. Bd4 {Black has ensured that this didn't come with tempo, but White is doing fairly well here. Just compare the bishops and note the highly mobile kingside majority!}) (17... a5 $5 18. Bd4 {Ensuring that the bishop is safe, helping to obstruct the one on f7, and even introducing ideas of a timely Bc5 exchange.} a4 19. Ke2 {As White always has Rb1, Black's problem here is: how to safely advance the pawns any further? It's not so easy.} Rfc8 20. g4 {The engines slightly prefer White, and so do we. Further expansion with f2-f4 and then perhaps h2-h4 is on the way, and it's still not so easy to see how Black can force the pace in a good way on the queenside.} Rxc1 21. Rxc1 b3 $2 22. axb3 {The first point to note here is the strength of 22...axb3? 23.Rc3! , and if 23...b2 24.Rb3 or 23...Ra3? 24.Rc8+ and wins.} a3 $5 23. f4 {White has the a1-square under control, and Black's defence does not look a pleasant one as White prepares to hurl Harry down the board.}) 18. Bxd4 {Clearly the pawn must go.} Bxa2 19. Ra1 Bf7 (19... b3 $5 {This saves the bishop and a-pawn, albeit while stranding the former out of play and forcing Black to give up the exchange.} 20. Bc4+ {20.Ke2!? Proceeding in unhurried fashion so is also very tempting and likely a stronger practical choice. For example: 20...Rfc8 21.Be4! Rc7 22.Bb1! Black is going to lose a clear pawn on the queenside.} Rf7 21. h4 {White would now love to get 22.h5 in or 21...h5?! 22.g4! .} Kf8 $1 22. Bxf7 Kxf7 23. f4 $1 {An important advance, taking control of g5 before going h4-h5. The position isn't especially clear, but the engines slightly prefer White, who may even yet castle and has the safer king position.}) 20. Rxa7 $1 {White can safely snaffle as he doesn't have to allow any awkward checks on a1.} Rxa7 21. Bxa7 Ra8 $6 (21... Be5 22. Ke2 {Fairly essential with ...Ra8 such a threat.} Ra8 23. Bc5 b3 24. f4 {Even after this superior defensive try, White is definitely for choice. He may probe with Be4, but Bb1 could well be a better approach, keeping Black's front b-pawn fully under control while allowing White to expand in the centre with e3-e4, as well as on the kingside with h2-h4-h5.}) 22. Bd4 {Covering a1, thereby leaving White fully in control and clearly better.} Bc5 23. Be5 {It's not too hard to dodge Black's little tactics ahead of going Ke2.} Bd6 24. Bb2 $5 {This may look risky, but the strong Romanian Grandmaster had no doubt already spied his 26th move to maintain full control.} Ra2 25. Bd4 Bc5 $6 (25... b3 26. Ke2 Bb4 27. Rd1 Be6 28. f3 {This would have kept the game going longer for Black, but also been pretty unpleasant for him, with the b-pawn going nowhere and White all set to expand in powerful fashion on the kingside.}) 26. Bb1 $1 {The bishops cover all the entry squares and the tactics work for White.} Ra5 (26... Bxd4 $2 27. Bxa2 Bxa2 28. exd4 b3 29. Kd1 $1 {The king is in time to halt the front b-pawn and the pawn ending is winning for White:} b2 30. Kc2 b1=Q+ 31. Rxb1 Bxb1+ 32. Kxb1 Kf7 33. Kc2 Ke6 34. Kd3 b5 35. f4 Kd5 36. g4 b4 37. f5 {And the win becomes clear.}) 27. Bb2 $5 (27. Bxc5 Rxc5 28. Ke2 {would have been pretty strong, followed by Be4 or even e3-e4 and d2-d4, but Parligras's choice is also a good one, retaining the bishop-pair.}) 27... b3 28. Ke2 {White is in full control and all set to go Rc1 then expand, but even so, Black shouldn't have now rushed to force an exchange.} Ba3 $6 29. Bxa3 Rxa3 30. Kd3 $1 Ra1 31. Kc3 {Black had seen enough. White will simply take full control with Kb2 and Rc1, after which the b-pawns shouldn't be too long for this world, and that's assuming that White doesn't just prefer to roll his huge central majority.} 1-0

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Reti - Part"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.02.21"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pranesh, M. vs. Livaic"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "B27"]
[PlyCount "83"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. e4 ({Our Reti route into the game would be:} 1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nf6 {2...g6 3.e4 Bg7 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 This would be yet another route - more on this move order in Chapter 3 [/variation/35967563/#/5/w].} 3. Nc3 g6 4. e4 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {And we've transposed to Pranesh-Livaic.}) 1... c5 2. Nf3 g6 {The Hyper-Accelerated Dragon, but it quickly becomes a standard Accelerated Dragon.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. c4 {The teenage Indian, then still a strong IM, sets up the classic Maroczy Bind, clamping down on the d5-square.} Nf6 6. Nc3 {We're definitely back in familiar territory, and now Black opts for the Gurgenidze variation, named after the highly creative and strong Georgian player Bukhuti Gurgenidze.} Nxd4 {Exchanging without delay.} (6... d6 7. Be2 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 {is a slightly more common route to the same position as the game.}) 7. Qxd4 d6 8. Be3 Bg7 ({White can play this before Be2 here, as clearly} 8... Ng4 $4 {wouldn't be wise with the kingside fianchetto yet to be completed.}) 9. Be2 O-O 10. Qd3 $5 {Our favourite square for the queen, who may now drop back to c2 in the event of any ...Nd7-c5 manoeuvre, and White is now all set to castle.} Be6 11. O-O (11. Bd4 $5 {This immediate challenge on the long diagonal, aiming to exploit Black's decision not to go 10...Nd7, is our preferred move order:} Qa5 12. O-O {And play has again transposed into Pranesh-Livaic.}) 11... Qa5 12. Bd4 Nd7 (12... Rfc8 13. b3 Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. f4 {Just a reminder that this would be thematic expansion from White, as we saw in our detailed theoretical coverage in Chapter 2b [/variation/36008143/#/15/w].}) 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. b3 ({Ever a useful move, securing c4 before going f2-f4 and thereby avoiding} 14. f4 $2 Qb6+ {.}) 14... a6 15. f4 $5 f6 ({White might also manoeuvre or prepare a gradual queenside advance, but it's also very much possible to stick with our favourite space-gaining advance, as we'll now see. White immediately threatens to cause serious early problems with} 15... Z0 16. f5 {.}) (15... Rab8 $2 16. f5 $1 Ne5 17. Qg3 Bd7 18. Nd5 {Black has managed to save the bishop, but that's the end of the good news for him, since there's simply no good way to defend e7:} Rfe8 19. Nxe7 $1 Rxe7 $2 20. f6+ {.}) 16. Kh1 $5 (16. h3 $5 {would also have been good prophylaxis, followed by Kh2, again taking the king off the g1-a7 diagonal.}) 16... Rfc8 17. Nd5 $1 {Heading forwards and rightly refusing to fear an exchange on d5.} ({The text move was also a novelty:} 17. a4 Nc5 18. Qc2 Qb4 19. Rab1 {This was Sadhwani-Abdulrahman Mohammad, Chennai 2022, where perhaps Black should have tried to break out:} b5 $5 {19...a5 20.h3 This left Black low on counterplay and White with a pleasant edge in the game.} 20. Na2 $1 Qa3 {20...Qa5 21.b4! Qxa4 This transposes.} 21. b4 $1 Qxa4 22. Qb2 {Black's queen is trapped, and he can't obtain quite enough compensation:} Nb3 $1 23. Qxb3 Bxc4 24. Bxc4 Rxc4 25. e5 $1 Qxb3 26. Rxb3 fxe5 27. fxe5 dxe5 28. Ra3 {The dust settles to leave Black with three pawns for the piece, but they aren't the most threatening pawns ever, and with Kg1 next up, White must be slightly for choice.}) 17... Qd8 $6 {Covering e7 while keeping the rooks on the queenside is fairly natural, but probably also a mistake.} (17... Bxd5 $5 18. exd5 {This structure looks rather pleasant for White to human eyes, not least with Rfe1 then Bg4 on the way, but the engines may well be correct that Black should still have tried it:} b5 $1 19. Qe3 Re8 20. cxb5 axb5 21. a3 {Even here, White should have a small but pleasant edge with the plan of b3-b4 in in conjunction with Rfe1 and/or g2-g4, seizing some useful space on the kingside}) 18. Qe3 {Ever a good square for the queen in such structures. Now Black will struggle to exchange on d5.} Rab8 (18... Bxd5 $6 19. exd5 Nc5 20. Rae1 $1 {Bringing another piece over to the sector of the board where Black lacks pieces of his own, the kingside. White may next advance with f4-f5 or simply h2-h4-h5, leaving Black with a pretty unpleasant-looking defence.}) 19. a4 $1 {As usual in the Maroczy Bind, White wants to keep control of both d5 and b5 wherever possible, and here this strong prophylactic advance leaves Black devoid of counterplay, which is likely why he should have taken the opportunity to exchange on d5 back when he could have at move 17.} Bf7 {This doesn't achieve too much, although already good advice for Black is hard to come by, bar to dig in for the long haul.} 20. Rad1 $1 {Pranesh doesn't fail to follow the important principle: improve your worst-placed piece.} a5 (20... e6 21. Nc3 Qc7 22. h4 {The knight has gone from d5, but Black remains dangerously low on counterplay thanks to White's control of d5 and b5. White might simply build up against d6, but we'd be extremely tempted to pursue a second weakness in the black king, perhaps with h2-h4-h5 and Rf3-h3.}) 21. Bg4 $1 {Probing while threatening to exchange on d7, then win the exchange.} Bxd5 {Black is clearly and unpleasantly worse after this, but it was still likely the best defensive try.} (21... e6 22. Nc3 Qe7 23. Nb5 Rc6 {Black is badly tied down and White many good moves here, including:} 24. Qd2 Nc5 25. e5 $1 dxe5 26. fxe5 {Itching to break in down the long diagonal after 26...fxe5? 27.Qc3 .} f5 27. Bf3 {Black has no time to take on b3, unless he wants to give up the exchange, thereby leaving White clearly for choice thanks to his extra space, superior bishop, and especially the hole on d6.}) 22. exd5 f5 23. Bf3 {Keeping Black's knight out of e4 as the defence remains a rather unpleasant one, fairly solid though Black still is.} Nf6 $6 (23... Nc5 {This was likely necessary to at least remind White that he too has one weakness: b3.} 24. g4 $5 Qf8 $1 {24...fxg4? 25.Bxg4 Rc7 26.f5! The attack is surely too strong with fxg6 followed by Be6 but one idea.} 25. Rg1 $1 {Maintaining the tension. With Rde1 next up and then the idea of gxf5 Qxf5; Be4 White still maintains at least a very pleasant edge.}) 24. Rde1 Rc7 25. Qd4 {Pinning as the idea of h2-h3 and g2-g4 becomes quite attractive, while clearing the e-file so that White can increase the pressure with Re6.} Kg8 26. h3 (26. g4 $1 fxg4 {26...Nxg4? 27.Bxg4 fxg4 28.f5 The attack will surely crash through.} 27. Bd1 {With f4-f5 and then Bxg4 or Bc2 on the cards, White remains clearly for choice, and this might well have been stronger than the game continuation.}) 26... h5 $1 {Pretty much essential, as Black could hardly allow White to blow open the kingside with g2-g4.} 27. Re6 Kf7 28. Rfe1 b6 29. Kg1 $5 {Calmly does it. There's no need to rush when you have full control, so Pranesh brings his king slightly closer to the centre and off the h-file in preparation for a timely g2-g4 break.} h4 30. Qe3 (30. Qf2 $1 Qh8 31. Qe3 Qf8 32. g3 $1 hxg3 33. h4 {This, followed by Kg2xg3 and an eventual h4-h5, is how the engines prefer to continue improving the white position.}) 30... Rbb7 $6 {The Croatian Grandmaster overprotects e7, but should probably have preferred to keep a rook on the back rank.} (30... Rcb7 $5 31. Kf1 $5 {The white king sets off on a Petrosianiac journey to the queenside, and only once the king is safe will White set about arranging the g2-g3/g4 break. 31.g3?! hxg3 32.Kg2 Qc7! 33.Kxg3 Rh8 With a rook on h8, White will find it much harder than in the game to force through h3-h4-h5.}) 31. g4 $1 {This well-timed break threatens to exchange on f5, then move the king and invade down the g-file.} hxg3 32. Kg2 Qf8 (32... Qh8 $5 33. Kxg3 Qh6 34. h4 {34.Qe2!? This and only then h3-h4 also makes good sense with the black rooks still tied down to the defence of e7.} Nh5+ 35. Bxh5 Qxh5 36. Rg1 $1 Rc8 $1 {36...Qg4+?! 37.Kf2 Qxh4+ 38.Kf1 White's king is now quite safe and g6 is falling: 38...Qh5 39.Rexg6! Qxg6 40.Rxg6 Kxg6 41.Qe6+ Kg7 42.Qxf5 Thanks to the agile queen, it won't be at all easy for Black to set up a fortress, and White should be able to force through f4-f5-f6 at a timely point, then pick off d6, with good winning chances.} 37. Kh3 Rh8 38. Qf2 {Even here, White's ability to win the queen for two rooks on g6 is a good one, when Black may remain tied down to b6 and the passed h-pawn should be a useful asset.} Rh6 $2 39. Re2 $1 Rh8 40. Rg5 Qh6 41. Qe1 {With Reg2 followed by Qe6+ on the way, White should be winning.}) 33. Kxg3 Rc8 34. h4 $1 {Livaic's position has quickly become critical, with h4-h5 threatened to blow open the kingside and his queen tied to the defence of e7.} Re8 35. h5 $1 {Brutal play from Pranesh, who plays this stage of the game with great energy.} Qh6 (35... gxh5 $2 36. Rxf6+ $1 Kxf6 37. Qe6+ Kg7 38. Bxh5 {Black isn't going to survive as White's remaining rook comes to g1 or h1 with some effect.}) 36. hxg6+ (36. Rxf6+ $1 Kxf6 37. Kf2 {This would have forced the win followed by Qe6+ and Rg1.}) 36... Qxg6+ 37. Kf2 Ng4+ $2 (37... Qg7 {is a stouter defence, although even here White likely would have won:} 38. Qe2 $1 Qh6 39. Bh5+ $1 {Thanks to the pin and the possibility of Rxf6+, White is winning the exchange.}) 38. Bxg4 Qxg4 39. Rh6 $1 {Threatening to trap the black queen with Rg1, as well as to finish off the black king.} Rg8 40. Qe6+ Kf8 41. Rf6+ $1 {Finishing crisply.} exf6 42. Qc8+ (42. Qc8+ Kg7 43. Qxb7+ {Black will be mated if he goes back to f8, but otherwise he will lose the queen. Pranesh went on to a landmark result as he dominated the famous Rilton Cup to win by a point and also secure his GM title.}) 1-0

