1. c4 (1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. h4 {would, of course, be our modern Reti move order.}) 1... Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. Nf3 g6 5. h4 $1 ({Wasting no time in both avoiding the main lines of the Grunfeld (} 5. d4 {), and seizing an early initiative.}) 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. h5 c5 8. Qa4+ $5 {A discombobulating check to which all Black's responses have downsides, as we noted in Chapter 4a [/variation/36141522/#/8/w].} Qd7 9. Qc4 b6 10. Ng5 e6 11. Qh4 $1 {With c5 and f7 secure, so the queen's business on c4 complete, White swings his most powerful piece across to h4, teeing up a certain queen sacrifice.} Qe7 12. hxg6 $1 {Here we go...} hxg6 13. Qxh8+ {Clearly forced by this point, as well as pretty strong.} Bxh8 14. Rxh8+ Kd7 15. d4 {We ended our theoretical coverage here [/variation/35967636/#/15/w]. White threatens Rh7, as well as Ne4 and Bg5, and would appear to have more than enough compensation for the queen.} Nc6 {Logically preparing to bring the knight to d8 to defend f7.} (15... cxd4 $6 {It would be hard to criticise an opponent for trying to break out so, but this is a line-opening exchange which White should welcome.} 16. Rh7 $1 {Consistent and even stronger than recapturing on d4.} Qc5 17. Bd2 $1 {Calm and also very strong defence. As well as f7, White threatens cxd4 followed by Rc1 or Rd1.} dxc3 18. Be3 $1 Qa5 19. g3 $1 {Since 19...c2+ can simply be met by 20.Bd2, White is able to bring another piece into the attack.} c2+ $5 {19...Bb7 20.Rxf7+ Kc8 21.Bh3! Bxe6+ is a big threat, and Rc1 also on the way. As David Cummings put things on ChessPublishing, 'White should win.'} 20. Bd2 Qa4 21. Rxf7+ Ke8 22. Rf4 {Even against this engine-approved try, White must be clearly for choice with his powerful initiative. The pawn on c2 surely isn't long for this world, a timely Re4 will target e6, there are still ideas of Nf7 and Nd6+, and even Bg2-e4 could present serious difficulties for the defence. And, unsurprisingly, after a couple of minutes, the engine assessment goes over '+1' and begins to grow.}) 16. Rh7 Nd8 17. Ne4 $1 {With f7 secure, White finds a new role for the knight, preparing to cause a degree of chaos on the dark squares with Bg5.} Bb7 (17... cxd4 $2 18. Bg5 $6 {18.a4! This is simply pretty strong, bringing the dark-squared bishop powerfully into play via another direction. 18...e5 19.g3! Continuing to harass the poor black queen. Rarely can bishops heading to a3 and h3 be so potent together. 19...Ne6 20.Ba3 Nc5 21.Bg2 Black has saved his queen, but will do well to save the game, since not only is the rook on a8 hanging, but White also threatens cxd4 exd4; Rc1.} Qa3 $1 19. Rd1 $1 Bb7 20. Rxd4+ Bd5 21. c4 {Even here White enjoyed a strong initiative and went on to win in Mchedlishvili-Madaminov, New Delhi 2023.}) 18. Bg5 Qf8 {Clearly forced, and now White might repeat moves to emphasise control, although in any case he is certainly correct to play on.} 19. Nf6+ $1 Kc8 20. e4 {Finally, on move 20, setting up a big centre against the Grunfeld. Factor in Black's suboptimal coordination and White's compensation should be clear. The immediate threat is to further cramp Black while increasing the pressure with d4-d5, then g2-g3.} a5 $5 21. Rh3 $1 {A change of approach. White will now be able to swing the rook over to c3 or b3 in the event of a pawn exchange on d4, and also gets ready for ...Ba6.} (21. d5 $5 {These two correspondence players may well have spent far longer with powerful computers on this position than your authors, but we can't see too much wrong with this consistent advance. For example:} exd5 {21...Ba6? 22.Rd1! Bxf1 23.d6! The threat of Bh6 means that White is winning material.} 22. g3 {Threatening 23.Bh3+, and if 23...Ne6 24.Rd1.} Bc6 $1 23. exd5 Qe7+ 24. Kd2 $1 Bxd5 25. Re1 $1 {White has jettisoned the d-pawn, but his pieces coordinate brilliantly.} Be6 26. Rh8 $1 {Certainly, in an over-the-board game, you'd have to heavily fancy White here, with Bg2 one idea, Ne4 Qd7+; Kc1 and then Rd1 another.}) 21... Ba6 $1 22. Bxa6+ Rxa6 23. e5 $1 {Kudos to Rallabandi, who clearly judged well from afar that his strong central bind supplied by the pawns on d4 and e5 would supply promising, lasting compensation.} cxd4 24. Ne4 $1 f5 $1 {Further computer-approved precision.} (24... dxc3 $2 25. Nd6+ Kb8 {25...Kc7 26.Bxd8+ Kxd8 27.Rxc3 It's fast becoming a massacre down the open central files.} 26. Bf6 {And the threat of Rh8 is terminal.}) 25. Nd6+ Kb8 26. Ke2 $1 {Preparing to double on the h-file as White realises there's no need to hurry with the recapture on d4.} Ra7 $1 (26... dxc3 $2 27. Rah1 Nf7 28. Nxf7 {Black can save his queen, but not also the king:} Qa3 29. Bd2 $1 Qxa2 30. Rxc3 {Unsurprisingly the attack is just far too strong.}) (26... d3+ $2 27. Kd2 {Once again the open h-file will prove Black's undoing.}) 27. cxd4 Nf7 28. Rah1 $1 Rd7 29. Rh7 {Fine, controlled play from Rallabandi, never really allowing Black the chance to escape White's grip.} Ka7 30. Nxf7 Rxf7 31. d5 $1 {Giving up the central clamp, but White's bishop is superbly placed to help shepherd a central passed pawn down the board.} Ka6 32. Rxf7 Qxf7 33. d6 Qd7 {Clearly, Black's only real try is to go active and hope for a perpetual check, but Rallabandi has everything worked out.} 34. Rd1 $1 Qb5+ (34... b5 35. Ke3 $1 b4 36. Kf4 a4 37. Be7 {The incursion of the white king into the black kingside should prove decisive.}) 35. Ke1 Qb4+ (35... Qxe5+ $5 36. Be3 Qc3+ 37. Rd2 $1 f4 $1 38. Bxf4 Qc1+ 39. Ke2 Qc4+ 40. Kf3 {The king will escape to safety on the kingside, thereby leaving White with excellent winning chances.}) 36. Bd2 (36. Ke2 $4 Qg4+ {Naturally, White was never going to blunder so in a correspondence game.}) 36... Qe4+ 37. Be3 $1 Qb4+ (37... f4 $2 38. d7 fxe3 39. d8=Q {And Black is out of tricks.}) 38. Ke2 Qb5+ 39. Rd3 Qd7 (39... Qb2+ $2 40. Kf3 Qb5 41. Rd4 {Retreating to d7 in the game isn't a good sign, but here Black would be out of checks and simply left with an inferior version of what now occurs.}) 40. Ke1 $1 {Very precise. White can now move the rook without ...Qb5 being check and only wants to bring the king to d2 once ...Qa4+ is no longer an option. The overall plan is simple: to run Black out of good moves and so create a zugzwang situation.} a4 41. Kd2 (41. a3 $1 Qb5 42. Rd1 Qd7 43. f3 {With Black stymied on the kingside, this should also be winning after Kf2 and Rc1-c7.}) 41... Kb7 42. g3 Ka7 43. Ke1 {There's no need to rush with Black pretty much unable to shift the queen.} Ka6 44. a3 $1 {Finally. The dark-square blockade is now complete, and Rallabandi is able to manoeuvre to effect a breakthrough on the queenside.} Kb7 45. Rd2 Ka6 46. Rb2 b5 47. Rc2 $1 (47. Rc2 b4 $5 48. Rc7 Qd8 49. Ra7+ $1 Kb5 50. Rb7+ Kc4 51. Rxb4+ Kc3 52. Rxa4 {It's a technical win, since the black queen remains so passive and Delroy the d-pawn so powerful.}) 1-0

