[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Smyslov, Vasily vs. Karadzha"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A16"]
[PlyCount "79"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. c4 {The seventh world champion, Vasily Smyslov, begins with the English Opening.} (1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 {This would be our Reti-approved route towards the King's Indian.} d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 $5 {Our favourite little wrinkle and now one route into the game position would be:} e5 7. d5 Nbd7 8. O-O Nc5 9. Bc2 a5 10. a3 {.}) 1... Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. O-O Nc5 9. Bc2 {Preserving an important bishop as the game is almost fully back on track.} O-O 10. a3 {All is now set for Rb1 and b2-b4, just as we saw in Chapter 5b [/variation/35967693/#/10/w].} b6 $6 {Such a blockading type strategy is not unknown in club and internet chess, but White should largely welcome it. Black usually proves unable to hold up c4-c5 forever, and when that advance does finally arrive, it will pack an even larger punch.} 11. Rb1 $6 (11. b3 $1 {is a slower approach than ideal, but a good one here. There was one notable point behind Black's last, which this bypasses.} h6 12. Rb1 Kh7 13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 Ncd7 15. Be3 {White is a tempo down on the game, but still somewhat for choice since his queenside play is faster than anything Black can muster on the other wing.}) 11... h6 $6 {Missing a definite chance.} (11... a4 $1 12. Be3 Bd7 13. Nd2 {With e4 secure, White is finally ready to go after a4, but Black is in time to protect it.} Qe8 {With ...Nh5 on the way, Black enjoys decent counterplay.}) 12. b4 {The ideal advance. Smyslov is fully back in the groove.} axb4 13. axb4 Ncd7 14. Be3 {Refusing to fear ...Ng4, supporting the c4-c5 break and also facilitating Ra1.} Kh7 (14... Ng4 15. Bd2 {Now h2-h3 or Ne1 will drive Black backwards and it's too early to push the f-pawn:} f5 $2 16. h3 Ngf6 {16...fxe4 17.Bxe4} 17. exf5 gxf5 18. Bxf5 {White has netted a pawn and made serious inroads on the light squares.}) 15. Ra1 $1 {White would love to take control of the a-file and then invade down it.} Ba6 $6 16. Nd2 {Covering c4, but also a thematic move in general. The knight will be very well placed here should White ever get c4-c5 then Nc4 in.} Ng8 17. Ba4 $5 {Threatening to win material with Bc6.} Bb7 $6 (17... Bc8 $1 18. Qe2 $5 {18.Bc6 Rxa1 19.Qxa1 f5 20.f3 Ndf6 White is probably slightly better, but with ...Nh5 on the way, Black definitely has some counterplay.} f5 19. f3 {Securing e4 and especially a retreat square for the bishop.} Ndf6 20. Bc2 {Challenging for the a-file for a second time as White retains a pleasant advantage. With c4-c5 imminent, he would certainly be somewhat ahead in any race scenario.}) 18. Bc6 $1 {Invading with tempo and also enabling White to follow up a rook exchange with Qa4. As Smyslov has realised, White is forcing a favourable structural transformation.} Bxc6 (18... Rb8 $6 19. Ra7 Bc8 $6 20. Nb5 {Black has retained the light-squared bishops, but c7 and then his entire position is about to collapse.}) 19. dxc6 Ndf6 20. f3 {By no means the only good move, but it makes definite sense to keep Black out of g4 and so facilitate Ra4.} Qe7 21. Ra4 Rfb8 {Black's play feels all rather too unhurried. After all, with such a fish bone wedged on c6 in the throat of his queenside, he isn't going to be able to defend on that flank forever.} (21... h5 $5 {At least facilitating ...Bh6 would have allowed Black to unravel to an extent and possibly still acquire a bit of counterplay on the kingside.}) 22. b5 $1 {Clamping down further on the black position ahead of doubling rooks.} Qd8 23. Qb3 (23. Ra6 $5 {This would also have been strong, since Black doesn't really want to exchange rooks here:} Rxa6 24. bxa6 Ra8 25. Qa4 Qc8 26. Ra1 {With Nd5 to follow or a6-a7 and Qa6, not to mention Ndb1-c3-b5, Black surely wouldn't be able to hold out forever.}) 23... Rxa4 24. Nxa4 Ra8 25. Ra1 {Smyslov proceeds in a positional and unhurried fashion.} (25. Nb1 $5 Nh5 26. Nac3 {is the engines' preference, looking to either break through with c4-c5 or Nd5 followed by a piece sacrifice on b6.}) 25... Ra5 $6 ({Even after} 25... Nh5 $5 26. g3 Nf4 {Black feels too slow, but at least this would have complicated the struggle and given White a bit more to think about.}) 26. Ra2 $1 {All is now set for Nc3 or even Nb1.} Qa8 $2 {Black continues to operate on the wrong flank and be far too compliant.} 27. Nb1 {Continuing the positional tour de force.} (27. c5 $1 {This pretty much wins by force:} bxc5 {27...dxc5 28.Nc4 Ra7 29.Ncxb6! cxb6 30.Nxb6 Once again the connected passed pawns will prove far too strong.} 28. Nc4 Ra7 29. Nxd6 $1 cxd6 30. b6 {And the pawns will sweep all before them.}) 27... Ne7 28. Bd2 Ra7 29. Nbc3 {Our old friend, a sacrifice on b6, looms after the upcoming Be3.} Kg8 30. Be3 Nc8 {Desperately trying to cover b6, but Smyslov refuses to panic and continues to manoeuvre adroitly, no doubt all the while enjoying his total control of the position.} 31. Ne2 Ra5 32. Nc1 $1 {Heading for d3 and b4, or simply preparing to recapture in the event of exchanges on a2.} Nh7 33. Bd2 Ra7 34. Nc3 Rxa2 $2 {Once again, Karadzhaev is far too compliant.} (34... Ne7 35. Rxa7 Qxa7 36. Qa2 Qb8 37. Nd3 {With Nb4 and Be3 next up, Black is undoubtedly suffering somewhat, but at least this way, White would still have to find an accurate way to break through.}) 35. Qxa2 Qxa2 (35... Qb8 36. Nd5 {And the white queen will invade with decisive effect.}) 36. N1xa2 Ne7 37. Nb4 {The c6 vs c7 situation is going to cost Black the game.} Nf8 $2 (37... Nf6 38. Be3 $1 {Even here, White will either break through after Nd5 with a Bxb6 sacrifice or tee up a devastating piece sacrifice with Na6.}) 38. Na6 Ne6 39. Nd5 {Overloading the defence. The game is up for Black.} Nc8 40. Naxc7 1-0

