[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Dubov, Daniil vs. Carlsen"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A05"]
[PlyCount "107"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 Bg4 7. Be2 {Breaking the pin at the cost of a tempo to keep d4 secure.} Nfd7 8. Be3 {By this stage, you wouldn't necessarily know that White's light-squared bishop has moved twice.} e5 {A natural, very King's Indian challenge in the centre, if perhaps not best with the bishop on g4. We saw Black's alternatives in Chapter 5c [/variation/35967705/#/8/w].} 9. d5 {Naturally, White has no desire to see the centre open and let Black acquire easy counterplay.} a5 10. Nd2 {A sensible choice, forcing the exchange of light-squared bishops, which is usually in White's interests as it helps to reduce the potential of Black's counterplay.} (10. Ng5 $1 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 {This more aggressive choice, intending a quick g2-g4, was our recommendation, however, in Chapter 5c [/variation/35967710/#/11/w].}) 10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 f5 12. f3 {Preserving the bishop and maintaining the structure; White doesn't appear to gain much from an exchange on f5 here.} Na6 13. O-O-O $1 {With Black not having yet gotten in ...c6, this is an aggressive and good choice. The white king will be fairly safe on b1, and already there is a threat to open up the kingside with exf5 followed by g2-g4.} Nac5 14. Kb1 {A sensible choice, not least considering this was a blitz game.} (14. exf5 $5 gxf5 15. g4 {White wants to exchange on f5 to take control of e4, as well as open up the g-file for his king's rook.} fxg4 16. Rhg1 $1 {Much stronger than 16.fxg4 e4! With 16.Rhg1 ! White offers a pawn for a strong attack and can now meet 16...e4 simply enough with 17.Rxg4 .} gxf3 17. Nxf3 {With the knight en route for g5, then the queen to h5 or g4 if allowed, White enjoys promising compensation for the pawn.}) 14... a4 (14... f4 15. Bf2 {Black's problem here isn't so much that White might play for a gradual queenside advance, but that the kingside is by no means permanently closed. White can probe with h2-h4 and may then tee up the key g2-g3 break with Rdg1.}) 15. a3 $6 {Exchanging on f5 was still the way to go, but we mustn't be too harsh considering the time control and just who was sitting behind the black pieces.} Rf7 $6 16. exf5 $1 {At the third opportunity, Dubov seizes his chance.} gxf5 17. g4 Qf6 ({It is still a powerful break. Now} 17... fxg4 18. Rhg1 $1 {would again be a promising pawn sacrifice.}) 18. gxf5 Qxf5+ 19. Ka2 {White is still better after this, but there was no need to allow the black queen to become so active.} (19. Nce4 $1 {White will recapture in the event of any exchange on e4 with the f-pawn, is now set to break the pin with Ka2 and also to seize the initiative on the kingside with Rdg1.}) 19... Qc2 $1 20. Rc1 Qd3 21. Qxd3 $1 {Dubov readjusts well. White will still enjoy an extremely pleasant edge after the exchange of queens thanks to his control of e4 and the more active bishop, as well as the open g-file.} Nxd3 22. Rcg1 N7c5 23. Rg3 {White might as well involve both rooks before challenging Black's central semi-blockade with Nde4.} Kh8 24. Rhg1 Bf6 25. Nde4 {Thematically continuing with the aforementioned plan.} (25. Bh6 $5 {The engines are likely right that this is even stronger, seizing control of g7 ahead of heading forwards with Nde4.}) 25... Nxe4 26. Nxe4 {By now Bh6 is most definitely a major threat. Carlsen finds the only real defence.} Nf4 $1 27. Bxf4 $1 {This does leave Black with an unopposed dark-squared bishop, but also very little counterplay. Just compare the rooks and note too White's mighty knight on e4.} exf4 28. Rg4 Raf8 29. Kb1 $1 {Dubov doesn't fail to improve that most important of all the pieces in the endgame, the king.} (29. Rxf4 $2 Be5 30. Rxf7 Rxf7 {Black will regain the pawn and has suddenly acquired far more counterplay than White should allow.}) 29... b6 30. Kc2 Be7 (30... Be5 31. Ng5 Rg7 32. Ne6 Rxg4 33. Rxg4 {This also looks very unpleasant for Black since White can squeeze with the h-pawn and also has a pretty useful break in b2-b3.}) 31. Kd3 Bf6 32. R1g2 (32. Nxf6 $5 Rxf6 33. Kc3 {That was a big exchange on f6, but Black isn't going to be able to hold both a4 and f4.}) 32... h6 33. Rg6 {Probing, although once again the exchange on f6 would have been a pretty good one.} Bg7 34. Re6 Kh7 35. Nc3 Bxc3 $2 ({Aiming to tie Black down to a4. The engines now want to grovel no matter what with} 35... Ra8 {, but Carlsen was to prefer a rook ending where he hoped to have chances to activate and confuse the issue, objectively lost though he likely realised he was.}) 36. Kxc3 Rg7 37. Rxg7+ Kxg7 38. Re7+ Kf6 39. Rxc7 Re8 40. Rd7 Re3+ 41. Kd4 $1 {Keeping the king centralised as the talented Russian GM begins to make the rook ending look rather a straightforward one.} Rxf3 42. Rxd6+ Kf5 43. Rxb6 Rf1 44. Rb8 $1 {Activating the rook to the maximum. White's central clump of pieces will now easily outweigh the black f-pawn.} Rd1+ 45. Kc5 f3 46. Rf8+ Ke4 47. d6 Rd2 48. Kc6 {Black is clearly far too slow.} Rxh2 49. d7 Rd2 50. d8=Q Rxd8 51. Rxd8 h5 52. c5 {The c-pawn's a runner and a winner!} h4 53. Kb5 f2 54. Rd1 1-0

